from jsonb_to_recordset($NDTA_SEED$[{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"The fundamental frequency of a piezoelectric crystal used in ultrasonics is a function of","options":["its thickness","the velocity of sound in the crystal material","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"The ratio of vibration amplitude at resonance frequency to the amplitude of static thickness change is called","options":["fo","fr","the modulus of resonance","Q factor"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"A large Q factor indicates","options":["high damping","narrow bandwidth","wide bandwidth","low permeability"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Resonance peaks at frequencies of odd numbered multiples of the resonance frequency are called","options":["harmonics","PRF","multiple frequencies","sub-harmonics"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"In pulse-echo testing there is an advantage to using short pulses to excite the transducer because","options":["the dead zone is decreased","the frequency spectrum is broadened","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Of the various materials used for transducer crystals, lithium sulphate hydrate is the most critical because it","options":["looses its water of crystallization above 130 degrees C","breaks down at excitation voltages over 500 V","cannot be used in immersion testing","all of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"A PZT transducer will loose its piezoelectric property if","options":["immersed in water","used on a forging that has not been de-magnetized","used on a surface whose temperature is 140 degrees C","heated above its curie point"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"In addition to a low critical temperature, lithium sulphate hydrate","options":["is soluble in water so must be water proofed","is a poor impedance match to water","has the lowest coupling coefficient","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Waves used in ultrasonic testing of materials are ___________ in nature.","options":["mechanical","magnetic","electromagnetic","harmonious"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"In a longitudinal wave, zones of compression alternate with ________ zones.","options":["dead","rarified","subduction","anticline"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Elastic waves can be transmitted in","options":["air","water","solids","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"The smallest distance between two points on an elastic wave where the particles are in the same state of motion is the","options":["period","wavelength","frequency","hypotenuse"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"The maximum displacement of a particle from its point of rest in a sound wave is its","options":["velocity","amplitude of movement","frequency","wavelength"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Particle motion in a longitudinal wave is","options":["parallel to the direction of wave propagation","at right angles to the direction of wave propagation","retrograde","in counterclockwise ellipses"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"In transverse waves, particle motion is","options":["parallel to the direction of wave propagation","right angles to the direction of wave propagation","retrograde","in counterclockwise ellipses"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Rayleigh waves are a phenomenon associated with","options":["solid to liquid boundaries","solid to air boundaries","solid to solid boundaries","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Surface waves limited on two surfaces are also called","options":["long. waves","lamb waves","shear waves","P waves"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Rayleigh, shear and longitudinal describe","options":["wave forms","wave modes","wave lengths","wave guides"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"In general, the result of two waves interacting on each other can be found by","options":["strobe lighting","vector addition","cross-multiplying","linear summation"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"The point where no particle displacement occurs on a standing wave is called","options":["an anticline","an antinode","a node","a dead zone"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"The point where maximum particle displacement occurs on a standing wave is called","options":["an anticline","an antinode","a node","a peak detector"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Wavelength of sound is determined by","options":["(velocity) / (frequency)","(frequency) / (velocity)","(frequency) X (velocity)","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Compared to water, the acoustic impedance of steel is","options":["higher","lower","about the same","higher or lower depending on the wave mode"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"2,500,000 cycles per second (cps) is also expressed as","options":["25 kHz","2.5 MHz","2.5 mHz","25 GHz"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"The product of acoustic velocity times the density of a material gives","options":["power intensity","frequency","wavelength","acoustic impedance"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"In steel, shear wave velocity as compared to longitudinal wave velocity is about","options":["twice as fast","the same","one half as fast","one quarter as fast"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"The usual form of denoting acoustic impedance is","options":["Z","A","I","R"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"If a material borders on empty space the interface is called","options":["a vacuum","infinity","a free boundary","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"In determining the coefficient of reflection, a negative value indicates","options":["reduced amplitude","loss of sound pressure","phase reversal relative to the incident wave","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Phase reversal of an ultrasound wave upon reflection from a sonically softer material is indicated by","options":["a zero R value","a negative R value","an R value greater than 1","increased resonance"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Incidence of a sound wave from a solid to a gas is considered a free boundary condition because","options":["there are no particles in a gas","all sound is lost in transmission","the acoustic impedance of a gas is essentially zero","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Bending of a sound wave upon entering a new medium is explained by","options":["Krautkramer's law","Snell's law","Boyle's law","Hooke's law"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"If a sound beam is incident on steel from water at 20 degrees, the refracted transverse wave will have an angle","options":["greater than 20 degrees","less than 20 degrees","about 20 degrees","that cannot be determined"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"The change from longitudinal to transverse waves (and visa versa) at a boundary is called","options":["Snell's law","mode conversion","reciprocity","reversal"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"The incident angle at which the transmitted longitudinal wave first ceases to exist in the diffracting medium is called the","options":["longitudinal angle","short angle","first critical angle","second critical angle"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"The incident angle at which the transmitted transverse wave first ceases to exist in the refracting medium is called the","options":["long angle","short angle","first critical angle","second critical angle"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"The critical angle for the longitudinal wave is also called the","options":["right angle","snell angle","first critical angle","second critical angle"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"The critical angle for the transverse wave is also called the","options":["right angle","Snell angle","first critical angle","second critical angle"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Mode conversion in ultrasonics occurs at","options":["defects","corner reflectors","only free boundaries","all boundaries"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"For a longitudinal wave entering a medium of lower acoustic velocity, the refracted longitudinal wave angle in the new material will be","options":["totally internally reflected","the same","less than incidence angle","greater than incidence angle"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"The law of reflection requires that","options":["the angle of reflection equals the angle of incidence","the normal to the reflecting surface, the reflected ray and incident ray lie in the same plane","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"The \"bending\" of sound waves at gaps and openings is accounted for by","options":["reflection","diffraction","density","acoustic pressure"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"According to geometric-optic treatment of sound, acoustic pressure","options":["increases with distance from source","decreases with distance from source","varies unpredictably with distance from source","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Reflection and refraction phenomenon are illustrated in geometric-optic treatment of ultrasound by means of","options":["mirrors","equations","rays and straight lines","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"In practical ultrasonic testing, mirror surfaces can be used with sound beams to","options":["image flaws","reach points of difficult access","reduce scatter","reduce short wave dispersion effects"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"The interference pattern produced in front of a transducer face is a result of","options":["rarefaction","dispersion","diffraction","refraction"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"The distance from the probe face to the last main maximum on the beam axis is called the","options":["near field","far field","dead zone","ozone"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Acoustic pressure fluctuates in the near zone due to","options":["diffraction interference","dispersion","refraction","density fluctuations"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"A longitudinal wave generating transducer will have a given near field in steel.  If in water the near field for this probe will be","options":["the same distance","about half as long","about 1/4 as long","about 4 times as long"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Acoustic pressure along the beam axis moving away from the probe has various maxma and minima due to interference.  At the end of the near field pressure is","options":["a maximum","a minimum","the average of all maxima and minima","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Beyond the near zone of an ultrasound beam from a probe is the","options":["dead zone","Fresnel zone","far field","null zone"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Variations in acoustic pressure at right angles to the probes' sound beam in the near zone are a result of","options":["side lobes","overtones","sub harmonics","divergence"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"The angle of divergence is","options":["constant for a given piezoelectric material","applicable to the far zone only","increases with increasing probe dimensions","decreases with increasing wavelength"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"The \"main lobe\" of a rectangular probe is","options":["axially symmetric","broader in the small probe dimension","narrower in the small probe dimension","two dimensional"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Focusing of ultrasound is accomplished by","options":["curved piezoelectric crystals","lenses","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Difficulties determining exact lateral location and relative size of a flat reflector in the near zone result from","options":["the dead zone","ring down","multiple maxima and minima","absorption"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"AVG (or DGS in English) diagrams are used for","options":["establishing gain settings","determining vertical beam spreads","estimating flaw size","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Flaw detection using the through transmission method can give accurate information about","options":["flaw depth","flaw type","flaw orientation","none of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"In ultrasonic testing, a wave pulse contains","options":["a single well defined frequency","a range of frequencies","two full cycles","only positive going waves"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"The main contribution to loss of sound pressure of a beam incident on a rough surface is provided by","options":["scatter","mode conversion","refraction","diffraction"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"More scatter of a sound beam is had when using","options":["high PRF","short pulse lengths","higher frequency probes","lucite delay lines"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"For best results detecting a defect that may be irregularly shaped and slightly off perpendicular to the beam, the wavelength used should be","options":["the size of the defect","as small as possible","as large as possible to locate the defect","1 MHz"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"In ultrasonic testing by pulse-echo method, the sound waves off the probe are","options":["omni-directional","a single frequency","a range of frequencies","non-existent in the dead zone"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Higher frequency probes are not preferred for inspection of castings due to","options":["poor directivity","higher coefficients of transmission","higher coefficients of reflection","scatter"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Sound reduction over a distance can be accounted for by","options":["absorption","scatter","beam spreading","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Attenuation of ultrasound by absorption is a result of","options":["reflection","refraction","scatter","heating"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"For a plane wave, sound pressure is reduced by attenuation in a _______ fashion.","options":["linear","exponential","random","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"If a signal on your CRT is 28% FSH and 6 dB gain is added to the receiver amplifier the signal will be _______ FSH.","options":["34%","42%","56%","70%"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"If a signal is reduced from 84%  to  42% FSH, the number of dB gain removed from the receiver is","options":["2","6","12","42"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"A typical maximum thickness range for inspecting forged steel by ultrasonics is","options":["0.5 to 1m","1 to 2 m","1 to 10 m","10 to 100 m"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"As temperature of a solid increases the attenuation of sound in that object tend to","options":["increase","decrease","remain constant","vary sinusoidally"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Scatter is more likely to be a problem if","options":["grain size is small","grain size is large","a material is isotropic","grain crystals are cubic"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Scatter of ultrasound at grain boundaries is a result of","options":["frequency","in-homogenous inclusions","angulation","differences in elastic properties"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Scatter generally increases with","options":["increasing grain size","decreasing wavelength","increasing frequency","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"In ultrasonic testing a piezoelectric material is used to","options":["convert electric energy to mechanical energy","convert mechanical energy to electrical energy","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"The piezoelectric material first used for ultrasonic transducers is","options":["PZT","SiO2 (quartz)","Na Cl","PVDF"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"X-cut quartz crystal transducers are cut with active element face at right angles to the","options":["X-axis","Y1-axis","Y2-axis","Z-axis"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Shifts of the positive charge on the silicon and negative charge on the oxygen in a quartz crystals account for","options":["twin crystals","the piezoelectric effect","polymorphs","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"In order to generate mechanical displacements (ultrasound waves) in a X-cut piezoelectric crystal we must","options":["squeeze the crystal","heat the crystal","apply an alternating voltage","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Applied voltage on a piezoelectric crystal used in a transducer requires ________ to cause mechanical displacement","options":["electrodes","vibration","heat","all of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Methods of generating and receiving ultrasound by deformation of ferromagnetic materials in a magnetic field utilize the phenomenon called","options":["magnetics","electrodynamics","magnetostriction","eddy currents"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Magnetostrictive principles can be used","options":["for transmitting ultrasound","for receiving ultrasound","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Mechanical methods of ultrasound generation","options":["utilise electro-mechanical hammers","utilise rotating wire brushes","require no coupling liquids","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"The method whereby sound is transmitted through a plate from a transmitter on one side to a receiver on the other","options":["is used to characterize flaws","is called an intensity method","is used to determine flaw depth","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Pulse-echo ultrasonic testing is used for","options":["thickness testing","flaw detection","acoustic velocity determinations","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Using the pulse echo method with a 0 degrees probe (single crystal) on a flat steel plate 50mm thick, the pattern on the CRT would appear as","options":["evenly spaced multiples","randomly spaced multiples","multiples with increasing spacing between them","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"When testing thick specimens, it may be advisable to","options":["decrease the pulse repetition frequency","add reject","change to a higher frequency","use a delay line probe"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"In immersion testing you would normally position the","options":["main bang on the left edge of the CRT","entrance echo on the left of the CRT","first backwall on the right edge of the CRT","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Transmitter voltage pulse is triggered by the","options":["probe resonance","control pulse of the sweep generator","sweep delay control","vertical deflector plates in the CRT"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"The size and shape of ultrasonic probes used are determined primarily by","options":["the level II operator","the specific application","expected defect type and orientation","whether contact or immersion methods are used"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Attenuation is not a result of","options":["beam geometry","scatter","bond breaking at the molecular level","absorption"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Probe index, refracted angle, timebase and sensitivity are usually calibrated using","options":["calibrator electronics","tuning forks","calibration and or reference blocks","the test piece itself"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"When using angle beams (transverse waves) for ultrasonic testing, the position of a flaw signal on the timebase can be calibrated for","options":["sound path length","stand-off distance","depth of defect","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Which is not a commonly used target when establishing sensitivity for ultrasonic testing?","options":["side drilled holes","a tungsten ball","the 100 mm quadrant of the IIW block","flat bottom holes"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"The dominant frequency of an ultrasonic flaw detection system depends on the","options":["probe","machine receiver and amplifier","pulse propagation path","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"A probe constructed such that the ultrasonic waves converge at a point or line is a(n)","options":["dual crystal probe","focused probe","de-focused probe","immersion probe"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"The amount by which the electrical signal from the ultrasonic transducer is amplified is","options":["the gain","signal-to-noise ratio","6","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"Gain and attenuator controls on an ultrasonic machine are usually calibrated in","options":["arbitrary units","volts","decibels","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":1,"question":"A probe specially designed to be used totally un