lectric polarization are called","options":["cells","bi-poles","mono-poles","domains"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"A voltage applied across a slice of piezoelectric material will cause it to","options":["twist","expand","contract","either b or c depending on polarity"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Ferroelectric materials are made to respond in a piezoelectric fashion by","options":["using bi-metal electrodes","using only D.C. voltage","sintering the material","poling the material"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"A net dipole moment is found in ferroelectric ceramics such as PZT when","options":["heated above the curie temperature","the domains are frozen and aligned","used under water","use on highly retentive steel"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"In contact testing methods, the purpose of the layer of couplant is to","options":["reduce attenuation","stop back-scatter","allow only compressional wave to enter the piece","all of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"In which of the following properties, considered when dealing with transducer materials, does quartz excel in?","options":["receiving constant","transmitting constant","dielectric constant","coupling coefficient"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Curie temperature of a transducer material will indicate","options":["toxicity of vapour","coupling constant","acoustic impedance variations with temperature","maximum work surface temperature"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Di-lithium crystals are noted mostly for their","options":["high coupling coefficient","low dissipation factor","low curie temperature","warp drive operation on starships"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Internally reflected waves within a lightly loaded resonant transducer (ie. acoustic impedance on either side is lower than the transducer's)","options":["nullify resonance","change the resonant frequency","increase the maximum oscillation amplitude","are totally internally refracted"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"For continuous wave testing, rise time of the transducer oscillation relative to the applied driving voltage is","options":["longer than fall time","shorter","about the same","not important"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The first oscillation of a piezoelectric element hit by an alternating voltage pulse is","options":["higher than all other oscillations in that pulse","lower than all other oscillations in that pulse","never higher than the second oscillation in that pulse","higher or lower than the second oscillation depending on the front loading"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Acoustic transformers are constructed of","options":["araldite","cork","tungsten loaded epoxies","any transitional layer designed to achieve maximum power transfer"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The purpose of tungsten powder incorporated in transducer backings is to","options":["increase acoustic impedance","increase absorption of backward moving ultrasound","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Nickel and its compounds as well as cobalt and ferrites differ from other magnetostrictive materials in that they","options":["expand in applied magnetic fields","shrink in applied magnetic fields","are anti-magnetostrictive","are also piezoelectric"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Magnetostrictive transducers have application in","options":["drilling","welding","ultrasonic cleaning","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"In a standing wave, the points of zero pressure change are called","options":["null points","nodes","anti-nodes","the still zone"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"A lens shape that would result in a divergent beam in optics gives a convergent beam in ultrasonics because","options":["electromagnetic wavelengths are shorter","electromagnetic waves are faster in solids than liquids","mechanical waves are usually faster in solids than liquids","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Ultrasonic transducers used in ultrasonic cleaning apparatus are operating at a frequency of approximately","options":["25 kHz","200 kHz","0.5 MHz","50 MHz"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The purpose of ultrasonic vibrations added to the tip of a soldering gun when soldering aluminum or magnesium is to","options":["eliminate the need for penetrant inspection","make a fine grain structure with high shear strength","break through the oxide coating","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Which of the following is not a therapeutic application of medical ultrasound","options":["ultrasonic treatment of arthritis, bursitis, sciatica","destruction of brain tissue in neuro-sonic surgery","establishing health, sex and age of a fetus","destruction of gall stones"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The timebase or baseline is displayed as a horizontal line by means of","options":["line focus electronics","line focus optical lenses","a light spot moving across phosphor","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Increasing the pulse repetition frequency will result in","options":["decreasing sensitivity","increased resolution","altering the probes' frequency output","brightening the baseline"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"If it is difficult to resolve two defects separated by 0.5 cm, resolution may be improved by","options":["increasing gain","increasing soundpath","decreasing pulse length","decreasing probe frequency"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Damping is achieved in an ultrasonic transducer by","options":["electrical adjustment of the pulse","using high loss backing","using matching 