from jsonb_to_recordset($NDTA_SEED$[{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"A sharp signal with large amplitude response seen from one side of a weld but not the other, having a sharp drop off with both rotational and orbital motion would indicate the presence of","options":["porosity","lack of fusion","slag","cracking"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The use of ultrasonic methods to check fillet welds is usually restricted to determining the extent of penetration.  This is best facilitated by","options":["a guidance system to hold the probe at a fixed distance","c-scan presentations","45 and 60 degree probes in tandem","holographic techniques"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Size estimations of defects based on amplitude response are","options":["the best option available","never reliable","used by all codes","always referenced to side drilled holes or notches"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The amplitude reference line used to compare flaw response to reference hole response at varying depths is abbreviated","options":["ARL","AVG","DAC","DGS"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"If you are drawing a DAC for an inspection range of 200mm and your response from the 3/8 node reference hole at 125mm has already dropped to 10% FSH you will have to use","options":["a new calibration block","larger reference holes","the DGS (AVG) system","a split DAC"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"A transfer valve is established using","options":["published attenuation valves for the alloy tested","two shear wave probes in a through transmission technique","DGS (AVG) curves","multiple back-echoes from a normal beam probe"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"If coupling conditions on a test piece are better than on a calibration block the transfer value will be","options":["greater than zero","less than zero","not used","1 (one)"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Vertical extent of a defect is determined using","options":["a 6 dB drop method","a 10 dB drop method","a 20 dB drop method","any of the above is acceptable if the appropriate beam spread plot is made for comparison"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Acceptability of a defect is determined by","options":["code or customer requirements","amplitude relative to reference","length","type of flaw"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The most pronounced effects of beam deviation by surface roughness are had when using","options":["immersion testing","low frequency transducers","70 degree contact probes","normal beam probes"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The result of increasing the temperature of a test piece from 10�C. to 30�C. is","options":["increase sensitivity","decrease the refracted angle","decrease the acoustic velocity","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The ability to discern individual defects separate from the initial interface signal is called","options":["dead zone limit","near surface resolution","surface acuity","damping"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The IIW Block #1 cannot be used to calibrate","options":["angle beam resolution","range for time-base","time-base linearity","sensitivity"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The maximum amplitude response from the 1.5mm diameter hole in the IIW Block #1 is used to determine","options":["longitudinal wave sensitivity","shear wave sensitivity","dead zone distance","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"IIW blocks are constructed of","options":["ASTM-A36 steel","stainless steel","aluminum","any metal or alloy"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The 91mm step in the IIW Block #1 is used for","options":["setting shear wave range with longitudinal waves","establishing non-standard ranges","shear wave resolution determinations","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The purpose of the small Rompas or DIN block (IIW Block #2) is","options":["range calibration","determining exit point of probe","determining actual refracted angle","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The 5mm diameter through hole in the DIN or ROMPAS block is used for checking","options":["shear wave sensitivity","longitudinal wave sensitivity","beam angle","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"When setting sensitivity of a longitudinal probe using the IIW blocks","options":["total number and size of last echo are used","response from the side drilled hole is used","both a and b can be used","IIW blocks are never used to set sensitivity"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The dB difference between a signal 25% FSH and 100%  FSH is","options":["6 dB","8 dB","10 dB","12 dB"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"To reduce the influence of incident angle when evaluating beam characteristics the preferred target is","options":["a cylindrical target at right angles to beam axis","a spherical target of tungsten","a flat bottom hole","vee notches"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Given that maximum acoustic intensity occurs at the focal point, the focal point for a flat 100mm diameter 4 MHz probe in water is","options":["10mm inside the probe damping","the probe face","the end of the near zone","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"In the AVG (DGS) diagrams originated by Krautkramer in 1959, the reduced range is given","options":["as a fraction of the near zone","in millimeters only","as a ratio of the probe diameter","where the amplitude equals the ideal backwall echo"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"In immersion testing, defect sizing is improved in the flaw traverse technique measuring probe movement to 6 or 20 dB drop levels by use of","options":["lower frequency probes","focused probes","Y-cut transducer elements","oil coupling instead of water"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"To determine the functional, or operating frequency of a probe you need","options":["a UT machine capable of R.F. display","a frequency analyser","to know probe diameter and its near zone as measured in water","any of the above can be used"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The resolving power of an ultrasonic system depends primarily on","options":["the loop gain of the transducer","operating frequency","amount of gain used in the receiver amplifier","the pulse energy"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"When a flaw has a size that is less than the wavelength of ultrasound impinging on it,","options":["the AVG (DGS) system must be used for sizing","dimensions are determined using the 20 dB drop method","it is not possible to determine the flaws' shape","it cannot be detected"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Signal averaging, correlation, and filtering are techniques used in ultrasonic systems to","options":["extract weak signals from incoherent noise","improve resolution","characterize defects for type","none of these techniques are used in ultrasonic testing"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The process where by a re-current signal is extracted from incoherent noise is called","options":["amplitude modulation","frequency modulation","signal averaging","filtering"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Receiver noise must often be filtered out of a test system.  Receiver amplifier noise increases proportionally to","options":["the square root of the bandwidth","the inverse square of the bandwidth","attenuation","temperature"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"A group of ultrasonic transducers arranged in some form of geometrical pattern with individual transducers use sequentially as transmitters, receivers or both is called a","options":["sequenced array","switched pulser","C-scan array","multi-element probe"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Which is not used as an acoustic imaging method?","options":["deconvolution","sequenced array","liquid-surface levitation","holography"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"In order to determine a particular material parameter by ultrasonics you would need to find its","options":["critical angle","acoustic velocity and acoustic impedance","attenuation","any or all of the above depending on the parameter sought"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The so called delta technique derives its name from","options":["its origins in the Mississippi delta","measurements of changes in velocity (delta \"V\")","the triangular juxtaposition of transmitter, receiver and flaw","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Increasing a focused probe's focal length can have the advantage of increasing focal depth, but this is achieved at the expense of","options":["increasing attenuation","increasing focal spot size","reducing resolution","both b and c"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Which is not an advantage of electromagnetic acoustic transducers (EMAT)?","options":["high electric to acoustic power conversion","can inspect rough or coated surfaces","non-contacting","inspection of high temperature surfaces"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"In highly automated inspection apparatus, ultrasonic phased arrays permit","options":["elimination of mechanical scanning apparatus","increased resolution over a greater depth range","control of beam shape","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Rayleigh waves have","options":["distinctly different velocities from longitudinal and shear waves in the same medium","ellipsoidal particle displacement","a velocity slightly less than shear waves in the same medium","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"For crystalline material to have piezoelectric properties it must have","options":["asymmetry of crystal axes","silicon as one of its component elements","nuclear spin parity","no unstable isotopes"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"For unpoled poly-crystalline piezoelectric materials, an applied pressure results in","options":["polar alignment of crystal","radial mode vibration","maximum voltage","zero net voltage"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Even under ideal conditions, the electro mechanical coupling coefficient (k) will not exceed","options":["0.1","1","10","100"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"If the product of the relative transmitter and receiver efficiencies of quartz is 1, which of the following piezomaterials would have a product less than 1?","options":["PZT","ZnO","PVDF","none of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"A dual crystal probe using PZT as a transmitter and PVDF as a receiver, as compared to just PZT used in the send-receive mode would be","options":["about 7 times more efficient","half as efficient","hampered by low signal to noise ratio","useless"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The purpose of using metal powder in epoxies as probe backing material is to","options":["increase acoustic impedance of the backing to match the ceramic piezoelements' acoustic impedance","provide an electric conductor to the back electrode","decrease bandwidth","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"In ultrasonic testing, beam focusing is accomplished by","options":["placing lenses in front of the planar transmitter","suitably curved piezo material","specimen geometry","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The result of a cylindrical shaped lens on the front of an ultrasonic probe is a(n)","options":["point focused beam","line focused beam","asymptotic beam","negatively focused beam"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Which is not an advantage of electromagnetic acoustic transducers (EMATs)?","options":["no couplant needed","hot surfaces are more easily inspected","easily shaped beams","increased sensitivity over ferro electric probes"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Electromagnetic acoustic transducers (EMATs) generate ultrasound by means of","options":["cosmic awareness","eddy currents","mechanical contact","magnetic deformations"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"EMATs cannot be used to generate ultrasound in","options":["non-conductive material","magnetic metals","non-magnetic metals","both a and b"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The most common method used to determine the nature of a probes' sound field is by","options":["Fast Fourier transforms","impedance curves","side drilled holes","using two transducers, one transmitting and the other receiving"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"An angle beam probe is checked for refracted angle on an IIW and found to be 44 degrees.  The IIW block temperature is 10�C.  Moving to the 40 degree C. test piece the refracted angle will be","options":["more","less","the same","not possible to know"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"To determine the dominant frequency of a probe you would require","options":["an unrectified signal on a baseline calibrated in time","a rectified signal on a baseline calibrated in distance","a reference probe","an impedance matching circuit"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The time interval in microseconds between the first and last instant at which the value of the pulse reaches 10% of its peak amplitude is considered the","options":["pulse length","20 dB drop length","dead zone","rise time"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"When determining signal-to-noise ratio the suppression control is set at","options":["maximum","minimum","50%","suppression setting is not important"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"When determining signal-to-noise ratio, the noise is attributable to","options":["electrical noise from machine, cable and probe","metal grain structure","both a and b","inability for focus the baseline"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Probe index refers to","options":["nominal frequency of the probe","beam exit point","the refracted angle in the test piece","the incident angle from perspex"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"For a given range, deviations of + or - 2 degrees in refracted angle will result in greatest depth error for","options":["70_ probes","60_ probes","45_ probes","error will be constant at all angles"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Depth of the dead zone is determined by","options":["probe design","pulse energy setting","gain setting","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"A discontinuity whose shape, size location or properties make it detrimental to the useful service of the product in which it occurs or which exceeds the accept/reject criteria is a(n)","options":["defect","slag inclusion","crack","anomaly"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"A response or evidence of a response in non-destructive testing that requires interpretation is called","options":["an indication","a defect","a flaw","signal-to-noise ratio"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The component of ultrasonic wave attenuation resulting from conversion of mechanical energy to heat is called","options":["acoustic absorption","coupling","divergence","acoustic impedance"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The property which determines acoustic transmission across a boundary between two media is termed","options":["acoustic impedance","electric impedance","conductivity","transmissivity"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Coupling two media to provide optimum transfer of ultrasonic energy between them is","options":["a code requirement","acoustic impedance matching","best accomplished by dry coupling","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"For a given ultrasonic beam impinging on a surface, the angle of incidence, the angle of reflection and the normal to that surface are","options":["always equal","never equal","found by the inverse squared law","in the same plane"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Loss of acoustic energy in a material due to scatter, absorption and dispersion is called","options":["suppression","attenuation","damping","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"A curve showing the relationship of amplitude to distance travelled to reflectors of the same area is usually referred to as a(n)","options":["AVG curve","DAC curve","DGS curve","NDT curve"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The ultrasonic pulse received from the boundary of a body normal to the beam axis is termed","options":["backwall echo","a multiple reflection","the normal echo","a defect"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"An ultrasonic display in rectangular coordinates where distance or time of flight is represented in one direction and probe displacement represented on the other and reflected pulses as bright marks on a dark background (or vise versa) is called a(n)","options":["A-scan","B-scan","C-scan","tomograph"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Noise generated by the transmitting transducer which is produced in the receiving transducer of a dual crystal probe is called","options":["signal from noise effect","cross-talk","acoustic pick-up","FM cross-over"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"An assembly of ultrasonic crystals mounted so as to behave as though it were a single crystal is called a(n)","options":["acoustic mat","crystal mosaic","phased array","linear array"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The time interval between the initial pulse and the initiation of the time base sweep is termed","options":["range","time of flight","programmed off-set","delay"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The frequency at which the overall response of an ultrasonic pulse-echo flaw detection system is maximum is the","options":["dominant frequency","resonance frequency","nominal frequency","anti-resonance frequency"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The lowest acoustic frequency which will cause a condition of resonance to be established in a given material of given thickness is the _________ frequency.","options":["fundamental","parallel","series","anti-resonance"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"A probe which incorporates separate transmit and receive crystals in the same housing is called a","options":["dual crystal probe","T-R probe","delta probe","normal probe"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The unit of sound (or electrical) gain or attenuation, dB is","options":["one tenth of a bell","a ratio of voltages or intensities","derived from naval protocol","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The display of remnant reflections originating from previously transmitted pulses due to too high a PRF are called","options":["transients","trip signals","ghost echoes","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Harmonic frequencies occur at","options":["2 times the fundamental frequency","3 times the fundamental frequency","4 times the fundamental frequency","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The relationship between amplitudes of an indication in A-scan presentation and the magnitude of the corresponding received signals is used to determine","options":["vertical linearity","manual scanning speed","longitudinal/shear mode energy ratios","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The device which incorporates one or more ultrasonic crystals mounted inside a liquid filled flexible tire is commonly called a","options":["rubber tester","rotating head probe","wheel probe","plate probe"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Which pulse method of ultrasonic testing uses only a single crystal?","options":["pulse-echo","pitch-catch","through-transmission","all of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The source of ultrasound in acoustic emission techniques is","options":["sudden relaxation of stresses within the material","a transmitter crystal","rotary wire brushes","static discharge"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Resolving power of broadband transducers","options":["increases with soundpath distance","decreases with soundpath distance","is independant of soundpath distance","depends solely on near field length"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Examination of a metal's elastic properties by increasing the angle of incidence until either the longitudinal or shear mode disappears is called","options":["wave mode analysis","spectral analysis","specular analysis","critical-angle analysis"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"When doing immersion critical-angle analyses the pitch-catch technique is used.  The receiver probe is used to study the","options":["reflected longitudinal wave","reflected transverse wave","transmitted longitudinal wave","Rayleigh waves"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Non-contacting ultrasonic coupling, ie. coupling across an air gap has its advantage in","options":["avoiding fluid contamination of test piece","testing at elevated temperatures is possible","avoiding transducer wear on rough surfaces","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"When performing a \"normal beam\" inspection of 60mm thick plate by immersion technique, the minimum waterpath to avoid waterpath multiples in the first metal wall thickness display is","options":["15mm","30mm","60mm","240mm"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"If the longitudinal waves are required at an angle other than zero degrees from the normal in the test piece","options":["the incident angle must be less than the first critical angle","the incident angle must be less than the second critical angle","the incident angle must be between the first and second critical angles","you are out of luck-it can't be done"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Although no longer commonly used for thickness testing of steel plate, resonance testing still finds application in","options":["flaw detection in integrated circuits","locating nonbond areas in rubber to metal","shadow technique ultrasonic testing","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Ultrasonic systems similar to those used in nondestructive testing are used in","options":["ultrasonic welding","diagnostic medicine","de-watering units","ultrasonic machining"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Transducers used for resonance measurements would more likely be","options":["broadband-type pulse","high-Q factor","low-Q factor","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"When information is presented as a B-scan on an oscilloscope, intensity (or amplitude) of a signal is indicated by","options":["strobe effects for signals over a threshold amplitude","digital readout on the corner of the screen","brightness of the spot on the scope","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"When measuring crack depth using shear-wave soundpaths, amplitude drop and probe travel, you need in addition to various distances and the refracted angles","options":["a transmitting and a receiving transducer","the beamwidth in the vertical plane","maximum amplitude with respect to a side drilled hole","maximum amplitude with respect to a flat bottom hole"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"For a given flaw, with a physical vertical extent of 11mm, the probe requiring the maximum forward travel to locate the flaw ends would be the","options":["0�","45�","60�","70�"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"An increase in attenuation or a decrease in velocity in a material is generally indicative of","options":["degradation or loss of strength","an increase in compressive loading","an increase in tensile strength","decreasing pulse frequency"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Attenuation studies in ultrasound could be used to determine","options":["average gain size of metals","yield point of materials during elastic-plastic deformation","fracture toughness of stainless steel","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Ultrasonic methods used to monitor or detect fatigue cracks are based on","options":["attenuation effects","amplitude of reflection energy","both a and b are used","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"An advantage of using ultrasonic surface waves over other wave modes is","options":["good sensitivity to subsurface defects","the ease of focusing the beam","test piece contours are followed without loss due to direction changes","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The weld defect that results when a weld puddle solidifies from the outer edges and causes stresses sufficient to produce cracking is","options":["crater cracking","underbead cracking","transverse cracking","puddle jumping"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The purpose of removing a weld cap by grinding it flush with the base metal in preparation for ultrasonic testing is to","options":["reduce scatter from redirection of beam","improve volumetric coverage","increase sensitivity to near surface defects","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"When testing tubular products with ultrasonics it is essential to ensure a fixed alignment between the probe and workpiece since a slight shift of tube axis could result in","options":["a large change in incidence angle","damaging the probe","differential losses in frequency content","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"In immersion ultrasonic testing of tubular products, line focused probes have an advantage over point focused probes in that","options":["higher frequencies are available","higher inspection rates are possible","higher resolution is achieved","higher sensitivity is achieved"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"When inspecting tubing using ultrasonic immersion methods in the tube mill","options":["the tube is rotated under the ultrasonic probes","the probes are rotated around the tube","both a or b can be arranged","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Lamb waves are used to inspect","options":["threaded bar stock","for inclusions in TIG welded root passes","thin plate","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"In general, ultrasonic testing of cast iron is","options":["done at frequencies from 1-2 MHz","by immersion methods only","both a and b","avoided"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Which of the following non-metals would more commonly be tested by ultrasonics in the kiloherz range of frequencies?","options":["wood","concrete","rubber","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Ultrasonics when used on timber (ie. logs) can determine","options":["age by counting rings","diameter","presence or absence of decay","none of the above, ultrasound is not used to test timber"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Ultrasonic velocities of glasses such as quartz, fused silica and pyrex are","options":["not possible to determine","available for only the longitudinal mode","about the same as steel","about the same as water"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Ultrasonics has been successfully used in testing rubber tires for determining","options":["porosity location","de-lamination location","the state of cure","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Ultrasonic holography has an advantage over other imaging techniques in that it provides","options":["total information from a single pulse","a 3-dimensional display of defects","maximum inspection speed","the best sensitivity of all imaging systems"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Non-destructive testing is one of many applications of low-intensity ultrasound.  Which of the following is not an example of low-intensity ultrasound application.","options":["acoustic holography","ultrasonic fish-finders","ultrasonic cleaning","ultrasonic flowmeters"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The weak emission of light that sometimes accompanies cavitation in high intensity ultrasonic fields is called","options":["sonoluminescence","fluorescence","bioluminescence","ultraluminescence"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Diagnostic medical application of low intensity ultrasound has its advantage in","options":["its ability to detect phenomena X-rays cannot","destroying gall stones","generating therapeutic heat","all of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The Doppler effect is utilized in ultrasonic","options":["flaw detection","flowmeters","B-scanners","cleaners"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Ultrasound intensity used in low intensity diagnostic testing (such as nondestructive testing) is on the order of","options":["100�W/cm_","100mW/cm_","100kW/cm_","100MW/cm_"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Steel ball bearings would probably be tested nondestructively using","options":["ultrasonics","liquid penetrant","magnetic particles","radiography"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The term defect or flaw indicates","options":["a minimum or maximum size","suitability of a part for a given purpose","nature of the fault","none of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Ultimately the cause of any crack is","options":["corrosion","re-crystallization","stress","strain"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"Localized heating of metal objects can result in","options":["\"crazy\" cracks","grinding cracks","are strike cracks","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"In a valve casting, sponginess","options":["could result in a leak","could be found using liquid penetrant","is easiest found using ultrasonics","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"The term pipe refers to","options":["a forging defect","a weld defect","central shrinkage in an ingot","a central blowhole in a casting"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"A surface breaking crack located by ultrasonics","options":["will be easily located using eddy currents","may not by located by another NDT method","will be shorter if located with LPI","will be longer if located with LPI"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"If a procedure fails to take into consideration a significant variable, such as temperature, the result will be","options":["unreliable inspection results","missed defects","lack of repeatability","over sensitivity"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"If it is possible to automate a previously manually performed scan, you can always expect","options":["faster inspections","more accurate results","improved flaw detection reliability","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":2,"question":"When dealing with ultrasonic nondestructive testing the letters PZT stand for","options":["Paul Zamphir Tait, the discoverer of the piezo-ceramics","lead zirconate titanate","phosphoric zirconate tungstenate","none of the above"],"correct":