quency band","turn off any near by fluorescent lights"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"Materials such as barium titanate, lithium niobate and PZT can be more highly damped for a given over-all sensitivity than quartz because","options":["quartz is more fragile","quartz does not have the natural focusing of the others","quartz has a lower loop gain","quartz can not be driven at as high a pulse voltage as the other materials"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"Diagnostic medical applications of ultrasound do not include","options":["destruction of kidney stones","age and sex determination of a fetus","eye examination for detached retina","diagnosis of tumors and epilepsy"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"In ultrasonic testing, the analog apparatus called a peak detector is used for","options":["accurate time/distance measurements","defect sizing","amplitude determinations","attenuation measurement"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"Theoretically, accuracy in thickness or time measurements made by digital methods as compared to analog are","options":["more accurate always","more accurate only above 100 MHz sampling rate","less accurate","about the same"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"The technique of utilising the received echo signal to trigger the transmission of the next transmission pulse, thereby determining the pulse repetition frequency, is called the","options":["PRF method","T-R method","sing-around method","velocity dependent method"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"Horizontal and vertical graticules on the scope of an ultrasonic machine are usually permanently marked on the inside of the screen","options":["by electronic grid generators","to avoid parallax errors","to avoid being rubbed off","none of the above, graticules are always on the outside surface"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"Special electronic test equipment for calibration of ultrasonic instruments","options":["is never used in NDT","is used when optimum performance is required","can be replaced by calibration blocks","is usually supplied with the more expensive UT machines"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"To ensure reasonable near surface resolution, the amplitude of the trailing edge of the initial pulse lying inside the range of interest should not exceed","options":["50% full screen height","20% full screen height","1/4 total thickness at 100 mm range","1/10 total thickness at 100 mm range"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"In contact ultrasonic testing of butt welds sensitivity is determined by","options":["the smallest allowable defect and its position in the weld","defect size and orientation","size and nature (type) of defect","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"When establishing an ultrasonic test technique for a customer where a specific code does not apply, an agreement prior to inspection should exist to","options":["use maximum sensitivity, over the greatest extent and report all details","establish levels of importance and restrict inspection requirements to an acceptable minimum","use an existing code as reference","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"Total inspection time for any non-destructive test depends on","options":["condition of the test piece","sensitivity used","reporting level","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"Which of the following is not a consideration when selecting probe frequency?","options":["sound path distances","defect orientation","probe dimensions","grain structure of the test material"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"A significant advantage in using a small diameter probe for contact testing is","options":["increased resolution","better sensitivity","significantly less beam spread is had","they rock less on curved or uneven surfaces"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"Large probe of low frequency (2-3 MHz) are usually used for","options":["immersion testing","rapid scanning and initial defect detection","determining defect orientation","determining defect type"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"The refracted angle of a contact probe whose shoe has been adapted to a curved surface, where its axis of curvature is perpendicular to the incident sound beam, is determined using","options":["the 11W block #1","the 11W block #2","ALCOA Blocks","a reference block of the same radius as the shoe curvature"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"The method of sensitivity setting based on defect echo relative to a circular reflector giving the same amplitude signal at the same sound path is the __________  method.","options":["DGS","ASTM","DAC","reference reflector"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"Notches are to be avoided when establishing sensitivity levels for ultrasonic testing because their","options":["depth-to-width wavelength ratio dependence","geometry with respect to incident angle","both a and b","none of the above, notches are great reflectors to calibrate on"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"When a probe is placed on a convex surface divergence can decrease the near field unpredictably.  For this reason","options":["the DGS (or AVG) system is preferred","reference blocks are better than the DGS system","large diameter probes are curved to fit","the nominal frequency should be reduced"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"A recommended diameter for the diameter of a side drilled hole in a reference block used to set up a D.A.C. is","options":["1.5 mm","2.5 mm","one half the wavelength","2 times the wavelength"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"To detect transverse weld defects in a weld with a rough surface the operator should","options":["use a smaller probe","use a bubbler or water-jet technique","use the tandem probe technique","none of the above, such defects cannot be found by ultrasonic means"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"For shear-wave inspection of welds in heavy walled plate eg. over 100mm, it is recommended that the weld be scanned from 4 sides (when possible).  This is because","options":["70� probes will not find near surface defects","sound path distances become too large for a practical full skip inspection","standard 2 - 6 MHz probes cannot penetrate 100mm thick steel plate","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"Given a flat plate 25mm thick, a 45 degree probe is used to locate a defect.  Maximum amplitude is obtained with a soundpath of 41mm.  What is the depth of the flaw from the test surface?","options":["9mm","11mm","21mm","not possible to determine"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"A weld in a 30mm thick flat plate is found to contain a flaw using a 60 degree shear wave.  If sound path to the flaw is 85mm, the flaw depth is about","options":["17.5mm from the test surface","12.5mm from the test surface","1.5mm from the opposite surface","26mm from the opposite surface"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"The dynamic image of the echo envelope of a defect that results on the timebase from traversing (forward and backward) motion of the probe indicates the defects","options":["orientation","length","height","type"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"A ragged large amplitude signal is seen at just beyond the full skip distance when scanning an unground butt weld.  The signal is seen with nearly equal amplitude from both sides of the weld and the distance from exit point to weld centre-line is about equal.  The defect is most likely","options":["cracking","slag","excessive reinforcement","undercut"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"You are inspecting a single vee butt weld.  A large amplitude signal occurs with s