rop method has the advantage for sizing in that","options":["it works better at low frequencies than the 20 dB drop","no calibration of beam is needed","only two readings are needed for calculations","it need be done from one side of the test piece only"],"correct":1},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"Which material would it not be advisable to inspect with refracted transverse waves?","options":["titanium","aluminum","austenitic stainless steel","pyrex"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"Which material could most reliably be inspected using ultrasonics?","options":["brass","copper","stainless steel","wrought iron"],"correct":3},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"Several small defects that occur on the same wavefront of a beam from an unfocused probe appear as","options":["a single reflector","porosity","intermittent lack of fusion","slag inclusions"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"The disadvantage of a focused probe is","options":["lack of uniform sensitivity for large volume coverage","inability to resolve small defects","reduced power output","interference from edge effects of the focusing medium"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"The purpose of the methyl polymethacrylate cylinder in the IIW Block #1 is to","options":["determine total sensitivity of high power longitudinal waves","determine refracted angle","check longitudinal beam resolution","check near surface resolution"],"correct":0},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"When calibrating a 100mm range using a 45� probe on the 100mm radius of the IIW Block #1 (V1 block), the distance considered on the time-base is the successive backwall echoes because","options":["the distance to the first echo is too short","side wall effects must be considered","the zero point cannot be read from the initial pulse","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"UT","level":3,"question":"When using the IIW Block #1 for calibration of an 80� angle beam wedge for actual r