 conversion","RBE","pair production","Bremsstrahlung"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Alpha particles are easily stopped by","options":["a sheet of paper","5mm of wood","100cm of water","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"In the Compton scattering process, the incoming photon is","options":["completely absorbed","scatters with no energy loss","scatters with a loss of energy","scatters with an increase in energy"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"In compton scattering, the energy of the electron emitted is","options":["equal to the incoming photon energy","1/2 the incoming photon energy","1/3 the incoming photon energy","depends on the scatter angle"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The minimum energy of an incoming photon required for pair production is _______ MeV.","options":["0.51","1.02","5.1","10.2"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Pair production is always followed by","options":["alpha emission","electron capture","annihilation","nuclear fission"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"How many half value layers are needed to reduce a beam of radiation from 200mR/hr to 12.5mR/hr?","options":["3","4","5","6"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The relationship between radiation, intensity and distance from the source is ____________, (where I=original intensity, I'=new intensity, d=original distance, d'=new distance).","options":["I x d = I' x d'","I x d' = I' x  d","I_ x d_ = I'_ x d'_","I x d_ = I' x d'_"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The most probable interaction of a 5 keV photon with water would be","options":["photoelectric effect","Compton scatter","pair production","all of the above have equal probability"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The most likely interaction of a 150keV photon with water is","options":["photoelectric effect","Compton scattering","pair production","all of the above would have equal probability"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Which is not a \"gas detector\"?","options":["\"cutie-pie\"","GM counter","TLD","ion chamber"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"In an ionization chamber used for radiation detection, if insufficient voltage is applied to the electrodes","options":["ions do not properly adhere to electrode","no current flows in the circuit","radiation will not ionize the gas","ions created will recombine prior to reaching the electrodes"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"In the \"proportional region\" of voltage applied to an ionization chamber, ions created within the gas by radiation gain sufficient energy to","options":["cause Bremsstrahlung","penetrate the anode","create additional ions","cause continuous discharge"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Geiger counters operate in or near what is called the Geiger plateau.  This area of response refers to a(n)","options":["applied voltage","radiation sensitivity","ionization threshold","steady current flow"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"A material which emits light when struck by radiation is called a(n)","options":["photomultiplier","scintillator","ion chamber","film badge"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The function of a photomultiplier tube is to convert _______ into __________.","options":["gamma rays; electrical pulses","x-rays; photons","light; electrical pulses","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"In a photomultiplier tube, the electron ejected from the photocathode is accelerated by a voltage towards a","options":["NaI crystal","dynode","filament","photodetector"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"An advantage of a scintillation counter over a Geiger counter is its","options":["ability to detect small quantities of radiation","portability","ability to detect high activities without loses due to dead time","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The common logarithm of 100 (ie. log 100) is","options":["0","1","2","-2"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Energy can be defined as","options":["the product of mass and acceleration","the actual or potential ability to do work","the product of mass and velocity","voltage"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Energy of motion is given the name","options":["potential energy","kinetic energy","momentum","inertia"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Potential energy is energy of a body due to","options":["velocity","position","momentum","electrical capacitance"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Momentum can be defined by the product of","options":["force and distance","mass and acceleration","mass and distance","mass and velocity"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The force between 2 poles varies inversely with the","options":["distance between them","square of the distance between them","difference in pole strengths","product of the pole strengths"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"An electroscope is often used to detect","options":["magnetic fields","visible light","x-rays","insulators"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"A device used to measure the presence of electric charges is a(n)","options":["electroscope","conductor","electron microscope","Z meter"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Cables connecting the x-ray tube to the transformer affect the machine by acting as","options":["heat sinks","filters","capacitors","counter weights"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Flow of a charge in a conductor results in","options":["electric  current","capacitance","x-rays","voltage"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The practical unit of current in the SI (metric) system is","options":["volt","ampere","esu","watt"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The movement of a charge of 1 Coulomb past a point in 1 second is equal to","options":["1 watt","1 ampere","1 Farad","1 volt"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"If an electric current is flowing in a conductor it induces ______ in the surrounding space.","options":["ions","EM radiation","a magnetic field","voltage"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The opposition to current flow in a conductor is called _______.","options":["capacitance","reluctance","resistance","back EMF"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The negative electrode of an x-ray tube is always called the","options":["filament","anode","grid","cathode"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"In order to allow current in an AC circuit to flow in only one direction a ___________ is used.","options":["transformer","resistor","rectifier","rheostat"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"A vacuum tube with 3 electrodes is called a","options":["semi-conductor","transistor","pentode","triode"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"An x-ray tube filament has","options":["several hundred kV across it","about 10 volts across it","no more than 500mV flowing through it","several hundred amps flowing through it"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"With respect to the anode, the cathode is normally","options":["at a positive potential","at a negative potential","at a equal potential","at right angles"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The focal spot of the x-ray tube is located","options":["at the filament","at the cathode","at the anode","midway between the anode and cathode"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The reason the focal spot of the x-ray tube is kept small is to","options":["reduce heat generated","increase x-ray energy","limit the degree of image penumbra","obtain monochromatic radiation"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The filament of the common \"hot cathode\" style x-ray tube is nearly always made of","options":["aluminium","copper","tantalum","tungsten"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Radiograhic contrast is the","options":["same as film contrast","same as subject contrast","the sum of film and subject contrast","ratio of the radiographic density of the subject and the reference radiograph"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The sharpness of a radiographic image's outline, ie. the abruptness of density transition is termed radiographic","options":["contrast","latitude","sensitivity","definition"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"To verify the image quality of a radiograph _____ are used.","options":["penetrameters","IQI's","codes","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"IQI's or penetrameters are selected such that some aspect of their structure is related to","options":["radiation quality","film density","specimen thickness","the absorption coefficient of lead"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Image quality indicators can use_______ as an indication of radiographic sensitivity.","options":["holes","wires","metal step wedges","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"To avoid unknowing overexposure to personnel, a survey instrument should fail-safe.  To this end a malfunctioning meter should","options":["read zero","indicate excessively high fields","indicate a fluctuating field","turn itself off"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Exposure rates quadrupling as the distance is halved is explained by","options":["ASNT","reciprocity law failure","linear energy transfer","the inverse square law"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"As energy of beta particles increase their path in Lucite (acrylic resin)","options":["increases","decreases","remains constant","none of the above, the acrylic bond permits no entry of beta particles"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The radiation source used in autoradiography is usually","options":["an x-ray tube","Co-60","an isotope of gold","the specimen itself"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"When a radiographic image is recorded of a specimen using radiation emanating from that specimen the procedure is called","options":["Heimlich","autoradiography","ottoradiography","xeroradiography"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"With regards to the biological effects of ionizing radiation, the term \"direct effect\" indicates","options":["cell killing","DNA was ionized","an hydroxyl ion is formed","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"If an intermediate ion, such as; H+, hydroxyl ion, or free radical, is formed as a result of interaction with ionizing radiation, and this ion or free radical interacts with a DNA molecule, the action is called","options":["the indirect effect","termination","re-combination","the domino effect"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The relationship between the dose of radiation absorbed and the proportion of cells which survive when graphed is called","options":["H and D curve","HR curve","cell survival curve","dose curve"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Which of the following would not be considered a natural source of ionizing radiation dose to the average population?","options":["radon daughters","fallout","cosmic rays","potassium-40 in foods"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Given h=4.13z10^-18 keV.s   c=3.0x10^10cm/s   what is the wavelength of 8 keV x-rays","options":["12.4 x 10^-18 cm","12.4 x 10^-9 cm","16.2 x 10^-9 cm","18.6 x10^-10 cm"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"If the wavelength of a light photon is 5 x 10^-5 cm, its frequency is","options":["0.1 x 10^10 Hz","6 x 10^14 Hz","1.2 x 10^17 Hz","3.4 x 10^20 Hz"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"When an electron is removed from a neutral atom, the result is called a(n)","options":["photon","alpha particle","ion","isotope"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Electron shells of the atomic structure represents","options":["binding energies","energy levels","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Electron flow across the x-ray tube is","options":["constant","bidirectional","unidirectional","highly damped"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"To overcome the repulsion between electrons, electrons are steered towards a common point on the target by means of a","options":["filament transformer","focusing cup","grid","electron diffractometer"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The voltage across each component in a series circuit is ________ the resistance of the particular component.","options":["proportional to","inversely proportional to","inversely proportional to the square of","independent of"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The overall length of an x-ray tube is primarily determined by the","options":["filament current used","focal distance of the focusing cup","maximum peak kilovoltage the tube is used at","operator's specifications"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The result of repeated high anode loading is most likely","options":["melting the target","filament thinning","oxidation of the anode","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The purpose of the metal tube shield is","options":["to reduce leakage radiation from areas other than the shield aperture","provide electrical insulation mounts from the cable terminals","to house coolant oil","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Generally, the total work load that an x-ray tube can be safely operated at is limited by","options":["radiation intensity at 1 metre","line voltage to the high tension transformer","heat generated at the target and anode","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The tube voltage of a full wave rectified 60 Hz supply will have tube current at maximum __________ times each second.","options":["30","60","120","240"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Tube voltage in a halfwave rectified x-ray tube using a 50 Hz supply to the high tension supply will have maximum current flow ______ times each second.","options":["25","50","100","200"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Life of an x-ray tube filament is usually determined by","options":["kV rating of the tube","whether or not a rotating anode is used","its temperature during use","type of oil used for cooling"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The technique whereby x-rays are transmitted through a specimen onto a fluorescent screen which is viewed either directly or indirectly is called","options":["radiography","fluoroscopy","CCTV","transmission viewing"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"In fluoroscopic viewing, thin sections of a specimen of uniform material are","options":["brighter than thick sections","darker than thick sections","not likely to show any defects","not possible to contrast with thick sections"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Even with the use of image intensifiers, fluoroscopy in industrial radiography has limited application because","options":["sensitivity is poorer than film","no permanent record can be made","it is not as safe as film radiography","all of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The anode of an x-ray tube is angled to provide","options":["smaller focal spot","smaller effective focal spot","correct focusing of the electron beam","maximum reflectivity"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The purpose of rectifiers, \"valves\" (tube type) and capacitors used in the older x-ray tube units was to","options":["increase voltage across the tube","increase voltage across the filament","smooth voltage fluctuations","prevent short circuiting"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"In low power, low kV x-ray units where size and weight are to be kept to a minimum, half wave rectification of the voltage is achieved by","options":["Thyristor-based circuits","Villard circuits","Graetz circuits","the x-ray tube itself"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"A betatron is a(n) _______ used to make x-rays.","options":["man made isotope","electron accelerator","tuned transformer","constant potential generator"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"In a betatron, the electrons are accelerated in a","options":["steady magnetic field","steady electric field","travelling wave guide","circular path"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The Van de Graff generator is used in industrial radiography for","options":["eliminating electrostatic charges on film cassettes","collecting silver out of fixer solutions","making high energy x-rays","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"A 'Linac' is another term for a","options":["electrostatic generator","Van de Graff generator","betatron","linear accelerator"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"In a linear accelerator electrons are accelerated in","options":["annular wave guides","spiral paths","straight hollow wave guides","Greinacher circuits"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Which is not an advantage of a linear accelerator for producing x-rays?","options":["low cost","high radiation output","small focal spot dimensions","light weight"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"An exposure device housing a radio isotope for industrial radiography is also called a(n)","options":["isotope house","camera","shield","collimator"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The material used to provide the high degree of shielding needed in an exposure device (gamma camera) is _________.","options":["lead","zircoloy","depleted uranium","stainless steel"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The best definition of radiation dosimetry is;","options":["radiation protection measurement","the determination of the quantity of radiation which produces a given biological effect","the determination of absorbed dose and exposure","the selection of the correct isotope and film for a given exposure requirement"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Which of the following is not a means of detecting ionizing radiation","options":["LiF crystals","calorimetry","ionization chambers","all of the above can be used as detectors"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"If instead of a steady voltage applied to it at all times, an ion chamber was charged to a known voltage an allowed to discharge upon irradiation, it would be considered a","options":["direct reading dosimeter (DRD)","Geiger-Muller counter","proportional counter","discharge tube"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Ferrous sulphate is used as a","options":["chemical dosimeter","solid state dosimeter","fixer solution","radical scavenger"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Chemical dosimetry is","options":["used to calibrate other instruments","not sensitive to low doses","not a fast indicator of dose","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Theromoluminescence dosimetry makes use of the phenomenon that absorbed radiation energy","options":["ionizes a gas","causes ionization in solids","excites electrons to higher energy states in isolators","causes fluorescence"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Which is not a disadvantage of the thermoluminecent dosimetry system","options":["low accuracy below 0.1 mSv","sensitive to dirt and grease","not reusable","does not give direct information about contamination by radioactive material"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Detection of neutron radiation is by","options":["thermoluminescence","film badge","indirect ionisations","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"A calorimeter is used to measure","options":["chemical energy","heat energy","mechanical energy","light energy"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Sodium iodide, lithium iodide, zinc sulphide and bismuth germanate are examples of","options":["scintillation materials","developer chemicals","fixer chemicals","anti-flatulents"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The emulsion of an industrial radiographic film contains principally ________ crystals","options":["silver bromide","silver iodide","silver chloride","sodium thiosulphate"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"In radiographic film, imaging the suspension of silver halide crystals in a gelatinous binding agent is called a(n)","options":["super saturated suspension","argento-gel","emulsion","base"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"X-ray film is more often than not","options":["\"single-sided\"","\"double-sided\"","intrinsically different from gamma-ray film","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The metallic silver formed when an x-ray film is exposed but not developed is called","options":["fogging","blue tint","latent image","virtual image"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"With regards to their interaction with film, the difference between light and x-ray photons is a light photon ______ while an x-ray photon _________.","options":["exposes one AgBr molecule; exposes many AgBr molecules","is absorbed in the top layer of emulsion; is absorbed in the bottom layer","exposes many molecules in a single grain; exposes only one molecule","causes halation; does not"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The developer chemical provides ________ to an exposed silver bromide grain.","options":["a light photon","an electron","a lattice structure","heat"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The slope of a characteristic curve for an industrial x-ray film indicates","options":["speed","contrast","sensitivity","log relative exposure"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"On the characteristic curve of a film contrast is indicated by","options":["log relative exposure","density","area under the curve","gradient of the curve"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The slope of a line joining 2 points of specified densities on a characteristic curve indicating the contrast of a film is called the","options":["relative exposure","mean density","latitude number","average gradient"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"A film with high contrast will have","options":["low sensitivity","higher speed than low contrast film","lower speed than low contrast film","small latitude"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"A film with a large latitude will have","options":["a small toe on it characteristic curve","high speed compared to low latitude film","low speed compared to low latitude film","low contrast"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"When comparing the speeds of 2 films using their characteristic curves (density vs log relative exposure) the faster film curve will lie _____ the slower film","options":["above","below","left of","right of"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"When comparing the speed of 2 films using their characteristic curves (density vs. log relative exposure) the slower film curve will lie _________ the faster film.","options":["above","below","left of","right of"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The degree to which a radiograph is developed depends on","options":["type of developer","developer temperature","time spent in developer","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"In general grain size in a slow speed film is ______ a fast film.","options":["smaller than","larger than","the same size as","not as important as in"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"All other things being equal, the more photons required to produce a given density on a film","options":["the faster the film","the slower the film","the grainier the film will appear","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"If one film requires 10,000 photons per square cm to produce a given density and another film only 100 photons, the film requiring 100 photons will be","options":["slower","faster","grainier","both b and c"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"All other factors being equal, if an x-ray tube is operated at 3 milliamperes for an exposure, then at 6 milliamperes for another exposure; the beam intensity of the second exposure will be _____ the first.","options":["2-Jan","double","four times","the same as"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The product of the x-ray tube current times the time the tube is energized is termed the","options":["charge","exposure","intensity","field strength"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"x-ray exposures are given as the product of time and tube current in milliamperes (E=IT).  The same formula can apply to a gamma source but tube current is replaced by __________.","options":["source strength (curies or GBq)","specific activity of the source","the source decay constant","the photon keV equivalent"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The width of the \"fuzzy\" boundary of a radiographic image is","options":["the geometric unsharpness","a dimensionless ratio","a function of the radiation quality","all of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"When doing gamma ray radiography with a given source, which factor does the operator not control?","options":["film speed","source to film distance","radiation intensity","exposure time"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"When doing gamma ray radiography with a given source, which factor does the operator not control?","options":["film speed","source to film distance","radiation intensity","exposure time"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The contrast seen on a radiograph is a function of","options":["radiation quality","processing","density exposed to","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The contrast seen on a radiograph is a function of","options":["kilovoltage used","type of screens used","contrast characteristics of the film","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The radiographic equivalence factor allows an operator to make exposure corrections for variations in __________, when other factors are constant.","options":["kilovoltages","materials and alloys","exposure factors","distances"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The effect of scattered radiation is","options":["insignificant","to reduce radiographic contrast","primarily increased quality factor","not possible to reduce"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Radiographic undercut is a result of","options":["sliding two films together causing a static charge","scattered radiation from thin sections of a specimen onto shadow areas of thicker sections","incorrect placement of penetrameters","developer being too warm"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The purpose of masking a specimen with lead shot is to","options":["increase film latitude","provide a location to flash identification","reduce undercut caused by scattered radiation","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Using a \"filter\" on an x-ray beam","options":["is always recommended","is never recommended","\"hardens\" the x-radiation","\"softens\" the x-radiation"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Copper filters are used in conjunction with","options":["x-ray tubes","gamma cameras","both a and b","silver recovery systems"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"A radiographic film absorbs ______ of the direct beam in production of a radiograph, the rest being unused or used to generate secondary emissions that interact with the film.","options":["less than 1%","less than 10%","less than 50%","more than 50%"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"When lead screens are used in film radiography the back screen is sometimes thicker than the front screen.  This is to","options":["increase latitude","decrease mottling","decrease graininess","reduce backscatter"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Dirt, grease and even protective coatings are to be avoided on lead screens because","options":["they cause static marks on the film","they reduce the intensification provided by electron emissions","black spots result","mottling results"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Factory sealed films in lead oxide coated paper has the advantage of","options":["cleanliness","convenience","screen contact ensured","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Fluorescent screens used in film radiography utilize chemicals on the screen surface that are","options":["phosphorescent","luminescent","fluorescent","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"In general, increasing film speed has the effect of","options":["increasing latitude","increasing sensitivity","decreasing sensitivity","reducing required density"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The amount of film darkening in radiography is given the term","options":["transmittance","opacity","density","percent transmittance"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The instrument used to measure  the quantitative value of film darkening is a(n)","options":["opacitor","densitometer","DRD","light meter"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"A plot of exposure factor vs. metal thickness, for a given density is called a(n)","options":["characteristic curve","exposure chart","H and D curve","steel equivalence indicator"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"A gamma ray exposure chart may contain several lines each corresponding to a different","options":["film","source to film distance","density","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The smallest detail that can be discerned on a radiograph is generally termed","options":["penetrability","sensitivity","contrast","definition"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"In the DIN wire penetrameter method of determining radiographic quality, quality is indicated by","options":["resolution of 2 closely spaced wires","the smallest diameter wire visible","the thickest wire visible","length of wire visible"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Visibility of small defects in a radiographed object","options":["is assured by penetrameter visibility","is only as good as the largest IQI hole visible","can only be verified with wire IQI's","is not guaranteed by penetrameter visibility"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"When viewing a radiograph the lighting in the viewing room should be","options":["completely darkened","subdued","normal office work intensity","equal to the highest intensity of the viewer light"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Boxes of radiographic film stored in either the darkroom or inventory stores should be stored on edge, not stacked flat because","options":["labels are easier to read","emulsion could be damaged on the bottom boxes","emulsion would thin making the film slower","heat would be trapped and cause fogging of film"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Which is not an advantage of paper radiography?","options":["speed of access","viewing of densities greater than film","good image quality","portability and economy"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Paper radiography provides the radiographer with a","options":["positive image","negative image","mirror image","bad image"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Paper radiography can be used","options":["on the same objects as film radiography","only to monitor casting conditions","for electronic circuit evaluation only","not at all for industrial radiographic purposes"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The elimination of unwanted portions of the x or gamma ray beam at its source by use of shielding is called","options":["filtering","collimation","magnification","beam rectification"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Collimators should be selected","options":["by QC managers only","for gamma ray sources only","based on the film speed used","to be of size and shape to limit beam to only the area being radiographed"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The primary function of the developer solution is to","options":["soften the protective coating on the film","provide electrons to convert Ag+ to metallic silver","provide electrons to convert Br- to Bromine gas","both b and c"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Water acts as a solvent in the developer solution and constitutes ____ of the total volume of the solution.","options":["30%","50%","80%","95%"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Water is used as a component in the developer to","options":["maintain pH","accelerate development","act as a buffer","dissolve chemicals"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Water quality for the water used in the mixing of the developer solution should be","options":["distilled and filtered","\"soft\"","drinking quality of moderate hardness","similar to that in the \"Love Canal\" in New York State and passed through a 500 micron filter"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"As the temperature of the developer solution increases film speed __________.","options":["increases","decreases","increases until 32�C is reached then decreases","remains constant"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"A significant difference between manual and automatic film processing is that","options":["no stop bath is used after developer in the manual system","no stop bath is used after developer in the automatic system","no fixer solution is used in the automatic system","pH of the developer is much higher in manual processing"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Chemically speaking, the fixer solution used in film processing is","options":["acidic","alkaline","basic","neutral"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The purpose of water in the fixer chemistry is to act as a","options":["buffer","hardener","solvent for the other components","reducer"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"If no running water is available for final washing of a film, the recommended method in manual processing is","options":["fine spray with a watering bucket","reprocess the film starting at the stop bath","the cascade method using 3 or 4 water tanks","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"A general lack of overall film density is likely to be caused by","options":["insufficient fixer time","under exposure","excessive development time","SFD too short"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"A radiograph with excessive overall density is probably a result of","options":["light leaks","exhausted developer","radiation too hard","over exposure"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The film flaw that results from incorrect or unsuitable darkroom safelighting is","options":["overall yellow fogging","overall grey fogging","lack of density","dark patches"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"If a radiograph is produced with too short an SFD and yet processed to give good density, what imperfection is it likely to have?","options":["fogging","dark spots","lack of sharpness","clear spots"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"In manual processing of film, 2 or more films being developed at one time may result in the film sticking to one another or the tank wall.  This will be evidenced on the final processed film as","options":["clear patches","dark patches","dark sharp lines","clear sharp lines"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"If droplets of developer fell onto a film prior to development it would result in","options":["clear patches","dark patches","white streaks","mottling"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"A long dark line running through a processed radiograph can be due to what fault?","options":["electrical discharge","insufficient agitation in the fixer","a scratch in the lead screen","crimping the film prior to exposure"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The reason radiographic darkrooms are kept dark is because","options":["x-ray film is sensitive to light","electric discharge can be seen only in dark","there is no challenge to loading film with the lights on","they would have to be renamed if they were not dark"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The intensity of a safelight can be controlled by","options":["wattage of lamp used","colour of filter used","distance light is from film","both a and c"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"An increase of either time or temperature by 5% from that recommended for manual film processing will result in","options":["increased density","reduced contrast","reticulation","unacceptable fogging"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"When drying film, drying can be accelerated by","options":["increasing drier temperature to 150�F (51�C)","using an optimum hardener content in the fixer","adding acetic acid to the final rinse","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"If on the rare occasion a radiographer makes a radiograph that is too dark, either by overexposure or over development, it may be possible to diminish its density with","options":["increased clearing time","restrainer (sodium bisulphate)","optical reduction","photographic reducer"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The single most important advantage of automatic film processing over manual processing is","options":["cost","consistency of quality","portability","simplicity of chemistry"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"In industrial radiography silver recovery units are used to remove silver from the","options":["developer solution","stop bath solution","fixer solution","processed film"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"A film permitting 1% of the incident on it to be transmitted is said to have a density of","options":["1","1.4","2","2.8"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Transmission densitometers are used to establish density of","options":["inert metals","radiographic film","paper radiographs","radiographers"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The range of log exposures within which a satisfactory radiograph can be processed on a film is called","options":["contrast","speed","gamma","latitude"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"With x-rays, the same amount of film blackening is produced by the same exposure.  This is explained by photographic","options":["reciprocity law","development","characteristic curve","gamma"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"A high speed film is one which","options":["needs low exposure for a given density","needs low exposure for a given contrast","needs low exposure for a given latitude","needs low development time"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The fact that a source or focal spot has a finite size gives rise to","options":["absorption","graininess","penumbra","halation"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The width of the penumbral shadow is 