he above, they are essentially the same in nature"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"If your company had a 150kV x-ray unit, the maximum thickness of steel you could expect to radiograph would be about","options":["5mm","15mm","35mm","65mm"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Using a 400 kV x-ray machine the maximum thickness steel you might expect to radiograph with it would be about","options":["15mm","30mm","60mm","165mm"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The normal range of steel radiographed using IR-192 is","options":["5mm to 25 mm","25mm to 75mm","5mm to 100mm","45mm to 200mm"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The normal range of steel thicknesses radiographed using Co-60 is","options":["5mm to 50mm","5mm to 200mm","40mm to 100mm","40mm to 220mm"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"In radiographic testing, zircon sand is used for","options":["a masking material","xero-radiography","cleaning scum off manual processing tanks","phosphor paint on salt screens"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Flash radiography is used to make a radiograph of","options":["magnesium castings","materials of low flash point","high speed phenomena","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Exposure times for flash radiography of relatively slow events (such as monitoring metal casting pours) are on the order of","options":["a couple seconds","milliseconds","micro seconds","nano seconds"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"To achieve sufficient density on films used in flash radiography","options":["fluorescent intensifying screens are used","film emulsion thickness is doubled","development temperatures are increased","radiation from the explosion being monitored is used"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Flash radiography has application in studying","options":["ballistics","detonation phenomena","arc welding","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Neutron radiography has the ability to produce a visual record of changes in a specimen's","options":["density","thickness","composition","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Which is not a disadvantage of neutron radiography?","options":["cost","portability","imaging equipment needed","personnel hazard protection"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Electronic devices are inspected using ______ radiography to detect foreign materials such as cloth or paper, which might interfere with the operation of the device.","options":["x-ray","gamma ray","xero-","neutron"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The industrial imaging system whereby a radiographic image is viewed at the same time it is being irradiated is called","options":["flash radiography","real-time radiography","cine-radiography","autoradiography"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Another term for real-time radiography could be","options":["flash radiography","xeroradiography","fluoroscopy","autoradiography"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The limiting factor in unsharpness due to motion in real-time radiographic systems is the","options":["phosphor decay time","frame rate of display","human eye response","system excitation rate"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Radiation sources for modern real-time radiography systems are","options":["x-ray tubes","gamma ray isotopes","neutron source","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"A technique or process which modifies an original radiographic image so more important feature can be more easily detected and displayed is","options":["flash radiography","image magnification","computerized tomography","image enhancement"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Image enhancement techniques are used on","options":["real-time radiographic images","film based radiographic images","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Three dimensional imaging by radiographic methods is accomplished using","options":["beta-backscattering","x-ray fluorescence","flash radiography","tomography"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The beta backscatter technique is used for","options":["crack detection","measurement of coating thickness","determining moisture content","isotope determination"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"In thickness gauging using an x-ray source, thickness is determined using","options":["transmission attenuation","reflection attenuation","characteristic spectra","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The unit of ________ is the gray","options":["absorbed dose","equivalent dose","exposure","linear energy transfer"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The R�ntgen was a unit of exposure based on","options":["x-ray voltage","gamma ray intensity","biological effectiveness","amount of ionization in air"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"One sievert is equal to","options":["1 gray","10 mR","100 rem","1000 Joules"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Which of the following has the highest QF?","options":["beta rays","alpha particles","cold neutrons","protons"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Radioactivity of a substance is measured in","options":["curies","becquerels","R�ntgens","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"100 ergs of ionizing radiation per gram mass was the basis for the unit called the","options":["R�ntgen","rad","rem","RBE"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Nuclidic decay units in the SI system are becquerels (bq).  They are defined in","options":["energy per photon","disintegrations per unit mass","disintegrations per second","energy deposited per unit time"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The International Commission on Radiological Protection (ICRP), in its publication 26 made many recommendations including; \"all exposures shall be kept as low as reasonably achievable, economic and social factors being taken  into account.\"  This is the","options":["ICRA law","P26 rule","ISO fundamental policy","alara principle"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The lowest \"maximum permissible dose\" for a one year period is given for","options":["hands","feet","skin","whole body"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Which of the following is a dimensionless ratio","options":["QF","LET","Sv","Gy"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Which of the following would not be considered a man-made source of ionizing radiation dose to the average population?","options":["fallout","radiotherapy","diagnostic x-rays","radon daughters"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"A germ cell (sex cell), that has been altered due to the effects of ionizing radiation, when used in conception will result in a mutant.  This is a ___________ effect of radiation.","options":["lethal","somatic","genetic","side"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Which is not a long term somatic effect of exposure to radiation?","options":["cataracts of the eyes","tumors","lung cancer","erythema"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"An acute lethal dose of radiation is","options":["a large amount in a short period","a large amount over an extended period","2.5 Sv in a working lifetime","50 mSv in a year"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"A film badge used for personal dosimetry measures","options":["all external x, gamma and � doses","external x, gamma doses and all but the very soft � radiation","all alpha, �, x and gamma external doses","x-radiation doses only"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The holder for the personal dosimeter film badge is a(n)","options":["integral part of the measuring system","convenient way of holding the film","plastic case","unfortunate encumbrance"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The film badge holder used in personal dosimetry contains","options":["intensifying screens","filters","anti-static agents","extremity TLD's"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"MPD is the abbreviation for","options":["maximum possible dose","maximum permissible dose","maximum probable dose","maximum personal dose"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The MPD is a dose which is considered to be","options":["safe","acceptable","legal","lethal"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"When determining a radiographer's personal dose and relating it to the MPD, you must take into account","options":["all external exposures","all external and internal exposures","all medical exposures","all non-medical internal and external exposures"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"MPD's are expressed in units of","options":["R�ntgens","Gy (rad)","Sv (rem)","keV/cm"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"A person is considered \"occupationally exposed\" if he (or she)","options":["receives more than 5mSv/yr","enters a controlled area","exceeded ICRP recommended limits","receive dose due to their type of work"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The MPD for non-occupationally exposed personnel is set at","options":["5 �Sv/yr","5 mSv/yr","50 mSv/yr","5 Sv/yr"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"As compared to the MPD for the whole body, the MPD for gonads is","options":["higher","lower","the same value","higher or lower depending if the person is old or young and if male or female"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The maximum permissible body burden (MPBB) refers to","options":["x-radiation from medical sources","dose from ingested isotopes","dose from cancer treatment","total number of night shifts you can work in 1 year"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"In radiation protection terminology, a controlled area is where","options":["radiation  dose rates exceed 25�Sv/hr","radiation warning signs are displayed","access is controlled","personnel are provided with TLD's"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Maximum permissible body burdens are not fixed values but vary for","options":["each person","males and females","the isotope concerned","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Which is not a recognized method of protection from ionizing radiation sources stored in sealed containers?","options":["transportation in shielded containers","reduction of handling time","wearing a personal monitoring device","increasing work distance from the source"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"If radioactive material from a gamma source has been discovered to be \"spilled\" (capsule crushed and \"powder\" no longer confined) it should be immediately","options":["swept up","shovelled into a prepared hole","washed down with several hundreds of litres of water to dilute concentration","confined"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Lead is often used in x-ray rooms instead of concrete because","options":["lead is cheaper","lead provides the added benefit of acoustic damping","the total mass of lead required is less than the mass of concrete required","all the tables for HVL are based on lead"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Primary protective barriers are used in industrial radiography to","options":["intensify the useful beam","reduce the useful beam to the permissible level","reduce scattered radiation","prevent skyshine"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Secondary protective barriers are used in industrial radiography to","options":["intensify the useful beam","limit the primary beam to the permissible level","limit scattered radiation to the permissible level","stop cosmic rays"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"An atom that decays by giving off an electron from its nucleus is called a(n)","options":["alpha emitter","beta emitter","EC isotope","fusion product"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Escape of radioactive material from a sealed capsule or source is","options":["radioactive decay","determined by a form of leak testing","not significant","not detectable"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The quality of radiation refers to","options":["the linear energy transfer of x-rays","the amount of radiation energy at 1 metre","penetrating ability of x or gamma rays","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Radiation capable of producing ions is called _____ radiation.","options":["electromagnetic","corpuscular","ionizing","Hertzian"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Radiation exposure in excess of specified limits is called","options":["acute","chronic","overexposure","illegal"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Which of the following is not an example of electromagnetic radiation","options":["alpha rays","gamma rays","x-rays","ultraviolet  rays"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Depleted uranium is used in industrial radiography for","options":["shielding in isotope cameras","forming critical masses","autoradiography","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"10 mSv in SI units was _____ in the \"old\" system.","options":["1 rem","10 rem","100 rem","1000 rem"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"100 curies is _______ in the SI units","options":["3.7 x 10^10 Bq","37 x 10^6 kBq","3700 GBq","0.37 TBq"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"100 GBq in the old system would be","options":["3700 curies","370 curies","27 curies","2.7 curies"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Given a 1000 GBq source of IR192, what amount of lead shielding is needed