 salt intensifying screens is called","options":["geometric unsharpness","film unsharpness","screen unsharpness","mottly edge"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Which of the following materials can be used instead of lead for intensifying screens","options":["tantalum","copper","iron","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"A thin sheet of lead or lead sandwiched between sheets of tin is placed between the film and object being radiographed.  This provides a _______ effect.","options":["filtering","collimating","intensifying","scattering"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Close contact between film and metal intensifying screens is essential to obtain","options":["correct density","sharp images","shortest exposure time","correct subject contrast"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"A filter of lead placed between the film and subject being radiographed works on the basis of selective absorption.  Selective absorption is due to","options":["greater absorption for scattered rays due to their lower energy","scattered radiation enters the filter at an oblique angel","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Masks, collimators, diaphragms and lead backing are all used in radiography for","options":["reflection radiography","reducing contrast","filtering x-rays","reducing scatter"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Although film agitation in the developer is recommended for the first 30 seconds in manual development to ensure no bubbles stick to the film, continuous agitation through the whole time the film is in the developer will result in","options":["mottling","reticulation","underdevelopment","reduced development time"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Given a gamma emitting radioisotope producing a dose rate of 20�Sv at 1m distance, what will be the dose rate you measure at 2m when 5mm of lead are placed half way between you and the source?","options":["10�Sv","5�Sv","1�Sv","cannot be determined from given information"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"If the intensity of a radioisotope is 640 mR/h, at 1m what will reduce the field to 2.5R/h?  Given the HVL of lead for this source is 5mm.","options":["moving so you are 16m from the source","using 40mm of lead shielding","using 20mm of lead and moving back 4m from the source","all of the above will accomplish the same result"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"A radioisotope pellet is constantly emitting ionizing radiation","options":["of variable energy","of increasing intensity","opposite directions and polarized at right angles for each opposing direction","equally in all directions"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Isotope cameras are designed such that the dose rate at 6 inches from the surface does  not exceed the permissible dose rate when","options":["it contains a \"pill\" of the isotope it was designed for","the pill is at maximum design activity","the shutter is closed","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Which of the following is not a requirement of the storage enclosure used to house radioactive sources in source changers or exposure devices, when these items are not in use?","options":["made of fire proof materials","conspicuously marked with the type of source therein","provided with a lock to prevent unauthorized removal","located in a location under the jurisdiction of the responsible user and not in a residential area"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Radiation warning signs are located","options":["on all x-ray trucks for pipeline radiography","on x-ray tubes and gamma ray cameras","wherever and whenever dose rates exceed acceptable permissible levels","in gamma ray radiographic labs only"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"When the relative intensity of the x-ray photons from an x-ray tube are plotted against their wavelength large discrete peaks can be seen over the continuum.  These peaks are a result of","options":["continuous radiation","characteristic radiation","black box radiation","mains voltage fluctuations"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Which of the following film made by Kodak is the fastest?","options":["R","AA","M","T"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Which of the following films made by Dupont would be rated as slowest?","options":["Du NDT 70","Du NDT 65","Du NDT 55","Du NDT 45"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Given the relative speed of Gevaert D-2 film is 7 for a density of 2 and DuPont NDT 70 is 1 for a density of 2.  If 126 mAs were required for a density of 2 on the D-2 film, what is the exposure for the same density on NDT 70?","options":["18mAm","18mAs","14.7mAm","882mAs"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"The purpose of leak testing radioisotopes is to","options":["ensure the isotope strength is as stated by the manufacturer","verify quality of liquid penetrants","ensure the radioactive material is still safely inside the sealed capsule","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":1,"question":"Even if the capsule containing the source in a gamma camera is not leaking, a contamination hazard exists from","options":["ionized gases produced by the isotope","radon daughters","the depleted uranium shielding","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Mass is not a property of","options":["x-rays","beta particles","alpha particles","neutrons"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The smallest division of matter that can be isolated using chemical means is the","options":["electron","proton","nucleus","element"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The electron volt (eV) is a unit of","options":["electric charge","power","energy","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Energy having the ability to perform work by virtue of its position is termed _________ energy.","options":["electric","potential","thermal","kinetic"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"E-M radiation is a form of ________ radiation.","options":["atomic","particulate","characteristic","wave"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Ultraviolet light has a wavelength that is longer than","options":["x-rays","gamma rays","cosmic rays","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The effect of increasing the frequency of a gamma photon would be to","options":["increase its wavelength","increase its velocity","decrease its wavelength","decrease its velocity"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The number of electromagnetic waves passing a point per unit time is called","options":["wavelength","angstrom unit","velocity","frequency"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The energy (E) of a photon is related to its wavelength (L) by the equation (where h = Planck's constant)","options":["E=hc/L","E=cL","E=12.4L","E-hL"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Given h=4.13x10^-18 keV.s  c=3.0x10^10 cm/s  what is the energy of a gamma ray with a frequency of 5.6x10^19 Hz","options":["3.5keV","116keV","231keV","231MeV"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Given h=4.13x10^-18 keV.s   c=3.0x10^10 cm/s   what is the wavelength of 175keV x-rays?","options":["7x10^-9cm","7x10^-10cm","7x10^11cm","7x10^12cm"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"When an electron is given sufficient energy to raise it to a higher energy level within an atom, the atom is said to be","options":["in an excited state","ionized","bonded","paired"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The electron shell that is filled in a neutral helium atom is the","options":["K","L","M","N"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The photon energy emitted by the transition of an electron in the L-shell (binding energy 10keV) to the K-shell (binding energy 60keV) is","options":["0 keV","600 keV","50 keV","70 keV"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The energy required to remove a particle from the nucleus of an atom is the ________ energy.","options":["gamma","mass","binding","transition"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Neutron beams are especially dangerous because of the biological damage they do.  This is especially pronounced in the cell because of","options":["the percentage of the cell that water represents","the large collision cross section of hydrogen","the energy transferred to recoil protons","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Somatic effects of radiation are a result of","options":["damage to gametes (sex cells)","cell death","damage to cells other than gametes","working on the nightshift"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Exposure to natural sources of radiation for the average population, ie. cosmic rays, internal terrestrial sources, etc, amount to about _______ per year.","options":["2�Sv","2mSv","20mSv","200mSv"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Short term somatic effects of radiation refer to","options":["cataract formation","chronic exposures","acute exposures","genetic mutations"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"A continuous exposure to ionizing radiation for a period of several years would be considered","options":["somatic","genetic","acute","chronic"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Radiation safety standards, extrapolate the effects of high doses to low doses.  This extrapolation implies","options":["a latency period exists for any dose","there is no threshold dose below which no response occurs","all radiation doses do equal damage","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"A non-linear dose response curve indicates","options":["a latency period exists after exposure prior to radiation effects being manifest","no latency period exists","there is a threshold dose below which no response occurs","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The first detectable clinical effects of whole body gamma doses would not be seen until exposures of about","options":["30�Gy","30 mGy","300 mGy","3000 mGy"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The so called \"sensitive period\" during a woman's pregnancy when the fetus is most sensitive to radiation induced abnormalities is","options":["the first ten days after conception","ten days to six weeks after conception","six weeks to three months after conception","three months until birth"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"A small dose of x-radiation received by a pregnant woman will","options":["result in fetal death","cause brain damage in the fetus","increase chances of birth defects","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"If the peak voltage across an x-ray tube is 100 kV, the pre-reading kilovolt meter will indicate","options":["200 kV","141 kV","100 kV","70.7 kV"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"A(n) ________ circuit is one in which the current taken from the supply is at a maximum.","options":["resonant","inductive","capacitive","resistive"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Thermionic emission is the emission of ________ from heated surfaces.","options":["x-rays","photons","electrons","thermions"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Which of the following could function as a rectifier?","options":["an eddy current probe","an x-ray tube","a filament","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"A striking voltage is attained and the x-ray tube begins to conduct when the anode voltage is increased across a(n)","options":["amplifier","triode vacuum tube","gas filled triode","filter"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Real-time radiographic systems using either an image intensifier and a vidicon camera or a fluorescent screen and isocon camera combination can perform at _________ sensitivity.","options":["less than 1%","between 1.5% and 2%","not better than 5%","not better than 10%"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Signal averaging, grey level mapping and histogram equalizing are all digital processing techniques used for","options":["smoothing voltage in linacs","focusing neutron beams","image enhancement of radiographs","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"In most image enhancement techniques used in modern radiography the first step is __________ video signal.","options":["magnifying the","digitizing the image","making the \"negative\" image a \"positive\"","noise removal in the"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"A gauging method based on excitation and detection of characteristic x-rays for elemental analysis of a material is","options":["beta backscattering","neutron scattering","x-ray fluorescence","characteristic gauging"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The Debye-Scherrer powder camera is used in which gauging technique?","options":["beta backscatter","Compton scattering","neutron attenuation","x-ray diffraction"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The process of measuring, gauging, testing or otherwise comparing a specimen with applicable requirements would be termed","options":["inspection","quality assurance","quality engineering","configuration management"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Which method of radiography does not belong in this group?","options":["auto-radiography","fluoroscopy","real-time radiography","xeroradiography"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"To provide the true 3-D image obtained in a tomogram, as distinct from perspective images which are just shaded to give the effect of 3-D, what is needed is","options":["better CAD programmes for computers","images from two separated sources be presented to the viewers eyes","both forward transmitted and backscattered intensities be measured","x-ray sources capable of sweeping from 40keV to 250keV continuously"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Test results are nominally expected to be similar in large batches of items.  This information is often plotted and statistical information is obtained from the plots.  If n=number of valves, X=a test value, d=deviation or the difference of the individual value from the arithmetic mean, �=standard deviation, the equation _______ defines the arithmetic mean.","options":["(X1+X2+X3.....Xn)/n","(d1+d2+d3 .... dn)^_/(n-1)","�/x","(�)^_"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Test results are nominally expected to be similar in large batches of items.  This information is often plotted and statistical information is obtained from the plots. If n=number of values, X=a test value, d=deviation of the difference of the individual value from the arithmetic mean, �=standard deviation.  The equation ______ defines the standard deviation.","options":["(X1+X2+X3..... Xn)/n","�/X","[�/x]^_","[(d1_+d2_+d3_ ..... dn_)/(n-1)]^_"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Elements having the same atomic number (Z) but different atomic weights are","options":["isobars","isotopes","isomers","isometrics"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Isotopes have different","options":["nuclear charges","numbers of electrons","atomic weights","atomic numbers"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In gamma emission, the mass number (A) changes by","options":["0","1","2","-1"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The mass of � particle is _________ a proton.","options":["much lighter than","about the same as","slightly heavier than","much heavier than"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"If a nucleus in an excited state returns to its ground state but it does not emit a gamma ray, it will emit","options":["a positron","and internal conversion electron","an alpha particle","both a and b"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In decay by � emission, the � particle","options":["originates from the atoms' electron shell","pre-exists in the nucleus prior to emission","is formed only at the time of emission","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"When an unstable isotope experiences � decay, the number of neutrons","options":["increases by 1","decreases by 1","increases by 2","remains the same"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In � decay the mass number (A) changes by","options":["0","1","-1","4"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In decay by electron capture the number of neutrons in the nucleus changes by","options":["0","1","-1","4"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Alpha decay of Ra266 results in an isotope of Radon with an atomic mass number (A) of","options":["230","228","224","222"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Ra226 decays to Rn222 by alpha decay, if the atomic number (Z) of Ra is 88, what is the Z of Rn?","options":["92","90","86","84"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"6 mCi (milli Curies) is equal to _________ MBq (mega Bequerels)","options":["0.111","18","178","222"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Activity is plotted against time on semi-logarithmic graph paper because","options":["decay is exponential","the result is a straight line","it cannot be plotted on linear graph paper","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"A short lived isotope P-32 has a half life of 14.3 days.  How much of a 100mCi sample will be left after 3 days?","options":["94�Ci","87mCi","78mCi","63mCi"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"An isotope has a decay constant of 0.0107/hr.  If its original activity is 300�Ci