 no energy loss","scattered with a loss of energy","scattered with an increase in energy"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In Compton scattering, the scattered photon will have the least energy if the scatter angle is","options":["0�","45�","90�","180�"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In pair production, the particles created","options":["share the photon's energy equally","share all of the photon's energy","share an amount of energy less than the photon's energy","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"If the HVL of a material is 23.1cm, its linear attenuation coefficient is","options":["33/cm","3.3/cm","0.3/cm","0.03/cm"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Human tissue has linear attenuation coefficient of about 0.45/cm for 30 keV x-rays.  What percentage of these x-rays pass through 2cm of tissue.","options":["29%","36%","41%","53%"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"If the HVL of a material is 3.4cm, how much material required to reduce a beam of radiation to 25% of its original intensity?","options":["1.7 cm","3.4 cm","6.8 cm","10.2 cm"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The linear attenuation coefficient depends on","options":["photon energy","the type of attenuating material","both a and b","none of the above, it is an independent property"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"On which of the following does the linear attenuation coefficient not depend.","options":["photon energy","photon velocity","material density","material Z number"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"An advantage of the \"cutie-pie\" as a survey meter is","options":["it only responds to contamination","it isn't strongly dependent on gamma ray energy","it responds only to high energy radiation","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"When an ionization chamber is operated in the \"proportional\" region, the number of ions collected is increased by the","options":["Compton effect","proportional effect","avalanche effect","photoelectric effect"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The voltage range which a Geiger counter operates is","options":["300mV to 500mV","300 V to 500 V","1000 V to 3000 V","3000 V to 5000 V"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Geiger counters are restored to their normal quiescent state by the process called","options":["dead time","quenching","polarization","wall loss"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The most commonly used scintillation material used in radiation detection equipment is","options":["calcium tungstate","zinc cadmium sulfide","sodium iodide","caesium iodate"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In a scintillation detector, light emitted by absorption of energy in the NaI crystal is detected by a","options":["light meter","photomultiplier tube","calorimeter","thermoluminescent dosimeter"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In a photomultiplier tube the ejected electrons are generated at the photocathode by","options":["a voltage at the NaI crystal","a voltage at the dynode","the photoelectric effect","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The gain of a photomultiplier tube is very sensitive to","options":["the energy of gamma rays striking the scintillation crystal","the high voltage applied to the dynodes","a and b","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"If log 2 = 0.3, what is Log 8?","options":["0.6","0.8","0.9","1.2"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"It is generally true that a body in a high potential energy state","options":["can move to a low potential energy state without external work being applied","will gradually loose its energy as heat","is in a state of stable equilibrium","has a high velocity"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Kinetic energy is calculated by the equation","options":["E = mv","E = _mv","E = _mv_","E = mv_"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The directions in which the photon and electron move after a Compton scattering process are such that _________ is obeyed.","options":["Einstein's equation E = mc_","the law of conservation of energy","the law of conservation of momentum","conservation of electric charges"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The unit of energy most commonly used in x-rays and other atomic phenomena is the electron volt.  This is equal to","options":["the mass equivalent of an electron","the average energy of x-ray in a 1 volt x-ray machine","the mass of an electron time the speed of light squared","the energy of an electron accelerated through one volt"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Which of the following is not an energy unit?","options":["Roentgen","ERG","gram rad","electron volt"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The relative dielectric constant for a vacuum is","options":["0","1","3.14","10"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The practical unit of charge in the SI system is the","options":["abvolt","coulomb","ampere","esu"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The practical unit of capacitance is the","options":["Henry","Farad","Coulomb","esu"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"If one Coulomb changes the potential difference of a capacitor by 1 volt the capacitor is said to be rated at","options":["1 volt","1 Farad","1 Joule","1 Henry"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"If a 1�F and a 2�F capacitor is connected in parallel the resultant capacitance is ________ �F.","options":["0.5","1","2","3"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Movement of 5 Coulombs through a conductor is 2 seconds would mean a current flow of _______ amps.","options":["2","2.5","5","10"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The ratio of the voltage to the current flow in a given conductor is called its","options":["EMF","resistance","charge ratio","power"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"If a conductor has a potential difference across it of 1V and this produces a current flow of 100mA, the resistance in the conductor is _______ ohms.","options":["0.01","0.1","10","100"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"A 1 ohm and 1 ohm resistor in series will result in a total resistance of","options":["0.3 ohms","3 ohms","9 ohms","90 ohms"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"If 420 mA flow across a 50 kV potential in 1 second, the heat produced is __________ calories.","options":["0","420","2100","5000"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"If a conductor is moved in a magnetic field, and a potential difference in the conductor is induced, this is","options":["an eddy current ampere","a magneto-amp","electromagnetic induction","and electron volt"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The ratio of the voltage in the secondary winding of a transformer and the voltage in the primary winding is called the","options":["efficiency","transformer ratio","transformer output rating","induction rate"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In a 500:1 step up transformer, if the input voltage is 500 volts, the potential difference in the secondary coil will be","options":["1 V","500 V","50 kV","250 kV"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The curve representing voltage change with respect to time is called the","options":["wave form","frequency","sine","phase"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"If you use a D.C. meter to read current in an AC circuit it will read","options":["0","0.51 I max","I max","I max x �2"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Power used in resistance with D.C. applied as compared to the same resistance with the same R.M.S. AC voltage is","options":["equal","less","more","less than or equal to"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"When 3 separate windings are separated by 120� on the rotor of an AC generator, the voltages generated will have a phase difference of","options":["0�","60�","120�","240�"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"A vacuum tube with two electrodes is called a","options":["wheatstone bridge","diode","pentode","triode"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Which of the following is used as a rectifier?","options":["a diode","a transformer","an inductor","a resistor"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The 3 components of a triode are","options":["cathode, grid, anode","cathode, deflectors, screen","anode, diode, receptor","suppressor, anode, cathode"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The percentage of the kinetic energy of electrons accelerated toward the anode of an x-ray tube, that is converted to x-rays is","options":["less than 1%","about 10%","about 50%","variable depending on applied voltage"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The limited area of the anode on which electrons are bombarded is called","options":["target","filament","focal spot","cup"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The kilovoltage applied to the anode of an x-ray tube affects","options":["x-ray intensity","x-ray penetration ability","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In an x-ray tube, which quality is not consideration when choosing materials to construct the anode?","options":["high melting point","high atomic number","high atomic mass","high heat dissipation ability"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In the commonly used thermionic x-ray tube, the current across the tube is controlled by","options":["a rheostat","varying voltage in the primary coil of the filament transformer","varying voltage in the secondary coil of the filament transformer","varying the voltage in the secondary coil of the high tension transformers"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"To prevent x-ray tube current from flowing from anode to cathode during AC voltage cycles where the anode is negative with respect to the cathode","options":["valves or other rectifying devices are used","the anode is heated by a bleeder circuit","the cathode is heated by a bleeder circuit","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The potential of the focusing cup is always","options":["positive with respect to the filament","equal to the high tension voltage","the same negative potential as the filament","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"If operated at a kV below anode saturation potential, increases in tube kilovoltage result in","options":["tube breakdown","anode current being constant","anode current increasing rapidly","anode current decreasing rapidly"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In an x-ray tube, the target , usually tungsten, is mounted in the solid copper","options":["filament","focusing cup","cathode","anode"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The purpose of supporting an x-ray tube in a metal shield filled with oil is","options":["to provide anode cooling","to provide electrical insulation","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"X-ray units using potentials in the thousand kV range are cooled using","options":["water","mineral oil","freon gas","anode fins"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The purpose of rectifier circuits in the high tension AC transformer of an x-ray tube is to","options":["provide mono-chromatic x-rays","provide unidirectional current flow","prevent tube damage","both b and c"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The reason for using a rotating anode is","options":["to reduce heating on the filament","to increase radiation output","to keep the apparent focus small","a combination of b and c"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"As the target in an x-ray tube gets older, thermal stresses cause it to get rough and pitted.  The result is","options":["reduced x-ray output","increased risk of short circuit or arching","reduced maximum kV","no effect is had on the tube performance"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"If you suspect your x-ray tube filament has broken, it can be confirmed by","options":["no kV reading on the meter","no mA reading on the meter","the tube not being able to be turned on","film found to be black after processing"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Direct-fluoroscopy, ie. via a mirror or through radiation absorbing glass is suitable for","options":["thin and or non-metallic specimens","thick metals","lead based ceramics","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Low light closed circuit television cameras are used in conjunction with fluoroscopic setups to permit","options":["use of higher kV","remote safe viewing","increased brightness of image","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"X-ray television fluoroscopic images of quality equal to film radiography are possible using","options":["x-ray diffraction","filtered x-rays","digitizing and computerized image enhancements","ultra-fine zinc silicate output phosphors"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The anode of an x-ray tube is angled at about _____ to the electron beam.","options":["90�","73�","45�","17�"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Most modern x-ray units (post 1980's) utilize _____ circuits to provide smooth high voltage supplies to the x-ray tube.","options":["diode","triode","Villard","thyristor-based"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"One x-ray machine is operating under constant potential, another is operating under the same current and kV maximum conditions but half wave rectified.  The one using constant potential supply will have","options":["higher intensity of hard radiation","higher intensity of soft radiation","exactly the same radiation spectrum","equal exposure graphs"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Betatrons are used to generate x-rays in the range of _____ keV.","options":["10 to 30","300 to 800","1,000 to 5,000","10,000 to 30,000"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In a betatron, electrons complete _____ prior to being deflected at a target.","options":["1 revolution","several dozen of revolutions","tens of thousands of revolutions","hundreds of thousand revolutions"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In the Van de Graff generator, electrons from the primary electrode are transferred to the high tension electrode via","options":["a conveyor belt","alternating electro-magnetic fields","1 MeV potential","osmotic action"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Linear accelerators are made with a wide range of energies but for most NDT applications the energy range used is","options":["500-1000 keV","1-2 MeV","4-8 MeV","1-30 MeV"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In linear accelerators electrons are moved via","options":["photo-dynodes","charged conveyor belts","high frequency electromagnetic waves","repulsion ion drive motors"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Unlike the betatron, linacs","options":["operate in the MeV range of energy","accelerate electrons at a target","can operate at several energy settings","usually use transmission mode x-rays generated at the target"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Type 2 containers for isotopes used in NDT allow the source to be moved out of the shielded container.  Movement of the source to its exposure position is accomplished by","options":["mechanical crank and connecting cable","pneumatic action","hydraulic action","all of the above can be employed"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In order to check for possible leakage of radioactive material from a cobalt camera the _________ is used.","options":["TLD","wipe test","G-M counter","DRD"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"An absorbed dose is an amount of _______ per gram.","options":["radiation","energy absorbed","electrical charge","specific radiation"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"If 1 kg of matter absorbs a dose of 200 rads from a beam of ionizing radiation, 2 kg would receive _______ (neglecting attenuation) in the same exposure.","options":["100 rad","200 rad","400 rad","200 kg rad"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"To minimize error in dose readings from DRD's resulting from natural charge leakage you should","options":["calibrate the DRD weekly","record your DRD readings on a daily basis","stand on a grounding mat when charging the DRD","never 'zero' the DRD"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The usual ferrous sulphate dosimeter (Fricke) is","options":["ferrous sulphate in dilute sulphuric acid","a single large crystal","a dry powder","evaporated on platinum rods"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Polymerization of monomers by radiation is a principle used in","options":["chemical dosimetry","film radiography","xeroradiography","autoradiography"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Most thermoluminescence systems use ____ crystals.","options":["silver bromide","ferrous sulphate","lithium fluoride","zinc sulphide"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Upon heating a LiF chip to determine accumulated dose a graph of light emitted vs. heating time (at constant heating rate) is produced.  This graph is called a(n)","options":["characteristic emission chart","HD curve","absorption line","glow curve"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Neutrons are classified according to their","options":["mass","charge","spin","energy"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"A radiation detector that indicates the total amount of ionizing radiation received in an area over a period of time is a(n)","options":["proportional counter","rate-meter","integrating radiation detection instrument","Geiger-counter"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Which mechanisms are used to detect neutrons?","options":["(n,alpa) (n,p)","(n,d) (n,f)","(n,gamma)","all of the above can be used"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Crystals of AgBr for radiographic film are imbedded in","options":["lead foil","gelatin","cellulose","cellulose triacetate"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The thickest layer of the many layers making up a radiographic film is the","options":["base","substratum","sensitive emulsion","super coating"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In industrial radiographic film, the double sided emulsion provides _________ with respect to single sided film.","options":["increased sensitivity","decreased exposure time","increased contrast","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In addition to image production by direct x or gamma rays, double emulsified film for industrial radiography relies on","options":["electrons from lead intensifying screens","light from salt intensifying screens","both a) and b)","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The number of silver bromide grains in a film exposed per x-ray photon is","options":["1","10","100","dependant on photon energy"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The electron captured by the silver ion in the formation of a latent image in x-ray film originates from","options":["a bromide ion","the lead screen","pair production","annihilation of a neutron"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"If two thickness of metal are exposed at the same time and the thin section transmits 20% more radiation, what is the difference in the logarithm of relative exposure?","options":["0.08","0.2","0.8","1.2"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The purpose of specifying a minimum useful density on a film is to ensure","options":["maximum sensitivity","minimum useful gradient is met or exceeded","good latitude","minimum exposure time is used"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The exposure range covered within the useful density range is considered the ________ of a film.","options":["log relative exposure","contrast","latitude","sensitivity"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"If the range of densities of a radiograph are to fall in the acceptable range when using high contrast film, exposure conditions must be","options":["very precise","corrected for during development","adjusted by Farmer's solution","such that a minimum kV is used"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The spacing of characteristic curves of different films along the log E axis is a result of different film","options":["latitudes","average contrasts","speeds","supercoatings"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The location of the characteristic curve along the log relative exposure curve axis depends on","options":["film speed","radiation quality (hardness)","gradient","both a and b"],"correct":3}]$NDTA_SEED$::jsonb)
