from jsonb_to_recordset($NDTA_SEED$[{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The visual impression of non-uniformity in density of a radiograph is called","options":["graininess","halation","fog","sensitivity"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Increasing the time a radiograph spends in the developer solution","options":["increases speed of a film","increases contrast of most films","reduces time needed in the fix solution","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The size of a single silver particle resulting from the development of a single photographic grain in a radiograph is rarely larger than","options":["1mm","1 micron","1 angstrom","1 nm"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"More photons must be absorbed in a ________ film than a _____ film to produce the same density","options":["fast; slow","slow; fast","high contrast; low contrast","low contrast; high contrast"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Spectral sensitivity of a radiographic film refers to","options":["its ability to be used in neutron radiography","the photon wavelength dependence of the film","the type of screen it is used with","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Adjusting x-ray tube kilovoltage will vary the beam","options":["quality","intensity","dimensions","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The only way to increase penetrating ability when using a gamma source is to","options":["increase the source size (curies or GBq)","decrease the source to film distance","use the through transmission method","change the isotope used (eg Ir192 to Co60)"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"For maximum definition of an object being radiographed the source to film distance should be __________ and the object to film distance should be __________.","options":["minimum required; maximum possible","minimum possible; maximum required","maximum that is practical, minimum possible","5 time the object thickness, 1/2 the object thickness"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The equation Ug = F(t/D) defines","options":["film unsharpness","geometric unsharpness","total unsharpness","image magnification"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The equation (MT) /D_, where M=current, T=time, and D=distance defines the","options":["x-ray exposure factor","unsharpness factor","intensity factor","fudge factor"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Reduction of scatter will increase","options":["film contrast","subject contrast","film speed","exposure time"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"A radiograph of relatively low contrast is produced on a film that is known to have high contrast.  This can be accounted for by","options":["excessive development time","excessive fixer time","high subject contrast","low subject contrast"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"High radiographic contrast may be seen on a low contrast film if","options":["development time is low","fix time is high","subject contrast is high","film latitude is low"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Which has a higher radiographic equivalence factor than steel?","options":["magnesium","aluminium","titanium","brass"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Scattered x or gamma radiation is usually _______ than primary radiation.","options":["more damaging to tissue","more penetrating","a longer wavelength","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Indirect radiation originating on the film side of the specimen from the floor or walls is","options":["skyshine","undercut","backscatter","film unsharpness"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Scatter from sources external to the specimen is reduced by using","options":["masks","diaphragms","filters","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The end result of filtering an x-ray beam is to","options":["increase net contrast","decrease net contrast","increase or decrease contrast depending on the nature of the part radiographed","have no effect on radiographic contrast"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"A filter in an x-ray beam is normally meant to decrease net contrast, however under certain conditions it can increase contrast by","options":["selecting a filter material that removes hard radiation","reducing beam width","reducing beam intensity","reducing scatter causing undercut"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Radiographic screens used in industrial radiography are usually","options":["lead","fluorescent","cellulose triacetate","both a and b are used"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The purpose of lead screens used in film radiography is","options":["to absorb longer wavelength scattered radiation","increase photographic action on the film","intensify primary radiation more than scattered radiation","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Grease and lint are removed from the surface of lead foil screens using","options":["dilute HCl","mild detergent and a lint free cloth","a dry chamois","none of the above, grease and lint on screens are reason to throw out the screen"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"If film is left between lead foil screens for extended periods of time especially in warm humid environments it will cause","options":["chicken tracks","fogging","embrittlement","excessive contrast"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Fluorescent screens are not normally used with","options":["light alloy radiography","gamma ray radiography","high sensitivity radiography","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Density of film is a ratio of _______ light intensity.","options":["transmitted to reflected","transmitted to incident","incident to transmitted","incident to reflected"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Exposure charts for one x-ray tube cannot be used for another x-ray tube because","options":["at the same kV and mA settings different intensities can result","at the same kV and mA settings, radiation quality may differ","both a and b","none of the above, an exposure chart for one machine is about the same for any machine"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"An exposure chart gives exposure conditions to produce a certain density.  If you need to shoot for another density you can calculate this from","options":["the film's characteristic curve","the inverse square law","the anti-log of the exposure factor","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Changes in conditions used in making a radiograph that vary from those used to make an exposure chart require","options":["a correction factor be calculated","approval of the film manufacturer","approval of the QA department","approval of the customer"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The antilogarithm of the difference of the log of the relative exposure from characteristic curves of 2 films at a given density gives you","options":["the exposure factor","relative speed of the two films at that density","H and D ratio","an imaginary number"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Radiographic sensitivity depends on","options":["radiographic contrast","specimen contrast","definition","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Radiographic definition depends on","options":["geometry of the radiographic set-up","type of film","radiation quality","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The grouping together of individual small silver particles in an exposed and developed radiograph into relatively large clumps result in the visual impression of","options":["graininess","density","fogging","halation"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"IQI or penetrameters are made of","options":["steel","aluminium","brass","the same or similar material as the specimen being radiographed"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"American radiographic specifications usually stipulate 2 sensitivities; ___________ sensitivity and the ______ sensitivity.","options":["specimen; film","film; penny","hole; wire","contrast; detail"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"A disadvantage of the hole type penetrameter is that","options":["only contrast sensitivity is evaluated","only detail sensitivity is evaluated","it does not indicate by how much radiographic quality level is exceeded","it can not be used on non-ferrous alloys"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"A requirement for 1-2T sensitivity using an ASTM penetrameter requires IQI be ________and the hole _______ be visible.","options":["2% of the specimen thickness; diameter equal to the IQI thickness","2 thou. thick; 2% of the IQI thickness","1 thou. thick; 2 thou. diameter","1% of the specimen thickness; diameter equal to twice the IQI twice"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Wherever possible penetrameter placement is","options":["on the source side of the specimen","on the film side of the specimen","over the thickest part of the specimen","in the middle of the area of interest"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"For viewing radiographs with a viewer incorporating several fluorescent lamps","options":["radiographs should only be of moderate density","UV filters should be used","IR filtering glasses should be worn","cooling fans must be incorporated"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Which is not a precaution you need take when storing radiographic film?","options":["avoid pressure damage by storing boxes on edges","avoid short term cycling of humidity and temperature","never store unprotected film in bright light","never store film in the same room as the replenisher supply"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"As compared to film radiography, in paper radiography the term density","options":["has the same meaning","has a different meaning","has no meaning","is opposite to film terminology"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In processing of paper radiographs, a developer agent is incorporated in the emulsion and after passing through an activation solution the paper enters the ____ prior to drying.","options":["fixer solution","wash","de-mulsifier solution","stabilizer solution"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Image quality level that can be achieved using paper radiography is about","options":["ASTM 1-1T","ASTM 1-2T","ASTM 2-2T","DIN BZ 15"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Under excellent viewing conditions, the smallest density change that can be perceived by a viewing radiographer is","options":["0.006","0.06","0.1","0.2"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Collimators are made of","options":["lead","tungsten","depleted uranium","any of the above can be used"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Developer preferentially reduces","options":["bromide ions over silver ions","silver ions over bromide ions","exposed silver ions over unexposed silver ions","unexposed silver ions over exposed silver ions"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"When developer turns a deep brown colour it is considered to be","options":["oxidized","exhausted","in need of replenisher","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The purpose of the activator (sodium carbonate) in the developer solution is to","options":["swell the emulsion","speed up the ability of the reducing agent to donate electrons","both a and b","none of the above, sodium carbonate is not used"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Sulfites are often used in the food industry as a preservative.  When used in developer solution, sodium sulfite is a","options":["preservative","solvent","hardener","reducer"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The purpose of agitating film in manual development developer solutions is to","options":["provide fresh reducing agent to the film surface","maintain constant temperature through the solution","ensure replenisher is properly mixed into the solution","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Automatic processing is faster than manual processing because","options":["chemistry is more concentrated","temperatures are generally higher","no wash or stop is used after developer","both b and c"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The active agent in a fixer solution responsible for clearing away the unexposed and undeveloped silver bromide is","options":["acetic acid","aluminium chloride","ammonium thiosulphate","sodium sulphite"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"It is understood that fixer solution both cleans and fixes a film.  The rule of thumb states that total fixing time is _______ the clearing time","options":["half","equal to","twice","four times"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"As the temperature of the final wash increases","options":["required wash time decreases","required wash time increases","film density increases","film dimensions decrease"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"A radiograph appears to have normal density but insufficient contrast, this is likely due to","options":["excessively hard radiation","poor contact with screens","over-exposure, compensated for by shortened development time","either a or c could account for this"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Poorly stored film that is out of date would likely result in a radiograph that is","options":["lacking sharpness","characterized by mottled fogging","lacking density","lacking contrast"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Extreme under-exposure compensated for by excessive development will result in","options":["yellow fogging","grey fogging","lack of sharpness","excessive contrast"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"A film cassette, containing a film, that has been left in strong sunlight or near heat from a radiator, will upon processing display which flaw?","options":["lack of density","white deposits","clear patches","grey fogging"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Dark crescent shapes on a processed radiograph are a result of","options":["SFD too short","drops of fixer spilling on film prior to development","bending or crimping the film before exposure","bending or crimping the film after exposure"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"A film being manually processed was \"tapped\" gently to remove bubbles but clear streaks still occurred.  This is because","options":["developer was spilled on the film prior to development","developer contaminated the fixer","the film was not agitated enough during development","water splashed on the film before development"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Dark branching lines on a processed radiograph are probably a result of","options":["crimping prior to exposure","crimping after exposure","static electrical discharge","film scratched after exposure"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Generally speaking a darkroom can be divided into 2 specific areas","options":["wet and dry","left and right","dark and light","hot and cold"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"No film is completely insensitive to light, even safelight, x-ray film emulsion response to light is dependant on","options":["wavelength of light","intensity of light","duration of exposure to light","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"When conditions of manual film processing cause the gelatin to swell and crack the effect is","options":["re-combination","retrograde reduction","reticulation","reversal"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Ventilation in darkrooms is recommended for","options":["safety, to clear harmful fumes","operator comfort","reduction of static electricity","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The purpose of Farmer's reducer, or any photographic reducer is to","options":["decrease film density","decrease developer time","decrease fixer time","increase film density"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Films in automatic processors are moved from one bath to another via","options":["rollers","conveyor belts","moving clips","all of the above can be used"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Silver recovery from fixer solutions is accomplished by","options":["electrolysis","metallic replacement","chemical precipitation","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In order to ensure there is no variation in light intensity from the high intensity viewer, _______ are used.","options":["DC bulbs","diaphragms","UV filter","diffuser glass panels"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Prior to use after a brief warmup time a digital transmission densitometer is","options":["calibrated against a master density strip","switched to \"auto-cal\" mode","ready to use and will be accurate to +/- 0.02","adjusted to the intensity of the high intensity viewer"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Film artifacts result in","options":["false indications","excessive sensitivity","lower density","depth estimations of defects"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In a radiograph of a shielded metal arc weld, entrapped gas pockets that are aligned and separated by a relatively small distance is called","options":["piping porosity","linear porosity","pitting","straight porosity"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Elongated voids of entrapped gases in a shielded metal arc welds are","options":["linear porosity","piping porosity","worm hole porosity","either b or c"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The severity of wormhole porosity or hollow bead is usually determined by","options":["density","percentage of wall","width of penumbra","amount and length"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Nonmetallic weld inclusions are generally termed","options":["voids","slag","lack of fusion","porosity"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"If inadequate heat or current is applied during the root pass of a weld the result could be","options":["mis-match","undercut","lack of fusion","incomplete penetration"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In a weld ________ presents more of a stress riser than __________.","options":["porosity; lack of fusion","incomplete fusion; porosity","slag; incomplete penetration","tungsten inclusion; crack"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Lack of fusion in shielded metal arc is often difficult to detect using radiography because","options":["it is relatively narrow","it is usually transversely oriented","it is poorly orientated with respect to the beam","both a and c"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"A groove formed at the junction of weld and parent metal caused by melting away of the base metal during welding is","options":["underfill","undercut","underbead cracking","under achiever welding"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The ratio of direct x-ray exposure to the screen exposure required to produce a given film density is called the","options":["exposure factor","intensification factor","fuzz factor","sensitivity"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Salt or intensifying screens used in radiography are made of ________ material.","options":["fluorescent","phosphorescent","transparent","radio-opaque"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"If in a radiographic setup the source to object distance is 40cm, and the object to film distance is 10cm, what will the magnification factor be?","options":["0.25","0.8","1.25","4"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The star shaped defect occurring in the depression formed at the end of a weld bead is called a","options":["slag inclusion","transverse crack","crater crack","ninja star"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Micro-porisity would be most likely found in a radiograph of a(n) _________ casting.","options":["aluminium","steel","green","investment"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Apart from the problems of metal integrity, what would be the effect seen on the radiograph of accidentally adding large bits of copper wire to a melt of magnesium casting?","options":["areas of lighter film density","areas of darker film density","unfused chaplets","mottling"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"A casting radiograph showing branch-like darkened areas over a large area of what is supposed to be a constant thickness indicates","options":["aligned porosity","hot tears","shrinkage","sand inclusions"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"If a casting's chaplet was to fall prior to a pour and the core it supported was no longer supported, the casting defect most likely seen would be a(n)","options":["misrun","cold shut","unfused chill","core shift"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"All other things being equal, a casting (requiring radiography) should be radiographed","options":["after initial (rough) machining","after final machining","prior to hydrostatic testing","as early in its processing as possible"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Flash radiography is similar to conventional radiography with the exception that it","options":["provides time resolution","must be done at night","uses photographic paper not film","requires a moving source"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Very high speed film is required for flash film radiography.  This is because of the low output of flash x-ray systems.  Low dose at the film is a result of","options":["short pulse duration","large target to object distance","large target to film distance","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The technique that involves using a movie camera to record a radiographic sequence is called","options":["stop motion radiography","cine-radiography","sequenced flash radiography","the hollywood technique"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Cine-radiography is accomplished using","options":["sequentially fired multiple flash x-ray tubes","a single flash x-ray tube and multiple pulsing","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The main difference between photon and neutron radiography is seen in","options":["the way neutrons are removed from the beam","the recording medium","graviton theory","the transmission intensity equation"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The intensity of a neutron beam transmitted through a material is inversely proportional to","options":["the number of atoms per cubic centimetre","the neutron cross section of the material","the thickness of the material","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The units of neutron cross section are","options":["mils","barns","cm_","nurgs"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"To overcome the problems of detecting light materials, such as rubber, plastics, and water located within metals _______ radiography is used.","options":["neutron","betatron","flash","auto-"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Real-time radiographic systems ultimately require ionizing radiation be converted to _______ for viewing.","options":["electrons","holograms","latent images","light"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In real-time radiography using neutron beams, relative screen brightness _________ with increasing neutron flux.","options":["decreases","increases","remains constant","may go up or down depending on neutron energy"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Lead silicate glass is used in fluoroscopic cabinet units for","options":["high resolution phosphors","intensifying screens","increasing phosphor decay rate","radiation barrier windows"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"A variety of camera systems are used in real-time radiographic image displays.  Solid state cameras use _______ as the sensitive layer.","options":["linear or area arrays of photo diodes","liquid crystal diodes","pressure sensitive cells","pyroelectric elements"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Low contrast sensitivity and poor resolution of real-time radiographic images can be made to approach the quality of film-based radiographic images by using","options":["newvicon cameras","image enhancement techniques","neutron radiography","microdensitometers"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The primary limiting factor of any radiographic image enhancement procedure is","options":["signal noise","contrast","analog to digital conversion rate","the total number of pixels processed per frame"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In North America digitized video images of the TV analog image are often quantized into 512 rows and 512 columns, giving 262,144 picture elements.  These picture elements are called","options":["FFT's","bytes","bits","pixels"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The most common use for neutron gauging is to detect","options":["voids","hydrogen","cracks","tungsten"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The unit of absorbed dose in the SI system is called the","options":["Roentgen","Rad","gray","sievert"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The _______ of a particular radiation is equal to the ratio of the doses of a standard radiation and the radiation under consideration, which will produce the same biological response.","options":["gray","sievert","quality factor","LET"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"An absorbed dose (gray) times the quality factor (QF) will give you _________ in units of _________.","options":["dose equivalent, sieverts","exposure, sieverts","linear energy transfer, rem","exposure, RBE"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The value of 1Gy can be given as","options":["1 Coulomb/kg","1 calorie/kg","1 erg/s","1 Joule/kg"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Absorbed dose, no matter what it's units are given in, is a measure of","options":["energy deposited in a unit mass","effective biological damage","ionizations in a unit volume","the product of a and b"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"100 rad is the same as","options":["1 Gy","1Sv","10Gy","10Sv"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"100 millisieverts (mSv) is the same as","options":["1 rad","1 rem","1 mR","0.01 Gy"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The quality factor attributed to neutrons","options":["is constant","increases with mass","is higher for thermal neutrons than for fast neutrons","is higher for fast neutrons than for thermal neutrons"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Maximum annual dose limits for non-atomic radiation workers is","options":["the same as ARW's","1/2 allowed an ARW","1/10 allowed an ARW","1/100 allowed an ARW"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Personal monitoring devices (eg. TLD's, film badges and DRD's) are required by","options":["everyone working on a nuclear site or a site where radiography is carried out","everyone who receives more than 5mSv/yr.","radiosensitive people","all occupationally exposed personnel"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In radiographic dosimetry, a meter that measures dose, or exposure is a(n)","options":["Geiger counter","integrating instrument","rate instrument","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"\"Permissible dose\" divided by the \"exposure dose rate\" will give you the","options":["MPD","LET","acquired dose","allowed working time"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The maximum range a 4MeV beta particle is likely to have in water is","options":["1mm","25mm","100mm","1m"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The normal recording medium for autoradiography is the","options":["microdensitometer","xerographic plate","radiographic film","TV screen"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"To locate radioactive material in an inert matrix, the radiographic method you would probably use is","options":["autoradiography","flashradiography","neutron gauging","x-ray fluorescence"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"A free radical is of concern in radiobiology because of the damage it can cause.  It is","options":["the same as an ion","mutated RNA","an atom or molecule carrying an unpaired electron","the initial cancer cell"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Which somatic effect of radiation is likely to be considered to have a threshold (non-stochastic)?","options":["cancer","erythema (skin reddening)","serious hereditary ill-health","leukemia"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Which somatic effect of radiation is likely to be considered to have no threshold (stochastic)","options":["cataract formation","erythema (skin reddening)","benign tumor formation","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The average energy deposited per unit length of track of a charged particle is the","options":["QF","RBE","LET","specific ionization"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The quantity used to describe LET is","options":["keV/�m","J/s","esu/cm","eV/ion pair"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The value of QF (or RBE) is dependant on","options":["the type of radiation used","the organism used as a target for the study","dose rate-continuous or fractionated","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Biological effects of radiation are a result of","options":["mechanical shock due to radiation bombardment","heat produced upon absorption of radiation","chemical disruption","net electrical charge accumulated in the absorbing material"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Radiosensitivity of a tissue or organism increases with","options":["age of the organism","available oxygen in the organism's environment","fractionated exposures","number of cells"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The study of statistics on the action of irradiation of macromolecules is termed","options":["molecular biology","target theory","radiochemistry","radiobiology"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"A shoulder region on a cell survival curve indicates","options":["tough cells","radiosensitive cells","incomplete ionization of cytoplasm components of the cell","several \"hits\" must be made by the radiation to de-activate a cell"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"When evaluating the effects of radiation using a survival curve, if a sensitive target must be hit more than once to kill or deactivate the cell the curve will be","options":["linear after an initial shoulder","completely linear","linear at low doses only","completely non-linear"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The dose resulting in survival of only 50% of cells(or cell colonies such as hamsters or humans) is represented by","options":["n","Do","LD50","S50"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Given a study of specific cells where 250kV x-rays at 120 rad provide a mean lethal dose and the same cell type requires only 50 rads of thermal neutrons for the mean lethal dose.  What is the RBE (or quality factor) of the neutrons","options":["0.4","1","2","2.4"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"For a given number of ionizing events, radiation with high LET is more efficient at killing cells in the body because","options":["it is attracted to the cell nucleus","their ionizing events are not as widely separated","low LET radiation is repelled by sensitive sited","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"It is widely felt that the sensitive target for radiation-induced lethality in cells is in the","options":["chromosomes","cytoplasm","DNA","golgi apparatus"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Death from exposures in excess of 15,000 rads result from what is known as CNS, (Central Nervous System) syndrome.  After such an acute exposure death will result in","options":["a matter of hours","2 to 3 days","3 to 6 days","1 to 3 weeks"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"A disease characterized by increased rate of cell growth in an uncontrolled manner is","options":["chataractogenesis","measles","central nervous system syndrome","cancer"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The time between an acute exposure to radiation and the manifestation of radiation damage is","options":["2 to 3 years","the decay time","the latent period","the sensitized period"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Corpuscular radiation refers to","options":["all forms of ionizing radiation","the photon quantity of radiation","particulate ionizing radiation","electromagnetic radiation"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The multiplication factor to convert relative biological effectiveness (RBE) to the SI unit, quality factor (QF) is","options":["0.1","1","10","25.4"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"A blood disease, characterised by abnormal production of white blood cells, often associated with exposures to ionizing radiation is","options":["cataractogenesis","leukaemia","erythema","epilation"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Which of the following is not an example of corpuscular radiation?","options":["alpha rays","beta rays","gamma rays","neutron beams"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Radiation that is emitted by an irradiated material is considered _________ radiation.","options":["secondary","scatter","leakage","bonus"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The wipe test for a leaking radiographic source is not performed on the","options":["source guide tube","source projection tube","source itself","camera surface"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The biggest problem with using a leaking isotope source is that","options":["unsharpness is increased","exposure times are unaccountably longer","black blotches occur on the exposed film","parts and personnel can be contaminated"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Epilation is often quoted as a symptom of acute exposure to radiation.  It is characterized by","options":["temporary or permanent hair loss","skin reddening","uncontrolled cell growth","gastro-intestinal bleeding"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The ICRP has recommended radiation dose limits to _____ stochastic effects and _______ non-stochastic effects.","options":["optimize, minimize","enhance, reduce","minimize, prevent","prohibit, encourage"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Stochastic effects of radiation are those based on","options":["probability of risk","severity of damage","degree of benefit","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"In dual focal spot x-ray machines, fractional focus is always","options":["the larger of the two focal spots","a divergent focus (negative focus)","half the larger focus","less than 1mm"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"ASTM  type 1 films are ________ as compared to ASTM type 2.","options":["only used with fluorescent screens","slower and finer grained","cheaper","double sided"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The inherent film unsharpness caused in part by sideways scattering of x-rays within the film emulsion causes","options":["mottle","geometric unsharpness","graininess","only one side of a double sided film to be exposed"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"High contrast film allows the least variability of conditions for","options":["target to film distance","kVp","exposure","all of the above are equally critical"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"A microfocus x-ray tube is used in","options":["projection radiography","electron microscopes","imaging molecular structure of DNA","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"If source to detector distance is 60cm and the source to object distance is 6cm what is the magnification in this projection radiographic setup?","options":["0.1","1","10","determined by the focal spot size"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Image contrast is improved by projection microfocus radiographic techniques because","options":["all but low angle scatter is eliminated at the image plane","the intervening air filters microfocus x-rays","microfocus x-rays are intrinsically softer than regular focus x-rays for the same kVp","all of the  above"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The basis for most parallax methods used to establish depth is the","options":["inverse square law","reciprocity law","similar triangle relationship","exposure factor"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Digital radiography refers to","options":["computer enhancement and display techniques","digital densitometers","digital readout on personal dosimeters","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"When radiographing a weld it may be advisable to grind the surface to a smooth or at least clean surface.  The purpose of this is to","options":["reduce exposure time","ensure uniform density over the total surface","reduce chance of missing defects","improve film contrast"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The purpose of indicating distance along a weld on a radiograph by means of lead numbers is to","options":["correct for parallax","meet code requirements","accurately locate defects","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The purpose of the telescopic rod that flips out in front of the window of a spot x-ray tube is to","options":["centre the x-ray beam on the area of concern","filter the beam","protect the beryllium window","split the x-ray beam in two"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"If you use a magnifying lens to assist in viewing a radiograph it is usually 4x to 6x power.  If much greater magnification is used","options":["the high intensity viewer will burn out the retina","evaluation will be more stringent than code requirements","film gain will interfere with interpretation","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The influence a defect  is likely to have on a welded component is","options":["determined by its density on the radiograph","more severe for dynamically stressed parts","more severe for statically stressed parts","never possible to determine"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Elimination of macro-variations in image brightness across a radiographic image is accomplished using","options":["mini-focus x-rays","lead screens","beryllium filters","digital image processing techniques"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Which of the following is accomplished by digital image processing techniques?","options":["modification of image contrast","improve image sharpness","analyze image data for defect recognition techniques","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The essential quality required by the discrete detectors used in digital radiography is","options":["intensity of light","flat response to all radiation energy","low noise and fast response with no hangover (afterglow)","compact size"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The preferred material used as a radiation detector in real-time radiographic systems with digital processing is","options":["cadmium tungstate","tungsten carbide","silver bromide","silver iodide"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Pressurized xenon gas is sometimes used as a detector material in real-time radiographic systems but has limited use because","options":["xenon becomes activated with prolonged use","it is too expensive","gases are inefficient x-ray absorbs at high keV","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Charged selenium plates are used in","options":["flash radiography","real-time radiography","neutron radiography","xeroradiography"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The advantage of using backscatter tomography for 3-D imaging is","options":["very thick specimens can be tested","only one surface need be accessible","greatly increased resolution over transmission tomography","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"On Jan. 1, 1980 you were given 22 GBq of Co-60 (Half life 5.3 years).  What was the date it would have been 100 GBq?","options":["Feb. 28, 1965","May 5 1967","June 3 1968","June 27 1969"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Given 100 GBq of Co-60 (half life 5.3 years) what amount of time elapses before it is only 22 GBq?","options":["10.2 years","10.9 years","11.1 years","11.6 years"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"If you started with 55 curies of Ir-192 (half life 73 days), to what strength would it decay in 100 days","options":["20 curies","21.3 curies","22.4 curies","25.0 curies"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"111 curies of Ir-192 (t_=73days) is delivered April 1 1990.  If it is used until only 20 curies is left, what date is it taken out of service?","options":["July 4,1990","Sept. 27,1990","Nov. 30, 1990","Jan. 7, 1991"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"If an isotope of Ir-192 was measured to be 20 curies on July 7, 1990, when would it have been 222 curies?","options":["200 days ago","222 days ago","254 days ago","283 days ago"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"A radioisotope used in medicine has 2.5 day half life.  If 2 �curies are injected into a body, what amount of time elapses before it is 0.2  �curies?  (assuming no biological discharge)","options":["2.5 days","3.9 days","6.1 days","8.3 days"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Subject contrast is not affected by which of the following?","options":["developing time","beam collimation","kVp or isotope used","part thickness"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"For all radiographic techniques using x-rays with kilovoltages greater than about _______ kVp, lead intensifying screens are used","options":["40","80","120","250"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Use of copper or iron screens (front and back of film)","options":["is forbidden","produces better radiographs when used with Co-60 than lead screens","requires about twice the exposure time","both b and c"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"The thickness of metal intensifying screens is","options":["0.005\" front and back","0.005\" and 0.010\" back","0.010\"front and back","variable depending on radiation energy"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Multiple exposures made of a subject to illustrate some dynamic process, whereby the direct x-radiation is recorded on film is called","options":["auto-radiography","micro radiography","cineradiography","cinefluorography"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Multiple exposures made of a subject to indicate some dynamic process, whereby the image from a fluoroscopic screen is recorded on a continuous moving film (16 frames per sec) is called","options":["autoradiography","xeroradiography","cineradiography","cinefluorography"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Which of the following is a use of NDT?","options":["identification or sorting of materials","diagnosis of the cause of failure of a part","identification of a material's properties","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Sensitivity of a radiographic image in general can be said to be","options":["inversely proportional to specimen thickness","directly proportional to specimen thickness","constant for all thicknesses","totally independent of thickness"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"It can be taken as a rule of thumb that x-ray units should not generally be used in a range outside of ____ of its maximum output voltage.","options":["10-100%","90=100%","50-90%","75-110%"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Given a 50mm thick steel plate, you are to radiograph the butt weld in the plate.  The best radiographic image would be obtained using ________ as a source (all other things being equal).","options":["Co-60","Cs-137","Ir-192","300kVp"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"Three of the following films made by different manufacturers are rated at about the same speed.  Which is the odd one out?","options":["Kodak AA","Dupont NDT 70","Dupont NDT 65","Agfa-Gevaert D-7"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"If the relative speed of Kodak AA film is rated at 1 for a density of 2.0, what would DuPont's NDT 70 film be rated at for the same density?","options":["0.7","1","1.8","2"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"When rating relative speeds of various manufacturers they are ranked against a particular film (or grade of film) at a particular density.  What is the normal density used to rank the reference film at a speed of 1?","options":["1.5","2","2.5","3"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"To ensure the radioactive material remains safely in its stainless steel capsule manufacturers","options":["provide leak tests every 6 months","double encapsulate the isotope","take out liability insurance","use depleted uranium in the camera"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"When calculating the SFD required for a given geometric unsharpness as required by a code or standard the distance calculated will be the","options":["exact distance required","minimum distance required","maximum distance required","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":2,"question":"X-ray film classification is done in numerous ways but it is generally recognized as necessary because","options":["radiographers could not figure out which film to use","so many manufacturers are now producing films","economic advantages of fast film must be limited by required image definition","all films of the same speed made by different manufacturers are found in different classes"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Inertia is a property of","options":["matter","x-rays","neutrinos","light"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The periodic table of elements arranges the elements according to","options":["chemical properties","isotopes","crystal structure at 0�K","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The mathematical equation describing the law of electric forces is called","options":["Planck's Law","Einstein's Law","Newton's Law","Coulomb's Law"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"A single unit of electromagnetic energy is a (an)","options":["magneton","electron","phonon","photon"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"In E-M radiation, the three variables are; wavelength (L), frequency (f) and velocity (c).  They are related by","options":["c=fL","f=cL","L=f/c","L=fc_"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The energy (E) of a photon is related to its frequency (f) by the equation  (h = Plank's constant).","options":["E=hf","E=h/f","E=hf_","E=f/h"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"In photon physics the letter 'h' is used to represent ___________ in the equation E=hv (v=frequency).","options":["Einsteins' constant","the gamma constant","Plancks' constant","the photon fill factor"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"If energy is measured in electron volts and wavelength (L) in angstroms the correct equation to define maximum x-ray photon energy is","options":["E=12.4/L","E=12.4L","E=12400/L","E=12400L"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The speed of X and gamma radiation is about","options":["3.0x10^2 cm/s","3.0x10^10 cm/s","3.14x10^27 cm/s","6.0x10^33 cm/s"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Given h=4.13x10^-18keV-s  c=3.0x10^10cm/s  what is the frequency of 35keV gamma rays?","options":["1.2x10^20Hz","3.5x10^Hz","39.4x10^18Hz","8.5x10^18Hz"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Given h=4.13x10^-18 keV-s  c=3.0x10^10cm/s   what is the energy of a gamma ray photon with a frequency of 1.36x10^20Hz?","options":["125 keV","229 keV","562 keV","758 keV"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Given h=4.13 x 10^-18 keV-s   c=3.0 x 10^10 cm/s  what is the energy of a photon with a wavelength of 13 x 10^-9 cm?","options":["3.4 keV","9.5 keV","1.2 MeV","3.4 MeV"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"An x-ray photon has a frequency of 2.5 x 10^20 Hz, its wavelength is","options":["1.2 x 10^-10 cm","1.2 x 10 ^10 cm","7.5 x 10^10 cm","7.5 x 10^-10 cm"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The process of removing an electron from a neutral atom is","options":["polarization","ionization","polymerization","bonding"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The number of electrons in an energy level or shell can be found from __________, where in is the energy level number.","options":["2n","2n_","3n_","n_"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The electron shell closest to an atom's nucleus is termed the","options":["alpha shell","beta shell","K shell","L shell"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The maximum number of electrons possible in the L shell is","options":["2","8","16","32"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The equation E=mc_ was first derived by","options":["J.J. Thompson","Mme Curie","Planck","Einstein"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The difference between the mass of the nucleus and the sum of the masses of the particles making up that nucleus is the","options":["mass coefficient","delta force","binding energy","thermal power factor"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Elements having the same atomic mass but different atomic numbers are","options":["isobars","isotopes","isomers","isotones"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Stable nuclei usually have more _________ than ________.","options":["electrons, protons","electrons, neutrons","protons, neutrons","neutrons, protons"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"A nucleus having more energy than it has in its ground state is considered to be in a(n) _________ state.","options":["elevated","charged","excited","isomeric"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"If a nucleus is in an excited state, it can return to its ground state by emission of a(n)","options":["electron","gamma photon","neutrino","alpha particle"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"If an excited state nucleus returns to ground state via internal conversion","options":["an x-ray is emitted","an electron is emitted","an electron is captured","the atomic number(Z) increases"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"In �-  decay, the atomic number (Z) changes by","options":["-1","0","1","4"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"In positron decay, in addition to the positron a(n) ________ is also emitted.","options":["neutron","neutrino","electron","alpha particle"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"In decay by electron capture the electron captured usually originates from","options":["the K-shell","the L-shell","the M-shell","within the nucleus"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Electron capture is followed immediately by emission of","options":["a neutron","a positron","a proton","characteristic x-rays"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Auger electrons are associated with which form of nuclidic decay?","options":["�+","�-","alpha","electron capture (EC)"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The half-life, t_, is related to the decay constant, k, by","options":["kt_ = 1","k/t_ = 1","kt_ = 0.693","kt_ = -0.693"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The decay constant is","options":["the fraction of nuclei which decay per unit time","the rate of radioactive decay","the rate at which radiation dose is delivered","both b and c"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"A sample has an activity 'A' and decay constant k at a time t from its original activity, Ao, is determined by","options":["Ao=Ae^(kt)","A=Ao e^(kt)","A=Ao e^(k/t)","A=Ao e^(-kt)"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"A sample of Cs-137 has an activity of 30Ci.  What is its activity after 1 year knowing its half life is 30 years?","options":["29.4 Ci","28.8 Ci","26.6 Ci","14.7 Ci"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"If an isotope of iridium 192, t_=73days, has an activity of 50Ci on March 15, what is its activity June 1 that same year?","options":["24Ci","21Ci","19Ci","15Ci"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"If Fe-59 has a decay constant of 0.015/day, what percentage of a sample will remain after 74 days?","options":["50","33","25","15"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"What percentage of a sample's original activity remains after 1 hour if the sample has a 20.3 minute half life?","options":["43%","31%","19%","13%"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Indium 113 has a decay constant of 0.0069/min.  What is the activity of a 20MBq sample after 24 hours?","options":["0.96kBq","9.6kBq","96kBq","960kBq"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The number of ion pairs produced by a charged particle or energy quanta is called","options":["specific ionization","excitation frequency","LET","RBE"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Annihilation is a reaction between","options":["x-rays and gamma-rays","electrons and protons","protons and positrons","electrons and positrons"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The energy released in the annihilation reaction is","options":["511 keV","1022 keV","2048 keV","variable"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"When a positron interacts with matter it","options":["seldom annihilates","sometimes produces Bremsstrahlung","has a very high LET","binds to a neutron"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The photoelectron released from the atom as a result of the photoelectric process has an energy","options":["less than the incoming photon","equal to the incoming photon","equal to the incoming photon plus the binding energy of the electron","equal to the incoming photon minus the binding energy of the electron"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"After a photoelectric interaction with an atom, the most likely event to occur is emission of a(n)","options":["alpha particle","beta particle","neutron","characteristic x-ray or Auger electron"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"In Compton scattering, the scattered photon is considered \"back-scattered\" when the scatter angle is","options":["0�","45�","90�","180�"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The probability that a photon will undergo pair production ________ from 1Mev to 10MeV photon energies.","options":["increases","decreases","remains the same","is totally unpredictable"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The probability of a photon undergoing pair production ________ with increasing Z number of the interacting atom.","options":["increases","decreases","remains the same","is inversely proportional"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"If the linear attenuation coefficient of a material is 0.139/cm for 100keV x-rays, what percentage  of 100 keV beam will penetrate 1.2cm of this material?","options":["40%","65%","85%","92%"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The HVL in lead for annihilation radiation is 3.85mm.  What percentage of a beam of positrons penetrates 2.3 cm of lead?","options":["1.60%","2.50%","13.20%","15.80%"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The equation describing the relationship between half layer value (HVL) and linear attenuation coefficient (�) is","options":["HVL = 0.693/�","HVL = �/0.693","HVL = �(0.693)","� = 0.693(HVL)"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The relationship between radiation (initial intensity Io, final intensity I) and a material of thickness X having a linear attenuation coefficient � is given by","options":["I = Io � X","I = Io �/X","I = Io e ^ �X","I = Io e ^-�X"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The \"cutie-pie\" is a(n) ___________ counter.","options":["gas flow","sodium iodide","Geiger Muller","ionization"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"In an ionization chamber operated in the saturation region, the current is directly proportional to the","options":["radiation type","radiation energy","voltage applied to the electrodes","number of ions created in the gas"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"In the Geiger region of applied voltage, the ions in the gas get sufficient energy to","options":["cause Bremsstrahlung","create additional ions","penetrate the anode","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The _________ should be used for low-level surveys as it is more sensitive than __________ .","options":["Geiger counter; cutie pies","cutie pie; Geiger counters","ionization chamber; calorimeters","ionization chamber; TLD"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The amount of light emitted by a NaI crystal depends on the","options":["crystal diameter","crystal thickness","photon energy of the gamma ray","amount of photon energy absorbed by the crystal"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"At the photocathode of a photomultiplier tube ______ eject________.","options":["photons; electrons","photons; gamma rays","electrons; photons","electrons; x-rays"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Scintillation detectors can be used to detect different types of radiation by","options":["using different phosphors","varying the voltage on the dynodes","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"In dosimetry, a scaler is used for","options":["counting single pulses from a detector","determining maximum count rate from an isotope","determining the rate at which pulses are counted","establishing the time a radionuclide has been counted"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The value of ln e is","options":["0","1","2.3","2.7"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"What is the kinetic energy of an electron ejected from the K-orbit of an atom by photoelectric absorption if the K-orbit binding energy is 500 eV and the photon energy is 1 keV?","options":["0 eV","500 eV","1000 eV","2500 eV"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"In solids, liquids and gases, heat corresponds to","options":["vibration of molecules","electrical currents","pressure waves","chemical changes"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Collisions are described as elastic or inelastic.  Elastic collisions are those in which","options":["materials are stretched","the incident particl