rator"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"In the cold cathode x-ray tube the total current flow across the tube is due primarily to","options":["thermionic emission","anode heating","cathode voltage","gas ionization"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Large focal spot, low kV variability control, low tube current and long exposures are some of disadvantages encountered when using","options":["compound anodes","gas tubes","Van de Graff generators","hot cathode style tubes"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The tendency of the cloud of electrons around the heated x-ray filament to limit emission of more electrons from the filament is called the","options":["electron limit","space charge effect","thermionic saturation point","max amp"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The secondary windings of the filament and high voltage transformers are joined.  This puts the filament circuit at a very high potential.  Heating of the filament is not affected by the high voltage transformer because","options":["the transformer connection is co-axial","a rectifier is placed between the transformer secondary coils","the filament uses DC only","the filament transformer maintains a small biased voltage across the filament"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Focusing of the electron beam onto the target is controlled by","options":["shape and size of filament","shape and size of focusing cup","position of filament within the cup","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"If an x-ray tube is operated at kilovoltages higher than anode saturation potential it is said to be","options":["super saturated","emission limited","inverse rectified","short circuited"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"In the stationary anode style x-ray tube, the tungsten target plate is","options":["the same size as the actual focal area","much smaller than the actual focal area","mounted at 19� to the anode","mounted in the focusing cup"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The result of small quantities of gas entering the vacuum of an x-ray tube is","options":["unstable and uncontrollable tube current","increased kV","decreased kV","catastrophic explosion"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"To prevent an explosion resulting when the oil expands upon heating in an oil cooled x-ray tube ________ are used","options":["oil vents","expansion bellows","over-flow reservoirs","pressure control valves"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"A transmission target is utilized by","options":["hollow anode x-ray tube","bi-polar x-ray tube","uni-polar x-ray tube","cobalt camera"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Cooling a rotating anode x-ray tube is achieved primarily by","options":["radiation through the vacuum space","conduction through the rotor stem","conduction through the rotor bearings","convection in an oil bath"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Life of a rotating anode x-ray tube is usually limited by","options":["kV used","durability of the anode bearing","rectifying circuitry used","filament material used"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The amber coloured coating that forms on the inner surface of the glass of an x-ray tube originates from","options":["heating of the glass","irradiation of the glass","pitting of the glass","tungsten evaporate from the filament and target"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The problem with direct fluoroscopic viewing is","options":["low luminance of screens","blurry images","requirement of a completely darkened room","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"In the electrostatic image intensifier used in conjunction with fluoroscopic viewing, the input phosphor is coated with a cesium-antimony compound.  This coating is called the","options":["electrostatic film","photo-cathode","