elerators electrons are bunched into pulses with a time interval of a few ________ and at a pulse frequency of a few ______ pulses per second.","options":["nano seconds; million","micro seconds; hundred","milli seconds; thousand","pico seconds; dozen"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"For high energy x-ray units, in excess of 10MeV, very large source-to-film distances are often required because of","options":["\"skin sparing\" effects","damage to film cassettes","damage to film","x-ray beam width decreasing with increasing energy"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"For type-2 exposure devices using a flexible metal drive cable to position the isotope, the isotope capsule is attached to a","options":["zircalloy tube","pigtail","depleted uranium shield","quick disconnect coupling"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Should an isotope camera be found to be leaking radioactive material subsequent to a wipe test","options":["the depleted uranium is to be replaced","all exposures since the last wipe test are to be recalled","the source is to be destroyed","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"100 ergs is equal to one","options":["gram rad","rad","Roentgen","Gray"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The absorption of _________ is defined as 1 Rad","options":["100 ergs/gm in air","1/0.896 Roentgen","100 ergs/gm in water","100 ergs/gm"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The time it takes to reestablish the electric field intensity required in a G-M counter after the counter has been paralysed by ion avalanche is called","options":["resolving time","dead time","quench time","dwell time"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"In a Fricke dosimeter, the amount of ferric sulphate produced when a ferrous sulphate solution is irradiated is determined using","options":["a mass spectrometer","light absorption at a specific wavelength","a calorimeter","ph indicator"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"A chemical decomposition indicator of absorbed dose using a mixture of water and chloroform indicates dose by","options":["temperature increase","ph change","viscosity decrease","colour change"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"In LiF dosimetry, energy stored in the material as a result of irradiation is released by","options":["applying a voltage","heating","illuminating","resonating"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Film badge dosimetry has very few advantages over TL LiF dosimetry.  Which of the following is an advantage held by film badge dosimetry","options":["linearity of response","not sensitive to grease and dirt","useful over a wide dose range","reusability"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The lowest energy neutrons are termed ________ neutrons","options":["thermal","epithermal","slow","relativistic"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Thermal neutrons can be easily detected by using","options":["conventional ion chambers","activation of metal foils","a critical mass","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Proportional counters and scintillation detectors filled with gases containing boron are used to detect","options":["alpha particles","thermal neutrons","x-rays","positrons"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The base material of a radiographic film is normally","options":["gelatin","cellulose nitrate","a polyester","silver bromide"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Prior to coating the radiographic film base with the sensitive emulsion it must be prepared so the emulsion adheres to it.  This coating of cellulose ester and gelatin in water and acetone form the","options":["suspension","substratum","supercoating","infracoat"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Double sided film allows higher x-ray tube voltages to be used","options":["without deterioration in contrast","for thinner materials","without decreasing current","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The polyester used as the base for a double-sided radiographic film must be sufficiently thick to prevent kinking; however, if too thick the result may be","options":["excessive fogging","increased unsharpness","reduced aging ability","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Development of industrial radiographic film is the chemical reduction of","options":["metallic silver to silver halides","silver halide to metallic silver","silver acetate to metallic silver","gelatinous silver to metallic silver"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The development process of industrial x-ray film is catalyzed by","options":["zinc sulphide","dihydroxybenzene","sodium thiosulphide","the latent image"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Given gradient and density at four points on a characteristic curve for a particular film which point will have maximum contrast?","options":["density = 0.5  gradient =1","density = 1.0  gradient = 2.2","density = 1.5  gradient = 3.6","density =2.0  gradient = 4.1"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"In general, gradients of characteristic curves for industrial x-ray films should not be below","options":["0.1","0.5","2","5"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The influence of kV or gamma-ray quality on the contrast of a radiograph is primarily the result of","options":["contrast characteristics of the film","subject contrast","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"ISO (International standards organization) recommendations to determine \"average gradient\" of a film use densities (maximum and Minimum) of","options":["4.0 and 1.0","3.5 and 1.5","4.0 and 2.0","2.5 and 0.5"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Relative film speeds are derived using","options":["ISO rules","ASTM rules","Gradient at density = 2.0","a given density level"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Another name for the plot of the density on a radiographic film vs. the log of the exposure is the","options":["G-M  characteristic curve","French curve","D/E curve","H and D curve"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"A plot of the relative exposure vs. the resultant density is called","options":["an H and D curve","a characteristic curve","D log E curve","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"If development time is carried too far","options":["film speed may decrease","fog may increase","contrast may decrease","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The \"clumps\" of developed silver responsible for the graininess of a film are a result of","options":["single developed photographic grains","poor emulsion","statistical absorption variations","trapped bromide gases"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Increasing graininess with increasing kilovoltages is a result of","options":["fewer absorption events required for a given density","more absorption events required for a given density","more photon misses","the short wave limit"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The Bunsen-Roscoe reciprocity law for film density breaks down for","options":["low intensities of x and gamma rays used in practical applications","low exposure times used in practical applications","exposures to light","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"For maximum image sharpness the plane of the film and the plane of the object should be","options":["parallel","perpendicular","at 45�","imaginary"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Maximum magnification of a radiographic image occurs for parts","options":["at right angles to the beam","midway between source and film","nearest the film","with the greatest distance to the film"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Radiographic image magnification by placing the film at a distance from the object is practical when using linatrons and betatrons because","options":["natural magnification occurs with high energy x-rays","of their large beam spread","of the small focal spot size","high energy x-rays have such short wavelengths"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"All other factors equal, the exposure required to produce a given density radiograph is","options":["directly proportional to the source to film distance","inversely proportional to the source to film distance","inversely proportional to the source film distance squared","directly proportional to the source film distance squared"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"If given a radiographic technique in which you were told the isotope to use and the exposure factor, what is your exposure if the distance you use is 10cm?","options":["exposure factor times 1","exposure factor times 10","exposure factor times 100","cannot be determined"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"When deciding on the kilovoltage to use to produce a radiograph you should use","options":["as low a kilovoltage as other factors permit","10% more than the SWL indicates is required","50% more than the SWL indicates is required","as high a kV as other factors permit"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"When radiographing a part of uniform thickness, sensitivity will be greater for","options":["higher tube kV","lower tube kV","higher tube currents","lower tube currents"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Which kV range or isotope has a higher absorption of energy in aluminium than in steel?","options":["50 kV to 100 kV","100 kV to 150kV","Cs 137","none"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The radiographic equivalence factor for brass _______ with increasing photon energy from 50kV to 2000kV.","options":["decreases","increases","remains constant","varies unpredictably"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Scattered radiation reaching the recording film is more pronounced for","options":["thin subjects","thick subjects","composites","laminates"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The most efficient and cost effective means of reducing the effects of scattered radiation on a film is","options":["masks","lead screens","filters","collimators"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"In general the greatest proportion of radiation affecting the recording film originates from","options":["direct radiation","scattered radiation","specular reflections","annihilation radiation"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"When using a liquid as a masking material it is advised to use a solution of lead acetate and lead nitrate because","options":["the lead makes the solution a high absorber of x-rays","it has been found safe on all materials","no special precautions need be taken in its handling","none of the above applies, only distilled water is to be used"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Placement of copper-alloy filters near the x-ray tube (as opposed to near the specimen) have the advantage that","options":["scatter is reduced","soft radiation is more effectively removed","scratches and dents in the filter are not imaged on the film","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Mottling caused by x-ray diffraction can be differentiated from porosity or segregation by","options":["using a Debye-Scherrer camera","introducing a 20 micron copper filter","rotating the specimen 5 degrees and taking a second exposure","using a Potter-Bucky diaphragm"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"One drawback of using lead screens in film radiography is that","options":["primary radiation is intensified","exposure times are increased","scatter radiation is amplified","none of the above, there is no disadvantage"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The reason scratches on lead screens cause dark lines on developed radiographs is because","options":["surface area of the lead is locally increased at a scratch","light is emitted in the scratch area","developer works faster at scratch regions","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The purpose of gently rubbing the surface of lead foil screens with fine steel wool is to","options":["increase the surface area of the screen","remove shallow scratches","remove grease and lint","stop secondary emission off either front or back screen, whichever is rubbed with the wool"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Intensification factor is a term used in association with fluorescent screens. It is a ratio of","options":["exposure times","electron density","wavelengths of pear emission of light","decay of light persistence"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The equation D=log (Io/I) is used to define","options":["loudness","amount of radioactivity remaining","film density","x-ray attenuation in an absorbing material"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"An exposure chart can be adapted to any source to film distance provided","options":["exposures are given in terms of \"exposure factor\"","only 2 kV values are used","gamma exposures and not x-rays are used","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Given 2 films, x and y, x being faster than y, if the difference in the log of the relative exposures to obtain a density of 2 is 0.6, how long should the exposure be using film y if the exposure for film x took 1 minute?","options":["1.6 minutes","2.0 minutes","3.9 minutes","10.4 minutes"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"If a film requires 3.9 minutes to achieve a desired density under certain conditions, and under the same conditions another film requires only 1 minute, what is the difference in the log 