tandard sizes with ____ parallel wires in each","options":["5;5","4;6","3;7","2;9"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The two characteristics light from a radiographic viewer should have are","options":["blue-white colour; variable intensity","yellow-green colour; UV filtered","diffused; sufficient intensity","variable diffuser; ground connector"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The archival storage of exposed and processed film is time limited by","options":["residual thiosulphate","residual developer","integrity of the supercoating","chemistry of the base material"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Density in paper radiography is the common logarithm of","options":["(incident intensity/ transmitted intensity)","(incident intensity/ reflected intensity)","(incident intensity/ reflected intensity)_","(reflected intensity/ incident intensity)"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"In paper radiography the centre density for good viewing which would correspond to a density of 2.0 in film radiography is","options":["0.7","1","2","4"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Long term storage of paper radiographs that have only been stabilized can be accomplished by","options":["normal fix, wash and drying","re stabilizing","acid etching with 0.5M HCl","coating with polyurethane"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"For high energy x-ray sources (ie. >1MeV) film unsharpness","options":["increases with increasing voltage","decreases with increasing voltage","remains constant at all voltages over 1MeV","remains constant until 4 MeV than decreases quickly"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Projection radiography is used to","options":["show radiographic images to large groups of inspectors","enlarge small detail which might otherwise be too small to see","radiograph radioactive material so as to reduce fogging","both b and c"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Upon exposure of the silver bromide in film emulsion, the silver ion is converted to metallic silver and the bromide ion is","options":["bonded to an acetate ion and precipitates out","polymerized","monomerized","changed to bromine gas and absorbed in the gelatin"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The purpose of phenidone and hydroquinone in developer solutions is as","options":["buffers","reducers","activators","hardeners"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Modern developer solutions containing phenidone/hydroquinone are sometimes called","options":["MQ developers","PQ developers","PH developers","buffer developers"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The purpose of a restrainer in the developer solution, normally potassium bromide, is to","options":["prevent reduction of unexposed crystals","act as an anti-fogging agent","act as a preservative of the chemistry","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The purpose of adding starter solution to a new batch of developer is to","options":["partially deactivate the developer to control fogging","lower pH level of the solution","increase development rate","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The purpose of the short stop acid bath after manual development is","options":["lower pH to stop development action","prevents discolouration and calcium staining","preserves fixer pH","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"A significant component of a fixer solution is acetic acid, its purpose is to","options":["dissolve unexposed and undeveloped silver bromide crystals","neutralize the developer","harden the emulsion","act as a preservative"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"For prolonged (more than 5 years) storage of film without deterioration, hypo-retention or residual thiosulphate in the film must not exceed ________ �g/cm_","options":["500","100","5","0.1"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"A wetting agent is added to an extra tank after final rinse in manual processing to","options":["stabilize hardener","eliminate dichroic stain","eliminate brown stain","eliminate water droplets"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"A radiograph appears to have insufficient density and insufficient contrast.  This may be due to","options":["exhausted developer","radiation too soft","radiation too hard","film to object distance too large"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Excessive contrast on a radiograph can be attributed to","options":["radiation being too soft","radiation being too hard","SFD being too short","exhausted developer"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Lack of sharpness of radiographic image can be attributed to","options":["too short SFD","object moved during exposure","film to object distance too large","any of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"If a film is not agitated in the developer so air bubbles cling to the film surface the result will be","options":["clear patches","dark patches","white deposits","dark crescent shapes"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Insufficient washing after development can result in the release of carbon dioxide gas from the reaction of the akaline developer with the acidic fixer.  This will result in _____ on the radiograph.","options":["dark patches","blisters","clear crescent shapes","mottled fogging"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"If the water used to make up the developer, the fixer or the water for the final rinse is too hard the result will be","options":["grey fogging","yellow fogging","dichroic fogging","white streaks"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The leathery texture of a radiograph called reticulation is a result of","options":["old film","contaminated fixer","contaminated developer","extreme temperature differences between successive baths"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Safelight testing is performed to ensure safelight intensity is not excessive.  It is accomplished by","options":["test facilities at the manufacturer's","using a light meter","processing a film exposed to increasing time under the safelight","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"X-ray film is most sensitive to light in the _____ region.","options":["UV","blue","yellow-green","red"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"In film radiography, the \"gamma\" of a characteristic curve is","options":["the radiation used for the exposure","the slope of the straight portion of the curve","the antilog of the density","another name for the log of the relative exposure"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Manual processing in hot climates may cause chemical temperatures to rise in excess of 30�C.  Under these conditions it is recommended to","options":["add ice to the developer","add ice to all baths","add restrainer (sodium bicarbonate) to the developer","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Farmer's reducer is a solution of potassium ferricyanide and sodium thiosulphate, it is a(n) __________ reducer, acting equally on all silver in the treated film.","options":["additive","subtractive","proportional","logarithmic"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Gluteraldehyde is a hardener used in automatic film processor developer.  Its purpose is to","options":["activate the bromine gas","restrain phenidone action on the silver","retard swelling and softening of emulsion","replace the stop bath used in manual processing"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"In electrolytic recovery of silver from fixer solution, metallic silver plates out as \"flake\"","options":["on the cathode","on the anode","at the bottom of the tank","and floats to the surface"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Variable 