oded radiographs","cancer treatment","avalanche radiography"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The reason two or three \"film-screen\" packages would be stacked in a single cassette for a flash radiograph is to","options":["incorporate a filter-effect","magnify the image on the film farthest from the object","utilize \"light amplification\" from the stacked screens","image thick and/or dense objects"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Attenuation of a neutron beam depends on the specimen's","options":["neutron cross-section","atomic number","atomic weight","effective atomic radius or radius of the outer most electron from the centre of the nucleus"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The only practical source of neutrons from spontaneous fission used for neutron radiography is","options":["tritium-3 (H-3)","carbon-14 (C-14)","cobalt-60 (Co-60)","californium-252 (Cf-252)"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The transfer method of neutron radiography utilizes the principles of","options":["film backlash","autoradiograhpy","xeroradiography","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"X-radiography and neutron radiography can be considered","options":["equivalent NDT methods","competitive NDT methods","complimentary NDT methods","unsafe NDT methods"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The advantage of the d,T accelerator system of neutron generation as a radiographic source compared to Cf-252 is","options":["portability","safety, it can be shut off","high yield","abundance of thermal neutrons"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Fiber bundle scintillators are used for ________ in real-time radiography.","options":["fluorescent screens","filtering out soft radiation","frame triggers","warning personnel of scattered radiation"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Direct viewing of fluoroscopic screen images is usually done with the eyes adapted for","options":["myopic vision","scotopic vision","photopic vision","hyper myopic vision"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The relative biological effectiveness given as a quantity in the SI system is termed","options":["RBE","quality factor (QF)","MPD","sievert"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The R�ntgen was the unit of x-ray exposure.  The name of this unit in the SI system is","options":["gray","becquerel","alara","none of the above, there is no direct equivalent"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Given a subject has absorbed 10J/kg of ionizing radiation energy from a Co60 source its equivalent dose is","options":["100 rem","100 gray","100 sieverts","10 sieverts"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Radiation intensity has traditionally been given in R�ntgens/second   (R/s).  No SI name exists for the quantity but 1 R/s= 2.58x10^-4","options":["C/kg-s","A/kg","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"If a bio-mass of 2kg has 10Gy of x-radiation energy deposited in it, the equivalent dose will be","options":["20kGy","20Sv","10Sv","5Sv"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"If the QF for alpha particles is 20 and a biomass of 100kg received 100 Joules of deposited energy from alpha radiation, its whole body dose would be","options":["2000Sv","200Sv","20Sv","2.0Sv"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Quantity factor has units of","options":["C/kg","J/kg","Sv","none of the above, it is unitless"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The maximum amount of radiation dose accepted as having no biological effect is","options":["0Sv","1�Sv","2.5�Sv","2.5 mSv"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Most countries follow ICRP recommendations for annual maximum permissible dose (quarterly limits are likely to vary from country to country).  ICRP recommends atomic radiation workers whole body dose not exceed ________________ per year.","options":["5 mSv","50 mSv","5 mRem","50 Rem"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Occupational exposure to ionizing radiation for female atomic radiation workers is reduced","options":["at all times","during working hours only","during child-bearing years","during pregnancy"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"If radiation is of a mixed origin (eg. photon and particulate),  correction or differentiation of the contributing components of the beam can be determined using","options":["an integrating meter","two meters of differing sensitivities","a beta-meter","a diffi-que"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"If you are allowed 100�Sv exposure in one week and when working at your post in the exposure facility and the dose rate is 5�Sv per hour; what is the amount of time you can be working during exposures?","options":["40 hours","20 hours","10 hours","5 hours"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The advantage of using parafin as a neutron absorber shield is off set by","options":["cost of material","the fire hazard it presents","the secondary radiation it generates","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Depending on the specimen and what is to be discerned about it, autoradiographic exposures may be as long as","options":["30 minutes","6 hours","24 hours","several days"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"A significant problem in producing a good autoradiographic image of a highly radioactive specimen is","options":["edge effects","maintaining contact","motion blur as specimen and film are brought together","shaping the lead screens to fit the part"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"About 75% of the damage to cell DNA by x-rays is due to","options":["the direct effect","the OH radical","overheating","mitosis"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Electrons knocked out of atoms in an absorbing material by a heavy ion are called","options":["radicals","pi-mesons","delta rays","free spirits"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"A large amount of energy is deposited in a absorbing material at some depth after entering the absorber.  This is unique to the heavier particles and pi-mesons, on a graph of relative dose vs. depth this peak of energy is called","options":["Emax","Bragg peak","absorption peak","absorption edge"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"When all sources of possible radiation exposure are examined over the total world population, accumulated dose from natural sources accounts for about _______ of our total dose. (This averages both ARW's and non-ARW's)","options":["10%","20%","50%","80%"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"A tissue that is more likely to be affected by radiation than another tissue (eg. gastro-intestinal tract tissue as compared to muscle) is considered","options":["tumorous","radiosensitive","carcinogenic","chronically mutant"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The most radiosensitive tissues in the mammalian body are the","options":["brain cells","muscle cells","most rapidly reproducing cells","liver cells"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Contrary to research data, radiation protection standards are based on the assumption that","options":["the effects of a given amount of radiation is the same regardless of the time period in which it is received","information on radiation induced cancer can be lineally extrapolated from high to low doses","skin sparing effects of gamma radiation allow it to be given far greater doses than whole body","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"What amount of acute dose is likely to kill 50% of the people exposed within about 1 year of the exposure?","options":["20-50mSv","200-500mSv","2-5 Sv","20 -50 Sv"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Which of the following is not a recommended treatment for a person who has received an acute dose of gamma radiation?","options":["plenty of bed rest","drink lots of fluids","blood transfusions","strict environmental sterility"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"When a defective child is born to a woman the abnormality can be attributed to radiation exposure if manifest as a","options":["cleft palate","abnormal brain","stunted limb","none of the above, radiation does not produce a special kind of defect"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The International Commission on Radiological Protection (ICRP) treats somatic effects of radiation as either _______ or _____.","options":["safe, unsafe","stochastic, non-stochastic","good, bad","lethal, sub-lethal"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Somatic effects of radiation for which severity of effect varies with dose, and for which a threshold may therefore occur are called","options":["sub-lethal","cytotoxic","non-stochastic","fractionated"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Somatic effects of radiation for which the probability of an effect occurring, rather than its severity, is regarded as a function of dose, without threshold, are called","options":["cytotoxic","necrotic","hypoxic","stochastic"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"LET is an abbreviation for","options":["liver effective tolerance","linear energy transfer","length of electron travel","legal exposure time"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"If the range of a 1MeV electron in water is about 4mm, what is its average LET while slowing to rest?","options":["1.0MeV/�m","1.0keV/�m","0.25keV/�m","0.1keV/�m"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The formal standard radiation for determining quality factor (relative biological effectiveness) is","options":["50kV x-rays","250kV x-rays","cobalt-60","none of the above, all x and gamma rays have the same QF"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Molecules with unpaired electrons are called","options":["molecular ions","free radicals","alpha particles","mono-polar"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The products of irradiation in dilute aqueous solutions are a result of","options":["reaction of aqueous free radicals with the solute","direct disruption of the solute","reaction with hydrogen ions form by irradiation","reaction with oxygen formed by irradiation"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Graphing the logarithm of the fraction of cells unaffected by an irradiated dose against the amount of dose applied is called a","options":["Lindguivst curve","cell survival curve","kill chart","Rhesus plot"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"For exponential cell survival as plotted on a cell survival curve, the dose required to reduce a surviving fraction to 37% (in the \"straight-line\" portion of the curve) is the","options":["exponential  survival value","mean lethal dose","quasi-threshold dose","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The symbol Do in cell survival curves used in radiation biology represents the","options":["extrapolation number","quasi-threshold dose","mean lethal dose","dose required to kill 50% of the population"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The ratio of mean lethal dose for anoxic cells to the mean lethal dose for well oxygenated cells is called the","options":["oxygen enhancement ratio (OER)","partial pressure due to oxygen","therapeutic ratio","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Given, for particular cell type, the mean lethal dose for anoxic cells is 240 rads for 250 kV x-rays and 60 rads for thermal neutrons, and for well oxygenated cells the mean lethal doses are 120 rads for x-ray and 50 rads for thermal neutrons.  What is the oxygen enhancement ratio for the thermal neutrons?","options":["1.2","2","2.4","4"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"When more energy is deposited in a cell by ionizing radiation than is needed to kill the cell the effect is","options":["the overkill effect","wrap around","RBE saturation","quality factor reversal"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The two helical sugar phosphate strands of a DNA molecule are held together by","options":["polyester bonds","hydrogen bonded base pairs","enzymes","cytosine"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Central nervous system (CNS) syndrome is a form of radiation induced depth resulting from the breakdown of the neurological and cardiovascular systems.  This is associated with exposures of","options":["50-200 rad","200-500 rad","500 - 2000 rad","over 2000 rad"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"If anything is capable of producing cancer (and just about everything is) it is said to be","options":["contegeous","clonogenic","cargcinogenic","lethal"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The sections of DNA coding for specific characteristics that are inherited are the","options":["chromosomes","genes","hydrogen bonded bases","primidines"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Ionizing radiation refers to","options":["electromagnetic radiation","corpuscular radiation","radiation from the useful beam only","any EM or corpuscular radiation that is capable of producing ions"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"X-radiation that is emitted from an x-ray tube that does not make up the useful beam is","options":["wasted","scatter radiation","secondary radiation","leakage radiation"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Which of the following is not an observed symptom of an acute exposure to radiation?","options":["erythema","epilation","blood changes","delirium tremens"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"A radiation induced alteration in the DNA of a cell that does not kill the cell but alters characteristics of the off-spring of that cell is","options":["mutation","sterilization","clonogenesis","metamorphosis"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Grenz rays, typically used in x-ray diffraction work, have energies in the range of","options":["1-2MeV","500-1000 keV","50-100 keV","5-20 keV"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Heat dissipation characteristics of x-ray tubes are expressed in relation to the product of kV potential and mAs.  These products are called","options":["watts","calories","heat units","ergs"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The total number of heat units produced by a 250 KVp x-ray unit operating at 10mAs for 10 seconds is","options":["250 H.U.","25000 H.U.","62500 H.U.","not possible to determine from the information given"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Treatment required for high local skin doses of beta radiation is","options":["similar to thermal burns","bed rest and blood transfusions","not required","hopeless"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The so-called \"10 day rule\" applies to","options":["radiographers","non-radiation workers","trainees in any radiographic facility","women of child-bearing age"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The limits for stochastic effects of radiation, as recommended by the ICRP, are _______ those for non-stochastic effects.","options":["higher than","lower than","more realistic than","not different from"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"In dual focal spot machines the standard spot is 1.5mm, the other is 0.5mm.  The smaller spot is referred to the","options":["mini-spot","1/3 spot","fractional spot","son spot"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Changing from ASTM type 1 film to ASTM type 2 film increases","options":["exposure time","quality of image","sensitivity","production rate"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Changing from a slower fine grained film to a faster film allows you to","options":["reduce production costs","use lower kVp","increase latitude","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"In x-radiography, a faster film can produce a finer grained image than a slower film if","options":["target to film distance is increased","lower kVp is used","higher tube current is used","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"To be considered a microfocus x-ray tube the tube must have a(n)","options":["anode to cathode distance of less than 2cm","a target to film distance of less than 2 cm","a focal spot of less than 0.1mm","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Magnification in projection radiographic techniques is based on","options":["source to film distance","source to object distance","object to film distance","the ratio of SFD to object to film distance"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"In real-time projection microfocus radiography, dynamically positioning the object between the source and detector (changing source to object distance) is known as","options":["projecting","zooming","time lapse","strobe"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"A major drawback to projection microfocus radiography being accepted as general practise in industry is","options":["lack of contrast sensitivity","insufficient resolution","inaccuracy in sizing defects","the inability to display IQI's on the limited field of view"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Digital radiographic techniques can be applied to","options":["2 dimensional real-time radiography","non-film methods using imaging plates","3 dimensional (volume) representation of images","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The slope of the standard decay curve whereby activity is plotted against time gives an isotope's","options":["half live","specific activity","decay constant","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"In most radiography of steel under 50mm thick the largest portion of time spent in producing the finished product (radiograph) is in","options":["setting-up","exposure","development","all of the above equally"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Inspite of the fact that maximum detectability of nonfusion defects might occur if the x-ray beam is not parallel to the fusion wall, butt welds are usually radiographed such that","options":["the beam is parallel to the film","the film is at right angles to the weld","the beam is at right angles to the weld","the beam is at right angles to the film and 45� to the weld"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Prior to evaluating a component from a radiograph of the part, the radiograph is evaluated for quality based on","options":["latitude","density","sensitivity","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The thickness of smallest element (either wire or drilled hole) whose image can be seen on a radiograph, divided by the specimen thickness, all multiplied by 100 gives","options":["thickness sensitivity","IQI sensitivity","film sensitivity","a radiographer's IQ"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The totality of features and characteristics of a product that bear on its ability to satisfy a given need is termed the ________ of the product.","options":["durability","toughness","quality","cost element"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"A system of activities that provides evidence that the overall quality control job in being done effectively is","options":["quality control","quality assurance","quality engineering","non-destructive testing"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The system used for programming and co-ordinating the efforts of various groups in an organization to maintain or improve quality at an economical level is","options":["quality control","quality assurance","quality engineering","non-destructive testing"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Application of technological and scientific skills and specialised management techniques to achieve the required quality at an acceptable cost is the function of","options":["quality control","quality assurance","quality engineering","the NDT department"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Test results are nominally expected to be similar in large batches of items.  This information is often plotted and statistical information is obtained from the plots.  If n=number of valves, X=a test value, d=deviation of the difference of the individual value from the arithmetic mean, �=standard deviation. The equation ________ defines the coefficient of variation.","options":["[X1+X2+X3 ... Xn/n]","[�/X] (100)","[(d1_+d2_+d3_ ... dn_)/(n-1)]^_","(x-d)/�"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Large samples of test results, when plotted, usually result in Gaussian distribution curves.  If the mean value plotted is X and the value of the peak frequency is Xp and the standard deviation �, the skew factor is given by (X-Xp)/�.  If skew is biased towards low values the skew factor is","options":["0","less than 1","greater than 1","negative"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"A measurement of spherical porosity from a good quality radiograph gives the following results.  7 pores @ 2mm diameter, 17 pores @ 1.5mm diameter, 22 pores @ 1.1mm diameter, 34 pores @ 0.7mm diameter, and 20 pores @ 0.5mm diameter.  What is the mean diameter of these pores?","options":["0.79","0.86","0.98","1.1"],"correct":2},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"10 valves of thickness are derived using the beta backscatter technique, 9.8 �m, 9.9�m, 10.0�m, 10.1�m, 10.1�m, 10.2�m, 10.2�m, 10.4�m, 10.4�m, 10.6�m.  What is the standard deviation of thickness?","options":["10.17","10","9.91","0.245"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Which of the following could cause non-repeatability of film contrast when producing a radiograph of the same part?","options":["line voltage","line current","screen thickness","all of the above are variables"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"When it comes to repeatability of radiographic contrast, the most likely source of unintended variation is in","options":["source","source to film distance","manufacturers film quality control","extent of development"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Tungsten and tantalum screens (front and back of film) are used","options":["with high energy x-rays (15 to 30 MeV)","to reduce exposure time over that with lead screens","for nuclear grade castings only","never"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Iron or copper screens can be used in place of lead screens for","options":["thin wall tubing","cobalt 60 radiation","x-radiation below 100 kV","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"North American plaque type IQI's are (for most thicknesses) 1 1/2 inches long, occasionally they are required to be 2\" long to allow for the placement of lead letters.  These letters are used to indicate the","options":["main chemical composition of the IQI","main chemical composition of the object radiographed","level of acceptance criteria","class of film being used"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Ultimately, nondestructive testing has as its goal","options":["reduction of inspection costs","minimizing future costs","elimination of the need for inspection","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The document stating the details of the requirements associated with a particular NDT method is the","options":["code","standard","recommended practice","specification"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"A collection of standards, usually applying to a common product line, is the basis of a","options":["specification","code","reference standard","quality level"],"correct":1}]$NDTA_SEED$