from jsonb_to_recordset($NDTA_SEED$[{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"A test specification for a particular NDT method to be applied to a product as specified by a buyer is often drawn from a","options":["published standard","code","reputable NDT company","manufacturer of the product"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The study and description of a material property related to its resistance to fail under applied stress is","options":["fracture mechanics","nondestructive evaluation","tribology","finite element analysis"],"correct":0},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Kodak industrial radiographic film usually uses the exposure of AA film to rate the speeds of the film types.  If its relative speed is 1 to achieve a density of 2.0 what speed would Kodak R be rated at for a density of 2.0?","options":["2","4","7","10"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Kodak R film is rated at a relative speed of 7 for a density of 1.5.  AGFA-Gevaert D-2 is rated at 5.5 for a density of 1.5.  At what density is the D-2 film slower than the Kodak R?","options":["2.5","3","3.5","none"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"The quality level at which an inspector must discriminate between two classes of quality is the","options":["standard","inspection threshold","reject level","class distinction"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Leak testing of an Ir-192 exposure camera is used to detect","options":["Ir-192 contaminants","depleted uranium contaminants","radon daughters","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Thinner low density carbon fibres used in modern aircraft require low kV x-ray  potentials be used.  The problem with operating a 100 kV unit at the 15 kV required for the contrast required is","options":["excessive over heating reduces duty cycle","emission current is limited thereby requiring long exposure times","over-abundance of mono-chromatic radiation from characteristic spectra","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"RT","level":3,"question":"Radiographic resolution stated in line pairs per millimetre expresses a systems ability to","options":["detect individual flaws","resolve 2 closely spaced flaws in the lateral direction","establish thickness variations","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The advantage of using reversing D.C. for demagnetization is","options":["low heating effect","deep penetration","only one reversal is needed","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The magnetic flux in a part increases as applied field is increased.  The flux moves along the virgin curve of the hysteresis curve","options":["once each cycle of applied A.C. field","twice each cycle of applied A.C. field","only once when the part is completely demagnetized","for paramagnetic materials only"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"For demagnetizing large parts, field reversals are usually _________.","options":["lower frequency than for small parts","higher frequency than for small parts","the same frequency as for small parts","not needed"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"For best demagnetization results using a coil with A.C. and passing parts through it you should","options":["pass the part through with its long axis parallel to the coil axis","hold the part close to the coil","both a and b","switch the current on only when the part is centred along its length in the coil"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Small parts can be demagnetized in multiple lots by passing them through an A.C. coil provided they are","options":["stacked in a basket","apart in single layer","oriented long axis parallel to coil axis","both b and c"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"For rings and hollow parts a handy means of A.C. demagnetization is","options":["using a yoke","a central conductor using decreasing current","surge pulses through prod contacts","swinging field technique"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The most likely tool you would use to determine if a part has been adequately demagnetized is the","options":["Hall detector","field meter","electrogram","magnetometer"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"A problem with doing a head shot on a ball bearing is","options":["arc burns damage the surface","no defects are found","the field is distorted too much","they cannot be demagnetized"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The two classifications of media in MPI are","options":["fluorescent and non-fluorescent","wet and dry","magnetic and para-magnetic","high temperature and low temperature"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Prior to the use of magnetic particles to detect flaws by magnetic methods, flaws could be located in iron pieces using","options":["Hall detectors","ordinary magnetic compasses","electro scopes","electromagnetic resonance"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The ampere is a unit of","options":["electric current","electromotive force","electromagnetic force","magnetic intensity"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Total current in two parallel conductors can be determined by knowing the distance between the conductors and the","options":["dielectric constant of air","resistivity of the conductors","right hand rule","magnetic force exerted per unit length of wire"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The direction assigned to a magnetic dipole moment vector is determined by","options":["coil size","conductor diameter","current magnitude","direction of current flow"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The units Webers per square metre (Wb/m^2) are used to quantify a","options":["magnetic induction field","magnetic dipole","magnetic monopole","magnetic force"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Magnetic field lines are","options":["always concentric rings","symbolic only, and used to indicate spatial direction of the field","a result of the van Allan belts","of uniform density"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"A void in an otherwise homogenous magnetized material presents itself as a point magnetic dipole.  This is the basis for","options":["magnetic particle flaw detection","multi frequency eddy current","para-magnetism","de-magnetisation"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Magnetic properties of materials are a result of","options":["electric currents on the atomic and sub-atomic scale","the strong nuclear force","the ratio of protons to neutrons in the material","the weak nuclear force"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In a ferromagnetic material, a region where all the \"atomic moments\" are aligned parallel to each other is called a","options":["magnetic zone","confederation","domain","magnetic junta"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When discussing magnetization and its effects the magnetic induction field is usually represented by the letter","options":["B","H","M","Z"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When discussing magnetization and its effects the magnetic field intensity, or as its also called, the magnetic field is represented by the letter","options":["B","H","M","Z"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The phenomenon whereby the magnetization of a ferromagnetic sample lags the applied cyclic magnetic field is referred to as","options":["phase lag","Doppler effect","hysteresis","demagnetization"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When a hysteresis curve is generated for a ferromagnetic material, a magnetic field remains in the material when the applied field is returned to zero.  This field is called the","options":["coercive force","induction field","residual induction","resultant vector"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The value of H applied to bring the residual value of B to zero is called","options":["saturation field","demagnetization value","induction coercive force","phase reversal factor"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In order to be detectable by magnetic particle testing, a flaw must","options":["be surface breaking","be no deeper than 1mm below the surface","produce a perturbation of the induction field at the test surface","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"To detect a flaw by magnetic particle methods, techniques are developed to","options":["maximize field perturbations in the region of a flaw","optimize retentivity of the material","propagate the flaw by Barkhausen jumps","all of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Sensitivity of the magnetic particle method depends on the","options":["absolute magnitude of the induced field perturbation","spatial gradient of the induced field perturbation","magnitude of the applied field","surface flux density of the test piece"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Magnetic particle testing has an advantage over liquid penetrant testing because it can","options":["be used on ferromagnetic materials","locate surface defects","locate subsurface defects","be cheaper to use"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Magnetic particle testing is a practical test method to inspect.","options":["glass","ceramics","aluminum castings","none of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which is not an essential step in magnetic particle testing?","options":["establish a suitable magnetic flux in the test piece","application of magnetic particles","examination of test piece","post cleaning of test piece to remove magnetic particles"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Inherent discontinuities are formed during","options":["initial melting and refining of the metal","primary processing","secondary processing and manufacturing","in-service use"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When a discontinuity causes the magnetic field lines to be forced out of the specimen into the air, the field in the air is called a","options":["force field","leakage field","flux field","flaw field"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Magnetic particles are available in many colours to","options":["indicate degree of permeability","optimize visibility","indicate degree of rententivity","permit the inspector to choose a colour that will not clash with his/her clothing"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The deeper a subsurface defect gets below the surface","options":["the greater the flux leakage it produces","the harder it gets to magnetize the part","the larger it must be to be detectable","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In order to detect a flaw by magnetic particle testing the magnetic field must","options":["alternate","pulse","run parallel to the principal plane of the flaw","intercept the principal plane of the flaw"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The cgs unit of magnetizing force (H) is the","options":["oersted","gauss","tesla","Weber"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The cgs unit of flux density (B) is the","options":["oersted","gauss","tesla","Weber"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"If the ends of a long bar magnet are bent to form a circle and the ends perfectly fused together the result will be","options":["the magnet will no longer attract ferromagnetic material","a circular magnetic field","no magnetic flux leakage field","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"A bar magnet would be considered to be","options":["circularly magnetized","longitudinally magnetized","electromagnetically poled","cross-polarized"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which of the following is not a characteristic of magnetic flux lines?","options":["they attract each other","they form continuous loops","they do not cross each other","they decrease in intensity with distance from the surface"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Inside a bar magnet magnetic flux lines are considered to flow from","options":["north to south","south to north","east to west","west to east"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The direction of magnetic lines of force around a current carrying conductor is","options":["parallel to the conductor","at right angles to the conductor","45 degrees out of phase to the applied current","parallel or perpendicular to the conductor depending on which current flow convention is used"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"If a nail is brought to a bar magnet it is held by the magnet.  If another nail is now brought to touch the first nail it is held to the first nail.  Subsequent nails can be held in a long chain.  This is a result of","options":["induced magnetism","nail bonding","domain transfer","natural attraction of nail points to nail heads"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The end of the compass needle that points towards the northern region of the earth is called","options":["the north seeking pole","the magnetic north pole","the magnetic south pole","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The magnetic north pole is located","options":["at 90� north latitude","somewhere in northern Canada","at the north geographic pole","at Greenwich England"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"A single line of force represents the unit of magnetic flux in a field.  This is called a(n)","options":["oersted","gauss","weber","maxwell"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"A magnet can lose its magnetism by","options":["heating","hammering","both a and b","no known means"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Removal of magnetism from a part is termed","options":["domain scattering","demagnetization","stress relieving","the Hall effect"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"A permanent magnet configured such that both north and south poles are adjacent is usually termed a","options":["longitudinal magnet","circular magnet","parallel magnet","horseshoe magnet"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The \"image\" of a magnetic field produced by placing a magnet under a paper and sprinkling iron fillings on the top of the paper is called","options":["magnetic projection","magnetic holography","a magnetograph","flux painting"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Magnetic lines of force are","options":["isolated mono-poles","elongated bi-poles","manifestations of the \"string-theory\"","imaginary concepts for mapping magnetic fields"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Electric current which at regular intervals reverses its direction of flow is called","options":["AC","DC","alternating","both a and c"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In direct current flow electric circuits the unit of current is the","options":["ampere","ohm","mho","volt"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In alternating current electric circuits the unit of current flow is the","options":["ampere","ohm","volt","deci Bell"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Opposition to electric current flow in a D.C. circuit is termed","options":["ohmage","resistance","reactance","reluctance"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The unit of electrical resistance is the","options":["ampere","coulomb","ohm","volt"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The unit of potential difference in an electric circuit is the","options":["ampere","ohm","volt","Coulomb"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"A ferromagnetic material surrounded by a current carrying coil becomes","options":["diamagnetic","magnetized","an electromagnet","both b and c"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The unit of inductance is the","options":["farad","henry","Coulomb","abvolt"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The ability of a material to emit visible light while being irradiated by UV light is called","options":["fluorescence","phosphorescence","iridescence","Birefringence"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The typical duration of a coil shot is","options":["a fraction of a second","1 second","2 seconds","5 seconds"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The clamping contacts on a large stationary magnetic particle testing unit are called","options":["prods","heads","poles","shunts"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When a part is magnetized such that the flux lines run essentially parallel to the long axis of the part it is called","options":["parallel magnetization","circular magnetization","longitudinal magnetization","a long shot"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In magnetic particle testing prods are","options":["hand held electrodes","never used","used for longitudinal magnetization","substitutes for the central conductor"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The relationship relating electric current flow, voltage and resistance in electric circuits is","options":["relativity","Ohm's law","Snell's law","Kirchoff's law"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In electric circuit terminology the usual symbol for current is","options":["A","E","I","C"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In electric circuit terminology, the usual symbol for voltage is","options":["E","I","V","both a) and c) are used"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The common unit of electric power is","options":["amperes","volts","watts","horsepower"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"To determine the direction of magnetic field lines in a conductor (assuming - to + current flow) you can use","options":["the left hand rule","the right hand rule","a Galvanometer","a Wheatstone bridge"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"For a single straight conductor, assuming modern theory current flow, the fingers on the left hand point","options":["in the direction of the magnetic field lines","against the magnetic field lines","in the directions of the electron flow","opposite to the electron flow"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In the left hand rule as applied to a solenoid, the fingers point in the direction of","options":["north","south","current flow","force on the conductor"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In the left hand rule, as it applies to a solenoid, the thumb point in the direction of","options":["north","south","current flow","force on the conductor"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The relative amount of flux linkage between two coils (as in a transformer) is called","options":["mutual inductance","figure of merit","coupling coefficient","flux factor"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In order to operate as a transformer, two coils must be linked by a(n)","options":["iron core","air core","alternating magnetic field","copper wire"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The difference between a yoke and prods in magnetic particle testing is","options":["a yoke produces a circular field and prods a longitudinal","a yoke produces a longitudinal field and prods a circular","a yoke produces a longitudinal field and prods a parallel","none, the both produce circular fields"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"As one increases the size of the MPI test system from small yokes and portable units to large bench units the single most significant difference is","options":["length of piece that can be tested","the ability to use liquid suspensions in the big units","the amount of magnetizing current available","type of magnetic field that can be generated"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When single phase AC is halfwave rectified it is sometimes called half wave direct current.  The reference to direct current is because","options":["Lenz's law applies","current amplitude does not change","current flow direction does not change","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"A part that has been magnetized by ________ requires demagnetization.","options":["mechanical means","magnetic particle testing","a magnetic chuck","none of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Demagnetization of a part is usually required when the part is","options":["used near magnetically affected instruments","part of a moving assembly","to be finish machined","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The Curie point is","options":["320�C.","1650�F.","varies with the position on the earth relative to the north magnetic pole","varies for each ferromagnetic alloy"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The number of reversals normally required to properly demagnetize a part using electromagnetic means is","options":["1","5-Feb","30-Oct","50-100"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Demagnetization can be accomplished using","options":["A.C.","D.C.","a yoke","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"What shape is used for the particles used in magnetic particle testing?","options":["acicular (elongated)","spherical and flake","irregular","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which is a type of particle available for magnetic particle testing?","options":["wet visible particles","dry fluorescent particles","dry visible particles","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"What is the result if magnetic particles are made of a material of high coercive force?","options":["decreased mobility","high background","masking of defects","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Large sized particles are not used in wet magnetic particle testing because","options":["they drop from suspension too quickly","they form misleading indications called drainage lines","circulation pumps cannot move them off the tank bottom","both a  and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The purpose of large particles in the dry powder mix is to","options":["detect large defects","reduced background by \"sweeping\"","locate subsurface defects","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The reason agglomerations of fine magnetic particles tend to move through the liquid they are suspended in is","options":["increased mass","increased field strength","both a and b","the fluid dynamic shape that is taken on"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Maximum particle mobility is had for dry magnetic particles with _______ shape.","options":["spherical","elongated","flake","irregular"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The reason for adding a portion of spherical shaped magnetic particles to a batch of elongated shaped dry powder magnetic particles is to","options":["increase density","increase mobility","increase sensitivity","increase contrast"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The bulk magnetic indicator is not used for measuring","options":["uniform magnetic induction fields in air","uniform magnetic field strength in air","the existence of a magnetic field external to a part","leakage fields from discontinuities"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Daylight fluorescent dry magnetic particles","options":["require a standard blacklight for viewing","require a special filter on the blacklight","fluoresce brightly in visible light","have no place in NDT"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In MPI testing using dry powder, mechanical blowers can be used for","options":["particle application","removal of background particles","pre cleaning of gritty surfaces","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Dry magnetic particle powders must be handled with care because","options":["the ferrous powders and pigments are considered nuisance dusts","exposure to skin can cause acute melanoma","inhalation can result in silicosis","both b and c"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"For sensitive wet method magnetic particle testing, coloured particles are  typically 5 to 15 �m diameter.  Unpigmented ferromagnetic oxides for the same sensitivity would be","options":["0.5�m to 1.5�m","50 �m to 150�m","0.5mm to 1.5mm","useless"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In general, likelihood of flaw detection by MPI is statistical and increases with","options":["flaw size","age of inspector","current used","amount of power (or ink) used"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which is not a factor that will affect the level of magnetic flux leakage from a flaw?","options":["defect size","defect shape","part thickness","applied field strength"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"What is the purpose of limiting the flux density generated in a piece being MPI tested?","options":["reduce the occurrence of false reporting of flaws","prevent arcing","ensure saturation is not achieved","provide more particle mobility"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"For precise delineation of the contour and extent of a magnetic particle indication is required the best way to record it is","options":["photography","tape transfer or lacquer","etching","hand sketches"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Flow lines found by MPI in a steel forging are","options":["always rejectable","non-relevant indications","seen only with the aid of a microscope","evidence for magnetic domains"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When photography of fluorescent indications is performed ____________ are used to prevent overexposure of film.","options":["F-stops","fish-eye lenses","special filters","black and white film"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"For photography of MPI indications the use of a tripod is recommended.  Why?","options":["the camera with all the attachments is too heavy","exposures are long and camera movement would ruin the shot","to facilitate a mount for the light meter","none of the above-tripods are never used"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Photographs of fluorescent indications require which type of film?","options":["instant black and white","regular black and white","regular colour","any of the above, generally no special film is needed"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In photography of NDT indications filters are often incorporated as part of the lens optics, why?","options":["to remove unwanted light","to balance colour of light used","both a and b","none of the above, filters are forbidden"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The slope of the virgin magnetization curve at the origin of a hysteresis plot is called the","options":["original magnetization","flux density","permitivity","initial permeability"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"When a ferromagnetic material is placed in an inducting field H, and H is increased until the incremental permeability is simply the free space permeability this point is called the","options":["magnetic saturation","inflection point","reversal point","Barkhausen limit"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The small jumps in magnetism as a ferromagnetic material is exposed to an increasing induction field are termed","options":["incremental permeability","Delta M's","magnetic scatter","Barkhausen jumps"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"A closed magnetic path through one or more materials is considered a magnetic circuit.  As such, it can be considered analogous to an electric circuit, the magnetic equivalent to voltage is","options":["reluctance","magnetostriction","magnetomotance","magneto-voltage"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The difference in colour between an MPI indication and the background colour of the part tested is critical in evaluation of a part.  The colour difference is referred to as","options":["contrast","lumens","luminosity","indication intensity"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Dry magnetic particles should be applied so they have a minimum velocity when they reach the test part.  The reason being","options":["to avoid a peening effect on the part","to ensure they can be caught by leakage fields","so pigments are not knocked off","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The choice of colour of dry magnetic particle to use depends on","options":["colour of part being tested","ambient light at the test location","type of defect required to be found","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"What is the name of the technique whereby a part is magnetized first and the particles applied after the magnetizing force is removed?","options":["residual method","leakage field method","time lapse MPI","delay technique"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"What is the name of the MPI technique whereby the magnetic particles are applied to a part only during the time the magnetizing force is applied?","options":["the inertial technique","the continuous method","the synchronized method","the time-metered method"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The localized overheating of a part being magnetic particle tested, arising from high resistance or sparking at the electrical contact point is","options":["burning (or arcing)","coagulation","feedback","background noise"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The general appearance of the test surface on which indications are to be viewed is termed","options":["purple haze","backdrop","background","carrier"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The purpose of contact pads placed on the electrodes used in MPI is","options":["ornamental","to redirect flux patterns","top secret","to improve electrical contact"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The buildup of magnetic particles due to excessive magnetization of the part under test is called","options":["furring","fall-out","magnetic hair","magnetic writing"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"A \"split-coil\" attachment for MPI use is used for","options":["varying the number of turns in a coil","varying the magnetizing current strength in the part","positioning over a part with no free ends for normal coil access","both a and b"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"A five turn coil on a bench unit is 30cm diameter.  If 2000amps are passed through it will result in","options":["10,000 ampere turns","12,000 ampere turns","60,000 ampere turns","unknown"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The process whereby the magnitude and significance of an indication is determined is termed","options":["examination","interpretation","evaluation","rejection"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"A \"keeper\" is used on a permanent magnet to complete the magnetic circuit.  The purpose of this is to","options":["prevent loss of magnetism","provide an intensification of flux","provide longitudinal magnetization","provide circular magnetization"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Parallel magnetization is","options":["not possible","not a recommended practice for MPI testing","the same as longitudinal magnetization","a substitute for overall magnetization"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The non-relevant indication resulting when the surface of a magnetized part comes in contact with another piece of ferromagnetic material is","options":["bearding","furring","magnetic writing","break lines"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which of the following materials has the highest relative permeability","options":["iron","vacuum","air","gold"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The two basic decisions made before an MPI test is carried out are","options":["minimum size of defect to find and type of current to use","minimum size of defect to find and type of particle to use","type of current and type of particle to use","which code to use and how fast to perform the test"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"To detect a flaw in a low carbon steel shaft, if you suspect the flaw is about 6mm (1/4\") below the surface which method would you use?","options":["A.C.","half wave rectified A.C.","an A.C. yoke","a pair of permanent magnets"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which is the best material for detecting defects wholly below the surface using MPI tests?","options":["dry powder","wet fluorescent","wet visible","all are about equal for the same current"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Low carbon steels must have the continuous method of MPI testing used on them due to","options":["the skin effect","the Hall effect","low retentivity","carborization occurring from the residual method"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The magnetizing current in the continuous wet method, when the bath is applied by flooding from a nozzle, is usually applied","options":["during the whole time it takes to wet the part","immediately after flooding is stopped","after the bath stops dripping from the part","both before and after bath application"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The normal duration required for a magnetizing \"shot\" in the continuous wet method is about","options":["1/4 to 1/2 second","1/2 to 1 second","1 to 2 seconds","2 to 5 seconds"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Prods or clamps are used to produce which type of magnetization?","options":["longitudinal","circular","parallel","swinging field"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When a central conductor is used inside a tube the type of magnetization employed for the testing of that tube is","options":["longitudinal","circular","parallel","swinging field"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Generally an electromagnetic yoke is considered to be used for producing","options":["longitudinal magnetization","circular magnetization","field distortions","either a or b depending on if it is an A.C. or D.C. yoke"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Field strengths of the magnetic field produced by a solenoid (or coil) can be changed by","options":["changing the number of coil loops","changing the current in the coil","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"For the same diameter, length and current used, the difference between using a non-magnetic and a ferro-magnetic central conductor is","options":["magnitude of magnetic field on the outside surface of the conductor","directions of defects detected","both a and b","no difference"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When performing MPI using prods, the current used depends on","options":["prod spacing","part thickness","prod diameter","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The guideline to use 40 amperes of magnetizing current per mm of part diameter applies to","options":["head shots","coil shots","central conductor shots","de-magnetization"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"If using the rule of thumb of 40 amps per mm of part diameter for a head shot, what current is required to magnetize a 20mm diameter copper bar?","options":["400 amp","800 amp","1600 amp","none of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"If 24000 ampere turns are required for coil shot using a 5 turn bench coil, what should your current setting be?","options":["2400 amps","4800 amps","12000 amps","24000 amps"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In what way does surface roughness hinder the MPI test on a part?","options":["hindrance of particle migration","reduction in contrast","distortion of the magnetic field","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"What do the following cleaning methods all have in common?  Shot blasting, sand blasting, wire brushing and scraping","options":["none are used for precleaning a part for MPI","none require  electricity","all are mechanical methods","all are environmentally friendly"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which cleaning method is not likely to be used to remove oil films prior to an MPI test?","options":["vapour degreasing","wire brushing","steam cleaning","ultrasonic cleaning"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The magnetic field produced by a yoke made of permanent magnets is _______ between the poles.","options":["longitudinal","circular","both a and b","constantly varying"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The swinging field MPI technique is used with","options":["sequenced D.C.","combined D.C. and A.C. fields","combined A.C. fields","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The advantage of the swinging field or multidirectional magnetization technique is","options":["cost of equipment","detection of small defects","time saving because it is single step test","both b and c"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When permeability of a material is quoted without an additional qualifying term the permeability referred to is","options":["initial permeability","incremental permeability","maximum permeability","osmotic permeability"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Current for circular magnetization of a part whose maximum permeability is 500 will be ___________ compared to a part with maximum permeability of 4000.","options":["more","less","about the same","it depends if A.C. or D.C. is used"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In MPI a handy rule of thumb relating current flow and suspected flaw orientation is; current flow should be directed _______ major axis.","options":["under suspected defects'","parallel to suspected defects'","perpendicular to suspected defects'","diagonally to suspected defects'"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The strength of a circular magnetic field is not diminished by ________ of a part.","options":["permeability","diameter","length","any of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"A 2cm diameter pipe and a 2cm diameter bar of the same steel alloy are each circularly magnetized by a 1000 amp D.C. head shot.  The strongest magnetic field will occur on the surface of the __________-.","options":["bar","pipe","pipe if its wall is less than 0.5cm","none of the above, fields will be equal"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When a hollow non-magnetic central conductor is used to induce a circular magnetic field in a ferro-magnetic cylinder maximum field strength is at the","options":["central conductor's outside surface","central conductor's inside surface","magnetic material's inside surface","magnetic material's outside surface"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When A.C. is used instead of D.C. for a head shot on a steel tube, the field on the inside surface of the tube is","options":["much less","much more","nearly the same","both are exactly zero"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The best way to determine magnetizing current required for irregularly shaped pieces is","options":["length to diameter ratio equations","40 amps per mm of part thickness","empirically (trial and error)","finite element analysis"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When using the prod method of MPI, defects are normally looked for","options":["between the prods","under the prods","in circles about 4\" (100mm) radius from the prods","in all of the above locations"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In order to maintain the same field strength at the midpoint of prods spaced 8 inches apart as was had with a 6 inch spacing you must","options":["increase the magnetizing current","decrease the magnetizing current","use D.C. instead of A.C.","use larger diameter prod electrodes"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which is not a consideration when choosing current type to use for prod inspection methods of MPI?","options":["particle mobility","safety","power consumption","heating effects on equipment"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Capacitive discharge methods of producing a magnetizing current do so for only a short duration.","options":["typically 1 to 2 seconds","typically 0.5 to 1 seconds","typically 10 to 100ms","typically 5 to 55 �s"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Precracked magnetic steel plates are an effective means of","options":["qualitative analysis of MPI bath concentrations","quantitative analysis of MPI bath concentrations","calibrating ammeters on MPI bench units","sizing unknown MPI indications"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Typical pocket sized magnetic field indicators are used to measure","options":["magnetizing force in a coil","external residual fields","internal residual fields","circular field strength during current flow"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"A low cost rugged tool used to measure residual magnetic field strength of ferromagnetic parts is a","options":["residu-meter","shunt meter","magnetic field indicator","Helmholtz coil"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"A good magnetic field indicator (MFI) should have which characteristic?","options":["rugged supports to prevent damage to the pointer needle","not be easily demagnetized by strong external fields","not induce magnetic poles of the parts they test","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Excessive background in wet fluorescent MPI testing results from","options":["excessive current density","excessive particle density","excessive blacklight intensity","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The standard steel ring 7/8\" thick having a 1 1/4\" diameter central hole and 12 0.007\" diameter holes arranged with increasing depth from the outside edge of the ring is called a(n)","options":["annular ring","Ketos ring","ASME ring","DIN ring"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Probability of seeing a wet fluorescent MPI indication","options":["increases with increasing blacklight intensity","increases with decreasing white light background","increases with decreasing blacklight intensity","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Although settling time prior to measuring wet fluorescent magnetic particle concentration is now increased to 1 hour for most standards, complete settling usually takes","options":["15 minutes","30 minutes","2 hours","24 hours"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When viewing the oil carrier of wet fluorescent particles (ie. the liquid without the particles) under blacklight it usually has a _________ tint.","options":["yellowish","bluish","yellow/green","reddish"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The purpose of adding an antifoaming agent to wet MPI bath is to","options":["reduce suds resulting from agitation","eliminate phosphates for environmental protection","prevent fluorescent material from disbonding from the oxides","all of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Indications from medium to deep surface breaking seams found using A.C. MPI","options":["are not possible to find","usually look alike","require extra large particles","form double indications"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Fastest particle settlement in an MPI bath would occur for","options":["small dense particles in a low viscosity liquid","small dense particles in a high viscosity liquid","larger dense particles in a low viscosity liquid","all of the above would settle about the same rate due to the Bernoulli effect"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"MPI indication width tends to increase for increasing","options":["defect width","defect depth","magnetizing current strength","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Because in general, there exists a direct relationship between indication width and seam (defect) depth, a minimum magnetizing current level can be set to","options":["maintain uniform indication widths","detect significant flaws","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Very fine MPI particles which fall into a crack opening can cause the flux lines to remain in the part, this could result in","options":["over estimating crack depth","over estimating crack length","missing the crack altogether","missing the crack all together if nonfluorescent particles are used"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When lighting requirements are specified for a blacklight viewing of fluorescent MPI, 20 lux white light intensity is","options":["a recommended maximum","a recommended minimum","only a rough estimate","must be strictly met to ensure visibility of indications"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"What method is used to ensure proper magnetization levels are used?","options":["formulae (rules of thumb)","testpieces","gauss/tesla meter","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"An advantage of MPI over LPI (Liquid Penetrant Inspection) is that ___________ using MPI.","options":["ceramics can be tested","ferromagnetic materials can be tested","coated surfaces can be tested","it is always more environmentally friendly"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The difference between magnetic particle testing and magnetic flux leakage testing is","options":["the type of sensor used to detect fields","the type of magnetizing current used","the thickness of part that can be tested","none, they are exactly the same"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The \"standard depth of penetration\" resulting from the skin effect is caused by","options":["hysteresis","alternating current","direct current","Hall detectors"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"To understand magnetic particle indication formation you should consider","options":["discontinuity parameters","magnetic field parameters affecting the external flux leakage","how the magnetic particles react to passing through the leakage fields","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The main purpose of a ferrite core in the coil type flux sensitive devices for magnetic field testing is","options":["reduction of electrical noise","to amplify  the flux density","enhancement of the Hall effect","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In addition to flux density amplification, ferrite cores in coil type flux sensitive devices provide","options":["support for the wire turns","minimizing of detrimental eddy current effect","both a and b","no useful purpose"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The crystals used in Hall detector type flux sensitive devices are","options":["piezoelectric","pyroelectric","magnetostrictive","semiconductors"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The main advantage of the Hall detector as a flux sensing device is","options":["the small size of its active area","the low voltage required to run it","its direct readout of field","its ability to be used in both northern and southern hemispheres"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The main disadvantage of a Hall detector as a flux measuring device is","options":["its small size","variability between units","high cost per unit","poor temperature characteristics"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"A ferro-probe (or Foerster microprobe) has a high frequency alternating current in a coil mounted on a _______ core.","options":["ferrite","diamagnetic","hard","paramagnetic"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which materials are not used to make wet method particles for MPI testing?","options":["finely divided iron","red iron oxide","black iron oxide","brown iron oxide"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Most non-fluorescent magnetic particles used in the wet method are","options":["red iron oxide","unpigmented ferromagnetic iron oxides","fluorescent particles viewed without a blacklight","not reusable"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"For a given mass of fluorescent magnetic particles, 60�m sized particles would be more visible by containing more fluorescent pigment than 125�m particles.  The reason for this is the smaller particles","options":["less binding resin is needed","have a stronger chemical affinity for fluorescent pigments","have more surface area","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which is not an advantage of oil based vehicles versus water based vehicles of wet magnetic particles?","options":["low corrosivity to ferrous alloys","low fire hazard","low electrical hazard","reduced risk of causing hydrogen embrittlement"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which is not an advantage of water based vehicles versus oil based vehicles of wet magnetic particles?","options":["cost","speed of indication formation","lower electrical hazard","lower fire hazard"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When fine fluorescent magnetic particles are seen floating on the surface of their water carrier like dust and no amount of mixing disperses them it indicated","options":["particle breakdown","insufficient or lack of wetting agent","excessive pump speed","the particles require demagnetization"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Rust inhibitors placed in MPI water baths","options":["provide only short term corrosion protection","are neutralized by fluorescent particles","double as antifoaming agents","all of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Mineral seed oil is sometimes added to a part after MPI testing with water or oil based baths to provide","options":["a demagnetizing effect","wash off excess magnetic particles","both a and b","longer term rust prevention"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Water used in preparing a water based MPI bath","options":["must be de-aerated","must be demineralized","both a and b","can be straight tap water provided it is free from dirt particles"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The best way to control oil contamination of MPI baths is","options":["use only oil for bath vehicles","effective precleaning of parts","organic osmotic type filters","inorganic micron sized filters"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When preparing a bath from dry concentrated MPI particles, in either oil or water vehicle, if the tank is not equipped with a re-circulation pump uneven distribution resulting from hand stirring can be avoided by","options":["premix the quantity into a paste in a blender or small container before adding to the bath","presoak the correct quantity in wetting agent or emulsifier","mounting an egg-beater on the tank","wrapping 3 turns of coil around the tank and applying maximum A.C. to the coil when adding the powder"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Settling volume determination used to establish MPI bath particle concentrations usually uses which implement?","options":["a pipette","a centrifuge tube","a ph meter","a mass indicator (triple beam balance)"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Bath concentrations for magnetic particle testing are usually specified as having","options":["a maximum value","a minimum value","a range of values","the same values for visible and fluorescent particles"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The result of vibrating a sample of magnetic particle bath being tested for concentration is to","options":["increase setting speed","decrease apparent concentration by compaction","increase apparent concentration by fluffing","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The source of contaminants that can cause erroneous concentration readings for MPI baths is","options":["dirt from the test piece","dirt form the atmosphere","salts precipitating from hardwater","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The practical upper limit temperature of the part surface performing MPI on a part using a water vehicle is","options":["20�C.","80�C.","100�C.","212�C."],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Blacklight intensity in post 1990 specifications nearly always quote minimum irradiance in","options":["lux","footcandles","candela","�W/cm_"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The unit of illuminance used to quantify white light for visual inspections is","options":["lux","candle power","�W/cm_","milliphotos"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The SI that is now used as the standard measure of the wavelength of light is the","options":["m (meter)","nm (nanometer)","mm (millimeter)","� (angstrom unit)"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"As light intensity decreases in the visible range the retina's cone shaped cells shut down and the ______ shaped cells assume the role of light collection.","options":["round","square","rod","pyramidal"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The cells commonly referred to as the \"cone shaped cells\" and the \"rod shaped cells\" are to be found in the","options":["eye","ear","nose","penitentiary or asylum"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Eye glasses with blue-absorbing filters are used to view fluorescent indications because","options":["higher levels of blue-violet light can be used without diminishing contrast","higher levels of blue-violet light can be used to enhance fluorescence","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Maximum contrast when viewing magnetic particle indications would occur for","options":["bright daylight conditions","subdued daylight conditions","darkened conditions as for blacklight viewing","none of the above, contrast is a constant"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In MPI testing, the difference between the amount of light reflected by the surface of a test piece and the amount reflected by an MPI indication is called","options":["colour contrast","brightness contrast","resolution","signal to noise ratio"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"If two objects, such as an MPI indication and its background test surface have the same apparent brightness but reflect light at different wavelengths they would exhibit","options":["colour contrast","brightness contrast","photo harmonics","good resolution"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Eyeball fluorescence results in","options":["cataracts","lens deterioration","an unpleasant but harmless sensation","permanent colour blindness"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"To reduce the discomfort of eye fatigue when performing fluorescent MPI you can","options":["take breaks at regular intervals","wear yellow-green tinted glasses (of the appropriate filtering ability)","both a and b","increase dark adaption time"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The purpose of the deep purple filter used on the mercury vapour lamp is to","options":["block most visible light given off the arc","block most UV light below 300nm given off the arc","absorb only a narrow band of energies centred around 365nm","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Dark adaption from bright daylight to full darkened conditions for a blacklight viewing booth will require about","options":["30 seconds","2 minutes","5 minutes","10 minutes"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In automated scanning systems used for defect detection in MPI testing unwanted background lighting is illuminated by","options":["diodes","filament rectifiers","filters","lenses"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which of the following can result in an increased output from a blacklight?","options":["bulb aging","line variations in voltage supply","dirt on the filter","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which of the following can result in a non-relevant MPI indication?","options":["sharp corners","holes drilled near the surface","shrink fits","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which is not a source of a false indication in MPI testing?","options":["a scratch","a shrink fit","scale","a burr"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The purpose of running the circulation pump prior to performing the MPI settling test is to","options":["eliminate residual fields","permit the skimmer to remove high density contaminants","ensure even particle distribution","degasify the suspension"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The first thing you would do if your mercury arc blacklight did not have adequate intensity when tested is","options":["re-calibrate the meter","clean the filter","replace the bulb","put a voltmeter at the receptacle to determine line voltage"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Cracked blacklight filters are","options":["replaced","useable if the opening does not exceed 25�m","can be used on manual but not automated systems","OK to use as long as they stay in the holder and the edges do not present a cutting hazard"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"An MPI gage cannot be used to estimate adequacy of","options":["circular magnetization","longitudinal magnetization from a coil","the direction of the magnetic field","any of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which is a means of determining if the applied magnetic field is in the correct orientation?","options":["pie gages","shim gages","Hall detectors","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In a totally automated MPI system, the bath concentration","options":["is not important","is monitored by continuously measuring opacity","required continuous addition of particles","is monitored by an employee taking samples for the settling test at one hour intervals"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In the wet MPI method, timing of the magnetizing current with respect to the flowing of bath over a test piece is especially important if the test piece is of low retentivity because","options":["a safety hazard exists if the shot is too long","de-polarization of the particles can occur","indications could be washed off if flow continues after the shot","both a and c"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The primary advantage of the television imaging systems over flying spot systems used for MPI scanning systems is","options":["cost and availability","resolution","depth of field","simplicity of electronics"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The glass commonly used as a filter for blacklights is Kopp 41 (Kopp Glass Inc. Pittsburg, PA.,USA).  It effectively","options":["blocks all visible light","blocks all UV light","transmits \"soft\" UV light over 330 nm wavelength","both a and c"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Automated scanning systems rely on the _______ to establish if an MPI indication is real or not.","options":["intensity of fluorescence","linear nature or patterns of defects","absence of background noise","type of laser light used"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The problem with using drawings or written descriptions as a means of recording an MPI indication is","options":["they are highly dependant on the writing or drawing skills of the inspector","background condition cannot be determined","it is not considered a permanent record","all of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The tape transfer method of recording an MPI indication is easiest to use with","options":["oil vehicle wet fluorescent MPI","water vehicle wet visible MPI","dry magnetic particle method","water vehicle wet fluorescent MPI"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"A major problem with trying to take a tape transfer of an MPI indication where the vehicle was oil instead of water is","options":["longer drying time","loss of fluorescence","residual oils break down the tape","none of the above, oil vehicle wet MPI indications are easier to transfer than water vehicle"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which method of recording MPI indications is different from the others?","options":["a photograph","tape transfer","alginate impression or magnetic rubber","fixing coatings"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When using fixing coatings to adhere MPI indications to the test piece surface the part is usually dried.  What is the reason for this?","options":["to allow time for the indication to form at the flux leakage point","to allow time for the background to clear off","to allow the coating to adhere to the part","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which of the following methods of recording MPI indications is different from the other 3?","options":["magnetic rubber","tape transfer","fixing coatings","alginate impressions"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The magnetic rubber method of producing permanent records of MPI indications","options":["is only used in laboratory experiments","requires very long duration magnetization shots","must be photographed immediately as the rubber breaks down within 24 hours","is the fastest and easiest recording methods for MPI indications"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The recommended way to make high quality recordings of MPI indications is by","options":["tape transfer methods","magnetic rubber","photography","cast ceramic molds"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The magnetic particle method does not work if the magnetic flux density is below","options":["100 tesla","10 tesla","1 tesla","none of the above, there is no sudden cut off point below which MPI does not work"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When the central conductor MPI method is used to inspect a ring shaped object, or short cylinder","options":["only inside diameter surface flaws can be found","only outside diameter surface flaws can be found","both inside and outside surface and subsurface flaws can be found if the wall thickness is not too great","none of the above, central conductors cannot be used for ring shaped objects"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Rating of yokes is either by the force needed to pull one leg off the specimen or by the lifting power of the yoke.  The lifting force of a yoke is","options":["half the pull off force","twice the pull off force","18 kg.","4.5 kg."],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When lifting power of an A.C. yoke is specified in kg. you must also specify a minimum","options":["current draw","test piece thickness","prod spacing","coil length"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When rotating field MPI techniques are used it is required that you use","options":["fluorescent particles only","the wet method","dry powder","straight D.C. magnetization"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"On which of the following surfaces would you not likely use the dry MPI method?","options":["hot surface up to 300�C.","undressed weld surfaces","wet or oily surfaces","rough casting surfaces"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The region outside a magnet, where the magnet exerts its influence is the","options":["magnetic field","Barkhausen region","Lorentz zone","de-magnetized zone (DMZ)"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The following are properties of what? a) they begin and end on poles, b) they appear to repel each other, c) their direction is that in which a free north pole would travel.","options":["electrons","magnetic lines of force","gravitons","strong nuclear forces"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"If a ferromagnetic material is not taken to magnetic saturation on its hysteresis loop it will follow ________ when the applied field is reversed.","options":["the virgin curve","a minor loop","straight line","none of the above, it will be stuck at the termination point"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In a unmagnetized ferromagnetic specimen the net (macroscopic) magnetization is","options":["zero","greater than 0.1 Oersted","greater than 1.0 Oersted","at least 10.0 Oersted to be considered ferromagnetic"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"During magnetization of an initially unmagnetized specimen the total number of domains in the specimen","options":["remains constant","increases","decreases","first decreases and then increases at saturation"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Steels used in transformer cores and electromagnets would have which characteristics?","options":["relatively small areas are enclosed by the B-H curve","small field intensities cause large flux densities","relatively low coercive force","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The super magnets, such as samarium-cobalt and neodynium-iron are virtually impossible to de-magnetize by any means other than raising their temperature over the curie point because of","options":["low retentivity","low coercivity","high coercivity","high retentivity"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"As compared to inspecting at the middle of a long tube, when inspecting the end of a tube using the longitudinal MPI method, ______ are required of the coil.","options":["higher fields","lower fields","longer shots","shorter shots"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"For field applications, in order to induce a longitudinal field in a section of piping, if a fixed coil or split coil is not available, you would probably use","options":["prods","several turns of welding cable around the pipe","a yoke","two shots using circular magnetization"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"As paint coating thickness increases on a ferromagnetic plate, the force required to pull the yoke off the plate","options":["increases","decreases","remains constant","may increase or decrease depending on type of paint"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"How are circular magnetizations applied to cylindrical specimens?","options":["rotating yokes","central conductors","passing current along the part","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The purpose of a silicon controlled rectifier (SCR) in the circuitry for pulsed or capacitor discharge magnetization is","options":["to ensure the pulse in unipolar","a safety feature","to act as a filter to eddy currents","a delay line device"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"What is the disadvantage of doing MPI by the residual method when looking for sub-surface indications?","options":["lack of particle motion","excessive surface noise can mask small indications","the time it takes for eddy currents to die down","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which could be considered \"sub-surface flaw\"?","options":["external pitting on tubes' OD surfaces","internal pitting on tubes' ID surfaces","laminations or porosity","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"\"Banding\" of magnetic particles when using the dry powder method with prods indicates","options":["insufficient current","excessive current","particle size is too small","particle size is too big"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Most portable field indicators, such as the \"pie\" gauge are used to","options":["accurately determine relative sensitivity","quantitatively determine field strength","indicate general direction of surface fields","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Irregularly shaped parts that have been magnetized are demagnetized by","options":["suspending it in an east-west orientation and beating lit","passing it through a long coil (solenoid) using decreasing A.C.","both a and b","there is no effective way to completely demagnetize an irregular part other than heating over the curie temperature"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Soft iron bars placed across the pole ends of horseshoe magnets are called","options":["stoppers","keepers","reflectors","magneto-strictors"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"To detect radial cracking on a bolt flange 2cm thick, 30cm diameter with an inside diameter of 25cm you could probably use","options":["2 head shots","a central conductor for circular magnetization","a yoke","prods"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The most important factor in MPI for detectability of a defect is","options":["current strength","strength of induced magnetism","direction of induced magnetic field","all of the above are equally important"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Welding machines, magnetic chucks, contact with electromagnetic lifting devices and permanent magnets are the cause of what problem?","options":["magnetic writing","unwanted residual magnetism in ferromagnetic parts","false indications","arc burns"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"If a UV filter used for photography of fluorescent indications was made of fluorescent material what would the effect be?","options":["cause fogging of the image","change the colour of the indication","change the colour of the background","both b and c"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When taking photographs of NDT indications it is often advised to take several exposures of the same view but using different f-stops.  The reason is","options":["to get several copies for multiple reports","to compensate for unforeseen conditions","to give the appearance of being professional","not all cameras have the same aperture for a given f-stop"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"What is the advantage of photography of MPI indications over other archival methods?","options":["highest resolution reproduction possible","the indication in relation to the test object is shown","storage life is nearly indefinite","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The problem with de-magnetizing a piece by raising its temperature to over the curie point is it","options":["is often impractical","is only effective for surface demagnetization","doesn't work for circular magnetization","doesn't work for longitudinal magnetization"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Ferromagnetic materials that contain very high residual fields are","options":["very hard to demagnetize","very easy to demagnetize","cannot be demagnetized","none of the above, retentivity has nothing to do with ease of demagnetization"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Ferromagnetic materials having very high coercivity have","options":["very high retentivity","very low retentivity","no retentivity","none of the above, coercivity is not determined by the magnitude of residual field"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When using reversing D.C. to demagnetize a part about 30 reversals of decreasing amperage are used in a time of","options":["2 seconds","15 seconds","30 seconds","120 seconds"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The best way to demagnetize a long tube would be","options":["reversing D.C. with a central conductor","pulsating A.C. with a central conductor","a portable yoke","passing the tube through an A.C. coil"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In most cases A.C. demagnetization methods are adequate for parts having a cross-section of not more than","options":["5mm","50mm","100mm","150mm"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The coil 30 point step down D.C. demagnetization is not an acceptable method for","options":["small sized soft steel objects at low production rates","medium sized medium hardness steel objects at medium production rates","small sized, soft steel objects at high production rates","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Field strength within a magnetizing coil","options":["greatest at the coil's centre","greatest near the inside wall of the coil","evenly distributed across the coil's area","opposite to that found in a demagnetizing coil"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which of the following is an acceptable practice for demagnetization?","options":["pass small parts through demag coils while stacked in baskets","pass short objects through demag coils end to end in a chain","use ferromagnetic trays or baskets to convey parts through the demag coil","all of the above are common good practice"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Operator safety as it concerns MPI testing equipment usually concerns the","options":["electrical and mechanical parts of the MPI equipment","petroleum distillates","inherent risks of the test site","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The safety hazard associated with petroleum distillates used as vehicles for MPI is","options":["fire and explosion upon ignition by arcing","dermatitis (skin irritation/infection)","inhalation of toxic fumes","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When working over tanks of petroleum distillates used for MPI particle vehicles the safety precaution that would be taken is","options":["grounding all motors","only work in the presence of blacklight to see any splashed oils on your person","ensure proper ventilation","post all material hazards documents near by"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Even a cool well ventilated environment, there is still a safety risk of explosion when performing fluorescent MPI.  What is the source of this risk?","options":["battery packs","transformer surges","high intensity discharge lamps","spontaneous combustion of vapours"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The ultraviolet light used in NDT for viewing fluorescent indications is called","options":["long wave ultraviolet","blacklight","UV-A","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Some blacklights come with thin outer glass filter envelope around the discharge lamp.  Should this outer shell break the inner lamp continues to work.  If the outer shell cracks you should","options":["replace the whole bulb unit at the end of the shift","turn it off and discard it immediately","check the intensity with a meter and continue only if still within permissible working range","not worry unless a piece of glass falls off"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Prior to the main electrodes arcing what must occur in the mercury vapour blacklight lamps?","options":["argon gas must be transferred to the outer glass envelope","the starter resistor must shut off","the mercury must vaporize","the main electrodes must heat up"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The purpose of the aluminized surface on the inside surface of the outer glass bulb of the mercury vapour lamp is to","options":["increase the heating rate on the vapour","produce a spot profile of light","protect the operator from excessive heat","filter out the UV-C radiation"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When voltage drops more than 15% or power has been switched off to the blacklight the arc ceases and attempts to immediately restart it will fail because","options":["the ballast capacitor takes time to build up its starter charge","the \"heater\" electrode is still cold","mercury vapour pressure must reduce by cooling before the arc will re-start","the re-set switch has been tripped"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Bulb radiance output from a mercury vapour blacklight can rise suddenly as a result of","options":["line voltage surge","steady vibration of the ballast","cleaning the filter","both a and c"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The phosphor coating on the glass filter envelope of blacklight tubes emits","options":["infrared radiation","UV-A and visible light","UV-B radiation","UV-C radiation"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The reason blacklight tubes are not used for critical fluorescent viewing is","options":["their irradiance is mush lower than the medium pressure mercury vapour lamps","they must be arranged in banks so present a safety hazard","the UV-A to UV-B ratio is insufficient","none of the above, blacklight tubes are equal to or better than medium pressure mercury vapour lamps"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In MPI testing (and any work with electric apparatus) risk of dangerous electric shock is increased in the presence of water or moisture on or around the body because","options":["water is a good insulator","Ohm's law breaks down in presence of water","the body's electrical resistance is lowered allowing higher currents to flow","water increases the voltage entering the body"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"From an MPI safety point of view, if you cannot eliminate the possibility of a spark occurring you should","options":["not perform the test","control the environment so an explosion cannot occur","only use D.C. yoke","only use an A.C. yoke"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Adherence to the empirical rules set down for MPI will","options":["ensure the smallest detectable flaw is always found","indicate reference standards are not required in MPI","often lead to over magnetization and poor coverage","always satisfy code requirements"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The purpose of the ketos tool steel ring is to","options":["determine the effectiveness of the magnetic particle system's performance, especially the particles","establish the length of defect that can be found","calibrate the ammeter","determine the current required on test objects"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which of the blocks listed below is not a magnetic particle inspection reference standard?","options":["spilt prism test block","magnetized test block","I.I.W. calibration block","tool steel ring standard"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The number of holes 0.07mm diameter found in the ketos tool steel ring standard is","options":["3","10","12","15"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Raised cross indicators and pie gages are","options":["the same thing","MPI field direction indications","quantitative flux meters","permeability indicators"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In MPI testing the pie gage is read by","options":["slots perpendicular to the flux lines producing distinct indications","slots parallel to the flux lines producing distinct indications","digital read-out","both a and b"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When viewing parts with blacklight both direct and reflected blacklight striking the eye should be avoided because","options":["dark adaptation is lost","cone sensors are \"killed\"","vision becomes clouded due to ocular fluorescence","vision becomes over-sensitive"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The mercury found in the mercury vapour lamp in its cold or off state is","options":["vacuum deposited on the quartz tube walls","condensed droplets of liquid mercury","vapourized and blended with an inert gas","actually mercurous oxide powder which acts as a phosphor"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Blacklights used for fluorescent indication viewing are usually mounted in fixtures for what reason?","options":["prevent transmission of visible light","support the filter","allow the beam to be directed to the inspection surface","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The advantage of tubular style UV lamps is","options":["quick starting","cool operating temperature","cheap to buy and operate","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"UV lamps used for viewing fluorescent indications tend to operate under higher than optimum design conditions.  As a result","options":["output is constantly higher","output is constantly lower","life expectancy is lower than manufactures' estimates","life expectancy is higher than manufacturers' estimates"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The unit of light intensity is the lux or footcandle which is based on the human eye's response to light.  Why is it an inappropriate unit for UV radiation?","options":["UV radiation is not sensed by the eye","UV radiation for NDT is filtered","because the fluorescence of the meter interferes with the reading","none of the above-the lux value is easily and accurately had by subtracting the filtered from the unfiltered readings"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The reason high quality UV light filters, having well defined upper and lower limits, are not used for measuring UV intensities in NDT applications is primarily because","options":["they are not available","of cost","they cannot be fitted to standard meters","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"UV meters should be calibrated about every six months, this is because","options":["it is stipulated in all QA manuals","sensors can deteriorate","UV filters can deteriorate","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"If coatings are left on a part to be MPI tested you must","options":["demonstrate detectability through the maximum costing thickness","get a Level II to ok the work","get a Level III to sign the report","both b and c"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"To detect fatigue cracks in a field weld you would most likely use","options":["a D.C. yoke","an A.C. yoke","permanent magnets","all of the above work well for fatigue cracks"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"For crack detection on a painted steel surface that has had the paint removed, MPI as compared to Liquid Penetrant testing is","options":["not as good","far better","only slightly better","about the same"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Particle concentrations for magnetic particles applied from aerosol cans are","options":["always constant-hence their advantage","known and accurate only when the can is full","never determined","not important as they are never used for critical work"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The prism block standard in MPI testing is used to evaluate","options":["total system sensitivity","yoke strength","particle suspension effectiveness","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When welds are required to have only partial penetration use of HWDC yokes often give rise to nonrelevant indications.  This can be overcome by","options":["using A.C.","increasing leg spacing","reducing magnetizing current","using a pie gage"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When using dry fluorescent powders outdoors, ambient lighting must be","options":["maximized","minimized","augmented by UV lamps","not less than 4,500 lux"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When performing MPI with A.C, the resulting eddy currents provide","options":["a demagnetizing effect","all the particle mobility","a means of performing 2 NDT test at one time","both b and c"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In order that they be held by weak leakage fluxes, dry magnetic particles must have","options":["mobility","high permeability","high retentivity","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Acceptance or rejection of a discontinuity found in a test object is controlled by","options":["the Level I inspector","the Level II inspector","the defect length","the service requirements of the part"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which of the following would risk erroneous test results for an MPI test?","options":["magnetizing current meter reads too high","magnetizing current meter reads too low","bath suspension concentration is too high","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"If the magnetizing current ammeter on your bench unit is no longer reading current when you hit the \"on\" switch for the current, the problem is","options":["a coil is burned out on the transformer","a loosened or broken connector","both a and b could cause the problem","the meter has been de-gaussed"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The decision an inspector makes as to whether or not an indication is to be accepted is","options":["interpretation","evaluation","dispensation","disposition"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Rejecting all parts in an MPI inspection which contain relevant indications is","options":["costly","not always necessary","required by code","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which of the following flaws in a highly stressed steel component is most likely to be cause for concern?","options":["a shallow vee shaped scratch","a small surface breaking pore","a medium sized sub-surface pore","4 small subsurface aligned pores separated by no less than 6mm"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Characteristics of discontinuities determine","options":["their detectability by NDT","their possible role as defects","materials' properties","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"MPI indication formation for dry powder methods will best be formed on _______ surfaces.","options":["coarse, horizontal","rough and slightly inclined","smooth, flat (horizontal)","smooth, vertical"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"For dry powder MPI methods, inspection on flat horizontal surfaces is preferred because","options":["particles are not pulled off by gravity","less powder is needed to form indications","only then can subsurface defects be located","all of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Cold working steel can result in non-relevant MPI indications, these result from","options":["micro fractures","permeability changes from increased harness","concentration of carbon into banded regions","none of the above, cold working does not produce non-relevant indications"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Although a welding machine can be used to supply many amps of current it is not used for practical MPI testing for which reason?","options":["welding machines cannot supply D.C.","voltages are too high","currents available are never sufficient","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which NDT method would you use to locate shrinkage in a steel casting?","options":["magnetic particle","liquid penetrant","radiography","ultrasonics"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which NDT method would you use to detect tight cracks in tungsten forgings","options":["magnetic particle","liquid penetrant","ultrasonics","radiography"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which NDT method would you use to locate defects in 15mm diameter monel tubing?","options":["magnetic particle","liquid penetrant","ultrasonics","radiography"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Which of the following NDT methods would be best suited to inspect thin wall (1mm) 15mm diameter monel tubing?","options":["liquid penetrant","magnetic particle","eddy current","radiography"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Magnetic flux lines intercepted by a discontinuity lying just below the surface flow","options":["across the discontinuity","around the edges of the discontinuity","through the air above the discontinuity","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Austenitic steels are","options":["non-magnetic","used for super magnets","used as magnetic keepers","all of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The most likely cause of no current reading when you apply a prod shot to a rough casting (assuming you have turned the unit on) is","options":["insufficient current setting","to great a prod spacing","poor prod/casting contact","incorrect current type (AC/DC)"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Dry magnetic particle techniques would not be well suited to finding","options":["transverse cracks in welds","grinding cracks","subsurface non-fusion in welds","unfused chaplets in castings"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"The maximum demagnetizing current used is always","options":["AC","DC","greater than that used for the MPI test","less than that used for the MPI test"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"When the contact heads of an MPI bench unit are used to direct current along cable to test a large or remote piece, the spacer placed between the heads is","options":["ferro-magnetic","copper","an insulator","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Horseshoe permanent magnets have their advantage in","options":["high flux density available","portability","the variety of sizes they are available in","being able to test stainless steels"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"\"Dam\" structures are used in MPI testing using _______ techniques.","options":["wet","dry","magnetic rubber","swinging field"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In MPI, the settling test is used to determine","options":["dry particle density","bath strength","bath condition (degree of contamination)","both b and c"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Magnetic particles used in wet methods have _________ to prevent clumping and high background buildup.","options":["low coercivity","low retentivity","low permeability","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"Low retentivity and low coercivity are requirements for magnetic particles to","options":["promote clumping","increase subsurface detectability","decrease background","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":1,"question":"In MPI testing the dry powder equivalent to the wet particle pressurized sprayer is the","options":["squeeze bulb","powder blower","particle shaker","static-discharge applicator"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The primary difference between magnetic particle testing and other methods of testing using magnetics, such as electromagnetic resonance, electron paramagnetic resonance and eddy current testing is","options":["intensity of field used","frequency of field oscillation","mono-pole versus bi-pole magnetics","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Two long conductors (wires) are placed parallel and near to each other.  When current flows in the same direction in both wires there will exist a","options":["net repulsive force between the wires","net attractive force between the wires","neutral zone at the midpoint between the wires","zone of cold fusion at the core of the wires"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Two long conductors (wires) are placed parallel and near to each other.  When current flows in opposite directions in both wires, there will exist a","options":["net attractive force between the wires","net repulsive force between the wires","neutral zone at the mid point between the wires","slight increase in gravitons between the wires"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Magnetic dipole moment is a","options":["vector quantity","scalar quantity","nuclear phenomenon","small unit of time"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The magnitude of the magnetic dipole moment is directly proportional to","options":["the amount of current in a coil conductor","the area of a coil conductor","both a and b","the ratio of current to coil area"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The magnitude of a magnetic induction field at a perpendicular distance 'r' from the centre of a long straight conductor with a current 'I' amperes is","options":["proportional to the current 'I'","inversely proportional to the distance 'r'","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"When a current is passed through a long circular conductor of radius R such as a wire the maximum magnetic induction field occurs at","options":["the centre of the conductor","0.707 R","R (ie. the conductor's surface)","1.414R"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The most significant factor contributing to a material possessing magnetic properties is","options":["the number of neutrons in the nucleus","unpaired electrons in the structure","the van Allen belts","whether ionic or covalent bonding is responsible for the crystal structure"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"In normal unmagnetized condition, the domains of a ferromagnetic material are","options":["randomly aligned","alternately aligned as on a checker board","non-existent until an external field is applied","found only at the curie point"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"In ferromagnetic materials the ratio of the magnetic induction field to the magnetic field intensity is called the","options":["susceptibility","permeability","permissivity","magnetic impedance"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The internal magnetic intensity of a specimen brought into an external magnetizing field will always __________ the applied field.","options":["be less than","equal","be greater than","reduce"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Magnetic circuits are equivalent to electric circuits hence have an equivalent equation to Ohm's law, the term equivalent to electrical resistance in magnetics is","options":["coercive force","reluctance","permeability","magnetic flux"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"In a magnetic circuit, which is equivalent to an electric circuit, the magnetic equivalent to electrical current is","options":["magnetomotance","reluctance","permittivity","magnetic flux"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The ability of the magnetic particle method to detect subsurface defects is not determined by","options":["specimen size","defect depth","defect orientation","strength of applied field"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Magnetic particle testing makes use of the phenomenon called","options":["magnetostriction","magnetic-flux-leakage","magnetomotive force","piezoelectric effect"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Which stage of processing can magnetic particle testing be used?","options":["Primary production and processing","secondary processing or manufacturing","in-service","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"For colour photography of both visible and fluorescent indications it is recommended to use","options":["film with greater than 500 ASA speed","normal daylight film","\"incandescent\" film","none of the above, colour photography is not recommended for NDT purposes."],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Polarizing filters are used in MPI indication photography for what purpose?","options":["to remove orange light","to remove infra-red light","to reduce highlights and reflections","to intensify yellow-green light"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"UV filters used in fluorescent indication photography ;are sometimes called","options":["crossed nichols","haze filters","Kodak filters","polarizing filters"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"When photographing MPI indications it is often a good practice to expose extra frames using higher and lower f-stops to compensate for unforeseen conditions.  This practice is called","options":["bracketing","betting to show","\"hedging your bets\"","full-stopping"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Which of the following is an advantage of video tape recording of MPI indications?","options":["ease and speed to produce","cost","availability to do subsequent image enhancement","both a and b"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The fact that only some magnetic domains resume a random orientation when the magnetizing field is removed accounts for what?","options":["retentivity","coercivity","permeability","nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR)"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The total coercive force of a magnetized piece is always","options":["equal to the saturation force","less than the maximum magnetizing force","greater than the maximum magnetizing force","determined by the residual field reduction equation"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The requirement for multiple switching of polarity and simultaneously reducing current amplitude is had for","options":["D.C. demagnetization methods","swinging field techniques","pulsed A.C. magnetization","surge magnetization"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"In the reversing D.C. method of demagnetization the current is gradually reduced to","options":["zero","the positive coercive force level","the negative coercive force level","negative saturation"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Demagnetization can be improved by","options":["vibrating the part","orienting the part in an east-west direction","rotating the part on its east-west axis during demagnetizing","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The zone of transition between one magnetic domain and the adjacent magnetic domain is called","options":["the magnetic affected zone","the cross-over","the Bloch wall","intermezzo"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Compared to particles used in wet MPI, those used in dry MPI methods are usually","options":["smaller","of higher retentivity","of higher magnetic permeability","more corrosion resistant"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"An excessive number of fine small particles in an MPI test will result in","options":["excessive background","clumping","irrelevant indications","detection of only surface breaking defects"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"What is an advantage to having some residual magnetism in dry magnetic powder particles?","options":["increased contrast","detection of weak leakage fields from subsurface defects","clumping","there is no advantage"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The demagnetization factor results wherever magnetic field lines leave a test piece.  In general the demagnetization factor","options":["decreases with part length","increases with part permeability","is independent of geometry and chemistry","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The apparent permeability of a part is a function of geometry.  This is a result of","options":["the inverse square law","the demagnetization factor","eddy currents and the edge effect","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The yoke break test was designed to evaluate flux strength in a steel plate through various coating thicknesses.  The force to pull the yoke off the plate","options":["decreased with coating thickness","varied with coating material used","decreased with coating thickness independent of coating material","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"An off centred central conductor with a pulsing current supply has the advantage in MPI testing of tubular products of","options":["locating inside and outside defects with equal sensitivity","eliminating eddy currents","inducing eddy currents which reduce non-uniformity of field","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"In general, a surface discontinuity is","options":["rejectable","more serious than the same discontinuity being below the surface","less serious than the same discontinuity being below the surface","always detectable by any NDT method"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"NDT specifications may be revised under which of the following conditions?","options":["new ways are developed to produce or evaluate test results","new materials are developed and need new test specifications","both a and b","none of the above; specifications cannot be changed until the codes they reference are changed"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Ultimately the function of any NDT inspection is to","options":["find all defects in the part tested","locate only those discontinuities deemed harmful in the object tested","ensure all parts tested will be safe to use","find all discontinuities that the proper use of the test method is capable of indicating"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The reliability of finding deep defects wholly below the surface has decreased with the use of the harder alloyed steels used in pressure vessels.  This is due to","options":["the fact that D.C. magnetization units are not available","HWDC units not being available anymore","permeability decreases with increasing hardness","the higher the pressure rating of the vessel the lower the rententivity of the steel will be"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Which of the following should not be in the list?","options":["ingot","bloom","billet","slab"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The collection of magnetic particles caught by a leakage field in a magnetic particle test indicates a discontinuity's","options":["location","shape","size and extent","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Very wide surface cracks may not produce a powder pattern because","options":["the surface opening is too wide for the particles to bridge","detectability is based of the length to width ratio","wide cracks are always shallow","all of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Magnetic particle testing would give best results when used on","options":["cast gray iron","soft steel","hardened steel","stainless steel"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Which of the following might be considered a disadvantage of magnetic particle testing?","options":["speed of operation","relative expense","need to demagnetize parts","detection of shallow defects"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Eddy current testing can also be used to detect surface and sub-surface defects on ferromagnetic materials but is usually inferior to magnetic particle testing because of","options":["inspection speed","requirement of large saturating bias fields","depth and size estimations","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The cause of a magnetic particle indication is always a","options":["defect","surface blemish","discontinuity","surface breaking crack"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The void that occurs at the top centre portion of an ingot is usually called a","options":["hole","funnel","shrink cavity","sprue"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Segregation is a(n) _________ process discontinuity.","options":["inherent","primary","secondary","service"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Blowholes not welded shut in subsequent rolling processes can result in","options":["seams or laminations","pipe","segregation","laps"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Seams in bar stock formed from under-filled rolls are usually","options":["acceptable MPI indications","not detectable by MPI","nearly normal to the surface of the bar being formed","at an acute angle to the surface of the bar being formed"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Seams in barstock formed as a result of over filled rolls are usually","options":["acceptable MPI indications","not detectable by MPI","nearly normal to the surface of the bar","at an acute angle to the surface of the bar"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Another name for the \"unit pole\" is","options":["mono-pole","electromagnetic unit","north seeking pole","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"If a compass needle is brought near a bar magnet the needle will orient itself ______ to the magnetic lines of force at any point.","options":["parallel","perpendicular","toroidally","transverse"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The Weber is the MKS form of magnetic flux.  The cgs unit is called the maxwell.  1 weber = ________ maxwells","options":["10","100","10^6","10^8"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The magnetic flux per unit area is called the","options":["flux density","magnetic density","magnetic concentration","saturation factor"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Soft iron if brought into the field of a magnet will be","options":["permanently magnetized","temporarily magnetized","electrified","statically charged"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The Hall effect is used to","options":["demagnetize material","increase the permeability of ferromagnetic materials","measure magnetic fields","induce eddy currents"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"A Hall detector can be used to measure","options":["magnetic field strength","coercive force in a hysteresis loop","magnetic field direction","both a and c"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The negative magnetizing force required to reduce the flux density in a part to zero after saturation is called","options":["residual force","coercive force","demagnetizing field strength","null force"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The degree to which a material holds a residual magnetic field is termed","options":["saturation","negative saturation","reluctance","retentivity"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The opposition to the formation of a magnetic flux in a magnetic circuit is referred to as","options":["reactance","reluctance","resistance","antimagnetics"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"When an electric current, a magnetic field or an electrical potential drops off to zero, the reduction in amplitude of these quantities is given the same term.  That term is","options":["decay","spin off","lapse","lag"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Pulsating \"DC\" is considered the result of","options":["half wave rectified single phase AC","full wave rectified single phase AC","full wave rectified three phase AC","both a and b are considered to pulsate"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Commercial single phase alternating current can best be described as a","options":["straight line of fixe bias","sine wave","square wave","saw tooth wave"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Short duration currents resulting from sudden changes in electric or magnetic condition within a circuit are called","options":["Bremstrahlung","Barkhausen noise","noise spikes","transient currents"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Which of the following does not belong in the list?","options":["EMF","voltage","reactance","potential difference"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The core material used in an electromagnet is","options":["any insulator","heat resistant ceramic","ferromagnetic","copper"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"In magnetic particle testing, solenoids are used for","options":["magnetizing parts","demagnetizing parts","to evaluate indications","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The wavelength of blacklight used in fluorescent magnetic particle testing is usually around","options":["365�","3650�","285�","2850�"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"A solenoid can be considered to consist of several","options":["resistors","capacitors","diodes","loops"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"When a current is passed directly through a part the magnetization that results is considered to be","options":["longitudinal","circular","a coil shot","multi directional"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"A shot of magnetizing current passed through a part while clamped between the clamping contacts of a stationary unit is referred to as a(n)","options":["induction shot","coil shot","central conductor shot","head shot"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"A magnetic particle cluster resulting from a true leakage field but not originating from a metal flaw is a(n)","options":["anomaly","false indication","irrelevant indication","non-relevant indication"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Ohm's law can be expressed as","options":["E = (I) (R)","I = (E) (R)","R = (I) (E)","E = I_R"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"In a D.C. series circuit what resistance is required to cause a voltage drop of 170 volts when 5 amps are flowing?","options":["29.5 milli ohms","34 ohms","165 ohms","850 ohms"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"What is the current through a 50 ohm resistor if the potential across the resistor is 12 volts?","options":["240 mA","417 mA","24 A","600 A"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Which of the following is the relationship for electric power?","options":["I_R","EI","E_/R","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"\"Conventional current flow\" has electrons moving","options":["from negative to positive","from positive to negative","on the inside of wire conductors","on the outside of wire conductors"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The left hand rule for determining magnetic field direction applies to","options":["AC circuits only","DC circuits only","modern current theory","conventional current flow theory"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The purpose of the iron core in an electromagnet is to","options":["eliminate eddy currents","increase the magnetic flux density","brace the coils against the magnetic torque","provide an electrical ground route"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The lagging of flux density (B) behind the magnetizing force (H) is called","options":["phase lag","phase shift","doppler shift","hysteresis"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"In a transformer, if the voltage in the secondary winding is stepped down, the current in the secondary will be","options":["stepped up","stepped down","remain the same as the primary","D. C."],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"If Is and Ip are currents, Es and Ep voltages and Ns and Np number to turns in the secondary and primary windings of a transformer, which is not true.","options":["Ep Ip = Es Is","Ip/Is = Es/Ep","Es/Ep = Np/Ns","Ip/Is = Ns/np"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Alternating current used as a magnetizing source tends to concentrate the magnetic flux near the test piece surface because of","options":["the inverse square law","ohm's law","the skin effect","the Barkhausen effect"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Which is not an advantage of using AC for a magnetizing current?","options":["increased contrast","the skin effect","increase mobility","ease with which the part is demagnetized"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Penetration of the magnetic field, all other factors being equal, is greatest for","options":["half wave rectified single phase AC","full wave rectified single phase AC","half wave rectified 3 phase AC","full wave rectified 3 phase AC"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Ease of demagnetization depends on","options":["amount of residual magnetism in the part","if single or 3 phase rectified current was used for magnetization","the coercive property of the material","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The temperature at which a ferromagnetic material changes to a paramagnetic material is the","options":["Neel temperature","Curie point","an ambient temperature","plastic point"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Upon cooling a ferrous alloy below its Curie point, in the absence of an external field it","options":["remains paramagnetic","becomes ferromagnetic","becomes ferromagnetic but unmagnetized","emits UV light"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Initial demagnetizing current using electromagnetic techniques should be","options":["equal to maximum magnetizing current","slightly higher than maximum magnetizing current","slightly lower than maximum magnetizing current","slightly higher than minimum magnetizing current"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Which is not a recommended demagnetization technique using an A.C. coil?","options":["place the part in the coil and gradually reduce the current to zero","place the part in the coil and expand the coils to twice the diameter while current is on","with the current on, draw the part through the coil and away to a distance of 2 coil diameters","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Why is A.C. not an effective means of demagnetizing large parts?","options":["because they don't fit into the coil","due to transformer limitations on the current draw","because of the skin effect","because of low transformer efficiency"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"To eliminate the circular magnetism that exists in a part  by applying a longitudinal field may require several \"shots\" if the part","options":["is soft steel","is hardened steel","has a large L/D ratio","is not oriented north-south"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Substances whose molecular structure is such that an unbalanced antiparallel electron spin exists are said to have ferrimagnetism.  These substances are called","options":["ferrites","ferros","pharaohs","faeries"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Aircraft, automotive and railroad components that have been inservice for some time but not near an artificially produced magnetic field are often found to be strongly magnetized.  This is a result of","options":["friction between parts","the earth's magnetic field","geo-magnetic reversals","the electric field off the spark plugs"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The techniques used for demagnetization using D.C. are","options":["essentially the same as A.C.","more effective than A.C.","both a and b","less costly than A.C."],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Yoke demagnetization can be more effective than coil methods in some cases because","options":["they go A.C.-D.C.","they make contact with the part","the yoke is always D.C.","the field can be more concentrated"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"To detect residual circular magnetism in a circular part using a field meter you must","options":["hold the meter at 2 positions on the part at right angles to each other","make a saw cut into the part","use a circular field meter","use 2 field meters"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"A ball bearing is to be tested by MPI.  Which is the best option for magnetization?","options":["a coil shot","3 shots at mutual right angles using induced current","parallel magnetism","2 coil shots and one head shot"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Which is not a problem that might result if the wrong choice of particles is made in MPI testing?","options":["misinterpretation due to distorted indications","oversensitivity","failure to form indications","formation of indications too faint to detect"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The single most important property to consider in selection of magnetic particles is","options":["permeability","shape","size","none of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Magnetic particles used for wet MPI purposes are usually colour coated ___________.","options":["iron fillings","cobalt 59","ferromagnetic oxides","Alnico"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Clumping of wet magnetic particles on the test specimen is usually a result of","options":["the carrier being too viscous","the test surface being too rough for the particles used","too high a retentivity of the particles","relevant indication formation"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The size of most dry powder magnetic particles used in general flaw detection is","options":["less than 2 microns in any dimension","about 3000 to 4000 microns","a mixture of shapes and sizes","not a consideration in the test method"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The typical size range of dry magnetic particles is","options":["1 - 25 �m","25 - 100 �m","100 - 1000 �m","1000 - 5000�m"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The typical size range for wet magnetic particles is","options":["1 -25 �m","25 -100 �m","100 -1000 �m","1000 -5000 �m"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The particle shape of dry magnetic particles that is best suited to detection of weak leakage fields from sub-surface defects is","options":["spherical","elongated","flake","irregular"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The shape of particles used in the wet magnetic particle method is","options":["elongated","flake","spherical","not important"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Compared to visible magnetic particles, fluorescent magnetic particles are","options":["on average smaller","magnetically less sensitive","more dense","magnetically more sensitive"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Which is not a colour of magnetic particles that should be used on grit blasted surfaces?","options":["red","white","black","orange"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The advantage of the oil based magnetic particles as compared to the water based is","options":["cost of particles","sensitivity","the ability to use oil based in either oil or water","none of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"A combination of the residual and continuous MPI methods are sometimes used if","options":["you are using dry powder","the part is cylindrical","the part has relatively high retentivity","only a single shot is required"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Wet magnetic particles can be applied by","options":["using a hose and nozzle to spray the part","immersing the part in an agitated bath","both a and b","none of the above is recommended"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The condition reached in a ferromagnetic material subjected to an A.C. magnetic field such that the incremental permeability is one during part of each cycle is termed","options":["D.C. saturation","A.C. saturation","incremental saturation","half wave peaking"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"What is the condition reached in a ferromagnetic material subjected to a D.C. magnetizing current when the incremental permeability is unity?","options":["D.C. saturation","A.C. saturation","incremental saturation","magnetic limit"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The portion of an electromagnetic circuit that is inside the coil (winding) is called the","options":["Helix","core","solenoid","inductor"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"When a part is magnetized by a current flow of very brief duration it is said to be","options":["de-polarized","zapped","flash magnetized","residually magnetized"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"In full wave rectified A.C. the peak current is","options":["zero","2^_ times the r.m.s. value","2(2^_) times the r.m.s. value","0.707 times the r.m.s. value"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"When an electric current is forced to flow across a gaseous gap the result is","options":["fluorescence","an arc","an induction field","Barkhausen noise"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Articulated pole pieces are usually found on these.","options":["yokes","swinging fields","Hall detectors","Berthold penetrameters"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The closed path followed by a magnetic flux line or group of flux lines is called a","options":["bar magnet","magnetic circuit","flux core","magneto-loop"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"A device used to measure the strength of magnets or magnetic fields is a","options":["magnetometer","penetrameter","fluxometer","field densitometer"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The relative permeability of copper ;is","options":["0","1",">1","<1"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The relative permeability of a diamagnetic material is","options":["0","1",">1","<1"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The sensitivity of an MPI test is dependant upon","options":["magnitude of magnetizing current or field","the type of test medium","method of application of particles","a combination of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The type of magnetic particles used in an MPI test is determined by","options":["defect location, on or below surface","size of defect","convenience","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"To detect the #3 hole (0.7\" dia. 0.21\" deep) in a Ketos ring using a central conductor, which would detect the hole using the least current?","options":["half wave A.C.","D.C. surge","straight D.C.","A.C."],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Sensitivity of the residual method of MPI testing when the test part is immersed","options":["increases with carrier density","increases with carrier viscosity","increases with time immersed","decreases with particle size"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The standard 1/2 second \"shot\" duration in the continuous wet method assumes","options":["correct particle concentration","A.C. is used","D.C. is used","only head shots are required"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The decision to use circular or longitudinal magnetization is determined by","options":["part shape","suspected defect orientation and shape","whether or not you have a coil","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"When a tubular part is MPI tested using a head shot where the current is passed through the tube itself the field strength on the inside surface of the tube compared to the outside is","options":["the same","zero","about 1/4","4 times greater"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Shafts, drums and girders can be _______ magnetized by coiling a flexible cable around the part and passing a current through the cable.","options":["longitudinally","circularly","randomly","surface"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"As result of a head shot, the magnetic lines of force take the general form of","options":["a bar magnet","a horseshoe magnet","concentric rings about the part axis","an ellipse"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Equations for ampere turns required for a coil shot are usually qualified by conditions.  Which is not a condition usually stipulated?","options":["part permeability","maximum part length","effective coil length","fill factor"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"When is the equation It = 45000 /(L/D) used?","options":["for coil shots on parts with an L/D ratio >4","for coil shots on parts with an L/D ratio <4","for coil shots on parts centred in the coil","for central conductor shots"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Recommended D.C. current for a head shot is based on a part's diameter.  Rule of thumb for a head shot is _______ amps / mm part diameter.","options":["1","25","40","100"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Given a solid steel shaft 1m long and 20 cm diameter, what is the current recommended for a 5 turn coil shot assuming the bar is not centred in the coil?","options":["750 amperes","1000 amperes","1500 amperes","2000 amperes"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Given a hollow steel shaft 1m long and 10cm diameter, what magnetizing current would you use with a 5 turn coil with the part at the bottom of the coil?","options":["100 amperes","200 amperes","300 amperes","600 amperes"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Given a steel bar 1 foot long and 3 inches diameter, what current should you use for the coil shot with a 3 turn coil (part placed at bottom of coil)?","options":["100 amps","2000 amps","4000 amps","6000 amps"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"When it may be possible to damage parts exposed to magnetic particles or the liquid vehicle the inspector may have to","options":["use dry powder instead of wet method","use insulated prods","plug holes and mask surfaces","use coil shots only"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Vapour degreasing would not be an effective cleaning method for which material?","options":["oils","mineral deposits","waxes","greases"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"A problem with performing an MPI test on a part that does not have its thin layer of paint or plating removed is","options":["no subsurface defects can be located","cracks cannot be seen","the magnetic field disbonds the paint or plating","all indications have the \"fuzzy\" subsurface appearance"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"A coil shot is not effective if the ratio of the long to short dimension is less than","options":["1","2","4","10"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The purpose of a swinging field set up for MPI testing is to","options":["reduce set up time","reduce costs","improve depth sensitivity","increase detectability of randomly oriented defects"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"When using 2 A.C. fields to provide a swinging field MPI test ________ to be effective.","options":["only single phase A.C. is used","only 3 phase A.C. is used","the 2 fields must be 50� to 130� out of phase","the 2 fields must be in phase"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"In the swinging field method of MPI testing the application of the test medium (particles) is","options":["prior to the field application","during 