operty that changes with magnetic field intensity is","options":["resistance","ductility","density","permeability"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The purpose of arranging a Hall detector at the mouth or apex of a ferrite ring (ferrite C-core) is to","options":["eliminate lift off","provide a magnetic shield","concentrate flux leakage for better sensitivity","induce eddy currents that counter the Hall currents"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The difference between ferroprobes and flux gate magnetometers is","options":["ferroprobes are activated at high frequency","the number of coils used","the use of ferrites","none, they are the same flux detection device but with different names"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Application of a light lacquer or penetrant developer can be used in dry powder MPI tests to enhance contrast but the disadvantage is","options":["the powder cannot be reused after being in contact with the contrasting coating","the coating process can be a time consuming extra step","the removal of the coating, if needed, can be a time consuming extra step","both b and c"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The disadvantage of reusing dry powder magnetic particles is","options":["reduced colour","reduced contrast","increased proportion of larger particles","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Dry powders cannot be used in water suspensions for the wet method of MPI because","options":["they quickly oxidize","their settling rate is too high","clumping results","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Light intensity requirements for daylight fluorescent dry magnetic particles are","options":["the same as for non-fluorescent powder","the same as for wet fluorescent particles","not specified in present standards or specifications","equivalent to that found at the equator on a clear summer evening 1/2 before sunset"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The problem you would likely encounter if you tried to view daylight fluorescent dry powder in similar conditions used for wet fluorescent MPI (UV light in a darkened area) is","options":["no fluorescent response is had use a UV lamp","excessive background fluorescence","retina damage due to the frequency of light emitted","no problem at all"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Fe3O4 (subscript numbers) is the chemical formula for which iron oxide?","options":["black","brown","red","all of the above have the same formula"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"True material magnetic permeability is not important in magnetic particles until","options":["A.C. magnetizing currents are used","D.C. magnetizing currents are used","the L/D ratio of the joined particles exceeds 1","subsurface defects are required to be detected"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"If a settling test is performed on fluorescent wet particles, and after allowing the sample to sit unagitated over night (10-15 hours) a thin, brightly fluorescent layer forms on top of the sediment,","options":["the test is acceptable","particle breakdown is indicated","oil carrier breakdown is near","more dispersing is required"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Higher flash point oil based liquids are preferred for the carriers in wet MPI testing because of","options":["fire hazard considerations","operator breathing discomfort considerations","background fluorescence considerations","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"What is it about fluorescent magnetic particles that requires conditioning agents be added to the water used as their carrier?","options":["they induce rusting action","their pigments and binders are water repellent","they are soluble in straight water","they would sink too quickly without the conditioner"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Small amounts of sodium nitrate or sodium chromate in the water based MPI bath are used to","options":["kill background fluorescence","reduce foaming that results from agitation of baths","protect pieces against rusting","permit MPI on austenitic stainless steels"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Addition of a small quantity of mineral oil to an oil based MPI bath is occasionally used to provide rust protection.  The risk, however, is that","options":["viscosity will drop below required limits","viscosity will rise above required limits","particle concentration drops excessively","fluorescent particle breakdown will occur"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"What can oil vehicles used for MPI baths be contaminated with that water vehicles cannot?","options":["fluorescent pigments and resins","rust particles","grease","water"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"A marked increase in background blue fluorescence of the oil vehicle of an MPI bath as compared to the reference sample indicates","options":["probable oil contamination of bath","probable water contamination of bath","fluorescent particle breakdown","the blacklight is about to fail"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Particle coagulation in an MPI bath can result from","options":["water contaminants in an oil bath","oil contaminants in a water bath","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"In order that indication to background contrast be maintained so as to ensure consistency of defect detection in an MPI test what is required?","options":["ensure only visible particles are used (not fluorescent)","only water as a vehicle should be used","maintain particle concentration in the bath","ensure blacklight filter is clean"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"When using magnetic particle concentrations at the lower limit of the recommended range in a recirculating system, you will","options":["reduce background","require frequent concentration checks","steadily decrease the particle concentration","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Setting speed of an MPI bath sample is accelerated by","options":["vibration","magnetized particles","warming the bath (to 40�C.)","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Settling of magnetic particles in the centrifuge tube can be retarded by","options":["particles getting in each others way","upward flow of displaced liquid","both a and b","no known force or mechanism"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The upper limit for part temperature when using MPI in an oil vehicle is","options":["30�C.","50�C.","dependant on fire hazard based on flash point","primarily a health consideration"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The quantity measured in blacklight intensity has units of �W/cm_.  The quantity is","options":["luminescence","radiation","irradiance","illuminance"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The quantity measured in white light viewing has units of lux.  The quantity is","options":["luminescence","radiation","irradiance","illuminance"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"If the eye has no sensitivity to the power irradiated (eg. UV light) photometric units quantifying that light are","options":["meaningless","the same as radiometric values","1","0"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"In the retina the cells responsible for collecting light to visualize images are the","options":["epithelial cells","epitonic cells","neural cells","cone and rod shaped cells"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"An eye that has become accustomed to low light levels is said to exhibit __________ response.","options":["scotopic","photopic","myopic","mesopic"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"An eye that has adapted to bright daylight is said to be exhibiting ________ response.","options":["scotopic","photopic","myopic","mesopic"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The reason you can sometimes detect faint objects in the dark by not looking directly at them is because","options":["their is a high concentration of cone cells near the fovea","rod cells are concentrated off axis in the retina","of Lenz's law","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The electronic equivalent to the MPI term contrast would be","options":["rise time","signal-to-noise ratio","bandwidth","modulation"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Detection of MPI indications is accomplished by","options":["the human eye","imaging detectors","non-imaging detectors","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"At very low light levels (<0.03 cd/m_) colour differentiation is best for","options":["blue and green","green and yellow","blue and red","none of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The component in wet fluorescent MPI testing that is most likely to cause dermatitis is","options":["fluorescent dyes","solvent based carrier","dissolved salts in the tap water","ferromagnetic particles"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The mercury vapour arc was selected as a blacklight source because its spectrum","options":["gives a pure 365nm line with no other interfering energies","has a smooth rise and fall like the continuous x-ray spectrum but having a peak at 365nm","has several peaks, one of which is at 365nm","has no harmful UV emission"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Which vision requirement is a critical prerequisite for fluorescent MPI viewing?","options":["near vision","far vision","colour vision","television"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Non-imaging scanners used for indication detection in visible MPI testing systems detect","options":["magnetic flux variations","a decrease in reflected light","an increase in reflected or emitted light","magneto-luminescence"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Blacklight output for a given bulb bares what relation to line supply?","options":["varies directly","varies inversely","varies logarithmically","is constant above the startup threshold"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Which classification of MPI indication is not attributable to a flux leakage?","options":["relevant","nonrelevant","FALSE","defect"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"In an MPI test a scratch is considered","options":["nonrelevant","FALSE","false unless it occurs in notch sensitive or highly stressed materials","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"When performing the settling test for the wet method concentration determination you find the concentration too high.  To rectify the situation you would probably","options":["add more particles","add more carrier","throw out the bath and re-make it from scratch","recall all test pieces done since the last concentration test"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"If cleaning the filter does not correct low intensity of your blacklight during an intensity test your next step would logically be to","options":["measure the line voltage with a voltmeter","recalibrate the UV meter","replace the bulb","call the manufacturer to complain"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Calibration of a yoke involves","options":["lifting a specified weight","use of a shunt meter","use of a flux meter","use of an ammeter"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The \"pie gage\" is used in MPI to","options":["quantify field strength","indicate magnetic declination","indicate magnetic inclination","determine direction of the magnetic field in a part"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"In MPI, the thin metal devices with artificial subsurface discontinuities etched into them, which are used placed on the part to determine field direction and adequacy are","options":["Hall detectors","shim gages","magneto-densitometers","Ketos rings"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Automated inspection systems for MPI have their advantage primarily in","options":["reduced labour costs","consistency and reproducibility","increased sensitivity","elimination of coffee breaks"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"When multidirectional magnetization is used to do an MPI test on a part ________ after the current is stopped.","options":["no fields remain in the part","3 fields at right angles to each other remain","2 fields at right angles to each other remain","1 field remains"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The imaging equipment used for MPI scanning systems is","options":["a television photodetector","a flying spot system","a holographic projector","either a or b can be used"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The advantage of the He-Cd laser used by the flying spot scanning system for automated fluorescent MPI, as compared to television imaging systems is","options":["higher resolution is available than for television systems","higher levels of fluorescent intensity are produced","depth of field is not a limitation and electronics is simpler","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Which of the following is a process used for pattern recognition in automated MPI scanning methods?","options":["neighbourhood processing algorithms","dedicated digital processors","microprocessor algorithms","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The pressure sensitive tape transfer technique recording MPI indications is used on","options":["dry method magnetic particle indications","wet method oil vehicle magnetic particle indications","wet method water vehicle magnetic particle indication","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Prior to taking a tape transfer recording of a wet fluorescent MPI indication you must","options":["blow off excess bath with a strong air stream","use only oil carriers for the particles","ensure the surface is completely dry","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"To accelerate drying of oil based vehicles off an MPI test piece so a tape transfer of indications can be made you could","options":["rinse the part with an oil solvent","spin the part on its long axis","ignite the oil","re-run the test with water vehicle MPI particles"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"In the MPI indication recording technique that utilizes fixing coatings the purpose of the spray coating is to","options":["bind the indication to the test surface","lift the indication for preservation elsewhere","improve background and thereby improve contrast","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Rubber replica materials such as alginates, when used to record MPI indications have their advantage in that","options":["they are the most sensitive form of record","they are easily stored in file folders","indications can be lifted from locations not directly viewed by the inspector","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Which is an advantage of the magnetic rubber MPI method?","options":["fast","inexpensive","useful for inaccessible areas","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Which is not an advantage of the magnetic rubber method?","options":["provides permanent replicas","a fast and easy process","useful for inaccessible areas","evaluation can be done remote from the test piece"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The advantage of using photography to record MPI indications is","options":["cost","simplicity","quality of image","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"When performing the residual technique of MPI you should use","options":["A.C.","rectified A.C.","D.C.","either b or c"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The reason the central conductor for MPI tests are often made of copper is","options":["to increase voltage","to increase current","to decrease heating effects","to decrease eddy currents"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"When a flexible cable is used in the \"laid-on-cable\" technique for MPI of welds, the cable is arranged such that the return loop of the cable is","options":["parallel to the outgoing loop and current flow is in the same direction","parallel to the outgoing loop and current flow is in the opposite directions","at right angles to the outgoing loop","wound opposite and above the outgoing loop"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Lifting force or pull-off force required by an A.C. yoke is less than required by a D.C. yoke because","options":["A.C. is not as important as D.C.","skin effect concentrates the flux at the surface","the direction of flux is perpendicular to the specimen surface for A.C. but parallel for D.C.","codes have not been modified to allow for the strength of new A.C. yokes"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The purpose of lead contact covers on prods for MPI testing is to","options":["increase flux density","increase current flow","reduce arc burns","prevent particle breakdown"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The width of a magnetic particle indication","options":["indicates flaw depth","is always wider than the actual flaw opening","is equal to the height of particle indication","is determined by the angle of repose"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The purpose of the Rowland ring is to","options":["reconstruct magnetic particle powders after particle breakdown","de-magnetize very small parts","investigate properties of ferromagnetic materials","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Laboratory studies of magnetic hysteresis properties of ferromagnetic materials are done using","options":["a Rowland ring","swinging field configurations","eddy current probes","A.C. - D.C. yokes"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"A hysteresis loop is used to demonstrate a materials' _________.","options":["stress-strain relationship","magnetic properties","conductivity","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Which of the following has the highest flux density at magnetic saturation?","options":["cobalt","gold","iron","nickel"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The presence of domain walls can be verified using","options":["extremely fine magnetic particles","swinging field techniques","a Rowland ring","nitrol etching techniques"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Both ferro and ferrimagnetic materials support relatively large _______ for relatively small _______.","options":["domain numbers, volumes","strain, applies stress","B, H","H, B"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Cobalt-samarium is considered one of the \"super magnets\" having a coercivity of several million Oersteds.  How would you easily demagnetize it?","options":["heat it above its curie temperature","hit it sharply with a hammer several times","place it in a 5 turn demag. coil","any of the above would suffice"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The apparent permeability of a part is a function of","options":["initial permeability","geometry","heat treatment","alloy (chemistry)"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The double coil system, whereby a tube to be MPI tested is passed through 2 coils arranged in tandem was designed to","options":["increase inspection speed","minimize the L/D ratio of the material","prevent the inspector's vision from being impaired","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Using an AC yoke, detectability of weld cracks decreases with increasing number of weld bead passes on a weld crown due to","options":["the Hall effect","concurrent leakage fields","the plate thickness increasing","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"A reason to magnetize a part circularly after it has been magnetized in the longitudinal direction, other than to find defects is to","options":["eliminate external fields on the end of the part","surface harden the piece","locate non-relevant indications","locate irrelevant indications"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"In pulsed or capacitor discharge magnetization, pulse effectiveness is dependent on","options":["pulse current amplitude","part length","pulse duration","L/D ratio"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The major cause of surface noise in MPI is","options":["surface irregularities","permeability variations","eddy currents","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Surface noise in MPI of specimens can result from","options":["residual stresses resulting from straightening","eccentricity in tube wall thickness","tempered welded joints","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"When inspecting a part with several diameters by passing current directly through the part you would","options":["test the part using current needed for the largest diameter","test the part using current needed for the smallest diameter","use several shots starting with low current for small diameters and increasing current for larger diameters","use several shots starting with maximum current for the large diameter then decreasing current for small diameters"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The advantage of the Burmah-Castrol strip over other portable surface field indicators is","options":["the number of slots available to determine sensitivity","it places the simulated flaw as close as possible to the test surface","its high coercivity","its low retentivity"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Demagnetization using an A.C. coil is limited to","options":["short parts (L/D<2)","long parts (l/D>2)","tubular products","about 1mm depth from the surface"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The purpose of the soft iron keeper used in conjunction with a permanent horseshoe magnet is","options":["to minimize leakage flux","reduces attraction to other magnets and magnetic debris","to prevent the magnet from losing its magnetism","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"If correct magnetizing current is unknown for a specific application","options":["use I= (45000) / (L/D)","do not test the part","determine the correct value by experimentation and record the results","use another NDT method"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"If a part is MPI tested using D.C. and an indication is located how would you estimate depth if it was not surface breaking?","options":["use HWDC or A.C and see if it still shows","reduce current","increase leg or prod spacing or increase coil diameter","all of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Placing an A.C. yoke onto a large part, then energizing the yoke and removing the yoke about half a meter from the part before switching off the yoke is a(n) _____________ technique.","options":["swinging field","demagnetization","longitudinal magnetization","exorcism"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Mag-Bag or reusable magnetic particle bags are used","options":["when no permanent record is required","in underwater inspections","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The result of the inability of a flawed region to sustain the same level of magnetization as the surrounding material is","options":["a crack","magnetic flux leakage field","an accumulation of electrons","spontaneous magnetostriction"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The relative magnetic permeability is dependant on","options":["the specific properties of the material tested","the strength of the applied field","the L/D ratio","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"A linear relationship exists between","options":["B and H for MPI testing of steel","flux density and minimum size of flaws detected by MPI","part thickness and current required to bring the part to magnetic saturation","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"How can low concentrations of MPI suspensions be compensated for?","options":["increase the magnetic field","use more volume of suspension per unit test area","use brighter fluorescent particles","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"A problem that if not corrected for in photography of fluorescent test indication, will overexpose a film, is","options":["film sensitivity to UV light","focus distortion due to limited wavelengths","small aperture settings to accommodate depth of field","all of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"To take close-up photos of indications located by MPI you require","options":["UV sensitive film","a macro lens","a low intensity fast UV flash","a tripod"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"When a D.C. bench unit, that does not have the step down demagnetisation option built in, is used to demagnetize a part with a cable wrap, how is current reversal achieved?","options":["manually switching the current selector","manually switching cable connections","re-wrapping the coils","none of the above, it cannot be used for demag purposes"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Field strength of a coil wrap magnetization set up can be increased by","options":["reducing turns","reducing current","reducing diameter of coil","reducing fill factor"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Almost anything MPI tested can be demagnetized to an acceptable level using reversing D.C. methods; but its disadvantage is","options":["low production rates","over heating of some surface finishes","severe arc burns","large equipment and dangerously high currents are used"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"When demagnetizing a ring shaped object by passing it through a coil you would","options":["pass it through with its shortest axis parallel to the coil's central axis","pass it through such that its diameter is parallel to the coil axis and it is held vertical","pass it through such that its diameter is parallel to the coil axis and it is held horizontal","roll it through the coil"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"MPI field meters are now provided with two units on the meter face, they would be","options":["Oersted and Gauss (Oe & G)","Oersted and Tesla (Oe & T)","Gauss and milli Tesla (B & mT)","MRayls and Hz"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The field strength of an A.C. magnetizing coil is about 36% of the surface value at a depth of 1mm into a steel piece.  About what percentage of the surface field strength would exist 4mm from the surface?","options":["50%","25%","5%","2%"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Safety hazard associated with blacklights used in fluorescent viewing of indications arises from","options":["skin burns upon contact with the lamp","retina damage from non filtered light","carcinoma due to skin exposure","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"At concentrations below their lower explosive limit, petroleum distillates used in MPI testing will","options":["be safe to use","give off noxious fumes","ignite with explosive force if exposed to flame","ignite without explosion if exposed to flame"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Why are the high intensity discharge lamps (mercury vapour) used in fluorescent viewing a safety hazard?","options":["the risk of implosion upon impact","the risk of explosion upon impact","toxic gases are given off if cracked or not properly sealed","fluorescent light they stimulate on the coated particles is hazardous to the eyes"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Because of its reddening effect on the skin, UV-B ultraviolet light is called _________ ultraviolet.","options":["dermicidal","germicidal","erythemal","short wave"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Which ultraviolet light is to be avoided due to its health hazards?","options":["UV-A","UV-B","UV-C","both b and c"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"What is not housed in the quartz tube of the standard high pressure mercury vapour lamps used for lamps used for fluorescent indication viewing?","options":["operating electrodes a starting electrode","mercury gas and liquid","a large value resistor","small starter electrode"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Why do the main electrodes of the mercury vapour blacklight not arc immediately upon switching on the current to the lamp?","options":["there is insufficient mercury vapour to conduct an arc","the main electrodes are not hot enough","the starter resistance is too low","both a and b"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"If a blacklight is used for frequent but only intermittent inspections it should be _______ between uses.","options":["switched off","switched off and placed under a cooling fan","left on continuously or in the standby mode if so equipped","switched off until about 4 hours of inspection have been backlogged"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Which of the following affect the life expectancy of a mercury vapour lamp?","options":["number of on/off cycles","ambient operating temperature","applied voltage and total on time","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"When long blacklight tubes are used instead of mercury vapour lamps the source of UV radiation is","options":["mercury vapour","neon gas","argon gas","a combination of inert gases"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Although total blacklight energy output of a bank of blacklight tubes may be about equal to a 100W mercury vapour lamp their irradiance is lower because","options":["the filter is more absorbent in tubes","they cannot be focused","the tube phosphor impedes transmission","the UV to visible ratio is higher for lamps than tubes"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Wearing of UV absorbing glasses has its advantage in that","options":["ocular fluorescence is completely eliminated","contrast is increased","sensitivity is improved","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Electric discharge from MPI equipment is usually only a problem when","options":["D.C. is used","A.C. is used","an explosive air-gas mixture exists in the area","when working underwater"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"An artificial discontinuity in a sample used to verify the effectiveness of a test system is a","options":["test piece","reference standard","notch","side drilled hole"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"In MPI testing artificial discontinuities are used for","options":["indicating field adequacy in the test object","determining equipment adequacy independent of the test object","determining the smallest sized flaw that can be detected","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The split prism test block utilizes which method of magnetization?","options":["an A.C. or D.C. yoke","a central conductor","prods","a coil"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The result of using \"shared flux\" discontinuity standards, such as the \"pie gage\", on convex surfaces is","options":["to verify depth sensitivity","insufficient magnetization will be used","excessive magnetization will be used","a good residual field under the gage"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Why is it actually incorrect to call the Hall detector meter a \"Gaussmeter\"?","options":["tesla is the proper metric unit","magnetic flux (B) would be measured inside the component","it actually measures field strength (H)","both b and c"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"On some small portable magnetic particle units there are 3 cable connection terminals.  They are for","options":["A.C., D.C. and ground","A.C., halfwave rectified and common","positive, negative and ground","north, south, centre"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The ballast in the power supply for the blacklight is a(n)","options":["autotransformer","isolation transformer","silicon controlled rectifier","programmable chip"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The requirement for an autotransformer to regulate current flow in a mercury vapour UV lamp is because","options":["voltage to the tube must be stepped down","the arc tube shows negative resistance and would destroy itself","of the high reactance presented by mercury","operators would forget to turn down the voltage after warmup"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The advantage of the 125W mercury vapour lamp over the 100W variety is","options":["less warm up time","up to maximum output faster","less susceptible to voltage fluctuations","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The large 400W flood lamp blacklights are used primarily for","options":["germicide purposes","locating large and medium sized indications","locating the finest defects with the finest particles","\"tanning shops\""],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Normal life expectancy for a 100W spot mercury arc lamp is about","options":["10 hours","100 hours","1000 hours","2000 hours"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"A 40W tubular UV lamp and a 400W mercury arc bulb have ______