above"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"In order to use a permanently magnetized block with a network of cracks as an MPI standard for evaluating a particle suspension you would need","options":["a perfect memory","photographic records","identical test conditions between test and standards","either a and c or b and c"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The great advantage of the prism block standard for evaluating the sensitivity and or effectiveness of an MPI suspension is","options":["accuracy for depth determination","speed compared to the settling test","its' ability to rate the total system","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"When performing visible MPI, lighting on the work surface","options":["is never left to the discretion of the inspector","is always left up to the inspector","may be left to the discretion of the inspector or may be specified by code or specification","is never to exceed 5,000 lux"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Even if a part is MPI tested by indirect means (ie. a central conductor) arcing can occur where the test part contacts other metal pieces.  The source of this arc is","options":["static discharge","Doppler effect","eddy currents","magneto-striction"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The requirement for dry magnetic particles to have a high permeability is especially important for","options":["circular magnetization techniques","longitudinal magnetization techniques","residual magnetism techniques","daylight fluorescent inspection"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The purpose of an NDT specification is to","options":["standardize test results","make the inspector liable in a lawsuit","to shift responsibility for potential part failure","ensure all defects are located"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The written document outlining the test parameters and acceptance criteria for a specific product is a","options":["code","specification","recommendation","standard"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Which of the following provides the NDT inspector with a brief outline of the steps to perform a test on a specific item?","options":["code","standard","procedure","specification"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Safety factors built into component design while still vitally important, are reduced to minimum values when","options":["the engineer has no liability","weight is a major consideration","all methods of NDT are performed","not building to an international code"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"In general, there is never a requirement for parts to be better than they were designed to be.  As a result, caution must be taken to guard against","options":["performing more than 1 NDT test per part","producing perfect parts","over-inspection","safety factors"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"A defect oriented with its major plane at right angles to the principal tensile stress is _________ compared to the same defect not a right angles to this stress.","options":["more likely to be harmful","less likely to be harmful","is benign","is benign if the tensile stress is a hoop stress"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Under controlled conditions, the width of an indication over a discontinuity that is wholly below the surface indicates","options":["defect height","defect width","defect depth from test surface","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"For a given linear defect lying completely below the surface, detectability _____________.","options":["increases with increasing permeability","decreases with increasing permeability","is unaffected by permeability","is unaffected by permeability only if D.C. magnetizing current is used"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Mill scale on steel plate can form non-relevant MPI indications because","options":["it cracks easily and the particles get wedged in the openings","the scale has slight permeability","the scale has such high permeability it prevents fields from getting into the steel being tested","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Localized cold working of steel can result in non-relevant indications.  These result from local increased hardness and are removed by","options":["de-magnetization","annealing or normalizing","surge-magnetizations","pounding the part with a soft mallet"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The problem with inspecting bearing race rings with a head-shot across the diameter of the diameter is","options":["distorted fields at the contact points","possible damage due to arcing","possible distortion due to excessive clamping pressure","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"A mixture with metallic properties composed of 2 or more elements, of which one of at least is a metal is a(n)","options":["alloy","isotope","allotope","metalo fiber"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Austenite is a nonmagnetic form of","options":["cobalt","iron","nickel","zinc"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Charcoal is an amorphous form of","options":["carbon","ferrous oxide","ferric oxide","calcium"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The main constituents of \"ordinary steel\" is (are)","options":["iron","iron and carbon","iron and nickel","iron, nickel and chromium"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"If a discontinuity is shallow and broad like a scratch, the flux lines may stream-line below the discontinuity.  This will result in","options":["a false indication","a non-relevant indication","a sub surface indication","a lack of indication"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Work hardening tends to decrease magnetic permeability.  Work hardened aluminium can be made more inspectable by MPI by","options":["annealing","carburizing","normalizing","none of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"\"Handling\" cracks located by MPI methods are typical of","options":["soft steel forgings","soft steel castings","gray iron castings","all of the above are subject to \"handling cracks\""],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"A metal that can be stretched easily without cracking is considered","options":["malleable","ductile","plastic","elastic"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"A metal that can be easily bent or permanently  distorted without rupturing is considered","options":["malleable","ductile","plastic","elastic"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"Defects found between prods are aligned _________ the line between the prods.","options":["outside","parallel to","perpendicular to","radially to"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The small regions between rivet holes are best MPI tested using","options":["prods","yokes","horseshoe magnets","swinging fields"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"When using magnetic rubber techniques to record MPI indications the magnetization is applied by","options":["AC or DC yokes","permanent magnets","conventional magnetic particle units","any of the above can be used"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"In the settling test for MPI, 3 components can occur, lint and dust, metal grindings and magnetic particle oxides.  Which will be the first to settle out.","options":["lint and dust","grindings","magnetic oxides","all will settle at the same rate"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"The magnetization experienced by a ferromagnetic material brought into the influence of an outside magnetic field is called","options":["remote field","inductance","leakage magnetization","transduction"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"When a HWDC yoke is equipped with articulating legs it is usually advantageous to have it also equipped with","options":["an ammeter","a fluxmeter","variable current control","a demagnetizing cycle"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"When checking the ammeter output of a conventional MPI unit the calibrated ammeter reading is checked against the unit's ammeter reading at a minimum of","options":["1 setting","2 settings","3 settings","5 settings"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":2,"question":"When small amounts of carbon are added to pure iron the result is","options":["non-magnetic iron","a \"super magnet\"","steel","stainless iron"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Although hysteresis measurements have sometimes been used to detect flaws, it is more often used to","options":["work harden steels","case harden steel","re-align domains","determine material properties"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Magnetic phenomena are explained as a result of electric  charges'","options":["relative proximity","magnitude","relative motion","rest mass"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"When two electric charges are brought to rest relative one another, the magnetic force between them is","options":["zero","proportional to the total charge","inversely proportional to the distance between them","inversely proportional to the square of the distance between them"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"If two long parallel conductors, 1 metre apart, each exerts a force of 2 x 10^-7 N/m of length of wire, the total current flowing in the wires is","options":["1 ampere","2 amperes","0.1 mAmp","1 pico Amp"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The magnetic induction that results in a torque of 1 N.m on a coil of the magnetic moment 1 A.m_, when placed with its axis perpendicular to the magnetic induction field is defined as","options":["1 coulomb","1 joule","1 Wb/m_","1 dyne"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The magnitude of a magnetic induction field at a perpendicular distance 'r' from the centre of a long straight conductor with a current 'I' amperes is","options":["inversely proportional to the current","proportional to the distance 'r'","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The use of closed loops to represent magnetic fields is based on an empirical evidence that","options":["Newton's second law of motion applies to magnetics","magnetic mono-poles do not exist","gravitons are ultimately responsible for magnetic forces","they can not be represented any other way"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"A material having all electrons paired can still show slight magnetic effects by electron perturbation when introducing an external magnetic field.  Such a material is considered","options":["paramagnetic","diamagnetic","ferrimagnetic","antiferromagnetic"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Magnetic domains in ferromagnetic materials","options":["encompass about 10^21 atoms","are usually about the size of a grain in a polycrystalline material","can be smaller or bigger than some grains in a polycrystalline material","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The summation of vectors representing the dipole moment per unit volume is represented by","options":["B","H","M","Z"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The ratio of the magnetic field intensity H, to the dipole moment vector M is referred to as the _____ of a material.","options":["permissivity","permeability","magnetic susceptibility","magnetic impedance"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Initial permeability is defined as the slope of the hysteresis curve at the","options":["origin of the virgin curve","maximum applied field","maximum field intensity (saturation)","point of maximum coercive force"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The largest value of B/H ratio along the virgin hysteresis curve is called the","options":["maximum permeability","saturation point","limiting field","incremental permissivity"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The magnetic field intensity required to reduce the magnetization \"M\" to zero is called the","options":["induction coercive force","magnetization coercive force","both a and b are correct","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Barkhausen jumps are a result of","options":["the state of a specimen's mechanical stress","movement of magnetic domain walls","magnetization rotation","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The ratio of magnetomotance to reluctance in a magnetic circuit gives the quantity","options":["magnetic flux","magnetomotive force","reluctance","admittance"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"In a magnetic circuit, a small air gap will provide a point of","options":["high reluctance","low reluctance","phase reversal","Barkhausen delay"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"To overcome detectability problems associated with magnetic field directionality in magnetic particle testing, magnetization of a test piece is required in at least __ directions.","options":["1","2","3","4"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Defect detection by magnetic particle testing relies on","options":["magnetic flux leakage","uniformity of geometry of a test piece","the Hall effect","all of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Which service defect would magnetic particle testing be used for?","options":["deformation","corrosion","wear","none of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Which of the following would be considered a service formed discontinuity","options":["fatigue cracking","heat treat cracking","cold shots","flash line tears"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Which of the following is usually accepted as being responsible for discovering magnetic particle testing as a means for locating surface cracks in magnetic materials?","options":["W. E. Hoke","A. V. de Forest","F. B. Doane","C. E. Betz"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"In very repetitive mass production tests, all variables of the test are controlled so that","options":["all defects are located","all defects exceeding a given length are located","only defects considered important are located","only subsurface defects are located"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Austenitic stainless steels contain large quantities of iron but magnetic particle testing is not recommended for them because","options":["the magnetic fields weaken the structure","they are non-magnetic","the coarse grain structure gives false indications","arcing sparks may ignite the metal"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Which of the following is a limitation of magnetic particle testing?","options":["relative expense to operate","ability to automate","ability to work through thin coatings of paint","none of the above would be considered a limitation"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Magnetic particle testing is preferred over ultrasonic and radiographic testing for locating","options":["forging bursts","shallow surface cracks","porosity","corrosion"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Which of the following magnetic discontinuities would indicate a defect?","options":["metallic discontinuity due to a force fit","the junction between two dissimilar ferromagnetic metals","the brazed joint between two magnetic metals","none of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Failure to remove the shrink cavity that forms at the top of an ingot will result in voids called __________ in the finished product.","options":["stringers","laps","pipe","hot tears"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"When certain elements of an alloy concentrate in the last-to-solidify liquid the discontinuity resulting is","options":["dissociation","dislocation","segregation","curie point deposits"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Liquid steel that splashes on the cool wall of an ingot mold and does not subsequently get reabsorbed by the main body of the pour, forms","options":["scabs","laps","seams","cold shuts"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"During the primary processing procedure of rolling an ingot, if the rolls become over filled the resulting discontinuity is a","options":["lamination","lap","cupping","flakes"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Flakes are internal ruptures in steel that are a result of","options":["too rapid cooling","release of hydrogen gas","abrupt thickness changes","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"A magnetic pole exerting a force of one dyne on a pole of equal magnitude one cm away defines one","options":["electromagnetic unit (emu)","Coulomb","Henry","graviton"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"What is the repulsive force between 2 like poles, one 30 emu. the other 40 emu, placed 6 cm apart in air?","options":["12 dynes","24 dynes","33 dynes","66 dynes"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"What is the net force between two bar magnets each 30cm long place in line with their north poles 10 cm apart (making the south poles 70 cm apart), assume a pole strength of 140 emu is concentrated at each pole.","options":["175.5 dynes attraction","175.5 dynes repulsion","280 dynes attraction","280 dynes repulsion"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"If the field intensity (H) in an induction field of an area in air is found to be 50,000 oersteds, what is the flux density in that field?","options":["50,000 gauss","50,000 webers","500,000 webers","cannot be determined"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Alignment of \"domains\" in a ferromagnetic material by the application of an external magnetic field is called","options":["domainization","magnetic resonance","nuclear resonance","magnetization"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The potential (voltage) measured across a Hall detector is inversely proportional to","options":["the current flow applied to the detector","the magnetic field strength","the thickness of the Hall detector plate","both a and b"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Magnetism produced in a ferromagnetic material by an outside magnetizing force is called","options":["permanent magnetism","temporary magnetism","magnetic induction","ferri magnetics"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"When a part is subjected to an increasing magnetizing force (H) until the induced field no longer increases other than that which would occur in air the point on the hysteresis curve is called","options":["the saturation point","the coercive force","the virgin curve","the induction turnaround"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The typical hysteresis curve is \"S\" shaped the point at the top of the \"S\" is the saturation point.  The opposite end of the \"S\" is termed their","options":["coercive force","negative saturation point","residual field","demagnetization point"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The inverse quantity of electrical resistivity is","options":["resistance","conductivity","reluctance","reactance"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The smoothest form of rectified AC voltage is","options":["half wave single phase","full wave single phase","full wave three phase","all of the above have the same quality voltage output"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The elimination of the reverse half of an AC cycle by electronic means results in","options":["half wave rectification","full wave rectification","pure D.C.","a short circuit"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The opposition to alternating current flow that results from a solenoid with an iron core is called","options":["resistance","reluctance","inductive reactance","capacitive reactance"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"3 phase A.C. from commercial supplies has the phases separated by","options":["60 degrees","90 degrees","120 degrees","different amounts depending on frequency"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"In electromagnetism, the product of the number of coil wraps made by a conductor and the current passing through that conductor is given as","options":["inductive reactance","abvolts","ampere turns","watts"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Induced electric current is produced by","options":["the transformer action","chemical reactions","van der Graaf generators","both a and c"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The inductance that results when 20 volts are produced by a change in current of 200mA in 0.1 seconds is","options":["0.1 henrys","1.0 henrys","10.0 henrys","100 henrys"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"A central conductor used in magnetic particle testing is used to _______ in a part.","options":["prevent arcing","generate a circular magnetic field","generate a longitudinal magnetic field","generate a multi-directional field"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"In magnetic particle testing, a short duration magnetizing current passed through a solenoid surrounding a part is called a(n)","options":["coil shot","encircling magnetization","central conductor shot","gap shot"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Any patch or cluster of magnetic particles occurring on a test piece that cannot be accounted for by a leakage field is considered","options":["anomalous","suspect","a false indication","a defect"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Multi directional magnetization provides","options":["2 or more magnetic fields in a part at the same time","2 or more magnetic fields in a part sequentially in rapid succession","only a coil shot and a head shot at the same time","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"If several magnetizing forces are applied to a piece simultaneously and one or more varies in direction or amount the result is","options":["multidirectional magnetization","a swinging field","a null field","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The reciprocal of resistance is","options":["conductance","conductivity","resistivity","ohms"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The reciprocal of resistance is conductance.  It is measured in units of","options":["ohms","micro-ohm.cm","codons","Mhos"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Ohm's law applies in","options":["all electric circuits","in AC circuits only","in DC circuits only","only in circuits where there is a linear relationship between voltage and current"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The sum of the currents flowing into a junction of an electric circuit is equal to the sum of the currents flowing out of the junction.  This statement describes","options":["Kirchoff's first law","Ohm's law","Thompson's law","Newton's second law"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The algebraic sum of the potential differences around a closed loop circuit is zero.  This statement describes","options":["Newton's third law","Kirchoff's second law","Snell's law","L.A. law"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Using modern theory current flow, if a conductor carried a current out of the plane of this paper (screen) ie. current flow towards you; the magnetic lines of force would move __________.","options":["clockwise","counter clockwise","towards you","away from you"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Field intensity at the centre of a typical 5 turn coil used for MPI would best be approximated by which equation?","options":["H = 2 I/10r","H = 2(pi)I/10r","H = 2(pi)NI/10r","H = 4(pi)NI/10r"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"A transformer, if connected to a D.C. supply on the primary side will result in","options":["a short D.C. voltage in the secondary coil","primary winding burn out","an AC voltage on the secondary side","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"A transformer in which the ratio of the primary to the secondary voltage equals the ratio of the number of turns in the primary and secondary coils is a(n) ___________ transformer.","options":["ideal","step up","step down","isolation"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"When the primary and secondary windings of a transformer are combined into a single tapped winding, at the expense of circuit isolation the result is","options":["an ideal transformer","an autotransformer","a step down transformer","a step up transformer"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The most significant disadvantage of using AC for MPI is","options":["detecting subsurface defects","the difficulty in demagnetizing the part","cost of equipment","lack of particle mobility"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Half-wave rectified AC is commonly used for magnetic particle inspection but cannot also be used for demagnetizing a part because","options":["of the skin effect","it produces circular magnetization in the part","the current does not reverse","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Three phase MPI units have a significant advantage over single phase units in","options":["simplicity of design","reduced current input requirements","safety features","that timed shots can be made"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Which is not a reason to demagnetize a part?","options":["subsequent machining of the part","subsequent painting or plating of the part","subsequent re-magnetization of the part in a different direction using higher field intensity","the part will be electrically welded"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"In addition to bringing a ferromagnetic material to its curie point, in order to demagnetize the part by heating what else must be done?","options":["rotate the part on its long axis","rotate the part on its short axis","cool in the absence of an external field","orient the part east-west"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The most thorough form of demagnetization is provided by which method?","options":["electromagnetic techniques","A.C. techniques","D. C. techniques","heating through the Curie point"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The reason for using several small decreases in current when demagnetizing a part by electromagnetic means is to","options":["prevent arcing","avoid electron precession","ensure the reverse field overcomes the coercive force","curtail leakage fields from transient currents"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"In order that a yoke with pulsating half wave D.C. be used to demagnetize a piece you must","options":["move the legs to the maximum separation","move the legs to the minimum separation","switch the unit off and on at 25 Hz","ensure the unit has a current reversing circuit"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"It is recommended that longitudinal magnetization be performed as the last step in a 2 step operation.  The purpose of this is","options":["to make demagnetization more effective","to allow the use of a field meter to check effectiveness of demagnetization","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The minimum number of reversals ideally required to demagnetize a part using D.C. demagnetization is","options":["1","2","5","10"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Fe2 O3 is composed of 2 types of atoms having anti-parallel electron spins that are unbalanced.  The result is","options":["no magnetic field on the macro scale","paramagnetism","ferrimagnetism","Carlsbad twining of crystals"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Unreasonable requirements for demagnetization levels called for in specifications should be","options":["used until the code is changed","modified in light of what needs to be done","disregarded completely","used on military contracts only"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Demagnetization using oscillating currents in a D.C. energized solenoid system operate at a frequency of","options":["25 Hz","50 Hz","60 Hz","resonance determined by the circuit"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Ring shaped parts passed through an A.C. coil demagnetizer should be","options":["\"rolled\" through the coil","held steady for 2 seconds in the coil","passed through the coil diagonally","sent through from left to right then from right to left"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"A qualitative substitute for a field meter is a(n)","options":["gamma gun","short length of light iron wire","dosimeter","ammeter"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Extremely fine dry powder magnetic particles are well suited to detect defects resulting in weak leakage fields; however, they are not suitable for production type inspections because","options":["they take too long to form indications","the cooling fans prevent them forming indication","excessive background masks indications","dry powder is not used for production type inspections"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"To reduce background and detect only large flaws using dry powder MPI you could","options":["use a mixture of only large particles","use a reduced magnetizing current","both a and b","do nothing, as all sizes of indications will always be detected"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Agglomerations of fine particles in the wet MPI method have the advantage of","options":["increased speed of movement through the carrier","increased visibility","reducing background","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The particle shape best suited for dry magnetic particle detection of broad shallow defects is","options":["spherical","elongated","flake","irregular"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Colours of magnetic particles are a result of","options":["natural oxide colours","bonded dyes","natural metallic colours","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The purpose of applying liquid penetrant developer or chalk in alcohol to the surface of a magnetic particle test piece is to","options":["improve electric contact","protect the surface against arcing","provide a high contrast background for viewing","perform oil and whiting testing simultaneous to the MPI test"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The advantage of water suspended magnetic particles as compared to oil suspended is in","options":["cost of the liquid","cost of the particles","safety","both a and c"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"In addition to the magnetic particles what else is mixed with the paste preparations purchased for the wet visible magnetic particle method","options":["corrosion inhibitors","wetting agents","suspension and dispersing agents","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The residual method of MPI is most reliable for","options":["surface defects","porosity","wire rope testing","soft iron specimens"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Failure to stop flooding a part with the magnetic particle bath at the same time the magnetizing current is cut off results in a poor test because","options":["excessive drainage occurs","weakly held particles can be removed","excessive background builds up","insufficient contrast results"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The development of the most effective MPI technique for a specific part is","options":["taken from military procedures","empirically derived","theoretically derived","usually with the wet fluorescent method"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The fluid containing magnetic particles for the wet method is sometimes referred to as","options":["flux pool","magnetic ink","magnetic soup","polar sausage"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Indications not well defined, such as sub-surface indications might be are usually termed","options":["diffuse","split","furry","flux indicators"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The purpose of the Sutherland flask in MPI testing is to","options":["pour magnetic ink over the test piece","establish intensity of fluorescence","determine the proportion of solids in the bath","calibrate the ammeter on the bench unit"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"In half wave rectified A.C., the peak current is","options":["zero","2^_ times the r.m.s. value","2(2^_) times the r.m.s. value","0.707 times the r.m.s. value"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The ferromagnetic portion of an electro-magnet, not surrounded by windings, forming a fixed magnetic circuit and serving to complete that circuit is also called a(n)","options":["core","yoke","solenoid","electrode"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"What is the term given to a test piece similar to the product being tested but having artificial or natural discontinuities similar in size or extent to the maximum acceptable in the product?","options":["acceptance standard","test piece","artificial flaw standard","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"A magnetic flux indicator having a cross-shaped discontinuity below an adjustable cover is a(n)","options":["ASTM flux meter","Berthold penetrameter","defect-o-meter","Ketos ring"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"In MPI testing techniques, magnetic rubber is used to","options":["erase defects","prevent arcing at electrode  contrasts","obtain replica castings of indications","damp out Barkhausen noise"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The equations which when combined with the appropriate boundary condition can be solved to describe all electro-magnetic phenomena are ____________ equations.","options":["Maxwell's","Einstein's","Poisson's","Gauss'"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The relative permeability of a paramagnetic material is","options":["0","approx = 1",">1","<1"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The choice of type of current to use for an MPI test is determined by which factor?","options":["defect orientation","location of defect (on or below surface)","colour of particle used","whether continuous or residual method is used"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"For a given output of magnetizing force, which is best adapted to portability and least cost in equipment?","options":["battery operated D.C.","A.C.","permanent magnets","all are about equal"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The peak current on a full wave rectified A.C. MPI unit reading 1000 amps would be","options":["500 amps","707 amps","1414 amps","200 amps"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The effect of increasing hardness of steel on the detectability of subsurface defects is to","options":["increase the threshold current required","decrease the sensitivity for a given current","both a and b","have no effect"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Maximum sensitivity from the continuous wet method is obtained when","options":["the part is immersed in the bath during magnetization","the magnetizing current is left on while the part is removed from the bath","the bath uses fluorescent particles","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"If the principal direction of potential defects in a part to be MPI tested is not known you should","options":["call an engineer","consult the manager","read the code requirements","do both longitudinal and circular magnetizations"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Which is not an advantage of using the central conductor technique to test tubular or hollow products?","options":["both inside and outside surfaces can be tested","both axial and circumferential flaws are detected","direct electrical contact need not be made","several small pieces can be tested at the same time"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Indirect circular magnetization is produced by","options":["a central conductor","prods","a head  shot","a coil shot"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"When the magnetizing current in an MPI test is passed through an auxiliary conductor to produce a useful magnetic field in the test part it is called","options":["indirect magnetization","parallel magnetism","longitudinal magnetization","direct magnetization"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Equations are often quoted recommending a specific number of ampere-turns for  longitudinal magnetization of parts.  It is usually a guide to ensure what minimum flux density in the part?","options":["1 gauss","100 gauss","100 lines per mm_","10^6 lines per mm_"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"When is the equation It = (1700R / �eff) used?","options":["for coil shots on parts with an L/D ratio >4","for coil shots on parts with an L/D ratio <4","for coil shots on parts centred in the coil","for central conductor shots"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The equations It = 45000 / L/D  and It = 35000 / L/D+2 are both guidelines for coil shots, the condition that differs for each is","options":["part permeability","coil to part diameter ratio","location of part in coil","no difference, one can be used instead of the other"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Given a solid steel shaft 1.5m long and 50cm diameter, what current setting should you use if you had a 5 turn coil and the part is not centred in the coil?","options":["1000 amperes","2000 amperes","3000 amperes","4000 amperes"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Given a hollow steel pipe section 75cm long, 25cm diameter with a 2cm thick wall, what magnetizing current would you use with a 3 turn coil if the part is placed at the bottom of the coil?","options":["1000 amperes","2500 amperes","3500 amperes","5000 amperes"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Given a steel bar 1 foot long and 2 inches diameter, what current should your coil shot use with a 5 turn coil and the part centered in a coil 300mm diameter?","options":["600 amps","1600 amps","3200 amps","6000 amps"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"If MPI is to be used on a part by means of prods and geometry prevents prod spacing of more than 45mm you should","options":["reduce current to 100 amps","use D.C. and minimum current","use A.C. and minimum current","use another form of inspection"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Paint on a part to be MPI tested need not be removed if","options":["indirect magnetization is used","its thickness is less than 0.1mm","the size of defect sought is not too small","all of the above criteria must apply"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"A 1/2 metre long pipe 5cm diameter is to be longitudinally magnetized using a 5 loop coil shot.  If the loop is 400mm radius what current is used when the pipe is centred in the loop?","options":["625","1250","2500","5000"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Should an irregularly shaped part have a long to short dimension (L/D) ratio of less than 2, in order to longitudinally magnetize the piece with a coil shot you would","options":["end pieces should be added to extend the length","coil diameter should be increased","coil diameter should be decreased","the number of loops in the coil should be decreased"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"When a part is subjected to the magnetic field of a D.C. yoke and the circular magnetization from an A.C. head shot, the result is","options":["a short magnetic circuit","a swinging field","no particle migration","halving the A.C. frequency"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"What is the reason A.C. yokes are constructed of laminated transformer sheet?","options":["to reduce eddy current loses","to increase depth of penetration","to prevent transformer black-out","for cost cutting reasons"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"A problem with indication formation when using the swinging field technique is","options":["indications are not held by magnetic force","indications are easily washed away by the bath","both a and b","there are no problems associated with the swinging field test method"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Effective permeability �eff can be approximated for coil magnetization of cylindrical objects by which relation?","options":["45000 / (L/D)","6 (L/D) -5","35000 / [(L/D)+2]","piD_"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"In order that the standard equation for current be used, what is the maximum diameter bar that can be tested by coil shot when centred in a coil 40cm diameter?  ie. cross-sectional area of bar not to exceed 1/10 the coil.","options":["44cm","63cm","126cm","160cm"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Four bars of the same alloy steel are cut and to be circularly magnetized using a 1000 amp head shot.  Which bar will have the greatest surface field strength?","options":["10mm diameter 1000mm long","15mm diameter 1000mm long","20mm diameter 500mm long","25mm diameter 100mm long"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"You are given 3 conductors each 2cm diameter and 30cm long.  Two are non-magnetic, one solid the other hollow; and one is ferromagnetic and solid.  Which will have the strongest field at a distance of 3 radii from the centre if each is carrying 1000 amps D.C.?","options":["the non magnetic bar","the non magnetic tube","the ferromagnetic bar","none of the above, all will be equal"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"When steels of high permeability are MPI tested the formulae for calculating magnetizing current to use","options":["are totally useless","over estimate requirements","under estimate requirements","are applicable no matter what value permeability is"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"If a long rectangular bar, 2cm X 6cm is circularly magnetized using the 40 A (D.C) per mm about 2400 amps would be used, where would maximum field strength occur?","options":["in the middle of the 2cm face","in the middle of the 6cm face","at the corners","none of the above, field would be uniform around the surface"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"When D.C. is passed through an irregularly shaped part the current is","options":["distributed evenly over the cross-sections","concentrated on the outside surface","concentrated on the inside surface","concentrated on the sharpest curves and edges"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Calculations for coil shot current requirement stipulate length to diameter ratios from 2 to 15.  If the part has an L/D ratio of less than 2 you should","options":["use a different NDT method","use 2 in the equation","use an extension on the piece of the same material as that tested","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Calculation for coil shot current requirements stipulate they be used for length to width ratios of 2 to 15.  If the L/D is greater than 15 you should","options":["use a different NDT method","replace the coil shot with a head shot","use the value 15 in the equation","reduce the coil diameter"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Half wave rectified A.C. is preferred over D.C. because of","options":["better particle mobility","reduced power consumption","less heating of equipment","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Circular magnetism is preferred over longitudinal magnetization for what reason?","options":["less current is needed","fewer poles result which could cause confusion","equations to calculate current are simpler","most defects are located by circular magnetization"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"A critical limitation to the settling volume test for determining wet MPI bath concentrations is","options":["the expense of equipment","the application to aerosol spray preparations","time required for the test","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"When performing A.C. yoke MPI on a part having a restrictive geometry such that both legs of the yoke cannot be used to straddle the area, an optional technique would be to use","options":["A.C. yoke leg extensions","the single leg technique","a D.C. yoke","the through wall MPI method"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Because the permeability of air is _______ the magnetic field indicator can be used to measure both the magnetic induction field in air and the magnetic field strength in air.","options":["0","1","compensated by a permanent magnet","calculated after saturation"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Because the magnetic permeability of air is 1 a magnetic field indicator can be used to measure both the magnetic induction field in air and the","options":["magnetic field strength in air","reluctance of the test material","permittivity of the test material","magnetic resonance of the test material"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Why is it impractical to design a magnetic field indicator using a single strong magnet and a spring to return the indicator needle to zero?","options":["changes in the magnet's strength would require constant recalibration","a strong poled sensing magnet would induce magnetism in the test piece","both a and b","none of the above, most magnetic field indicators infact use a single magnet and zeroing spring"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The NDT method having the worst record for reliability and repeatability of crack detection in ferromagnetic parts is","options":["liquid penetrant","magnetic particle","ultrasonics","radiography"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The Ketos ring has been a Standard in the MPI test method since 1941; however, it is not a reliable standard because of variations in","options":["permeability","hardness","alloy","resistivity"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Quantitative artificial flaws are essential for","options":["setting up procedures","establishing acceptance standards","evaluating performance","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Specifications (such as Mil-STD 1949A) have been modified to allow 1 hour settling time instead of the previous 1/2 hour because","options":["some manufacturers couldn't meet the specifications","increased safety requirements for flash point requires higher viscosity carriers","larger proportion of smaller particles are now required to detect smaller defects","both b and c"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Misinterpretations result from observations to meet the specification for fluorescent baths which states \"for fluorescent baths, examine the liquid directly above the precipitate with UV light.  The liquid shall be essentially nonfluorescent.\"  The misinterpretation is caused by","options":["insufficient concentrations of particles","fluorescence of submicron particles that have not settled","excessive UV light intensity","viewing with safety glasses"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Due to load demands on power supplies ___________ is the preferred current for MPI on larger parts.","options":["three phase full wave rectified","single phase full wave rectified","single phase half wave rectified","all of the above place equal demands on supply"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"When plotting width (or height) of MPI indication versus magnetizing current for surface breaking seams in billets, a more linear curve results when using","options":["D.C.","full wave rectified 3 phase D.C.","larger sized particles","smaller sized particles"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Occasionally a thick MPI indication will form as a result of wet particle attraction to deep seams.  Once the current is turned off the indication collapses and smears the background.  This may be prevented by","options":["adjusting particle concentration","adjusting current strength","both a and b","none of the above, it is intrinsic of the flaw characteristics"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Magnetic particle baths used for billet inspection tend to have a greater proportion of larger particles than small.  The reasons for this is","options":["small particles tend to get caught in scale","the fine shallow defects located by small particles are not important in billet inspections","small particles take too long to form indications","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"When magnetic rubber replicating techniques are used, the orientation of a crack into the part can be determined by","options":["symmetry or asymmetry of particle accumulation in the setting medium along the indication length","orientation of the elongated particles","dip direction of the indicator penetrameter","video enhancement techniques"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The number of amperes of magnetizing current or ampere-turns to use on a test piece will be specified by a","options":["code","standard","a general specification","a specific specification"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The frequency response of a gauss/tesla meter should be","options":["D.C.","0 to 60 Hz","0 to 300 Hz","60 to 1 kHz"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"When performing an MPI test on a coated part, maximum coating thickness that can be tolerated is","options":["determined by demonstrating detectability of minimum allowable defects","25 �m for ferromagnetic coatings","75 �m for non- ferromagnetic coatings","both b and c"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"A sharp magnetic particle indication has formed on testing a large (3m diameter) submerged arc circumferential seam.  The indication runs for the complete circumference and an acid etch shows the indication to occur at the weld-parent metal fusion line, but no visible non fusion is seen.  What is the probable source of the indication?","options":["magnetic permeability difference between metals","subsurface crack","subsurface slag","subsurface non-fusion"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"At the skin depth, also considered the standard depth of penetration, the magnetic field intensity resulting from a 60 Hz A.C. in steel is","options":["zero","22% of its surface value","37% of its surface value","not possible to determine"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Maximum curvature of external magnetic flux leakage fields occurs for","options":["narrow surface breaking defects","wide shallow surface defects","subsurface defects","curvature is the same regardless of defect shape or position"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Which of the following flux sensitive devices is time dependant?","options":["magnetodiode","a long straight wire","flux gate magnetometer","the ferroprobe"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Which of the following flux sensitive devices is not time dependant?","options":["a long straight wire","a Hall detector","search coils","ferrite core coils"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The Hall voltage generated in a Hall detector is","options":["inversely proportional to the Hall coefficient","directly proportional to the sensing crystal thickness","inversely proportional to the sensing crystal thickness","inversely proportional to the current applied to the sensing crystal"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The reason for using a high frequency A.C. voltage on the semiconductor crystal in a Hall sensor is to","options":["increase bandwidth","avoid resonance in the sensor","eliminate the thermoelectric voltage component","improve response to the deeper sources of flux"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Which of the following compounds is a commonly used semi-conductor material used as a Hall detector sensor crystal?","options":["InSb","OsO","NaCl","ZrNb"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"In the semiconductor magnetodiode flux sensing device the p-zone and n-zone are separated by the","options":["pn zone","dm zone","recombination zone","interzone"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Which form of artificial lighting could not be used to view daylight fluorescent dry magnetic particles?","options":["normal incandescent lights","sodium vapour lights","mercury vapour lights","white fluorescent tubes"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The dry powder method of MPI would not be used for","options":["surface discontinuities in welds","hot tears in castings","grinding cracks","any of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The primary consideration in storage of dry magnetic particles is","options":["temperature","moisture","electric fields","light intensity"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"At temperatures of around 150�C. fluorescent powders lose their visible contrast.  This is because","options":["the pigments are organic compounds that decompose at elevated temperatures","some fluorescent organic compounds lose their ability to fluoresce at a particular temperature","of the Curie temperature effect","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"A typical minimum light intensity of 1000 lux is recommended for viewing non-fluorescent dry powder.  This may be barely adequate if","options":["the test surface is dark or covered with scale or rust","the test surface is rough machined","the test surface is finely polished","safety glasses are worn"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"AMS 3040 is a specification for properties of magnetic particles properties.  One test requires a glass cylinder of specified dimensions be stuffed with the powder to be tested.  The powder in the cylinder is used as the core of a transformer coil.  For 11 kA/m input on the primary, a minimum of 2.5V must occur in the secondary with the correct circuitry.  Since the volume of the cylinder limits the amount of powder the test limits the amount of","options":["inert pigment and resins in the powder","large sized particles that can be used","small sized particles that can be used","all of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The difference between red iron oxide (alpha) and brown iron oxide (gamma) apart from colour is","options":["magnetic properties","crystalline structure","one is used for MPI and the other is not","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"For fine wet particles, those with high permeability are no more effective than those of only moderate permeability due to","options":["magnetic breakdown","the monopole effect","the shape demagnetization factor","compensation by specific gravity differences"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Most specifications for establishing properties of oil carriers for wet MPI will state","options":["minimum viscosity","maximum viscosity","maximum viscosity at a specified temperature","minimum fluorescence permitted"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"In wet method of MPI testing when water is used as the carrier, conditioners are used to","options":["inhibit rust formation","enhance wetting of particles and test surfaces","reduce forming that results from agitators","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"When too much antifoaming agent is added to the water vehicle for wet fluorescent MPI testing what is the result?","options":["cavitation","loss of the bath's wetting ability","formation of the only large bubbles","particle breakdown"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Sodium nitrate and sodium chromate are the traditional rust inhibitors added to water based MPI baths.  They are no longer recommended because","options":["they accelerate fluorescent particle breakdown","the concentrations needed cause pitting in the metals tested","of their high level of toxicity","cheaper options are now available"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Use of anti-freeze in water based MPI baths is not feasible as a method to prevent freezing because","options":["it would etch steel","it enhances foaming","the viscosity would exceed recommended limits","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Oil contamination in a water vehicle MPI bath can result in","options":["congealing particles","destroying the wetting ability of the bath","disbonding of pigments from the ferro cores","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"To overcome the sticky mass that occurs as a result of water contamination in an oil bath for MPI you can easily","options":["filter out the water","use a skimmer","add a small amount of oil soluble emulsifier","heat the bath with an immersion heater to boil off the water"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Maintaining a strict control on particle concentration in the MPI bath eliminates which variable in an MPI test?","options":["indication to background contrast","visibility of indications","mobility of particles","magnitude of current required"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Particle concentrations in MPI baths are specified by","options":["weight of particles per volume of bath","settling volume of particles per volume of bath","both a and b","parts per million (ppm)"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Some specifications require the sample of MPI bath be de-magnetized before performing the settling test.  What is the reason for this demagnetization?","options":["magnetic condition of bath can affect settling rate","repulsions effects can increase the apparent settled volume (fluffing)","attraction effects can decrease the apparent settled volume (compacting)","both b and c"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"In general, centrifuge tubes having narrower settling stems (1.5mL, 1.0mL, and 0.2mL stems available), tend to __________ for the same bath.","options":["show lower concentrations","show higher concentrations","show equal concentrations","produce faster settling"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Online continuous monitoring methods are not often used to establish MPI bath concentrations because","options":["cost of equipment is too high","accuracy is reduced since contaminants cannot be allowed for","both a and b","no such equipment exists"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The lower limit for part temperature when using MPI in an oil vehicle is","options":["20�C.","0�C.","-20�C.","variable from oil to oil and depends on viscosity at a given temperature"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Measurement of E-M radiation at all wavelengths is the concern of","options":["radiometry","photometry","photospectroscopy","spectrometry"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"__________ is concerned with the measurement of E-M radiation in the visible region only.","options":["radiometry","photometry","optometry","occularity"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"To convert from radiometric units to photometric units you must","options":["take the sum of the power radiated at each wavelength times the relative luminosity of the eye","divide by the photosensitivity factor","use the Kodak equation","multiply by 1 ie. they are equivalent"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Visible light is usually considered to have wavelengths in the range of","options":["350 to 800 nm","3500 to 8000�","400 to 760nm","both a and b are correct"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The variable response exhibited by an average eye as it crosses over from scotopic to photopic vision is termed","options":["mesopic vision","myopic vision","hypermyopic vision","A. C. vision"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"At the area around the point of the retina where visual axis strikes there is a slight depression called the fovea.  The cells in this area are almost exclusively ____________-.","options":["mutanogenic","rod shaped","cone shaped","dichotomous"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Under good viewing conditions for fluorescent MPI, indication contrast ratio can be a high as","options":["5:01","20:01","200:01:00","1000:01:00"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Reasonable probability of MPI indication detection would require a brightness contrast ratio of at least","options":["2:01","10:01","50:01:00","100:01:00"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"A pure red MPI indication with wavelengths 600nm on a background of pure blue at 470nm having equal brightness","options":["causes eye strain","has poor brightness contrast","has poor colour contrast","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"As ambient lighting changes from bright daylight conditions to dim blacklight viewing conditions maximum colour sensitivity of the eye changes from","options":["green to yellow","yellow to green","orange to blue-violet","blue to red"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The preferred gas for use in vapour arc lamps used for blacklight production is","options":["argon","mercury","neon","sodium"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"For extended viewing of visible magnetic particle indications of critical tests requiring 2000-5000 lux lighting the effect may be","options":["eyestrain","eyeball fluorescence","cataracts","none of the above, 2000-5000 lux is only slightly higher than normal room lighting."],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Laser light sources are often used in non-imaging detector systems for MPI because","options":["coherent light is easier to detect","they produce narrow and intense beams","they can be made to emit light in the yellow-green light range","defects preferentially absorb coherent light"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Photoelectric sensors used in scanners for non-imaging MPI detector systems are","options":["always set to have the same sensitivity as the human eye","used to determine defect depth","rarely the same brightness or colour sensitivity as the human eye","all capable of holographic projections"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"In MPI of aerospace components, copper penetration resulting from prod or electrode contact will cause","options":["rejection of the part","distorted current flow","distorted flux patterns","both b and c"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"What is the risk if a nonrelevant MPI indication is encountered?","options":["actual discontinuities can be masked","actual discontinuities can be interpreted as nonrelevant","both a and b","none of the above, non relevant indications are self evident"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"If the results of an MPI test make you suspect the indication seen is nonrelevant, originating from hardness or alloy differences, you would","options":["double check results by magnetizing a different direction","verify using penetrant or ultrasonic methods","reject the part (\"when in doubt throw it out\")","accept it if it shows up on a similar piece in the batch"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"A letter or number hardstamped into a part and ground off prior to MPI testing can result in","options":["local changes in the part's magnetic properties","nonrelevant indications","magnetic writing","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Burned out or low output mercury arc bulbs should be","options":["returned to the manufacturer for recharging","disposed of in a glass recycling bin","disposed of as hazardous waste","shipped to third world countries for continued use"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Mercury arc UV bulbs should not be handled with bare hands because","options":["finger prints reduce intensity","acidity of fingers can cause glass failure","finger greases alter the output spectrum","you don't know where they've been"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Calibration of an MPI machine used to apply magnetizing current to a part requires","options":["comparing current readings on the machine to a calibrated ammeter","a flux meter","lifting a specified weight, depending on type of current used (A.C. or D.C.)","a combination of a and c"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"To determine if magnetizing fields are present and balanced in a multidirectional operation you would use a(n)","options":["Hall detector","MPI shim gage","field indicator","Ketos ring"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Fully automated magnetic particle inspection systems can only be cost justified if","options":["large numbers of parts are tested","parts tested have similar size","parts tested have similar shape","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The magnetic particle testing portion of an automated system can be a time consuming step.  To decrease the inspection time in such a setup you would","options":["use multidirectional magnetization","increase magnetizing currents","increase conveyor speeds","decrease the duration of the \"shots\""],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"In an automated scanning system for MPI testing, the photodetector is","options":["a photomultiplier tube","a vidicon camera","a photomultiplier","any of the above can be used as the photodetector"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The flying spot scanning system requires _________ to permit the system to discriminate rejectable discontinuities from background noise.","options":["material handling accessories","pattern recognition algorithms in the CPU","a laser bar-code reader","an RF signal averaging programme"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Automated MPI systems that include the ability to scan and sort indications require some form of ___________ processing or algorithms.","options":["pattern recognition","light filter","intensity threshold","positional encoded"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"When tape transfers are used to record an MPI indication","options":["the record is complete","written descriptions of part and orientation are still required","acrylic sprays must be added to preserve the tape and prevent loss of particles","both b and c"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"For tape transfer recording of fluorescent particle indications, best results are had if","options":["non-fluorescent cello-tape is used","black or dark coloured paper is used for backing","both a and b","the residual technique is used"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"If taking a tape transfer of an MPI indication where a water carrier has been used, the drying of the surface can be accelerated by","options":["short blasts of compressed air","gentle rinsing with acetone","vibrating the part","2 or 3 sharp taps with a soft faced hammer"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"When tape transfers are used as a means of MPI test records the adhesive often dries out and tape becomes brittle thereby limiting the time it can be archived.  Under optimum conditions the tape transfer record might last","options":["6 - 12 months","1 - 2 years","5 - 10 years","10 - 20 years"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Rubber replica records of MPI indications are bulky.  Archival is often accomplished by","options":["photographing the indication in the replica","sectioning the replica sample and gluing pieces on paper","using a heat gun to shrink the sample similarly as one shrinks heat shrink tubing","compactor units"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"If it is determined that the \"magnetic rubber\" requires deaerating, it is done","options":["prior to initial mixing of the base","just prior to the addition of catalyst","just after the catalyst and stabilizer are added","after the total mixture is on the test piece"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The reason for long duration magnetization shots when using the magnetic rubber method is","options":["the requirement of \"dams\" for the rubber","high viscosity of uncured rubber","prod or leg spacing must be greater to accommodate the dam structure","particle size is extra small so more are required to form the indications"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Photography as a means of high quality recording of MPI indications is very costly because","options":["it is labour intensive","equipment is costly","many exposures may be needed to optimize results","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The reason not to use A.C. for residual MPI is","options":["the depth of penetration","the uncertainty of which point on the hysteresis curve you cut off the current","the back EMF from eddy currents keep the residual field below the flux density threshold for MPI","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The \"laid-on-cable\" technique used in MPI of welds requires the cable be spaced away from the test surface and the return loop be about ten times this space away from the first loop.  The applied current is determined by","options":["the spacing of cable off the test surface","the cable length along the weld","weld crown width","specimen thickness"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The advantage of the \"laid-on-cable\" technique for MPI of weld is","options":["convenience for underwater testing","no danger of arc burns","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"On irregular shaped specimens, the magnetic field is more likely to follow the surface contours if","options":["prods are used","fixed coils are used","D.C. is used","A.C. is used"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Lead contact covers used on prods for MPI testing should only be used in well ventilated areas because","options":["increased current draw dims lighting","over heating causes noxious fumes","galvanic reactions occur when lead and copper are brought into contact","when high currents are passed through lead the oxygen level in the air is depleted"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The process whereby a magnetic tape (similar to that used in a tape recorder) is placed on a test piece during magnetization then removed and processed for analysis and results viewed on stripchart or oscilloscope screen is called","options":["magnetography","Hall-o-graphy","ferrography","magneto-sonics"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Magnetic susceptibility for _______ materials is a positive value.","options":["ferromagnetic","paramagnetic","diamagnetic","non-magnetic"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Magnetic susceptibility for ______ materials is a negative value.","options":["ferromagnetic","paramagnetic","diamagnetic","non-magnetic"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The region on the hysteresis loop's virgin curve where the flux density B increases in a non-linear fashion with increasing field intensity H, is termed the","options":["Rayleigh region","virgin region","non-coerced region","totally recoverable region"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"In magnetic studies using a Rowland ring, by removing the effect of H from B you can plot","options":["magnetostrictive effects","a magnetization curve","remnant curves","a straight line for all ferromagnetic materials"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Ferrites are used as cores for \"pick-up coils\" in magnetic flux leakage amplifiers.  Their advantage for this purpose originates because","options":["amplification occurs without inducing eddy currents","of their high thermal conductivity","of their high electrical conductivity","both b and c"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"In low carbon steels, chemical composition, inclusion density, residual stress and heat treatment can determine which magnetic property?","options":["saturation","remnance","coercivity","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The measure of how far from unity (1) permeabilities of dia and paramagnetic materials is / are termed","options":["magnetic susceptibility","relative permeability","incremental permeability","reluctance"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"From a magnetizing point of view, the worst case scenario an MPI inspector would encounter when performing a circular magnetization on a part is","options":["the material is initially magnetized to maximum remnance in the opposite direction to his inspection","the L/D ratio exceeds 7","the L/D ratio exceeds 15","the part is too long to fit between the head stocks"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"In pulsed or capacitor discharge magnetization techniques the effectiveness of a lower amplitude current will be greater for deep flaws than a high amplitude current if the pulse length of the low amplitude current is longer.  This is due to","options":["the inverse reluctance of steel tubes","the limiting depth of penetration by eddy currents","L-C-R resonance effect","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The miniature Hall detectors which have Hall sensor and regulated power supply on a chip have the advantage over sensing coils that","options":["they approximate point sensors","output is not a function of relative velocity through the magnetic field","they can be used on longitudinal circumferential and radial magnetic fields","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The reason some specifications do not permit MPI by passing current directly through the part is","options":["insufficient sensitivity","risk of arc burns","excessive furring results","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The Burmah-Castrol strip is","options":["a portable surface field indicator","the region of high flux density between weld metal and heat affected zone","the region of high flux density between parent metal and the heat affected zone","a magnetic tape for archiving MPI test results"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"A typical level of field strength in a part considered to be demagnetized is","options":["O Oe (zero)","1-2 Oe","no more than 10 Oe","no more than 50 Oe"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"In order for a component to achieve a minimum specified service life after an NDT inspection has accepted it, it is important for the NDT engineer to allow for","options":["operator error","sub-critical crack growth","fracture toughness","shock loading"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The choice of the NDT method to use is dictated primarily by","options":["cost in time and manpower","ability to automate a system","the largest defect that might be overlooked","number of parts to be tested"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"When indications are not formed on a test piece being tested by MPI what is the reason?","options":["part is defect free","part is not ferromagnetic","no current or too low a current","any of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The advantage of re-usable magnetic particle bags is that they","options":["are non-contaminating and have good sensitivity","simplify clean-up and require little or no preparation","both a and b","none of the above, there is no such apparatus"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"A threshold exists in the detectability of flaws using MPI for which parameter?","options":["flux density in the part","lighting for evaluation","number (density) of particles on the test piece","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The magnitude of the magnetic leakage field is determined primarily by the","options":["absolute permeability","flux density in the region","stresses remaining in the material","type of current used"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"For a code or specification to stipulate a minimum flux density be achieved in a test piece for MPI testing is","options":["not practical since it cannot be easily measured","based on HWDC testing","a result of Ketos ring tests","only applicable to coil shots"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"To compensate for variations in relative magnetic permeabilities, codes and specifications","options":["recommend using swing fields","use conservative estimates of permeability","require use of HWDC","require use of MPI penetrameters"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The shortcoming of stipulating particle concentration as an indicator of magnetic particle suspensions is","options":["particle breakdown can not be discerned","no information is had about the ability of the suspension to form indications","contaminants can be included unknowingly","no shortcomings exist"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Which artificial test piece is the most reliable for evaluating performance of an MPI particle suspension?","options":["pre-magnetized pieces such as the German MTU","flux shunt type-pie gage","flux shunt type-wire indicators","all of the above are the same"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Completely automatic cameras used in auto mode are not recommended for photography of MPI indications because","options":["they always underestimate light intensity","depth of field is not adequate","they cannot normally compensate for the extreme exposure conditions","too much film is wasted by the auto-advance"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The purpose of a shutter release cable in photography of MPI indications is","options":["to allow the operator to avoid the UV flash","to minimize or eliminate camera motion","to co-ordinate magnetizing current and shutter release","unclear, but all MPI indication photographers use them"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Photography of fluorescent indications is only possible if","options":["UV filters are used","the blacklight is turned off and a UV flash is used","35mm films are used","blacklight illumination angle to the test surface equals the angle the lens views the indication"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The best all around UV filter for fluorescent indication photography has its cut off at ____________.  This allows an image most resembling that seen by the human eye in a darkened booth.","options":["355nm","390nm","420nm","460nm"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Polarizing filters can be used for photography of fluorescent indications if UV filters are not available since they effectively block UV light, however they have the drawback that","options":["only 10% to 25% of visible light is transmitted","exposure times are greatly increased","they can only be used with reflex lenses","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Reciprocity failure is a problem that exists when performing photography of fluorescent indications.  It is a result of","options":["filter fluorescence","long exposure times","polarization due to the Brewster angle","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Alternate north and south poles, which can result from magnetic chucks or lifting magnets, are recognized by","options":["alternate north and south poles in close proximity","increased surface roughness","an inability of the ferromagnetic material to hold magnetic particles","the depoling of a permanent magnet brought into contact with it"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Reversing direct current contact demagnetization is usually used for","options":["parts that were D.C. magnetized","parts where A.C. demagnetization is not effective","both a and b","none of the above, D.C. contact is not recommended for demagnetization"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"In reversing D.C. magnetization of a part using a coil, the test piece is","options":["held stationary in the coil","rotated during the step down process","drawn through the coil during stepdown of current","sprayed with magnetic particles to verify demagnetization"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Reversing D.C. demagnetization is often incorporated into the design of large bench units for what reason?","options":["safety","economic","portability","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Pulsating reversing D.C. coil demagnetization has the advantage over A.C. coil demagnetization in that","options":["penetration is far greater","less current is required","it is faster","higher residual field strengths can be removed"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"In general Hc (coercive force) increases with","options":["retentivity","permeability","part hardness","domain size"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Which of the following demagnetizing methods would be used in high production rate demagnetization of small, medium hardness steels parts?","options":["cable wrap A.C.","cable wrap D.C.","through current (decaying current)","none of the above are recommended"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Coil demagnetization of parts with L/D ratios less than 3 is a problem.  This is solved by","options":["rolling the parts through the coil","adding ferromagnetic pole pieces to the object's ends","surge currents in the coil","moving the part into the coil so the part straddles the coil then rotating the part 180� and then continue to move the part through the coil in the same direction"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Specifications requiring residual fields less than 0.3 mT are often unreasonable because","options":["the earth's field is usually greater than this","no technique other than heating to above the curie point can achieve less","in most cases, subsequent machining or welding, or instrumentation is not affected by this level of field","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The presence of a small axial field strength at the end of a tube indicates","options":["the last magnetizing shot was a coil shot","no circular magnetization exists in the part","the vector sum of fields has a slight axial component","both a and b"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The lowest temperature at which a liquid gives off gases sufficient to form an ignitable vapour at the liquid's surface is the","options":["flash point","dew point","lower explosive limit","upper explosive limit"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Above the upper explosive limit volatile petroleum distillates used in MPI testing will","options":["spontaneously explode","explode only if exposed to an open flame","explode if exposed to a cool spark","will present no explosive hazard as concentrations are too rich to burn"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"What are the 3 classifications of ultraviolet light?","options":["actinic, germicidal and short","UV-A, UV-B and UV-C","long, short and ultrashort","darklight, blacklight and invisible light"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"UV light from wavelengths of 100nm to 280nm are used in","options":["NDT fluorescent viewing","sun tanning salons","sterilization and germicidal purposes","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The purpose of the blacklight's ballast is to","options":["provide the lamp's starting voltage","regulate current to the arc","both a and b","shut off the heater resistor"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"What allows current to flow in the high pressure quartz tube of a mercury vapour lamp upon initial start-up?","options":["the high value resistor","argon gas","mercury vapour","conductive quartz"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The pressure inside the quartz tube of a mercury vapour regulates, to a large extent, quality of the emission spectrum.  What is the pressure, in atmospheres, of the gas in the quartz tube of a blacklight used for fluorescent indication viewing?","options":["1","10","100","1000"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"In the standard mercury vapour lamp, the quartz cartridge is housed in an outer bulb filled with","options":["mercury vapour at positive pressures","an inert gas at positive pressures","an inert gas at lower than atmospheric pressure","a vacuum"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"After about 4 minutes warmup time the blacklight has reached its peak irradiance.  After that, when left running with a constant voltage","options":["output slowly decreases to an equilibrium  value","out put remains constant","output remains constant except for occasional sputtering of the mercury vapour","the spectrum content gradually shifts to mostly UV-B"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The \"blacklight blue\" glass filter envelope around the ultraviolet light tubes is coated on its inside surface with","options":["mercury paint","an aluminized coating","bluish white phosphor","nothing"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Although UV-A produced by blacklights used in fluorescent indication viewing for NDT is not believed to be a health threat, you should","options":["avoid direct exposure to hands and eyes","keep hand exposures of 5000�W/cm_ to less than 200 seconds","both a and b","none of the above since UV-A is considered safe"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"When the electric field strength exceeds the breakdown value for air the result is","options":["a spark","magnetic coupling","generation of free radicals","formation of an unstable isotope"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"When MPI is performed in grain elevators or flour mills there is a danger of","options":["an explosive air-gas mixture being ignited","an explosive air-dust mixture being ignited","magnetic fields stimulating yeast growth","both a and b"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"In order to establish a correlation between the response of an NDT test system and the severity of a discontinuity _______ are used.","options":["artificial discontinuities","reference standards","codes","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Regular use of a reference standard during a test will","options":["ensure the smallest detectable defects are found","ensure consistent results","maximize the number of rejectable pieces","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"To avoid excessive flux densities resulting from traditional empirical formulae used in MPI testing","options":["always use half the calculated current","reference standards are used","codes and specifications are being rewritten","eddy current is recommended"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Experiments on ketos rings indicated a lack of uniformity (1986 experiments).  For the same conditions, different rings would show different numbers of hole indications.  This was accounted for by _____ differences between rings.","options":["hardness","annealing","chemistry","none of the above-it could not be accounted for"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"When an object is tested using a D.C. coil, the so called \"quick break\" magnetization utilizes ________ to detect transverse defects at the ends of the test object.","options":["capacitor discharge","eddy currents","liquid nitrogen cooled Hall detectors","RF filters"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Photosensitive eyeglasses darken in the presence of UV radiation.  This makes them","options":["ideal for blacklight viewing safety purposes","ideal for enhancing contrast and sensitivity","useless for blacklight viewing of indications","both a and b"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The current to the blacklight is regulated by an autotransformer.  The autotransformer has the unique feature of having","options":["both primary and secondary coils combined into a single tapped winding","an air core","a double output (secondary) winding","a vacuum core"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"A single rod conductor 10cm long moving at 10m/s through a 10,000 gauss magnetic field at right angles to the field will induce what voltage between the ends of the rod?","options":["1 mV","1 V","10 V","100 V"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"A wire 10cm long cuts a magnetic field of 10,000 gauss at 45� moving 10m/s.  What voltage is induced between the wire ends?","options":["141 mV","0.7 V","14.1 V","7 V"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The intensity of blacklight irradiance (�W/cm_) from a 400W flood lamp mercury arc lamp as compared to a 100W spot mercury arc lamp (both with plain filter) as measured at the beam centre at the same axial distance is","options":["16 times greater","4 times greater","1/2 the intensity","1/10 the intensity"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Apart from its health hazard, a potential risk of breaking the tube containing the mercury in the mercury vapour lamps is had from","options":["mercury causing particle breakdown","the MPI test may have to be redone","mercury contacting aluminum or other metals can cause cracking","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Gross errors or differences may exist between UV output measured from a calibration lamp and the lamp in question even though the lamps are nominally the same eg. 100W spot.  Why?","options":["the UV meter is never accurate","the lamp spectra are different","the calibration lamp is \"absorption\" calibrated whereas the standard UV lamp is \"emission\" calibrated","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Ultraviolet radiometers used for NDT all use","options":["high pass filters","low pass filters","bandpass filters","no filters"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Even if all UV sensors were calibrated and found to be identical, measurements of a given UV lamp at the same distance would have different values if different manufacturer's meters were used.  This is because","options":["no 2 filters are the same","the area of the UV sensor varies for each manufacturer","the spectrum of the lamp is not constant enough","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The most important variable when testing a piece coated with a thin non-conductive layer (such as paint) with an A.C. yoke is","options":["the getting sufficient flux into the part","getting sufficient flux leakage out of a defect site","both a and b","none of the above, A.C. yokes cannot be used on painted surfaces"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"For underwater MPI it has been found that the A.C. yoke can be used in the \"single leg\" technique.  The magnetic field produced for this is","options":["longitudinal","circular","radial","swinging"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Small cracks in steel plate that has been sandblasted are best tested for using","options":["LPI","MPI","Rayleigh waves (UT)","eddy current"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Which property of magnetic particle suspensions is not an important factor considered by the inspector?","options":["consistency (repeatable results)","relative sensitivity (compared to others)","cost per unit tested","signal to noise ratio"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"When using the prism block standard for evaluating a magnetic particle suspension, increased quality is indicated by","options":["length of indication","breadth of indication","depth of particles forming the indication","number of facets on the prism that have been covered by held particles"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The addition of extension pole pieces to A.C. yokes has the effect of","options":["increasing field strength midway between the poles","decreasing field strength midway between the poles","changing the field pattern from longitudinal to circular","changing the field pattern from circular to longitudinal"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Although it has been proven that some defects can be located through some types and thicknesses of paint, a reason to remove paint for MPI testing is","options":["paint type and thickness is not known","HWDC yokes cannot couple through paint","both a and b","none of the above, defects are hidden by paint removal techniques"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"When inspecting pipes using A.C. and rectified A.C. circumferential magnetization, pipes should be insulated from each other and insulated from metal racks they might be supported by.  This is because","options":["adjacent metals demagnetize the inspected part","arcing can result from the induced eddy currents","excessive particle build up at the contact points will result","none of the above, there is no need for such insulation"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Arcing is of concern in MPI testing of some parts because","options":["it can cause unwanted local hardening","it can result in a preferential corrosion site","it will hinder subsequent ultrasonic or radiographic testing","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"A nonlegal document that is written by a recognized association of some authority, that recommends actions to achieve certain goals is considered a","options":["specification","standard","code","working procedure"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"A standard when made enforceable by making it a legal document (law) is then considered a","options":["specification","code","by-law","procedure"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"An NDT procedure does not normally include","options":["acceptance criteria","testing sequences","calibration requirements","equipment requirements"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The use of \"safety factors\" in the design of an item is to","options":["eliminate the need for NDT","shift liability to the inspector","allow for unknown or unpredictable stress concentrations or operating conditions","require the use of more material in fabrication making the unit robust"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"In MPI testing, a design constriction in the metal path through which the flux must flow results in","options":["reduced flux flow","non-relevant indications","loss of magnetic coupling","\"short-circuiting\" the magnetic circuit"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"If a defect is suspected in a region of MPI non-relevant indications, such as from splines, you would","options":["demagnetize the piece and remagnetize at a current level just below that required to form the non-relevant indications","reinspect the part with a different magnetizing direction","use liquid penetrant to verify the results","scrap the part"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"The non-relevant MPI indication found on curved cold rolled plate and having an incomplete criss-cross pattern 45� to the axis of curvature are caused by","options":["inter granular cracking","intra granular cracking","Luder lines","segregation of alloy constituents"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"When a metal is heated to a predetermined temperature (below melting point) and holding it there for a period of time then cooling it at a slow rate, it is said to be","options":["annealed","work hardened","normalized","recrystallized"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Metal's crystalline structures that are reversible through transformations are termed","options":["allotropic","eutectic","ferrotopic","transmorphic"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Austentic or gamma iron is normally stable only at high temperatures unless _____________.","options":["told otherwise","alloyed with another metal such as chromium or nickel","held at the curie temperature","the Neel temperature is exceeded"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Lower temperature plastic deformation resulting in strain hardening of a metal is","options":["tempering","cold working","normalizing","decarburization"],"correct":1},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"After an MPI test post cleaning of a part that is irregular shaped and made of soft steel can be especially difficult because","options":["of demagnetization being incomplete","the particles used are very hard and imbed themselves into the part","particle dyes tend to run and discolour the piece","the carrier fluid is not emulsifiable"],"correct":0},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"A binary alloy having a lower melting point than its neighbouring compositions is considered","options":["anomalous","a solder","a eutectic alloy","austenized"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Killed steel is steel that has been","options":["demagnetized","D.C. magnetized","deoxidized","quenched in oil"],"correct":2},{"method":"MPI","level":3,"question":"Quenching is a means of rapidly cooling a metal by","options":["immersion in liquids","immersion in gases","direct contact with another metal","all of the above"],"correct":3}]$NDTA_SEED$::jsonb)
  as t(method text, level int, question text, options jsonb, correct int);
