el":1,"question":"When preparing an alkaline solution for precleaning you should","options":["add warm water to the alkali salts","add cold water to the alkali salts","add weak acid to the alkali salts","add alkali salts slowly to cool water"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Strong acids or bases used to preclean parts may be present after precleaning.  These can be removed by","options":["water rinse","a neutralizing rinse","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Masking and plugging of a test piece are done to","options":["preserve surface conditions","prevent ingress of penetrants into hard to clean areas","allow for different penetants to be applied","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"If not removed from the test piece, developer powder can","options":["interfere with processing","increase corrosive action","interfere with part fitting or operation","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Post inspection removal of dry powder developers is","options":["the most difficult developer to remove","by water rinse or air blast","best achieved using solvent cleaner","accomplished by ultrasonic cleaning"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"A good job of precleaning will result in","options":["money savings","reduced rework","fewer missed defects","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"The change of state from a liquid to a gas or vapor is called","options":["condensation","evaporation","sublimation","freezing"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"The way in which penetrant enters a defect is by","options":["gravity","negative pressure","positive pressure","capillary action"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"The force responsible for developer drawing penetrant from a flaw is","options":["gravity","electro static","electro magnetic","capillary"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"The smallest opening you could expect a good liquid penetrant to enter is","options":["1 nano-metre","1 micro-metre","1 milli-metre","1 centi-metre"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Penetrants with high flash points are more likely to have","options":["high toxicity","low fluorescence","high rep. rates","low evaporation rates"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Microscopic cracks can be made visible with visible dye penetrant because","options":["Snell's law provides a magnification of indications","developers provide a contrasting background","developers tend to enlarge crack width by spreading dye","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Plastic film developers are used","options":["on plastics only","for maximum sensitivity","if permanent records are wanted","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"All indications found by NDT methods are","options":["rejectable","direct","indirect","dimensionally correct"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"In order to reliably interpret a liquid penetrant indication the inspector should","options":["know the capabilities of the test method","be aware of the test material (alloy)","know the work history of the part","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"The liquid that transports the detectable dye is called","options":["oil","ketone","carrier fluid","dye penetrant"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"A block used to examine the effectiveness of one liquid penetrant (or technique) relative to another is called a","options":["penetrameter","penetrant comparator","calibration block","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"The action of developer in soaking up penetrant to cause maximum bleedout for increased sensitivity is called","options":["blotting","casting","dislocation","crack formation"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"The process of determining whether or not a part is acceptable is called","options":["interpretation","evaluation","discrimination","inspection"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Seams, cold shuts and forging laps share what in common?","options":["all are unique to steel","all give linear penetrant indications","all are service defects","LPI is the only method to detect them"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Penetrant indications of porosity in ceramics","options":["appears the same as in metals","are difficult to find with LPI","do not exist","have different shapes depending on firing temperature"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Which of the following are you likely to find on an LPI procedure?","options":["brand name and type of penetrant used","details of pre-cleaning, application and dwell time","details of removal, developer and development time","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Cracks in plastics occur","options":["upon cooling from a molten state","during handling and assembly","as a result of inservice operations","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"The source of impurities in molten metals which can result in LPI indications is","options":["dissolved or entrapped gas","non-metals such as oxides and sulphides","slag","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Although not the most valuable or reliable method of evaluation, this is the most popular LPI evaluation tool,","options":["cracked aluminum comparator block","hydrometer","light meter","nickel-chrome test panels"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"The usual standard quench cracked metal comparator block is made of","options":["aluminum","stainless steel","titanium","whatever is available"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Cracked aluminum comparator blocks and chrome surface crack test panels provide","options":["quantitative comparisons of materials and techniques","qualitative comparisons of materials and techniques","a means of estimating crack depths","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Analysis of halogen and sulfur content of penetrant materials is the responsibility of the","options":["metallurgist","NDT engineer","penetrant materials manufacturer","any of the above may be assigned the responsibility"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Liquid penetrant inspection  materials","options":["present no pollution hazards","can be easily removed from the ecosystem","contain many potential pollutant materials","are lobbied against by Pollution Probe and Greenpeace"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"The most obvious and therefore most troublesome source of pollution from LPI materials is","options":["remover solvents","dyes","developer powders","emulsifiers"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"In testing of aluminum plate, liquid penetrant testing is preferred over ultrasonics to locate","options":["very fine porosity","bursts","laminations","crater cracks"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Liquid oxygen systems use a specially designed penetrant called LOX safe.  This is used almost exclusively in which industry?","options":["nuclear","aerospace","automotive","electronic"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"If a discontinuity is wider than it is deep the best LPI technique is to use","options":["water-washable penetrant","post-emulsifiable penetrant","solvent removable penetrant","visible dye penetrant"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Many lubricating oils are somewhat fluorescent and penetrate well.  If not removed they may result in","options":["excessive bleedout","false indications","double intensity of indications","excessive indications"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"If it is possible to salvage a part after visible LPI locates a defect","options":["reinspection is not necessary","the indication may be left on for the person repairing it","reworking must occur immediately","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Rinsing of visible dye penetrant","options":["can only be done with approved nozzle spray","continues until the red colour is removed from the surface","should not take more than 15 seconds","should not take more than 45 seconds"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"The rinsing aid required in the post-emulsifiable technique is","options":["water","sponge or rag","emulsifier","black light"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"When applying dry powder developer it is important to ensure","options":["the powder is well mixed","the part is completely dry","the part is above 25 degrees C.","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Specific gravity is checked using a","options":["hygrometer","hydrometer","three point balance","litmus paper"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Accumulations of used fluorescent penetrant in the inspection booth","options":["cause false indications","cause reduced dark adaptation","should be removed annually","poses no concern"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"The least likely system to contain contaminants or degradation of its constituents is","options":["kits using aerosol-spray cans","automated dip tanks","small manual dip tank baths","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Ingestion of penetrant materials from aerosol spray cans is","options":["lethal","likely to cause gastric upsets","harmless","recommended for dermatoses"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"A somewhat linear intermittent penetrant indication would be formed by a","options":["crater crack","hot tear","forging lap","cold shut"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"If the washing (removal) of excess penetrant is insufficient the result will be","options":["false indications","missed defect","poor contrast","removal of shallow defects"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Lack of penetration would be a defect found when doing a penetrant inspection of","options":["castings","forgings","plastics","welds"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Sharp penetrant indications are caused by","options":["pores","crater cracks","tight narrow discontinuities","P. E. techniques"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"To ensure reliability of the LPI system periodic inspections are required by governing specifications for","options":["penetrant material","penetrant equipment","both a and b","there are no such specifications for LPI"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"An effective way to avoid missing defects due to penetrant system malfunction is to","options":["use approved materials only","do a system performance test daily","use the aluminum test block on the first of each month","test all pieces twice"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"If an inspector is viewing a faint fluorescent indication that is poorly contrasted he will usually","options":["turn up the black light voltage","get his eyes closed to the work surface","use a brighter fluorescent dye","resort to the visible dye method"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"The human eye becomes more sensitive to light when","options":["dark adapted","light adapted","t.v. adapted","sleeping"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Exposure to ultraviolet radiation is regulated by","options":["the Ministry of Health","the Atomic Energy Control Board","the Radiation Protection Board","none of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Having verified the sensitivity required using a cracked aluminum plate, the inspector should ensure production pieces inspected using this technique use","options":["the same type of penetrant","the same drain and developer times","compatible materials","the same material and times"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Fluorescent penetrants tend to lose colour brilliance as a result of","options":["exposure to high temperature","exposure to light","contact with emulsifiers","contact with developers"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"More resistant fluorescent penetrants tend to be","options":["more green than yellow","more sensitive to tight flaws","less sensitive","unstable"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Comparison of penetrant sensitivity to the unused control standard is performed","options":["daily","monthly","yearly","by the manufacture"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"Materials used in liquid penetrant inspection should be checked against an unused standard","options":["daily","annually","periodically depending on the material and property","by the manufacture"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":1,"question":"A cooler in conveyor LPI inspection system is","options":["a quench tank","used to cool parts coming from the drier","set at 4 degrees C.","never used"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"In NDT, liquid penetrant testing had its origins in","options":["the brittle lacquer method","the ringing technique","the oil and whiting technique","the work done by Dr. Rontgen"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Penetrant tests can be used on","options":["ferrous metals","non-ferrous metals and powdered metals","ceramics, glass and plastics","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Detectability of a defect by LPI is affected by","options":["the surface condition of the test piece","the geometry of the defect","the \"family\" of penetrant being used","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"When preforming LPI on very large surfaces (ie. several  hundreds of square metres)","options":["you should apply penetrant with a paint brush to the    whole surface","you should apply penetrant to a small area at one time and complete the test prior to testing the next area","multiple nozzle sprayers should be used for washing","colour contrast method is best to use since no black   light need be carried around"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"LPI is preferred over MPI on ferrous metals","options":["when many small parts of complex geometry are to be inspected","to verify that a defect is \"surface breaking\"","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"When working with ferrous metals, magnetic particle is preferred over liquid penetrant because","options":["they can detect subsurface as well as surface cracks","they can detect cracks filled with contaminant","in general, it is faster and cheaper","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The single most important feature of fluorescent penetrant testing is","options":["its seeability under \"dark light\"","economic advantage","great penetrating ability","ability to find shallow open defects"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"A penetrant makes its way into fine cracks and openings by","options":["wetting action","gravity feed","static attraction","capillary action"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The purpose of an emulsifier is","options":["to mix with the penetrant to allow it to be washed off  with water","to protect the reservoir","to reduce dwell time","to reduce toxicity of the penetrant"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"A wet developer is one in which the developer powder is","options":["in suspension","in solution","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Fluorescence is the abililty of a substance to","options":["glow in the dark","absorb white light and retransmit in the infrared       region","absorb infrared light and transmit visible light","absorb ultraviolet radiation and convert a portion of it to a longer wavelength and retransmit it as visible light"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Penetrability is influenced by surface tension, wetting   ability and viscosity, but only with respect to","options":["each other","a specific test surface","the density of the penetrant","ambient temperature"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Highly volatile substances are not used for penetrants because","options":["they would dry inside the defects","they would be too hard to clean off","loss of material would occur when used in open          containers","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"For the purpose of safety, manufacturing standards usually limit flash points of penetrants to","options":["under 55 degrees C","under 100 degrees C","over 55 degrees C","over 100 degrees C"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The result of too long a dwell time of a penetrant containing an emulsifier on an aluminum part can be","options":["pitting","cavitation","excessive bleed out","blotching"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The most popular method of evaluating a penetrant is","options":["the fatigue test bar","the aluminum test block","plated strips","the Meniscus test"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"An example of a processing crack is","options":["hot tear","crater crack","fatigue crack","forging crack"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Which is not a defect which occurs during service of a part?","options":["forging crack","fatigue crack","stress-corrosion crack","heat checks"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Penetrant indications of porosity are","options":["always acceptable","occasionally rejectable","twice the diameter of the pore","four times the diameter of the pore"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Microshrinkage is a characteristic discontinuity primarily associated with","options":["aluminum forgings","milling at too low a speed","magnesium casting","stainless steel castings"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"A correlation study between nondestructive and destructive testing is used to","options":["develop spot check inspection frequency","establish accept/reject criteria","establish effectiveness of a penetrant","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Liquid penetrant testing of plastics is done to","options":["ensure final product is free of defects","save money by eliminating flawed parts prior to further working","select good raw material and improve processes","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Some sort of testing should be done at various stages of manufacturing so that","options":["several departments can share inspection costs","different test methods can be used","costs are cut by eliminating unsuitable material","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"In the cracked aluminum test block, the purpose of the 2mm wide groove is to","options":["provide a trough for excess penetrant","indicate the middle of the block","separate the two test sections","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Although the usual cracked comparator block is made of aluminum, they can also be made of","options":["steel","titanium","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Post emulsified penetrants were developed in the 1950's specially for inspection of","options":["turbo-prop blades","high temperature ceramics","jet turbine blades","investment castings"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Separating penetrant and emulsifier in the post emulsified method optimises","options":["penetrability","washability","drain time","capillary action"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"An advantage of post emulsifiable liquid penetrant inspection is","options":["its ability to detect shallow open defects","its ability to detect tight, fine defects","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Post emulsifiable penetrants can be made with","options":["high tolerance to acids","high tolerance to chromates","high concentration of dyes","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Which is not a disadvantage of the post emulsifiable method","options":["low water tolerance","increased handling","cost","fillet and keyway inspection"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Water evaporating into air at atmospheric pressure would do so _________ as compared to evaporating into a vacuum","options":["slower","at the same rate","faster","not at all"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Reducing the prevailing atmospheric pressure to the vapor pressure of a liquid at the existing temperature results in","options":["an igniting of atmosphere","boiling of the liquid","condensate formation","freezing"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Capillary force is proportional to","options":["size of surface openings","surface tension","contact angle","all of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Capillary force is inversely proportional to","options":["surface tension of the liquid","contact angle the liquid makes to the test surface","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The LPI method used to test malleable iron castings because","options":["malleable iron is not magnetic","magnetic particle testing is not reliable","LPI is faster","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The PE method is preferred on forged jet turbine blades to locate","options":["shallow oxide filled laps","tight seams","shallow porosity","micro shrinkage"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Defects in forging dies are located using","options":["magnetic particle testing","colour contrast penetrant","a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Billets are cut to form","options":["forging blanks","extruding blanks","both a and b","stubs on \"Le Metro\" in Montreal"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The actual amount of light reflected or emitted by an indication is called","options":["seeability","contrast","sensitivity","emission constant"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"All colour contrast penetrant dyes are viewed with your eyes adjusted for","options":["scotopic vision","photopic vision","myopic vision","polyoptic vision"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"In scotopic vision (dark adapted) the eye's maximum colour sensitivity shifts down to the","options":["blue-green","yellow-green","blue","ultraviolet"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Black light used in penetrant testing has its peak at","options":["5550 angstroms","4850 angstroms","4250 angstroms","3650 angstroms"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Fluorescent dyes can be purchased which fluoresce with","options":["yellow-green colour only","yellow-green and blue green colour","in many colours from blue to red","red colour only"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Fluorescence of dye can be reduced by","options":["exposure to UV light","acid","heat","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Dry concentrate yellow fluorescent dyes are used primarily","options":["for verification of indications found with normal dyes","in liquid oxygen environments","as a transportation cost savings method","where large volumes of liquid are required for leak detection"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Dye fluorescing indicators were designed to provide good visibility of cracks without","options":["developer","precleaning","a black light","all of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Acid etching has been successfully used in penetrant testing to","options":["increase contrast","remove thin layers of grease prior to testing","increase the surface width of cracks","increase fluorescence"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Anthracene and fluoranthene, present in some fluorescent dyes, are considered","options":["carcinogenic coal tar products","the most favourable of dyes to use","contaminants","best used on aluminum"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Developer increases seeability of a defect by","options":["blotting action","providing a reflective base for penetrant viewing","covers confusing backgrounds","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Sharp definition of defects is accomplished by","options":["long dwell time","frequency of black light used","particle size and shape of the developer","solvent developers"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Developers may be of several types","options":["dry powder and water suspension","water soluble and solvent suspension","both a and b","neither a nor b"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Dry developers should be","options":["able to cling to dry metal","non-hygroscopic","non-toxic","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Removal of developer is accomplished by","options":["water or solvent wash","air blast","mechanical washer","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Wet developer is applied","options":["before drying","before washing","before emulsifying","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"If used with fluorescent dye, a wet developer usually has a ph value","options":["on the acidic side","on the alkaline side","neutral","none of the above, ph is not important"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The lowest practical temperature for testing with water suspendible developers is","options":["20 degrees C","0 degrees C","4 degrees C","40 degrees C"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"A risk of leaving water suspendible developer on some aluminum alloys is","options":["surface corrosion and or pitting","interference with machining","the thermite reaction","surface hardening"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Solvent suspendible developers are used primarily in","options":["fluorescent penetrants","oil and whiting","colour contrast penetrants","post emulsified penetrants"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Removal of solvent developers is usually accomplished by","options":["wire brush or high pressure water blast","water or solvent washing","steam cleaning","removal is not necessary as it flakes off"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"On rough surfaces the best developer to use with fluorescent penetrants is","options":["dry-fluffy","water suspendible","water soluble","solvent suspendible"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The only means of ensuring cracks are free of water from previous operations and/or cleaning is by","options":["heating","vapour degreasing","dry-cleaning","solvent cleaning"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"A major problem with aerosol spray application of penetrants is","options":["lack of sensitivity","uneven application","excessive propellant","wasted material through overspray"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"If drain time is in excess of 30 minutes","options":["defects may be blurred","more penetrant may be added","extra developer is needed","fluorescent penetrant is not effective"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The single most effective aid to penetration of penetrant is","options":["vibration","preheating the part","vacuum","preheating the penetrant"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Use of a cloth dampened only slightly with a solvent is","options":["slow for large quantities","effective for spot checks","both a and b","not recommended practice"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The removal technique that removes the most penetrant from defects is","options":["solvent wash","water wash","post emulsified waterwash","rag wiping"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Use of water to remove penetrant is best applied by","options":["damp cloth","dipping","hose and nozzle","bucket and sponge"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The emulsifier applied in the P.E. method is to react with","options":["the metal surface","the developer","the surface film of penetrant","cleaning solvent"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Compressed air is used in drying on","options":["hard to get at recesses","large surfaces","production line inspections","compressed air is not used for drying"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Compressed air when used to remove gross amounts of water","options":["speeds drying time","forms better indications","blurs defect indication","is a waste of time"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"In the post emulsified system, the function of hot air drying after penetrant removal is","options":["to remove excess water","to heat up the test piece","to decrease dwell time","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"A good dryer should have","options":["thermostatically controlled moving air","a conveyor belt","a vent for fumes","safety interlocks"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The 'part' temperature when drying is completed should be about","options":["225 degrees F.","65 degrees C.","room temperature","100 degrees F."],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The rule of thumb for development time is","options":["twice the penetration time","the same as the penetration time","one half the penetration time","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Where cleaning has been by wiping or solvent and no dryer is available the preferred developer is","options":["dry powder","solvent","water suspended","any of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The most frequently used developer for colour-contrast penetrants is","options":["water soluble","dry powder","water suspendible","solvent supendible"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Reprocessing a part after the initial penetrant inspection will usually result in","options":["new indications being found","irrelevant indications","reduced sensitivity","identical results if not repaired"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"A significant risk to optimum results with water-washable fluorescent penetrant is","options":["light leaks","over developing","over washing","excessive pre-cleaning"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"It is not recommended to use water-washable fluorescent penetrant below","options":["110 degrees F.","70 degrees F.","10 degrees C.","0 degrees C."],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Contaminants introduced in to water-washable penetrants will","options":["render the penetrant useless","have different results depending on penetrant and contaminant","float to the bottom of the tank","float to the top of the penetrant"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Water contaminated water washable fluorescent penetrants can be recognized by","options":["opaque appearance and thick texture","unusual clarity","water drops on the penetrant surface","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Chlorinated solvents contaminating your penetrant tank are introduced from","options":["mixing families of penetrants","solvent removers","evaporation","vapour degreasing"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The preferred colour for liquid penetrants used in leak detection is","options":["yellow-green","green-blue","orange","red"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Addition of fluorescent agents to operating hydraulic systems","options":["prevents formation of leaks","eliminates a step in the LPI method","allows on line black light inspections for leaks","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The accidental introduction of acid into fluorescent penetrant will result in","options":["turning the penetrant opaque","no change","a slight increase in drain time","destroying the fluorescent dye"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"If a 200 litre tank of penetrant has a water tolerance of 8%, how much water can be added before it must be dumped?","options":["800 ml","17400 ml","1.6 l","18 l"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"A 250 litre tank of penetrant has water tolerance of 15%.  How much water is added before it must be dumped?","options":["15 l","15 ml","375 ml","44.1 l"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"A 100 litre tank of penetrant has water tolerance of 18%.  How much water can be added to the tank before it is not useable?","options":["82 ml","22 l","180 ml","1800 ml"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"When removing water washable penetrant from large parts with hose and nozzle, you should","options":["start at the top and move down","start at the bottom and move up","start in the middle and work out","not worry about wash direction"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"When removing water washable penetrants detergents added to the wash water should be","options":["strong","weak","compatible","avoided"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Contamination of developer by drops of penetrant is serious because it results in","options":["spurious indications","large balls","small balls","total destruction of the developer"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"If using a circulating pump to agitate a wet developer bath, ensure","options":["wetting agents are used","anti-foam agents are added","no air is introduced by the pump","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"In order that fillets and recesses do not entrap excess wet developer","options":["the part is run twice","the dryer temperature is increased","the part is turned during drying","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"If inspection of parts is delayed","options":["indication from larger defects loose sharpness","small indications become prevalent","retesting is needed","wet developer can only be removed with vapour degreasing"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"For occasional blacklight viewing of small parts inspectors use","options":["curtained booths","small table top viewing cabinets","enclosed rooms","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"As little as ______ ft candles of black light energy is needed to detect gross defects","options":["20-30","90-100","200-300","900-1000"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"If a part has excessive fluorescent background due to poor washing in should be","options":["re-tested starting with pre-wash","re-washed","re-developed","rejected"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The fundamental difference between post-emulsified penetrant and water-wash penetrant is","options":["dwell time","development time","type of developer used","there is no fundamental difference"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"In the post-emulsified method, washability is controlled by","options":["dwell time","emulsification time","developer time","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"After emulsification and washing, the post emulsifiable method is the same as the water-washable method except for","options":["drying time","development types available","inspection lighting","no exceptions"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Generally, post emulsifiable penetrants have a penetration time ___________ water washable penetrants.","options":["longer than","shorter than","the same as","twice that of"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Post emulsifiable penetrants have the best qualities to re-run parts several times because of","options":["ease of removal by vapour degreasing","no residue being left in defects","low tolerance to water","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The close attention that must be paid to _________ is an annoying aspect of the post-emulsifiable method.","options":["precleaning technique","part surface condition","developer time","emulsification time"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Post emulsifiable penetrants tend to have longer life before deteriorating than water washable penetrants because they have","options":["less volatility","greater tolerance to water","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The most harmful contaminant to post emulsifiable penetrants is","options":["fatty acids and cutting oil","water","rust particles","chromates"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Viscosity is used to determine drag out.  Units used to measure viscosity are","options":["poundals","m/sec","centistokes","milligravs per cc"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Maximum penetration times are likely to be used when using post-emulsifiable penetrants when looking for","options":["porosity in steel castings","cracks in glass to metal seals","laps in magnesium","segregation in titanium alloys"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Penetration time with post-emulsifiable penetrant is minimum for","options":["steel","aluminium","manganese","plastic"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"In the post emulsifiable method the risk of overwashing is","options":["greater with cold water","greater than in the water washable method","about the same as the water washable method","no risk"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"There is evidence to indicate the most sensitive developer to use with the post emulsifiable penetrants is","options":["water suspended","water soluble","solvent soluble","dry powder"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Some inspectors doubt the usefulness of developer.  It can be established by","options":["rejection statistics","draw-out values","aluminum test block","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Near ultra-violet radiation causes","options":["phosphorescence","fluorescence","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The notable difference between phosphorescence and fluorescence is","options":["effecting radiation","persistence after applied radiation","frequency to transmitted light","temperature"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Dyes used in fluorescent penetrants fluoresce in the _____ region of visible light.","options":["blue-green","yellow-green","red and orange","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The most common colour for dyes to fluoresce is in the blue-green range because","options":["maximum seeability is achieved","it offers highest sensitivity","it is most favourable seeing for the eyes","cost of material is lowest"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"It has been found that the optimum wavelength for blacklight to energize fluorescent dyes is","options":["365 nm","260 nm","4000 angstroms","5500 angstroms"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Kopp 41 is a type of","options":["penetrant","emulsifier","glass filter","developer"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Small tubular blacklights and incandescent black lights have limited use","options":["due to the intense heat generated","where gross defects are the only concern","in hospitals","for high intensity daylight fluorescent penetrants"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The purpose of the resistor in series with the heating element on the quartz tube of the mercury vapour lamp is to","options":["act as a ballast","limit current to the heater","provide a spark to the mercury","regulate light output"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The 400 watt mercury arc black lights","options":["are not suitable for portable inspection","function in the same manner as the 100 watt lamps","provide 10 times the illuminated area of 100 watt lamps","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The seeability of a fluorescent indication","options":["is inversely proportion to blacklight intensity","is proportional to black light intensity","is proportional to the wavelength of black light","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The best way to determine the effect of variations in line voltage on the output of a mercury vapour lamp is by","options":["ohm meter","ammeter","shunt meter","light meter"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Mercury vapour blacklights, due to filters, dirt, and lack of ventilation, can heat up to very high temperatures.  The result is","options":["eye fatigue","increased aging of the lamp","increased hazards to the operator","pressure drop in the mercury vapour"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"If a mercury vapour blacklight is switched off, then required to be used again within 5 minutes it will","options":["not need the 5 minute warm up time","probably not work","cause the quartz tube to over pressurize","risk shorting the starter electrode"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"If line voltage drops below 90 volts a mercury vapour lamp may","options":["burn out","shut off","explode","emit more near UV light"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"If line voltage increases to above 120 volts a mercury vapour lamp may","options":["burn out early","shut off","explode","exit less near UV light"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"When inspecting a part with a black light the beam of light should be","options":["at right angles to the part","at an angle to the surface and away from the eye","at an angle to the surface and towards the eye","a minimum of 20 cm from the part"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"To obtain good photographs of black light indications it is recommended to use","options":["very short exposure times","only polaroid film","slow speed film","high speed film"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Visibility of indications in the colour contrast method is hindered by","options":["opacity of developer to white light","transparency of developer to black light","requirement for flat white background","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The actual cost of colour contrast penetrants may be more than fluorescent penetrants because","options":["the market is larger and manufacturers can make higher profits","less demand merits higher pricing","more dye must be added to the penetrant","sufficient profit is make on black lights"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"A significant consideration in using red dye in colour contrast penetrants is","options":["cost","its high degree of solubility","low flash point","high flash point"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"A suggested penetration time to locate cracks and pores in welds using non-water wash colour contrast penetrants is","options":["1-2 minutes","2-5 minutes","10-20 minutes","20-40 minutes"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Water based developers tend to dry","options":["unevenly","faster than solvent based developers","slower than solvent based developers","at defects first"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"In colour contrast inspection of parts, glare from intense white light reflected off the flat white developer causes","options":["eye fatigue","\"shine\"","reversal","reduced sensitivity"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"If rerunning a test using colour contrast penetrant the part should be","options":["emulsified and washed","vapour degreased","pre-heated","dipped in the penetrant for the total dwell time"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Equipment for application and handling in penetrant inspection is usually required","options":["if large numbers of small pieces are tested","for a high degree of repeatability of sensitivity","when large parts are regularly inspected","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"In a well equipped shop, the various penetrant operations are assigned as specific","options":["stations","booths","rooms","stops"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Agitation of liquid penetrant in dip tanks","options":["is accomplished by rotating agitators","is accomplished by bubbling air","prevents de-homogenization","is not required"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"For high production inspection of large parts a facility may be equipped with","options":["sewer treatment equipment","overhead or roller conveyors","wooden floors","big dip baskets"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"For emulsification of large areas on large parts not possible to dip, application is best accomplished by","options":["brushing","multiple sprays","hose and nozzle","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The use of black lights at the wash station is advisable, however outside light exclusion","options":["is difficult","is not possible","is not required","is mandatory"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Recirculating hot air dryers can be automated by means of conveyor belts whose speed is","options":["50 mm per sec.","100 mm per sec.","200 mm per sec","coordinated with proper drying cycle"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Dust control of the very light \"fluffy developer\" is accomplished by","options":["specially fitted covers","suction openings at the top of the bin","developer guns","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Agitation and application of developer by means of pumps may have the disadvantage of","options":["clumping","foaming","over spray","no disadvantage is risked using pumps"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Sorting as to acceptable or rejectable is done at the","options":["inspection station","developer station","post cleaning station","any of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Low output sealed blacklights can be used to replace mercury arc tubes","options":["if output exceeds 100 watts","in areas where risk of explosion exist","any where","no where"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"An indication is determined to be a defect if","options":["it is so called by a level II tech","it is so called by a level III tech","it is long enough","none of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Notch shaped defects occurring in regions of high stresses are called","options":["flaws","stress-raisers","EDM notches","cracks"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Severity of defects is usually","options":["easily determined","quantitatively described","qualitatively described","not a factor considered in LPI"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Choosing the correct method of LPI test requires","options":["knowing the capabilities of the LPI methods available","history of the part","intended use of the part","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Which factor does not determine the LPI technique to be used?","options":["Expected service of part","form and stage of manufacture of the part","expected defect orientation","cost of inspection"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Basically there are only _______ methods of penetrant inspection","options":["2","3","4","5"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The two basic considerations for any LPI test choice are","options":["sensitivity and cost","speed and sensitivity","type of defect and sensitivity","type of defect and size of part"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Often the choice of a penetrant type and method is a compromise between","options":["what can be found and how fast can we find it","what needs to be found and what can be found","cost and sensitivity","cost and benefit"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Broad open defects require a penetrant with","options":["good penetrability","extreme brilliance","extreme emulsification control","short penetrant time"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"After an acid pre-cleaning, magnesium castings should be","options":["thoroughly water washed and dried","cooled","vapour degreased","oiled and whitened"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Developing time for micro porosity as compared to regular porosity, is","options":["more","less","the same","varies"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"A false indication may result from","options":["threads and key ways","transfer of penetrant from another part","turbine wheel christmas trees","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Aside from increasing the integrity and safety of manufactured pieces, non destructive testing cuts costs by","options":["increasing production rates","reducing personnel","eliminating poor stock prior to processing","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Investment castings are usually make from","options":["high temperature corrosion resistant alloys","malleable iron","white metal","plastics"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"When testing investment castings using LPI, the best method to use is","options":["fluorescent post emulsifiable","fluorescent water washable","colour contrast solvent removable","any method is acceptable"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The post emulsified technique is often used on forgings because","options":["flaws are usually open and shallow","flaws tend to be filled with oxides","flaws tend to be tight and fine","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"LPI can be used to locate _________ in welded lead seams.","options":["porosity","fatigue cracks","laminations","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Fatigue cracking is a result of","options":["a combination of corrosive environment and stress","shock loading","cyclic loading","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"LPI has been used in dentistry to","options":["locate cavities in teeth","locate cracks in dentures","aid an anesthesia","detect pyorrhea"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Liquid penetrant is ideal for leak detection in","options":["pressurized systems","vacuum systems","open tanks or vessels","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Hydraulic fluids under pressure can be used to determine if leaks are present by means of a","options":["pressure gauge","hydrometer","hygrometer","densitometer"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"In evacuated glass vessels for electronic devices, the best method for locating leaks between electrodes and glass is","options":["liquid penetrant testing","a pressure gauge","halogen leak testing","mass spectroscopy"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Developers used for leak detection liquid penetrant testing are","options":["of the water soluble type","usually chalk","solvent suspendible only","optional"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Welded seams can be tested immediately following welding at temperatures of 600 degrees F. with liquid penetrant","options":["if the test is done at a pressure of 100 atmospheres","using a high temperature water soluble penetrant","if the test is done in less than 30 seconds","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"When performing leak detection using liquid penetrant technique longer dwell times are required if","options":["the material tested is thick","large porosity reservoirs exist","fine cracks or micro shrinkage is the source of leak","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Compared to radiography, ultrasonics, and eddy current, the MPI and LPI methods provide","options":["exact defect dimensions","a defect record directly on the part surface","no means of permanent test record","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"In order to evaluate a defect an inspector must have","options":["a knowledge of the test","a knowledge of the material tested","a knowledge of the applicable codes","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Acceptability of discontinuities is established","options":["knowing the service requirements of the part","by a series of nondestructive tests","by the inspector","by statistics"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Size  and severity of an indication is indicated by","options":["intensity and spread of penetrant on the developer","speed of formation","extents of the indication","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Tests are run on liquid penetrant materials in order to","options":["test for physical properties","establish suitability for specific applications","verify uniformity of different batches","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Which test would not be considered an evaluation test for liquid penetrant","options":["meniscus test","viscosity test","fluorescent brightness test","water drop-through test"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Measurement of which physical property of a penetrant would not be performed by the technician using the penetrant?","options":["density","flash point","sulphur content","water content"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Stability of fluorescence is measured in units of","options":["a percentage relative to original","ergs","lumens","watts per square metre"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Dimensions of the aluminium test block are typically 3\" X 2\" X 3/8\" with the direction of rolling in the","options":["3/8\" direction","2\" direction","3\" direction","diagonal"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The aluminum test block is heated to about 950 degrees F. before quench.  This is verified by","options":["colour change of the metal","tempilstick","thermostat","bi-metal thermistor"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The aluminum test block cannot be used to compare two","options":["types of developer","black lights","removal methods","colour contrast penetrants"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The usual material used for plating in the \"cracked plated strip tests\" is","options":["chrome","nickel","iron","lead"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Plated strips used for penetrant comparison tests can be used","options":["once","2 or 3 times","10 to 12 times","with fluorescent penetrants only"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The water drop through test is used to test","options":["fluorescent water washable penetrants","post emulsifiable penetrants","dry developer","water suspendible developers"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The dispersibility test for wet developers is used to determine","options":["how fast at will cover a part","how evenly developer is distributed on a part","the washability of the developer","the ease with which it returns to suspension"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The corrosion test for wet developers uses a small aluminum block","options":["placed in boiling developer","treated with developer in hydrochloric acid","treated with developer in sodium hydroxide solution","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The quantity recorded in the Pensky Martens closed cup test is","options":["viscosity","water content","sulphur content","flash point temperature"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"To verify continuing dependable results when using penetrant test materials","options":["only aerosol cans should be used","operating control tests are run","covers are kept on tanks","manufactures guarantee performance"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Penetrant that is found to contain water at 80% of its maximum tolerance level should be","options":["diluted with penetrant","distilled","discarded","homogenized"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"If no sediment occurs in the glycerin breakdown test it indicates","options":["the penetrant is acceptable","damage due to freezing","an excess of oil contaminants","gross water contamination"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Recommended maximum water contamination for emulsifiers is","options":["5%","20%","50%","75%"],"correct":1}]$NDTA_SEED$::jsonb)
