from jsonb_to_recordset($NDTA_SEED$[{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"If the wetting ability test indicates uneven wetting","options":["add more developer","add more wetting agent","correct the mixture to the appropriate specific gravity","discard the developer bath"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Blacklight is considered to be in the range of","options":["long wavelength ultraviolet","short wavelength ultraviolet","short wavelength infrared","500 to 800 nm"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Working with a damaged filter on a blacklight may result in","options":["defects appearing red instead of blue-green","missing defects","conjunctivitis","irrelavent indications"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The single most important quality of vision required by an LPI inspector is","options":["colour vision","dark adaptation","visual acuity","depth perception"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The LPI method of NDT is limited by","options":["smeared metal surfaces","porous materials","inexperienced or poor operators","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The carrier liquid for dyes used in LPI","options":["is always oil based","varies depending on the dye type","is fluorescent only if colour contrast dye is used","is independent of dye type used"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Hydrophilic emulsifiers operate by direct emulsification by means of","options":["diffusion","chemical reaction","kinetic action","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Penetrant viscosity can be an indicator of","options":["sensitivity","penetrability","both a and b","neither a nor b"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Fluorescent dye penetrants are considered to be more sensitive than colour contrast penetrants because they are","options":["less viscous","more visible","lipophilic","hydrophilic"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"GOX, LOX and low sulphur/halogen content penetrants can be used","options":["if certified by government organizations","in small quantities in well ventilated areas","only on structural steel","in third world countries"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Recommended safety standards set the minimum flash point of penetrants used in open tank facilities to be","options":["40 degrees C.","57 degrees C.","93 degrees C.","110 degrees C."],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Excess penetrant is removed by","options":["self or post emulsification and water washing","hand wiping and solvent removal","hydrophilic removal and agitation","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"An important purpose of emulsification in LPI is to","options":["stop developer action","improve \"signal\" to \"noise\" ratio","\"freeze\" defects in position","reduce bleedout time"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Lipophilic emulsifiers blend into the post emulsifiable penetrant by","options":["diffraction","diffusion","capillary action","gravity"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The advantage of a long penetrant drain dwell time for dipped parts is","options":["reduced emulsification time","reduced contamination of emulsifier","increased rate of bleed out","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Emulsifiers often contain dyes, pink or red in white light, pink /orange under black","options":["so they don't show through developers","to distinguish them from penetrant liquids","to provide a background","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Dry developers and water-suspended wet developers are usually less sensitive than solvent based developers because","options":["they are not as mobile","the particles are not as fine","solvent aids in formation of indications","solvent based developers provide higher contrast"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"If an LPI indication is found to be relevant the inspector must","options":["re-run the test","find another NDT method that cannot detect it","determine if it  is acceptable or rejectable","advise the production manager"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Bleed back refers to","options":["capillary action pulling penetrant back into a defect","reverse fluorescent method","re-occurrance of a penetrant indication after wiping away the original","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Dual response penetrants are","options":["both normal and reversed fluorescent","both water wash and solvent removable","view under black light or white light","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"If it is determined that heating a part prior to penetrant application is desirable, penetrant should be applied by","options":["spraying","paint brush","dipping","immersion until the part cools"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Open tanks of penetrant are subject to evaporation losses of volatiles.  This can result in","options":["decreased viscosity","changes in fluorescence","lowering the flash point","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The frequency of comparison test run on penetrant materials should be","options":["daily","weekly","monthly","based on work load, and climatic conditions"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Hydrophilic emulsifiers are shipped","options":["as dry powders","as concentrated liquids","on dry ice","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Concentration of hydrophilic emulsifiers used in dip tanks is ____________ than concentrations for spray application","options":["greater","less","about the same","varies with the manufacturer"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The rate of diffusion of lipophilic emulsifiers is a function of their","options":["density","colour","dragout","viscosity"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Emulsification using hydrophilic emulsifiers requires","options":["agitation or scrubbing action","the addition of detergents","the addition of a wetting agent","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The purpose of the pre-rinse cycle used by some using hydrophilic emulsifiers is to","options":["fix the position of penetrant","reduce emulsification time","remove contaminating solids","increase penetrability"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Sensitivity of a particular type of developer is often dependant on","options":["weather conditions","manufacturers' specifications","method of application to test part","its date of manufacture"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Cracking of developer coating during drying indicates","options":["drying is complete","excessive concentration of developer powder","excessive drier temperature","loss of wetting agent"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Non-aqueous solvent suspendible developers are applied by","options":["flowing","dipping","aerosol or electro-static spray","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Plastic strippable film developers","options":["are not yet commercially available","use organic polymers","have low sensitivity","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Even absolute values of fluorescence measured by photometers are not reliable without a reference standard because of","options":["variations in metals","variation in black light source","non-linear response of photosensors","meter saturation"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Evaluation of LPI tests for different depth cracks can be determined by","options":["increasing pre quench temperature on the aluminum block","capillary activity in the glass wedge","varying coating thickness on chrome plated brass panels","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"In LPI testing where abrasive polishing is required to remove contaminants or rough surface it should be followed by","options":["acid etching","vapour degreasing","water rinse","solvent washing"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"As compared to the non-flammable solvent developer, the low sulphur-low chlorine solvent developers' drying time is","options":["greater","less","about the same","depends on temperature"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Optimum resolution and sensitivity of indication occurs after _______ or development time.","options":["30 seconds","2 to 10 minutes","10 to 15 minutes","15 to 30 minutes"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"As an emulsifier becomes contaminated with penetrant, emulsification time tends to","options":["double","increase slightly","decrease","remain the same"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Field application of penetrant in temperatures just above freezing is best done using","options":["a brush","aerosol spray cans","a spray mixture with glycol","any of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The light fluffy dry powder developers are ideal for fluorescent penetrant inspections because","options":["they resist balling action","a white contrasting background is not essential","of their low density","of their super high absorptive qualities"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Electrostatic spray systems are used to apply","options":["penetrants","emulsifiers","developers","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The advantage of electrostatic application of penetrant materials is","options":["reduce risk of pollution","reduced dragout losses","no progressive contamination of solutions","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Spectral characteristics of white light used for viewing of visible dye penetrant is","options":["never a factor","improved using light rich in wavelengths reflected by the dye","improved using light deficient in wavelength reflected by the dye","chosen between 350 to 450 nm"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Normal recommended white light intensity on a test piece when using visible dye penetrant is","options":["10 to 20 foot candles","300 to 550 lux","4500 to 6500 nm","3 t 10 diopters"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Under normal daylight conditions the human eye is insensitive to blacklight.  In a darkened inspection booth the eye is","options":["twice as sensitive to black light","30 times as sensitive to black light","never sensitive to blacklight","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Which is not an advantage of tubular fluorescent blacklights","options":["cool operation","ease of focusing","quick starting","inexpensive"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Recommended minimum blacklight intensity for fluorescent penetrant testing is","options":["10 lux","100 footcandles","3 watts per square metre","3 micro watts per square metre"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"To convert light meter valves from watts per square metre to microwatts per square centimetre you multiply by","options":["100","10","0.1","0.01"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"For effective visibility when using fluorescent penetrant, blacklight to white light intensity should have a minimum ratio of","options":["2:01","10:01","50:01:00","100:01:00"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Mechanized scanning of fluorescent penetrant indications can be accomplished by","options":["television scanners","laser scanners","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Computerized pattern recognition and laser scanning in fluorescent penetrant inspections can","options":["not be accomplished","all but eliminate human inspection","be used to sort and assemble suspect indications for human decision","both b and c"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Which is not a method of precleaning used in liquid penetrant inspections?","options":["abrasive cleaning","salt bath","laser etching","electro cleaning"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Paint removal for LPI can be accomplished by","options":["solvent, acid or alkaline removers","abrasive removal procedures","burning or ignition","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Electrolytic cleaning liberates hydrogen and oxygen as part of the operation.  This risks","options":["oxidation of the test piece","formation of water","flames or explosions","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Prior to discarding used pickling solutions they should be","options":["cooled","filtered","neutralized","none of the above is necessary"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Salt bath descaling of tightly adhering scale is accomplished by","options":["thermal shock and chemical reduction","chemical \"banging\"","solution of scale by strong abrasives","acidic corrosion"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Cotton gloves for handling of test parts is recommended to","options":["ensure operator safety","prevent fingerprint contamination","absorb excessive bleedout","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The solvent ability of some penetrants and the absorptive quality of developers can","options":["result in dishpan hands","cause metal fatigue","leave a part cleaner after inspection than before","induce rusting"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Sodium nitrate or sodium chromate can be added to the postcleaning rinse water to","options":["prevent galling","prevent rusting","speed up evaporation","act as a wetting agent"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The most difficult developers to remove are the","options":["dry developers","wet aqueous developers","aqueous soluble developers","film type developer"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The tendency of a liquid to contract its surface to the smallest possible area is a result of","options":["gravity","surface tension","strong nuclear force","electromagnetic force"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The rate of evaporation is increased by increasing","options":["temperature","vapor pressure","Blotzman's constant","density"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The factor influencing penetrant entry into flaws is","options":["size of surface opening","surface tension of the penetrant liquid","contact angle between the liquid and test surface","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"A typical contact angle for a good liquid penetrant is","options":["less than 10 degrees","10 to 20 degrees","20 to 40 degrees","greater than 40 degrees"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"In a narrow crack, liquid penetrant cannot reach the crack tip due to","options":["gas pressure","surface tension","capillary forces","gravity"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The significance of a crack as related to potential failure of a part is determined by","options":["composition of part (alloy)","location of crack","structural design of part","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Self development techniques involve","options":["automated systems","no penetrant","no developer","no operator"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Spherical balls of glass (pyrolytic silica) have been used as developers with the result that they","options":["attained best results on microscopic cracks","proved inferior to calcium carbonate","are not as effective as chalk","tended to roll off the surface tested"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Plastic film developers have very high resolution of indications because of","options":["temperature inversion","dilution expansion effects","excessive bleeding and migration is inhibited","water solubility"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Treatment of a metal at an elevated temperature to remove residual stresses is called","options":["softening","case hardening","annealing","hot working"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Small cracks made by grinding, or forging strains in dies are called","options":["hot tears","chatter","checks","chipping"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"A material that has the ability to deform plastically without fracturing is said to be","options":["work hardened","plastic","wroughten","ductile"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Cracks that result from repeated loading and unloading are referred to as","options":["cold working cracks","fatigue cracks","forging cracks","transverse cracks"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"An indication which may be mistakenly interpreted as a discontinuity is called","options":["a defect","a false indication","an irregularity","a non relevant indication"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"In NDT, a response or evidence of response which requires interpretation to determine its significance is called","options":["a defect","an irregularity","an indication","a signal"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Small depressions in the surface of a test part caused by corrosion or cavitation are called","options":["depressions","karst","pitting","cavities"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Underbead cracking is","options":["not significant","only found in plastics","not detectable by LPI","the same as toe cracking"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"When an LPI indication is found, the effect it will have on the service of a part is estimated by","options":["codes","the inspector determining type and extent of the defect","a series of further inspections","the extent of bleedout"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Generally, sharp clear cut indications result from","options":["micro shrinkage","crater cracks","narrow linear discontinuities","undercut"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The problem testing pieces with LPI that have been lapped or honed is","options":["the compounds used clog openings","oils and greases used may fluoresce","both a and b","None of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The result of too high a part or penetrant temperature is","options":["heat shock cracking","missing fine defects","poor contrast","an explosion"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The depth of cracks formed in the chromium plated penetrant test panels is primarily a function of","options":["chrome alloy","rate of bending to produce fracture","degree of polishing on the brass subpanel","thickness of chromium plated"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Halogens and sulfur are to be avoided in penetrant materials used on stainless steel because","options":["they induce stress-corrosion cracking","they are highly toxic when mixed","fluorescence is reduced by the presence","all of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Which is not an effective method to help reduce potential pollution by penetrants?","options":["drain penetrants for maximum time","reuse emulsifiers until fully contaminated","filter and or treat rinse water","apply penetrants and emulsifiers by spray application"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"An effective way to reduce the polluting effects of penetrants is","options":["use completely water soluble penetrants","use bio-degradable penetrants","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"When using a post-emulsifiable penetrant, it is occasionally pre-rinsed prior to applying emulsifier.  The purpose of this is to","options":["speed up removal","degrease pollution treatment costs","decrease emulsification time","increase sensitivity to shallow defects"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"When a closed loop system is used to reduce pollution by penetrants, penetrant is removed from solvents by","options":["distillation","skimming","polymer net clarification","detergents"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The best penetrant method to use if you suspect a defect may be contaminated is","options":["water-washable penetrant","post-emulsifiable penetrant","solvent removable penetrant","visible dye penetrant"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"If speed of inspection is not a major consideration, recommended well time should not be less than","options":["2 minutes","5 minutes","15 minutes","30 minutes"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Emulsification time on rough surfaces is usually","options":["longer than on smooth surfaces","shorter than on smooth surfaces","determined by the alloy tested","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Developer cannot be applied by","options":["electrostatic spray","paint brush","dipping","none of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Application of dry developer is by","options":["electrostatic spray","dipping","dusting","any of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Exposure of the skin to some penetrant materials can result in","options":["conjunctivitis","dermatoses","tuberculosis","appendicitis"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"If when testing the specific gravity of a developer bath was higher than recommended you should","options":["add water","add developer","stir the bath vigorously","dump the bath and prepare a new one"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI