":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Radioisotopes in fluids such as Pd 109 in oil","options":["are used as radioactive penetrants","interfere with fluorescent dyes","destroy colour contrast dyes","have no purpose in LPI"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Although water is a very good penetrating fluid it is undesirable on a test part when doing LPI because","options":["it dilutes water solvable dyes","it prevents dye entry into defects","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Penetrant surface tension and viscosity are required","options":["by dry developers","by wet developers","by heating in a hot air drier","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Dark cobalt blue or deep purple dyes are used for","options":["colour contrast penetrants in bright sunlight","reverse fluorescent dye penetrants","infra red light viewing of LPI indications","rock band hair dyes"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Both fluorescent and visible dye penetrants are identified by","options":["dwell times","viscosity","method of application","method of removal"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The single most important factor determining the speed penetrant enters a flaw is","options":["surface finish","viscosity","method of application","depth of defect"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"For intricate shaped parts the best LPI method is","options":["water-washable fluorescent","solvent removable","post emulsifiable colour contrast","post emulsifiable fluorescent"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The correct unit of measure for blacklight intensity is","options":["foot candles","ergs","mW/cm2","dyne cm/s"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The greater the blacklight intensity and the lower the ambient light intensity","options":["the shorter the dark adaptation time required","the smaller the detectable indication","the shorter the development time needed","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Colour contrast ratios of penetrant vs background are determined using","options":["light meters","photofluorometers","xylene","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Contamination of developer with penetrant can result in","options":["false indications","masked indications","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"In order to spread quickly and evenly water suspended wet developers contain","options":["water","emulsifier","wetting agents","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Emulsifiers combines with penetrants to make a","options":["slurry","gel","water washable mix","suspension"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Cracked aluminum test blocks contain","options":["stress cracks","fatigue cracks","quench cracks","crater cracks"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The higher the penetration coefficient value is","options":["the greater the fluorescence is","the lower the viscosity is","the better the penetrating ability","none of the above, there is no such thing as penetration coefficient"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The smallest opening that can be entered by a liquid used in liquid penetrant inspection is","options":["10nm","5nm","limited by the molecular size of the penetrant material","unlimited"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Cast grey iron would be inspected using________ penetrant inspection","options":["solvent removable","post-emulsifiable fluorescent","water washable colour contrast","none of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"After removing excess penetrant the part must be thoroughly dry","options":["if wet developer is used","unless dry developer is used","if wet developer is applied by spray","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Steel ball bearing would be non-destructively tested using","options":["liquid penetrant","magnetic particles","radiography","eddy current"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The term defect or flaw indicates","options":["a minimum or maximum size","suitability of the part for a given purpose","nature of the fault","none of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Ultimately, the cause of any crack is","options":["corrosion","re-crystallization","stress","strain"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Localized heating of metal objects can result in","options":["\"crazy\" cracks","grinding cracks","arc strike cracks","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"In a valve casting, sponginess","options":["would result in a leak","could be found using LPI methods","would only be seen with radiography","a and b"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The term \"pipe\" refers to","options":["a forging defect","a weld defect","central shrinkage in an ingot","a central blowhole in a casting"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The sensitivity of a liquid penetrant system is determined by","options":["contrast ratios","colour intensity","ability to detect small defects","frequency of black light used"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"When using a series of cracked chrome plates each with different plating thickness we can expect for a given penetrant and technique that","options":["deepest cracks to be located more reliably than shallow cracks","shallow cracks to be located more reliably than deep cracks","more shallow cracks to be found than deep","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"When using a high sensitivity water-washable fluorescent penetrant, if we increase washing time from 25 to 60 seconds, sensitivity will","options":["increase slightly","decrease slightly","decrease by more than 30 %","remain unchanged"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"The effect of remover temperature on total \"crack brightness\" ___________ with temperature","options":["increases","decreases","varies unpredictably","remains unchanged"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"Essentially LPI is just an enhancement visual inspection.  As compared to cracklike defects volumetric defect enhancements by LPI are","options":["the same","much better","not as good","of no use"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"If a procedure fails to take into consideration a significant variable, such as temperature the result is","options":["unreliable inspection results","missed defects","lack of repeatability","all of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":2,"question":"If it is possible to automate a previously manually performed scan you can always expect","options":["faster inspection","more accurate results","improved flaw detection reliability","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The hot oil technique utilized","options":["the natural fluorescence of oil","a black light","hot lubricating oil","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Prior to the work done in 1941 by the Switzer brothers:","options":["Penetrant methods did not exist","magnetic particle testing was the only NDT method","the hot oil technique was used on non-ferrous metals","x-ray was the only method used on non-ferrous metals"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"In LPI, the term \"Family\" refers to","options":["the manufacturer of the penetrant","either fluorescent or non-fluorescent penetrant","the compatible group of test materials","a secondary distribution organization"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The reversed-fluorescence method employs","options":["a reversal order of the application of penetrant and    developer","low intensity fluorescent developer","filtered white light for viewing","a photographic technique for viewing"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The fugitive dye method","options":["was developed by an ingenious prisoner looking for     cracks in his cell","utilizes only fluorescent dyes","can only be applied by aerosol spray","utilizes ultraviolet light to destroy the thin film     of surface dye"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"An advantage of Liquid Penetrant over Eddy Current testing is","options":["it has better sensitivity to tight cracks","it is more easily used on ferrous recesses","it has better sensitivity to broad shallow defects","the temperature range at which it can be used"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Oil based penetrants cannot be used safely on","options":["ceramics","manganese castings","aluminium","rubber"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Plastics are best tested using","options":["alcohol based penetrants","oil based penetrants","water based penetrants","any of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The P.E. method stands for","options":["post emulsification method","pre-emulsification method","penetrant emission method","penetrant evaluation method"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Blacklight viewing is done with ultraviolet light having  a wavelength of about","options":["3650 angstroms","0.365 �m","0.000365 mm","any of the above is correct"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Leaker penetrant is specially designed for","options":["leak detection","crack detection in ceramic urinals","flaw detection in glass tubing","penetrant inspections done in conjunction with flux     leakage technique"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"In darkened surroundings, the eye dark adapts.  This is   called","options":["myopia","scotopic vision","hypermyopia","photopic vision"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"In bright surroundings the eye's sensitivity to light changes.  This is called","options":["myopia","scotopic vision","hypermyopia","photopic vision"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The viscosity of a good penetrant must be","options":["high","low","neither too high nor too low","viscosity has little to do with whether or not a material will make a good penetrant"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Wetting ability of a liquid used as penetrant is measured by","options":["centistokes","grammes per square centimetre","contact angle","a pipette"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The relationship between viscosity  and drag out is","options":["more pronounced at higher viscosities","most notable for lower viscosities","exponential","linear"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Occasionally a manufacturer mixes a volatile constituent with non-volatile penetrant for the purpose of","options":["reducing viscosity and speeding penetration","increasing sensitivity","increasing contrast","making the penetrant more readily absorbed by the developer"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The Penskey-Martens closed cup apparatus is used to determine","options":["density","seeability","contrast","flash point"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Capillary pressure for any crack-like defect can be increased by","options":["a wider crack opening","reducing the surface tension of the liquid","increasing the equilibrium contact angle of the liquid and crack surface","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Evaluation of the sensitivity of a penetrant must be qualified by","options":["a given purpose or defect type","a given material tested","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The relative amount of light reflected or emitted between an indication and its background is termed","options":["seeability","contrast ratio","sensitivity","reflection coefficient"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"When one moves from a well lighted area to a darkened area the ability to perceive contrast","options":["increases","decreases","remains unchanged","varies with the frequency of light"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The optimum colour for fluorescent dye penetrants (ie. viewed in black light) is","options":["blue-green","yellow-green","red","orange"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The natural tendency for the eye to magnify a small light source on a dark background is called","options":["the Diopter effect","the inverse square law","halation","scatter"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"A combination of fluorescent dyes to produce a more intense fluorescence and desirable colour is called","options":["multi dye","polyfluorescence","intensified dye","cascading"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Water based fluorescent penetrants","options":["are used with organic developers","have the lowest sensitivity","are used where combustible or oxidizable liquids cannot be used","have the lowest sensitivity to acid contamination"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Yellow fluorescent, oil penetrant is used primarily on","options":["rubber and plastics","ceramics","light alloys","stainless steel"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Solvent removable colour-contrast penetrants are made with liquids that are","options":["of low flash point flammable oils","of high flash point combustible organic compounds","non-combustible, non-flammable organic compounds","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Hydrocarbons such as anthracene,chrysene, and fluoranthene have been employed as","options":["dry powder developers","dry fluorescing indicators","solvent cleaners","capillary accelerators"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The breaking-film method","options":["is roughly the colour-contrast equivalent to the reversed fluorescence method","utilizes photographic emulsion on the test piece","is good only for shallow defects","requires a black light filter for lower frequency light"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Solvent developers, in addition to blotting,","options":["increase penetrant removed from a crack by solvent act-ion of the penetrant","have anti-corrosive benefits","make cleaning easier","can be used with all penetrants"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"If used with fluorescent penetrants developers should","options":["not be fluorescent","be of the appropriate family","only be of the dry powder type","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Fluorescent developer is","options":["not as sensitive as solvent suspension","only used in aircraft testing","used for the reversed fluorescence method","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Early developers were usually talc or chalk but these were later replaced by","options":["anthracene powder","amorphous silica powder","flour","ascorbic acid"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Which of the following is not a recognized type of wet developer","options":["solvent suspendible","water suspendible","solvent soluble","water soluble"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Sensitivity of wet developer is usually considered to be","options":["better than dry developer","not as good as dry developer","about the same as dry developer","can be better or worse depending on part tested"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"In addition to developer powder and water, water suspendible developers contain","options":["dispersing agents and inhibitors","removal agents and wetting agents","both a and b","neither a nor b"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"When dipping parts in water suspendible developer, when the parts are slightly warmer than room temperature","options":["extra safety precautions are needed","shock cooling is a risk","bath concentrations may increase too high","excessive bleed out is expected"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The major drawback to water soluble developers is","options":["irregular deposition upon evaporation","sensitivity","most water soluble materials are poor developers","cost"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"On rough surfaces, solvent developers","options":["show up the finest cracks","have the lowest sensitivity","cause excessive bleed out","provide highest contrast"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"For sharp fillet inspections, the best developer to use is","options":["water suspendible","water soluble","solvent","dry-fluffy"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"For colour contrast penetrants, the best developer to use is","options":["solvent","water soluble","water suspendible","dry"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Although dirt may not fill a defect it is still desirable to remove it because","options":["it can prevent wetting and even spreading of penetrant","it can contaminate penetrant is dip tanks","neither a or b","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Penetration or drain time is ___________ by the presence of oxides and/or carbon","options":["increased","decreased","unchanged","wasted"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"If parts are dipped into penetrant while still hot they should be","options":["checked for quench cracks","retested","submerged until cooled","cleaned thoroughly"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"A method of decreasing penetration time that is not effective is","options":["heating the test piece","vacuum application of penetrant","application of penetrant under pressure","vibration of the test piece"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The use of vapour degreasing to remove excess penetrant is","options":["forbidden","effective in some cases","limited to small parts","to be avoided on thin sections"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The best compromise for water temperature in the removal step is","options":["room temperature","100 degrees F.","40 degrees C.","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"When using water spray for the removal of excess penetrant it should be","options":["high velocity spray","coarse spray","at an angle to the surface","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Immersion washing for penetrant removal","options":["can be used with all self-emulsifying penetrants","is recommended for small parts","requires \"over-flow\" tanks with water at 150 degrees F.","improves background conditions"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The dry blast method of excess penetrant removal utilizes","options":["hot air","air driven solvents","sand blasting","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Very strong water blast with or without the admixture of air is","options":["never used","used on fugitive dye","used on non-emulsifiable penetrant","harmful to ceramics"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"In the dry-blast removal of surface penetrant, developer can be replaced by","options":["etching","sand blast particles","caustic salts","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Infra-red heat lamps are not an effective drying method in LPI because","options":["most energy is reflected","the frequency of light breaks down fluorescence","heating and drying is uneven","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"For drying thin metal sections around 8mm thick, air temperature in the dryer should be","options":["250 degrees F.","65 degrees C.","100 degrees F.","just under the boiling point of water"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"When using wet developer the developing time is usually","options":["completed after the part is removed from the dryer","longer than the dwell time","determined by the penetrant used","twice as long as the drying time"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Where heavy bleed out is expected the best type of developer to use is:","options":["dry powder","water soluble","water suspendible","solvent suspendible"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The preferred developer on rough surfaces is","options":["solvent suspendible","water suspendible","water soluble","dry powder"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"If a piece is retested with fluorescent penetrant after it was tested with colour contrast penetrant","options":["results will be identical","sensitivity will increase","sensitivity will decrease","no change should be noticed"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Water washable fluorescent penetrant is not recommended for finding","options":["laps","open shallow defects","cold shuts","cracks in glass"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Excessive dye in the manufacturing of a penetrant will result in","options":["instability of the penetrant","reversal","excessive brilliance","shine"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Penetrants used in open tanks are subject to deterioration by evaporation of volatiles.  This is corrected by","options":["replenishing the volatiles","inspecting only cold parts","air conditioning","nothing, evaporation can only be minimized"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Water washable penetrants can be designed to tolerate up to _____% water","options":["2","5","10","20"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Topping up a penetrant tank with more penetrant but of a different make can result in","options":["separation of components","longer drain times","reduced sensitivity","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Red fluorescent dye is preferred in liquid penetrant leak testing because","options":["it is not easily confused with the blue fluorescence of oils and greases","it has the best penetrating ability","standard yellow-green dyes are too coarse","it has the best sensitivity"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"If a vessel operated under vacuum is to be leak tested with liquid penetrants","options":["the outside is coated with penetrant and the vessel evacuated","the inside is filled with penetrant and the vessel pressurized","either a or b depending on access","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The main risk of testing cold parts is","options":["chilling the penetrant bath","condensed moisture forming on the part","increased drain time","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"If a 200 litre tank of penetrant, with water tolerance of 10%, picks up 200 ml of water per day, how many days elapse prior to dumping","options":["10","20","125","200"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"A 250 litre tank of penetrant with water tolerance of 15% picks up 200 ml per day.  How many days elapse prior to dumping?","options":["18","100","150","221"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"A 100 litre tank of penetrant having 18% water tolerance picks up 500 ml per day.  How many days could this penetrant be used?","options":["18","44","54","72"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Dip washing as a method of removing water washable penetrants is","options":["good for small parts","only for fluorescent penetrants","the simplest wash method","not recommended"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Removing water washable penetrants with detergents is avoided because:","options":["the additional emulsifiers would remove penetrant form defects","the alkaline components break down fluorescent dyes","the acidic components break down fluorescent dyes","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"In the absence of a dry powder bin, dry developer can be applied with","options":["a spray bulb","a dry paint brush","an air operated powder gun","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Wet developer, when mixed to a manufacturers' recommended concentration","options":["is always correct","may not be correct on all surface conditions","never need agitation","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Drying time of wet developer should not exceed","options":["total development time","one half the penetrating time","one half recommended development time","twice that require to just dry the surface"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"When operating in \"light-lock\" enclosed room for black light inspection ventilation or air conditioning is needed because","options":["oxygen is in short supply","developer fumes can be toxic","heat given off the black light","all of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"For field inspections using fluorescent techniques where total exclusion of light is not possible","options":["use only dry developers","use only wet developers","use high brilliance penetrants and high concentration black light","black light inspection is not possible"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Dark adaptation for black light viewing requires","options":["less than 2 minutes","about 5 minutes","20 to 30 minutes","more than 30 minutes"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Alkaline content of some wet developers and some emulsifiers can cause pitting if not removed from","options":["glass","steel","nickel","aluminum"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Penetrants used in the post emulsifiable method can be optimized for various qualities because","options":["absence of emulsifier makes a stable mixture","there is move room to add dye","of low water tolerance","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Maximum recommended operating temperature for post emulsifiable penetrants is","options":["the same as water washable","higher than water washable","lower than water washable","varies with defect to be found"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"When  applied to a penetrant coat surface, emulsifier blending time must compromise","options":["speed and time of contact control","speed and sensitivity","sensitivity and seeability","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Developers for the post emulsifiable penetrant method are restricted to","options":["dry powder","dry powder and solvent suspended","water soluble and water suspended","none of the developers is restricted"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Once an effective drain time and emulsification time had been established it should be strictly adhered to so that","options":["the manufacturer may be advised","results are consistent","time is saved","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"\"Dip washing\" is used with post emulsifiable penetrants to","options":["give the most effective wash","speed up wash time","act just as a emulsifier stop","eliminate emulsification time"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"If poor washing leaves spots on a part inspected with post emulsifiable penetrant it should be","options":["re-emulsified and rewashed","rewashed with high pressure spray","rejected","re-processed with penetrant after cleaning and drying"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"If wet developer and dry developer have equal sensitivity, on a smooth surface best results will be had using","options":["wet developer","dry developer","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Recommended development time for the post emulsifiable method is","options":["equal to penetration time","twice the emulsification time","equal to the drying time","half the penetration time or greater"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Luminescence is associated with","options":["infra-red absorption","ultraviolet absorption","low temperature emission","solar flares"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The wavelength of visible light ranges from about","options":["4000 to 7000 angstroms","3500 to 8000 angstroms","2500 to 4000 angstroms","5500 to 6500 angstroms"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The range of wavelengths normally associated with black light is","options":["4000 to 7000 angstroms","3000 to 4000 angstroms","500 to 800 nm","200 to 400 nm"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The high intensity daylight fluorescent dyes are more visible at","options":["noon","dusk and dawn","night","solar eclipses"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"High intensity daylight fluorescent dyes are more effective at dusk and dawn because of","options":["increased diffraction of UV light","low background","better dark adaptation of the eyes","increased reddening of the sun"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Kopp 41 is a type of","options":["penetrant","emulsifier","glass filter","developer"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"A UV filter can also pass infra-red light.  The result is","options":["of no consequence to the inspection","reduced sensitivity","increased perception in dark surroundings","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The purpose of the low current arc from the starter electrode in the mercury vapour lamp is","options":["to vapourize the mercury","to limit current of the resistor","a safety feature","all of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"In high pressure mercury vapour lamps, mercury vapour pressure is optimum at","options":["1 atmosphere","10 atmospheres","100 atmospheres","1000 atmospheres"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Which is not a contributing factor in the seeability of a fluorescent indication?","options":["amount of dye at the indication","grain size of developer","response of fluorescent dye in visible light emitted","amount of energy supplied by blacklight"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Aging in black-lights can be attributed to","options":["handling","heat build up","switching on and off","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"A plot of line voltage versus blacklight output indicates a (an)","options":["inverse linear relationship","direct linear relationship","an inverse logarithmic relationship","non predictable variation"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"When not in use continuously, a blacklight should be","options":["left on","turned off","cooled by oscillating fan","none of the above"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Wilsonite sunglasses, used to protect against UV light are","options":["red","orange","yellow","green"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Yellow tinted sunglasses are to be used only with dyes that fluoresce in the ___________ range of light.","options":["blue-green","green-yellow","red","orange"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Fluorescent inspection of hard to get at internal surfaces is accomplished by","options":["vidicon cameras","well-logging","black light borescopes","portable black lights"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Photographic recording of fluorescent indications does not require","options":["colour film","long exposures","camera lens filters","black light"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The major advantage of the fluorescent method over the colour contrast method is","options":["fewer steps are involved","cost","visibility of indications","more effective developer"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The high concentrations of dyes in colour contrast penetrants can result in","options":["re-crystallization of dye components","settling out of dye from penetrants","high costs","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Developer carrier liquid","options":["is normally alcohol","always has a high flash point","dissolves penetrant to bring it to the surface","is always lox safe"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Dry powder developers have been used with colour contrast penetrants but","options":["bleed out time is excessive","contrast ratios are greatly reduced","drying temperatures must still be to 120 degrees F.","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Defect severity may be over-estimated if","options":["a defect is broad and shallow","excessive developing time elapses prior to inspection","the defect is a hot tear","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"If it is found necessary to re-run a part after a colour-contrast inspection, it is advisable to use","options":["water-washable fluorescent method","post-emulsifiable fluorescent method","post-emulsifiable colour-contrast method","another type of NDT"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"It is not recommended to re-run a test the _____method after first using the colour contrast method.","options":["colour contrast water-washable","colour contrast solvent removable","water washable fluorescent","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Variations in appearance of indications are due to","options":["variations in material used","variations in technique","size and character of the defects","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"If a precleaning station is incorporated into the equipment used in a penetrant facility it should be","options":["adjacent to the penetrant station","equipped with drying facilities","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Bubbling air through penetrant in dip tanks","options":["reduces evaporation loss","should be avoided","prevents clumping of dye on parts tested","enhances dye brilliance"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The expendable technique refers to","options":["LPI done in accounting firms","high rejection inspection","facilities not equipped with sumps to recover excess penetrant","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"In production line inspection, the solvent remover station is","options":["after the emulsifier station","located beside the vapour degreaser","not usually used","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The preferred material for the wash tank is stainless steel because","options":["titanium is too expensive","plastic is too soft","it resists corrosion","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Recirculating hot air dryers obtain their heat from","options":["electric elements","steam","gas burners","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Developer guns also require","options":["air pressure","a dust collection system","a booth","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Application of solvent suspended developed is always","options":["the fastest technique","the cheapest technique","the expendable technique","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"To avoid rejected parts from returning to the production line, ________ are required","options":["trained inspectors","correct inspection procedures","good inspections lights","automatic sorters"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Small integrated units are","options":["for small parts only","all stations on a single frame","made for manual operation only","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"An indication that reveals a condition in the part that would interfere with the service of a part is called a","options":["blemish","defect","flaw","pore"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Maximum depth of a defect is usually measured","options":["from tip to toe of the defect","along the surface of the defect","at right angles to the part surface","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Defects are not normally classified as to","options":["type","frequency","origin","material in which they occur"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Method, material and technique chosen in an LPI test are determined by","options":["kind and size of defect to be found","number of parts to be inspected","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Low sensitivity LPI technique are adequate for","options":["economical inspections","parts where easy to find defects are the only significant defects","large numbers of parts to be tested","high production rates"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"A technique for LPI should ensure that","options":["all defects are detected","all defects of a minimum size are detected","no indications are found","defects which cannot be tolerated are found"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"When developing a technique for a particular application in LPI, you should consider","options":["operator experience","availability of electricity","manufacturers' reputation","intensity of fluorescence required"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Fluorescent penetrants of the post-emulsifiable variety are ideal for","options":["shallow and broad defects","tight and fine defects","anodized parts","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"A defect whose dimensions were 0.003\" deep by 0.002\" wide would be considered","options":["broad and open","fine","tight","equilateral"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"A defect whose dimensions are 0.0005\" wide by 0.0001\" deep would be considered","options":["fine or tight","open","broad","oblong"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Some foundries clean magnesium castings with acid prior to LPI","options":["to remove oxides from defects","to neutralize the alkaline effect of penetrant","if unfused chaplets are to be found","when oil quenching is done"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Post emulsified fluorescent penetrants are not recommended for inspecting fillets because","options":["they are too penetrating","the fillet geometry causes the fluorescent light to reflect away","of the risk of non-relevant indications","emulsifier is too difficult to control on fillets"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Aside from improving quality of manufactured pieces, statistics from non destructive testing can be used","options":["to increase production rates","reduce personnel","predict failure rates","improve materials and design"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"LPI assists in casting design by","options":["locating surface sand inclusions","optimising riser locations","eliminating the need for x-ray","all of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Gas turbine blades are usually made by","options":["die casting","investment casting","sand casting","spin casting"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Even ferrous materials are often inspected using LPI because","options":["it is more sensitive","it costs less","magnetic properties are not consistent","MPI is not lox safe"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"LPI can repalce MPI where","options":["costs can be lowered","subsurface defects are acceptable","de-magnetising is a problem","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Stress corrosion cracking is a result of","options":["compressive stress in a caustic environment","tensile stresses in a corrosive environment","cyclic loading","pitting"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"LPI is used in medicine","options":["as a steroid","to dye blood for tracing","to locate flaws in prostheses","as an aid to x-rays by locating bone breaks"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Aside from LPI, another effective method of detecting leaks is by","options":["soap bubble test","Halogen gas detectors","mass spectrometers","all of the above"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Locating leaks by pressurized fluids can be accomplished by","options":["natural fluorescence in the hydraulic fluid","adding fluorescent dye to the hydraulic fluid","simple visual inspection","any of the above may locate leaks"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"As compared to helium leak testing, liquid penetrant testing for leak detection is","options":["more sensitive","less sensitive","about the same sensitivity","more expensive"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Leak detection inspection using liquid penetrant on rubber lined aircraft fuel tanks can be performed","options":["with solvent removable colour contrast penetrant","by adding fluorescent dye to the fuel","by lox safe penetrant only","by none of the above"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Water based penetrants having a minimum of organic components are called","options":["lox safe penetrants","leaker penetrants","inorganic penetrants","hydro-organo penetrants"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Liquid penetrant leak detection techniques are an inadequate test when","options":["only through cracks are to be located","porosity and shrinkage are the source of leaks","there is a TIG root","non through cracks might propagate in service"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The step immediately following developing time is","options":["viewing to interpret results","viewing to evaluate results","\"N\" stamping","dark adapting of the eyes"],"correct":0},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"In order to accurately interpret test results an inspector must have","options":["a knowledge of the test","a knowledge of the material tested","a knowledge of the applicable code","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"If an inspector of a large number of parts becomes aware of a marked change in indication incidence he should","options":["tell the production manager to stop production","take a rest","check his equipment and technique","advise the QA department"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"In order to increase reliability and uniformity of test results, liquid penetrant tests are","options":["automated","required to follow standards","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Results of tests run on liquid penetrant materials used to establish physical properties are used to","options":["establish health and safety limits","determine economic factors","both a and b","none of the above"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Which of the following would not be an evaluation test run on wet developer","options":["corrosion test","water drop through test","removability test","dispersability test"],"correct":1},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"Fluorescent brightness of penetrants is measured using a (an)","options":["spectrophotometer","photofluorometer","aluminum test block","a or b can be used"],"correct":3},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The meniscus test is used to measure","options":["density","viscosity","relative thin film fluorescence","wet developer wetting ability"],"correct":2},{"method":"LPI","level":3,"question":"The centre groove of the aluminum test block is cut","options":["before heating and in the 2 inch direction","before 