d to reduce the voltage across the Hall element to zero in the absence of a magnetic field.  Why are these circuits needed?","options":["the control current causes a negative bias","the control current causes a positive bias","to provide temperature  compensation","either a or b depending on the applied electromotive force"],"correct":2},{"method":"ECT","level":3,"question":"How is the magnitude of the Hall voltage related to the angle the element normal makes to the magnetic field?","options":["V  is proportional to  cos �","V  is proportional to tan �","V  is proportional to sin �","V  is proportional to cot �"],"correct":0},{"method":"ECT","level":3,"question":"What is the advantage of using 3 Hall effect detectors mounted at mutual right angles to each other?","options":["insensitivity to lift-off","insensitivity to permeability changes","field magnitude and direction determination independent of probe orientation","increased sensitivity to long gradual property changes"],"correct":2},{"method":"ECT","level":3,"question":"Response of an inductive pickup coil is not uniform for what waveform?","options":["square waves","pulsed waves","sinusoidal waves","both a and b"],"correct":3},{"method":"ECT","level":3,"question":"When a Hall detector is used it is usually within the magnetic field of the excitation coil.  How is this signal used?","options":["it is not used, it is electronically subtracted","it is used as the lift-off reference for phase adjustment","it is part one of a two part multifrequency technique","it is used to compensate for permeability changes within the test specimen"],"correct":0},{"method":"ECT","level":3,"question":"Which of the following is not a magnetic field vector measured by a magnetic reaction analyzer?","options":["'Ho' the magnetizing coil field","'Hh' the magnetizing field made by the Hall detector material","'Hn' the net magnetic field from primary coil and test material","'Hr' the reaction field in the test material"],"correct":1},